Status](https://coveralls.io/repos/github/apache/rocketmq/badge.svg?branch=master)](https://coveralls.io/github/apache/rocketmq?branch=master)þ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/org.apache.rocketmq/rocketmq-all/badge.svg)](http://search.maven.org/#search%7Cga%7C1%7Corg.apache.rocketmq)þ[![GitHub release](https://img.shields.io/badge/release-download-orange.svg)](https://rocketmq.apache.org/dowloading/releases)þ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-Apache%202-4EB1BA.svg)](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html)þþ**[Apache RocketMQ](https://rocketmq.apache.org) is a distributed messaging and streaming platform with low latency, high performance and reliability, trillion-level capacity and flexible scalability.**þþIt offers a variety of features:þþ* Pub/Sub messaging modelþ* Scheduled message deliveryþ* Message retroactivity by time or offsetþ* Log hub for streamingþ* Big data integrationþ* Reliable FIFO and strict ordered messaging in the same queueþ* Efficient pull&push consumption modelþ* Million-level message accumulation capacity in a single queueþ* Multiple messaging protocols like JMS and OpenMessagingþ* Flexible distributed scale-out deployment architectureþ* Lightning-fast batch message exchange systemþ* Various message filter mechanics such as SQL and Tagþ* Docker images for isolated testing and cloud isolated clustersþ* Feature-rich administrative dashboard for configuration, metrics and monitoringþþþ----------þþ## Learn it & Contact usþ* Mailing Lists: <https://rocketmq.apache.org/about/contact/>þ* Home: <https://rocketmq.apache.org>þ* Docs: <https://rocketmq.apache.org/docs/quick-start/>þ* Issues: <https://github.com/apache/rocketmq/issues>þ* Rips: <https://github.com/apache/rocketmq/wiki/RocketMQ-Improvement-Proposal>þ* Ask: <https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/rocketmq>þ* Slack: <https://rocketmq-invite-automation.herokuapp.com/>þ column17: FAIRtracks is a JSON Schema defining a minimal standard for genomic track metadata.
column43: ![alt text](docs/fairtracks_logo.png "FAIRtracks logo")þþ# Table of contentsþþ- [FAIRtracks - metadata standard for genomic tracks](#fairtracks---metadata-standard-for-genomic-tracks)þ * [Overview of structure of the FAIRtracks standard](#overview-of-structure-of-the-fairtracks-standard)þ * [Making changes to the standard](#making-changes-to-the-standard)þ + [Dependencies for running the scripts](#dependencies-for-running-the-scripts)þ + [Overview of how to contribute](#overview-of-how-to-contribute)þ + [Overview of file types and auto-generation](#overview-of-file-types-and-auto-generation)þ + [1. Automatic `make` targets for initial setup](#1-automatic-make-targets-for-initial-setup)þ + [2. Main process (with `make` targets) for making changes to the standard](#2-main-process-with-make-targets-for-making-changes-to-the-standard)þ + [3. `make` targets for overview and cleanup](#3-make-targets-for-overview-and-cleanup)þ * [OPML file format](#opml-file-format)þ + [OPML editors](#opml-editors)þ + [How the FAIRtracks standard is defined in OPML](#how-the-fairtracks-standard-is-defined-in-opml)þ * [Validation](#validation)þþ# FAIRtracks - metadata standard for genomic tracksþþFAIRtracks is a set of JSON Schemas developed through the ELIXIR implementationþstudy: "FAIRification of Genomic Tracks", as a minimal standard for genomicþtrack metadata. For more information on the implementation study, please checkþout:þþhttps://fairtracks.github.io/þþþ## FAIRtracks version informationþþ**FAIRtracks v1.0.2**þþþ## Overview of structure of the FAIRtracks standardþþ- The FAIRtracks standard consists of a main JSON Schema and a set ofþ subschemas. A JSON document of track metadata must validate towards the mainþ FAIRtracks JSON Schema to be said to follow the standard.þþ- The main FAIRtracks JSON Schema is simply named `fairtracks.schema.json` andþ is documented here:þþ | Title | JSON Schema | Schema documentation | Example JSON document |þ |:-----------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------|:------------------------------------|:-----------------------------------------------------------------|þ | FAIRtracks JSON Schema | [fairtracks.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks.schema.json) | [fairtracks.md](docs/fairtracks.md) | [fairtracks.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks.example.json) |þþ- This top-level FAIRtracks JSON Schema contains, in addition to some generalþ metadata fields, four arrays of JSON sub-documents for the four main objectþ types in FAIRtracks: `studies`, `experiments`, `samples`, and `tracks`. Eachþ of these object types are described in a separate sub-schema:þþ | Title | JSON Schema | Schema documentation | Example JSON document |þ |:-----------|:-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|:----------------------------------------------------------|:---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|þ | Study | [fairtracks_study.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_study.schema.json) | [fairtracks_study.md](docs/fairtracks_study.md) | [fairtracks_study.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_study.example.json) |þ | Experiment | [fairtracks_experiment.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_experiment.schema.json) | [fairtracks_experiment.md](docs/fairtracks_experiment.md) | [fairtracks_experiment.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_experiment.example.json) |þ | Sample | [fairtracks_sample.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_sample.schema.json) | [fairtracks_sample.md](docs/fairtracks_sample.md) | [fairtracks_sample.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_sample.example.json) |þ | Track | [fairtracks_track.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_track.schema.json) | [fairtracks_track.md](docs/fairtracks_track.md) | [fairtracks_track.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_track.example.json) |þþ- FAIRtracks also contains the following convenience sub-schemas:þþ | Title | JSON Schema | Schema documentation | Example JSON document |þ |:----------|:---------------------------------------------------------------------------------|:--------------------------------------------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|þ | Phenotype | [fairtracks_phenotype.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_phenotype.schema.json) | [fairtracks_phenotype.md](docs/fairtracks_phenotype.md) | [fairtracks_phenotype.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_phenotype.example.json) |þ | Contact | [fairtracks_contact.schema.json](json/schema/fairtracks_contact.schema.json) | [fairtracks_contact.md](docs/fairtracks_contact.md) | [fairtracks_contact.example.json](json/examples/fairtracks_contact.example.json) |þþþ## Making changes to the standardþþ### Dependencies for running the scriptsþþ- Linux-like shell with "bash". Mac OS X will do, but you probably need toþ install either XCode (from the App Store) or theþ [XCode Command line tools](https://developer.apple.com/download/more/?=command%20line%20tools).þ- Python >= 3.6þ- Node.js >= v10 and npm >= 3.10.8þ- git (relatively recent version is probably best)þ- On Mac OS X, all the above can be installed usingþ [HomeBrew](https://brew.sh/index_nb).þ- An OPML editor is also recommended, but not required. Seeþ [OPML editors](#opml-editors) below for more information.þþ### Overview of how to contributeþþ1. Create personal fork in GitHub ("Fork" button).þ2. Clone the fork to your computer (e.g., `git cloneþ https://github.com/myusername/fairtracks_standard.git`).þ3. Run `make raw`, and edit the raw OPML files to your liking. For moreþ information about the `make` targets, seeþ [below](#overview-of-file-types-and-auto-generation).þ4. Run `make` or `make all`þ5. Repeat step 4 and 5 until you are satisfied with the changes.þ6. Run `make rawclean` to remove the raw OPML files before committing.þ7. Commit and push your changes to a feature branch in your personal fork andþ create a pull request, as described in the standardþ [GitHub Flow workflow](https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/).þ8. Once the Pull Request is accepted:þ - Pull the latest changes in the `master` branch to your local repo.þ - Rebase your feature branch on top of `master`.þ - Make sure that all commits are consistently built. The automaticallyþ installed `git-hooks` will also check for consistency. To make a commitþ consistent, rebuild it with the `rebuild_all.sh` script. To clean upþ previous commits, use interactive rebase as described underþ [1b. make git-hooks](#1-automatic-make-targets-for-initial-setup) below.þ9. Force push your feature branch to your personal fork, which should updateþ the pull request, and notify us.þþ### Overview of file types and auto-generationþþThere is an inherent order to the different types of files in this repo,þdefined in the `Makefile`. The FAIRtracks standard is almost fully defined inþthe OPML files found under `json/overview`, with just a small bit of top-levelþlogic being handled by [opml_to_json.py](scripts/python/opml_to_json.py). Allþthe JSON Schema and JSON example files are automatically generated based uponþthe OPML files. Such automatic file generation are handled by various `make`þtargets:þþ### 1. Automatic `make` targets for initial setupþþThese `make` targets are run automatically if needed by the other `make`þtargets, but are also available for manual use if there is need.þþa. `make venv`þ- Autogenerates a Python virtual environment in the `.venv` directory, if notþ already present. In case the Python executable you want to link up to theþ virtual environment is located in a non-standard path, you can use theþ environment variable ` PYTHON_EXE` before the first `make venv` command. Forþ instance:þþ ```bashþ PYTHON_EXE=/path/to/my/python3 make .venvþ ```þþb. `make git-hooks`þ- Installs the version-controlled git hooks into the local repo. The git hooksþ makes sure that:þþ 1. All changed files are committed togetherþ 2. All secondary files have been recompiled with `make`þþ The checks are run before git commits or remote pushes are finalized.þþ It is especially important that the git hooks are installed before merging orþ rebasing is done, as the SHA256 signatures of the JSON files may then need toþ be recalculated (by `make`) on merged/rebased commits. To fix such issuesþ (which will appear when trying to push to GitHub) one will need to carry outþ an interactive rebase:þþ 1. Start interactive rebase: `git rebase -i $FIRST_COMMIT^`, whereþ `$FIRST_COMMIT` is the first commit that need editing (you can find thisþ in the log messages from the failed remote push).þ 2. In the editor that appears, replace `pick` with `edit` for the commitsþ that needs editing. You should also at this point plan to clean up yourþ commits by reordering or squashing them, as well as improving the commitþ messages.þ 3. `./rebuild_all.sh`þ 4. For all changed files: `git add $FILE`þ 5. `git commit --amend`þ 6. `git rebase --continue`þ 7. Repeat iii-vi for all commits selected for editing.þþc. `make jsonschema2md`þ- Installs the node packageþ ["jsonschema2md"](https://github.com/adobe/jsonschema2md) which is used toþ generate the JSON Schema documentation. The package is installed underþ "node_modules", together with all its dependencies.þþ### 2. Main process (with `make` targets) for making changes to the standardþþThe following process should be followed when changing the contents of theþ`FAIRtracks` standard itself:þþa. `make raw`þ- This makes copies of the existing *.opml files into similarly namesþ *.raw.opml files. The raw OPML files are made to be opened for editing inþ [specialized outlining tools](#opml-editors). As such tools vary in the exactþ content of the exported OPML files, the raw OPML files need to be compiledþ into standardized, cleaned-up versions before they are committed to git.þ- You only need to run `make raw` once. If you accidentally run the commandþ twice, any existing raw OPML files will be renamed to *.raw.opml.old.þ- The raw OPML files are ignored by git and can be edited in an OPML editor ofþ choice. See [OPML file format](#opml-file-format) below for more information.þ- Be sure to delete the raw OPML files (with `make rawclean`) before carryingþ out any git commands. This is important, as *e.g.* changing branches will notþ change the raw OPML files, since they are ignored by git. Thus, if one failsþ to remove the raw OPML files before switching commits, `make` will justþ regenerate the prevous commit on top of the new one.þþb. `make` or `make all`þ- After the raw OPML files have been edited, `make` runs:þ - `make opml` to generate cleaned up, standardized versons of the raw OPMLþ files.þ - `make json` to generate JSON Schema files and related example JSON filesþ from the cleaned up OPML files.þ - `make docs` to generate Markdown documentation files under the `docs`þ directory.þþ All the generated JSON Schema files, as well as the top-level JSON exampleþ file, include a stable SHA256 signature of their contents.þþ### 3. `make` targets for overview and cleanupþþa. `make signature`þ- Computes and prints the stable SHA256 signature for all the JSON files.þþb. `make rawclean`þ- Removes all raw OPML and related .old files.þ- Should only be run if you are sure that all changes in the raw OPML filesþ have propagated to other files, i.e. you should make sure that you have runþ `make` first.þ- Raw OPML files must be removed prior to running any `git` command, asþ explainedþ [above](#2-main-process-with-make-targets-for-making-changes-to-the-standard),þ section 2a.þþc. `make clean`þ- Runs `make rawclean`, in addition to removing the virtual environment in theþ `.venv` directory, the git hooks, and the `node_modules` directory.þþ## OPML file formatþþ[OPML](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OPML) is a standard file format definedþspecifically for outlining software.þþ### OPML editorsþþRaw OPML files can be edited by specific outlining tools, but as the format itþis a subtype of XML one can also use generic XML editors:þ- On Mac OS, we recommend using the commercial toolþ [OmniOutliner](https://www.omnigroup.com/omnioutliner), as there are reallyþ no open source alternatives with similar user interface.þ- As an open source, platform-agnostic alternative, we recommendþ [TreeLine](http://treeline.bellz.org/).þ- The OPML files can of course also be edited manually, in which case you canþ ignore the raw OPML files completely.þþ### How the FAIRtracks standard is defined in OPMLþþ- Each `` tag defines a JSON property, with the hierarchy defined byþ the XML hierarchy.þ- The details for each JSON property is defined by a set of possible attributesþ for each tag. Many of the standard JSON Schema keywords are directlyþ supported:þþ | Attribute | Description |þ |:--------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|þ | `_name` | The name of the JSON property. |þ | `const` | Constant value (the only value allowed). |þ | `default` | Default value if no value is provided. |þ | `description` | Human-readable description of the property. |þ | `enum` | Set of values allowed, separated by |. |þ | `examples` | Set of example values, separated by |. All properties must have the same number of examples (or none) within each JSON Schema. |þ | `format` | Format of current string property. Supports all of the standard JSON Schema formats, and in addition we support two custom formats: "curie" and "term", for respectively Identifiers.org-resolvable CURIEs and ontology terms. |þ | `minItems` | Minimal number of items in current array property. |þ | `pattern` | Regexp format for current string property. |þ | `ref` | JSON Pointer to another JSON Schema to import under the property. |þ | `required` | If `"true"` the current property is required. |þ | `title` | Title of the JSON Schema |þ | `type` | Data type of the current property: string, object, array, number, or boolean. |þþ In addition to the standard JSON keywords detailed above, a set of extendedþ attributes have been defined:þþ | Attribute | Description |þ |:-------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|þ | `ancestors` | Ontology labels, separated by |, used to validate properties in `term` format. At least one of these terms must be an ancestor of the value in one of the specified ontologies. |þ | `autogenerated` | If `true`, the contents of the current property will be filled automatically by the FAIRtracks autogenerate service (to be implemented later). |þ | `comments` | Comments that will remain in the OPML files only. |þ | `constIf` | If the specified `if_property` has the specified `if_value`, the current property must follow the specified `then_value`, interpreted as `const`. |þ | `foreignProperty` | JSON Pointer to a linked identifier property in another schema. Two JSON documents, one following the current schema and the other following the foreign schema, are related if the values in the two linked properties are the same. |þ | `matchType` | Validation rule. For properties in `curie` format: either `basic`, `loose`, or `canonical`. For properties in `curie` format: either `exact`, `suffix`, or `label`. |þ | `namespace` | Namespaces, separated by |, registered in http://identifiers.org. Is used to validate `curie` values. |þ | `ontology` | URLs to downloadable ontologies in OWL format, separated by |. To be used to validate properties in `term` format, which is used for ontology `term_id` properties. |þ | `ontologyTermPair` | Pair of JSON Pointers in the format `id=IDPTR;label=LABELPTR`, where `IDPTR` and `LABELPTR` are JSON Pointers to, respectively, an ontology term id and its corresponding (primary) label. Currently only pointers to child properties are supported, e.g. `id=0/term_id;label=0/term_label`. To be used in autogeneration and validation. |þ | `requireAnyOf` | For every level of the object hierarchy, at least one of the properties with `requireAnyOf="true"` at that level is `required`. |þ | `requireIf` | If the specified `if_property` has the specified `if_value`, the current property is `required`. |þ | `unique` | If `"true"` the value of the current property must be unique across all JSON documents. |þþ For more information, please visit the FAIRtracks validator GitHub repositoryþ (see [VALIDATION.md](VALIDATION.md) for directions).þþ- The `constIf` and `requireIf` attributes require the value to follow aþ specific pattern:þþ | Pattern part | Description | Attribute(s) | Obligatory | Example |þ |:--------------------|:-----------------------------------------------------------|:----------------------|:-----------|:---------------------------------------------|þ | `if_property=` | Relative JSON Pointer to property to check | `constIf` `requireIf` | Yes | `2/technique/term_id=` |þ | `if_value` | Value to check for | `constIf` `requireIf` | Yes | `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0001853` |þ | `;` | If-then delimiter | `constIf` | Yes | `;` |þ | `then_property=` | Relative JSON Pointer to property to acquire `const` value | `constIf` | No | `1/term_id=` |þ | `then_value` | `const` value for `then_property` | `constIf` | Yes | `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SO_0000685` |þ | | | Pattern delimiter (between patterns if more than one) | `constIf` `requireIf` | No | |þþ- In order to support multiple OPML editors, the first `` tag in theþ OPML files (the one with `_text="#title"`) should contain all properties inþ alphabetical order, with an attached value (typically `"."` or `"0"`). Theseþ parameters are ignored for that line (as it is just used to generate theþ `title` of the JSON Schema).þþ- When adding, removing, or renaming attributes:þ - Please update the first `` tag (with `_text="#title"`) for allþ OPML files, as described directly above.þ - In most cases, new attributes should also be added to theþ `ATTRIBS_TO_IMPORT` constant in theþ [opml_to_json.py](scripts/python/opml_to_json.py) script, in the order inþ which they should appear in the generated JSON Schemas.þþ## Validationþþ- Please visit the [VALIDATION.md](VALIDATION.md) document.

An Android library (with test application) which performs authenticated appengine requests.
column43: # AboutþAppEngineAndroid is an Android library (with test application) which makesþit easy to perform authenticated requests to a Google App Engineþapplication.þþ# AuthorþGopal Sharma <gopalkrishnaps@gmail.com>þþ# LicensingþLicensed under modified version of the MIT X licenseþ(http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.php). See LICENSE file.þþAlthough this is not part of the license (I'm not sure whether I want toþadd it), I request that you notify me if you do in fact use this code inþany way. It always helps to know that someone else is using my work :)þþ# UsageþAll java source files required are in the package com.gopalkri.appengineandroid.þþYou will need to add a few things to your AndroidManifest.xml. þþ* Add permissionsþ  * android.permission.GET_ACCOUNTSþ  * android.permission.USE_CREDENTIALSþ  * android.permission.INTERNETþ* Add activitiesþ  * com.gopalkri.appengineandroid.AppEngineActivityþ  * com.gopalkri.appengineandroid.AuthenticationActivityþþYou will also need to add a layout xml file to your project: res/layout/appengine.xml.þþThe interface to AppEngineAndroid will be exposed via the AppEngine class. AppEngineþis a Singleton, but it's construction is non standard. The way to construct theþAppEngine instance is to start AppEngineActivity for result with requestCodeþAppEngineActivity.SETUP_AUTH. AppEngineActivity will do what is needed and return.þIt will call setResult with either AppEngineActivity.RESULT_OK orþAppEngineActivity.RESULT_FAILED. Once AppEngineActivity returns, you can get anþinstance of AppEngine via it's static method getInstance(). Note that getInstance()þwill return null if something went wrong with its creation. þþSee the com.gopalkri.appengineandroid.test.Home Activity for an example.

This program is a distributed streaming processing system with a similar design like Storm. A complete topology contains spouts(stream source) and bolts(processing unit) which process stream on a per-tuple base. The user gets to implement the specific application for each bolt using C++. This system is tolerant to one master failure at a time and two worker failures at a time.
column43: This program uses java, and the IDE outputs a .jar file. To run the jar file, do "java -jar mp3.jar 0" on the machines to run the program.þWhen you are in the program, you can initialize the introducer by input "initiate", and then "join" on other machines to join the membership list or "leav" to leave it.þThe filesystem commands are: "put localfilename sdfsfilename", " get sdfsfilename localfilename", "delete sdfsfilename", to upload, download or delete from the filesystem. Also we use "ls sdsfilename" to get all the files stored on the filesystem, or "store" to get all the files stored on one machine. In order to get latest versions of a file, input "get-versions sdfsfilename numversionsþlocalfilename".þYou can generate scripts with script.py by running "python script.py filename num", with num being the number of MBs of the file to generate.

## Weather Forecast ##þþ**Weather Forecast** is an Android application  for displaying weather details.þþ### Features ###þThe application shows the current weather details for the current location of the device. The details shown are: þþ1. Current Temperature (Celsius or Fahrenheit)þ2. Moisture in the Atmosphereþ3. Speed of the windþ4. Pressure (Metric or Imperial unit)þ5. Amount of rainþ6. Wind directionþþApart from this the application also shows the weather forecast for next 5 days.þ  þþ### Installation ###þInstall the given **.apk** file on an android device to start using the application. þþþ### Usage ###þThe application can be used on a daily basis to see the weather conditions and act accordingly for your plans.þ þ### Building Project ###þ1. Clone this repositoryþ2. Run `gradlew assemble` command in console with this repository as current working directory.þ3. The **.apk** file should be available in `/mobile/build/outputs/apk` directory.þþ**Note:** A "local.properties" file is also needed to set the location of the SDK in the same way that the existing SDK requires, using the "sdk.dir" property. Example of "local.properties" on Windows: sdk.dir=C:\\adt-bundle-windows\\sdk. Alternatively, an environment variable called `ANDROID_HOME` can be set.þþ**Tip:** Command `gradlew assemble` builds both - debug and release APK. Use `gradlew assembleDebug` to build debug APK. Use `gradlew assembleRelease` to build release APK. Debug APK is signed by debug keystore. Release APK is signed by own keystore, stored in `/extras/keystore` directory.þþ**Signing process:** Keystore passwords are automatically loaded from property file during building the release APK.þþ### Testing ###þThe application has been tested on following devices:þþ- Nexus 4 (Phone)þ- Nexus 5 (Phone)þ- Nexus 10 (Tablet)þ þþþ### Dependencies ###þ- GPS / Network Provider who can give your current locationþ- Internet Connectionþþ### Developed By ###þPrerak Sola

# Android Lollipop ExerciseþþAndroid app to use as the base app for implementing the following material widgets and animations that were introduced in Android 5.0 (API level 21).þþ* RecyclerView (the new ListView)þ* CardView (custom outline and shadow)þ* Ripple animation (touch feedback)þ* Palette (Incorporate dynamic color)þ* Shared Element Activity Transitionþ* Floating Action ButtonþþThe app is composed of two screens. The first screen displays a list of contacts, in which, each item is described by the contact's avatar and name. Once a contact is selected from the list, a second screen appears with additional details about the contact, including his contact no. and a floating action button to place a phone call to this contact.þþ**Contact List**þþ  ![Screenie|300](http://i.imgur.com/VSbsd4Gl.png)þþ**Contact Details**þþ  ![Screenie|300](http://i.imgur.com/NpKJJgdl.png)þþ## OverviewþþThe app does the following:þþ1. It uses a `RecyclerView` to display a list of contacts.þ2. `CardView` is used to display each contact in the list.þþSuggested extensions:þþ1. Add ripple effect to `CardView` to provide touch feedback.þ2. Use `Palette` to add dynamic color to contact item's background. Use the same color as the accent color for the views in details screen.þ3. Add shared element activity transition to provide a seamless experience by emphasizing continuity between activity transitions.þ4. Add a floating action button, clicking on which should enable you to directly place a call to your contact.þþ## LibrariesþþThis app leverages the following third-party library:þþ * [Picasso](http://square.github.io/picasso/) - For image loading

column43: # JTermþþJTerm is a terminal emulator written in Java with a very thin native layer toþconnect to the underlying pseudoterminal device.þþ## SetupþþRun this to compile the software:þþ    ./gradlew clean terminalShared createRuntimeþþand then execute the main script:þþ    ./terminal.shþþ## SpecificationþþUseful information on implementing a terminal emulator can be foundþon <https://vt100.net/>, especially the [VT102 UserþGuide](https://vt100.net/docs/vt102-ug/) and its chapter aboutþ[Received Character Processing](https://vt100.net/docs/vt102-ug/chapter5.html)þis a useful resource. The page that describes theþ[Xterm Control Sequences](https://www.xfree86.org/current/ctlseqs.html) isþalso a very good reference.þþOne day the [vttest](https://invisible-island.net/vttest/vttest.html) shouldþpass, but we're not there yet :)þþ## Keyboard shortcutsþþ### Tabsþ* Ctrl + Shift + T: create new tabþ* Ctrl + Page Up: move to next tab to the leftþ* Ctrl + Page Down: move to next tab to the rightþþ### Miscþ* Ctrl + Shift + F8: toggle status bar displayþ* Ctrl + Shift + F9: toggle toolbar displayþ* Ctrl + Shift + F10: switch color themesþþ## Todo listþþ* [ ] mouse selection for copy and pasteþ* [ ] reintroduce proguard compilationþ* [ ] make tabs clickableþ* [ ] display title in tabs and window barþ* [ ] implement font size increase / decrease

Flying Saucer takes XML or XHTML and applies CSS 2.1-compliant stylesheets to it, in order to render to PDF (via iText), images, and on-screen using Swing or SWT. The library implements (basically) the entirety of CSS 2.1 and aims to be fully compliant with the W3C specification; it includes a small handful of CSS 3 features.

You can use Flying Saucer in anyþway and for any purpose you want as long as you respect the terms of the þlicense. A copy of the LGPL license is included as license-lgpl-2.1.txtþin our distributions and in our source tree.þþFlying Saucer uses a couple of FOSS packages to get the job done. A listþof these, along with the license they each have, is listed in the þLICENSE file in our distribution.   þþþWHAT'S IN THE DISTRIBUTIONþ--------------------------þþ    "BINARY" DISTRIBUTIONþ    ---------------------þ    The binary distribution includes only those files you need to *use* Fying Saucerþ    in your own programs. The files are all Java JAR files and just need to be includedþ    in the CLASSPATH as described in the User's Guide.þþ    * core-renderer.jar: the main file, always in the classpathþ    * itext*.jar: support for generating PDF files as outputþþ    * core-renderer-minimal.jar: see note at end of this sectionþþ    In principle, for an application using only Swing JPanels for output, you couldþ    restrict yourself to using core-renderer.jar; however, we recommend you includeþ    core*, itext* and to avoid any linking errors/ClassNotFoundExceptions. Whenþ    in doubt, contact us via mail.þþþ    "SOURCE" DISTRIBUTIONþ    ---------------------þ    The source distribution includes all the relevant source code, libraries and buildþ    scripts to build and extend Flying Saucer. You'll need Ant if you want to use ourþ    build scripts. There are some files under source control (notes, some docs) whichþ    are not included in the source distribution. You can pull the whole lot from our sourceþ    tree by visiting our project website (URL at top of this doc) and extracting fromþ    source control.þþþþþGETTING STARTEDþ---------------þPlease see the user's guide (URLs listed above) for info on how to get started.þAt a minimum, you'll need core-renderer.jar in your classpath; itext*.jar þfor PDF output.þSome good entry points (classes) are:þorg.xhtmlrenderer.simple.XHTMLPanelþorg.xhtmlrenderer.simple.PDFRendererþorg.xhtmlrenderer.simple.ImageRenderer

column17: The ComiXed Digital Comic Management System
column43: # ComiXedþAn application for managing digital comics.þþ## Project Roadmap And Vision StatementþThe goals for this project are simple. It seeks to be the ultimate management tool for digital comic books.þþTo achieve this goal, the project will:þ * be portable:þ    * it can be hosted on the Mac, Linux or Windows, andþ    * it can be used by any web browser.þ * manage a library of digital comic books, including:þ   * the archive format of the individual files (CBR, CBZ, CB7),þ   * converting files from one format to another between the supported types,þ   * adding and removing images that make up the pages of the comic,þ   * managing what type a page is (front cover, alternate cover, story, back cover, advertisement, etc.)þ   * blacklisting pages based on hash identifiers so that they are ignored, andþ   * deleting blacklisted.þ   * consolidating the library, including performing any or all of the following steps:þ      * moving all files into a well-defined directory structure,þ      * converting comics to a single archive type,þ      * removing files from each comic that has been blacklisted, andþ      * updating the ComicInfo.xml file within each comic with the current metadata.þ* administrators can quickly import new comics into their library.þ* scraping metadata for comics from various sources, such as [ComicVine](https://comicvine.gamespot.com/).þ* allow managed access to the contents of the library:þ   * administrative users can create/delete other users,þ   * users can create reading lists,þ   * users can manage their read state for all comics in the library, andþ   * users can read comics using an OPDS application.þ* a plugin system allows administrators to customize the features in their application:þ   * plugins can be written by third-parties to provide new and custom functionality, andþ   * administrators can easily install plugins.þþ## What The Project Will Not Doþ * It is not a comic reading application.þ    * For that, we recommend applications like [Chunky](http://chunkyreader.com/) (iOS), [YACReader](https://www.yacreader.com/) (iOS), [Kuboo](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.sethchhim.kuboo) (Android), [Challenger Viewer](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.kill.geek.bdviewer) (Android)þþ## Statusþ * Project Build Status: [![Build Status](https://img.shields.io/endpoint.svg?url=https%3A%2F%2Factions-badge.atrox.dev%2Fcomixed%2Fcomixed%2Fbadge%3Fref%3Ddevelop&style=flat-square)](https://actions-badge.atrox.dev/comixed/comixed/goto?ref=develop)þ * SonarCloud Status: [![Quality Gate Status](https://sonarcloud.io/api/project_badges/measure?project=comixed_comixed&metric=alert_status)](https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=comixed_comixed)þ * You can download the latest **unsupported** release from the **Releases** tab. Every merge to the **Develop** branch triggers a new build.þþ## Overview And GoalsþComiXed is designed to be a cross-platform digital comics manager. It will:þþ * import your existing and new digital comicsþ * organize your comics under a single directoryþ * allow you to view and edit the details of the comic þ * search your comic library by comic detailsþ * identify, and delete, duplicate pages across comicsþ * provide access to your library from a variety of applicationsþþPaired with an application that can read your comics (such asþ[Chunky Reader](http://chunkyreader.com/)) you will have a very powerfulþand useful solution for managing and reading your digital comic collection.þþ## Supported Comic FormatsþþThe following digital comic formats are supported:þþ * CBZ (ZIP)þ * CBR (RAR)þ * CB7 (7ZIP)þþ## Building The ApplicationþþFor details on building things locally, please see the [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) files.þþ## ParticipatingþþThere are two mailing lists available for getting involved in the community.þþ### UsersþþFor users of the project. please sign up for our [user list](https://www.freelists.org/list/comixed). It's whereþgeneral questions, comments and discussions around the application take place.þþYou can also go [here](https://www.freelists.org/archive/comixed) to search the archives.þþ### DevelopersþþFor contributors to the project, please sign up for our [developer list](https://www.freelists.org/list/comixed-dev).þIt's where feature, coding and bug fix discussions take place.þþYou can also go [here](https://www.freelists.org/archive/comixed-dev) to search the archives.þþ## ContributingþþWhen working on a feature or fixing a bug, please write and test your code against the *develop*þbranch. Then, when it is completed, please send a [pull request](http://help.github.com/articles/creating-a-pull-request/)þto have the code imported.þþAll code should come with unit tests.þþIf the code is in good shape, then it will be included.þþIf the code needs some fixes or changes, the developers will provide feedbackþasking for those changes. Please apply them and resubmit your changes.þþAnd, if this is your first addition to the project, please add your name toþthe [CONTRIBUTORS.md](./CONTRIBUTORS.md) file with your pull request.þþ## Creditsþþ* example.cbz - https://www.contrapositivediary.com/?p=1197þ* missing_page.png - Original found at https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Comic_image_missing.svgþ* JWT authentication code based on https://www.devglan.com/spring-security/angular-jwt-authentication

# Hello World PhoneGap Template [![bitHound Score][bithound-img]][bithound-url]þþA PhoneGap Hello World templateþþ## Usageþþ#### PhoneGap CLIþþThe hello-world template is the default when you create a new application using the [phonegap-cli][phonegap-cli-url].þþ    phonegap create my-appþþCreate an app using this template specifically:þþ    phonegap create my-app --template hello-worldþþTo see a list of other available PhoneGap templates:þþ    phonegap template listþþ## [config.xml][config-xml]þþ#### android-minSdkVersion (Android only)þþMinimum SDK version supported on the target device. Maximum version is blank by default.þþThis template sets the minimum to `14`.þþ    <preference name="android-minSdkVersion" value="14" />þþ#### <access ...> (All)þþThis template defaults to wide open access.þþ    <access origin="*" />þþIt is strongly encouraged that you restrict access to external resources in your application before releasing to production.þþFor more information on whitelist configuration, see the [Cordova Whitelist Guide][cordova-whitelist-guide] and the [Cordova Whitelist Plugin documentation][cordova-plugin-whitelist]þþ## [www/index.html][index-html]þþ#### Content Security Policy (CSP)þþThe default CSP is similarly open:þþ    <meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" content="default-src * 'unsafe-inline'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; media-src *" />þþMuch like the access tag above, you are strongly encouraged to use a more restrictive CSP in production.þþA good starting point declaration might be:þþ    <meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" content="default-src 'self' data: gap: 'unsafe-inline' https://ssl.gstatic.com; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; media-src *" />þþFor more information on the Content Security Policy, see the [section on CSP in the Cordova Whitelist Plugin documentation][cordova-plugin-whitelist-csp].þþAnother good resource for generating a good CSP declaration is [CSP is Awesome][csp-is-awesome]þþþ[phonegap-cli-url]: http://github.com/phonegap/phonegap-cliþ[cordova-app]: http://github.com/apache/cordova-app-hello-worldþ[bithound-img]: https://www.bithound.io/github/phonegap/phonegap-app-hello-world/badges/score.svgþ[bithound-url]: https://www.bithound.io/github/phonegap/phonegap-app-hello-worldþ[config-xml]: https://github.com/phonegap/phonegap-template-hello-world/blob/master/config.xmlþ[index-html]: https://github.com/phonegap/phonegap-template-hello-world/blob/master/www/index.htmlþ[cordova-whitelist-guide]: https://cordova.apache.org/docs/en/dev/guide/appdev/whitelist/index.htmlþ[cordova-plugin-whitelist]: http://cordova.apache.org/docs/en/latest/reference/cordova-plugin-whitelistþ[cordova-plugin-whitelist-csp]: http://cordova.apache.org/docs/en/latest/reference/cordova-plugin-whitelist#content-security-policyþ[csp-is-awesome]: http://cspisawesome.com

column43: þ# SilentMajorityþþ**Table of Contents** *generated with [DocToc](http://doctoc.herokuapp.com/)*þþ- [SilentMajority](#SilentMajority)þ - [Summary](#Summary)þ - [Usage](#Usage)þ - [Result](#Result)þ - [Build](#Build)þ - [Configuration](#Configuration)þ - [Simulation Types](#SimulationTypes)þ - [HighD](#HighD)þ - [BiasedV](#BiasedV)þ - [CtrlTH](#CtrlTH)þ - [Others](#Others)þ - [Other Classes](#OtherClasses)þþþ## Summaryþþ拡張LTモデルによる意見発信のシミュレーションを行うプロジェクト及びパッケージ．þþ論文のモデルと実験はSilentMajorityLTクラスが取り扱います．þモデルそのものの実装はSimulationTaskLTクラス内でなされています．þSilentMajorityLTクラスは，ExecutorServiceを起動し，ジョブ投入と集計を行うためのエントリポイントです．þþExecutorServiceはマルチスレッド化のためのものです．þもっともシミュレーション自体はすぐ終わります．ネットワーク生成・読込がボトルネックです．その部分はマルチスレッド化されていません．þ1回の実行につき，ネットワーク生成は1回行われ，その上で意見配置等をランダマイズして同条件の実験を複数回行い，平均しています．þþ実験内容・パラメータ・最大スレッド数などの必要事項は設定XMLファイルで与えます．þþEclipse上でそのまま実行するほか，実行可能Jarに固めてサーバ上で使用もできます．þþþ## Usageþþ1. conf\_template.xmlを適当に書き換えて，別名で保存し，設定ファイルとします．(例：conf\_srv.xml)þ2. Eclipseで実行するか，実行可能Jarにエクスポートして，サーバで実行します．þ - Eclipse上で使う場合，実行構成の引数欄に設定ファイル名を入力して実行して下さい．þ - サーバで実行する場合は，`$ java -jar .jar conf_srv.xml`のように入力して実行して下さい．þ3. 出力はresultsディレクトリ，ログはlogディレクトリに格納されます．þþþ### Resultþþ結果出力のうち，最も見るべき部分は，制御変数の変化に対するヴォーカルな意見割合の変化です．þこれは出力フォルダに含まれるCSVファイル（`PosNegRatio.csv`）に自動で集計され，まとめられます．þグラフ化は行っていないので，Excel等を使用して下さい．þþ個々のサブディレクトリは各制御変数における試行結果を収束まで逐一出力したもので，細かい挙動の確認が必要となった時に用います．þþntwkで始まるファイルはネットワークダンプです．鈴村研のフォローネットワークデータと同形式で出力したCSVファイルと次数分布集計ファイルからなります．þþþ### BuildþþEclipseの場合，実行可能Jarへのエクスポートを利用して下さい．通常のJarでも同じだとは思いますが，その場合必要なライブラリを-cpオプションで指定する必要があります．多分面倒です．þþビルド情報はAntビルドファイルにしておくと容易です．研究室ネットワークであれば，STR33のホームディレクトリをエクスポート先にしておけば，ビルド後即コマンド実行できて楽です．þ起動構成として`SilentMajorityLT`というクラスを選択しておいて下さい．こちらが論文内容に対応しています．þエクスポートウィザードの起動構成選択からSilentMajorityLTが選べない場合，一旦キャンセルして実行構成の画面に行き，新規実行構成を作成しておけば多分できます．þþ既存のbuild.xmlは松澤の個人フォルダに向けてエクスポートしようとするので，設定を変更して下さい．þþþ## Configurationþþ設定ファイルの構造は以下のようになっています．þþ þ þ þ Configurationþ 10þ 0þ 0.90þ 0.4þ 10þ 0.0þ 0.02þ 21þ 1000þ BAþ 10þ þ 0þ 0þ ARGþ þþ単純なXMLになっており，各KeyとそのValueでシミュレーションのパラメータを与えます．þþþ実装されている実験それぞれについてただ1つずつの制御変数があり，この制御変数に下限と刻み幅，分割数を与えることで，特定条件についてシミュレーションが走ります．þ制御変数の各値について，指定された回数（`nIter`）ずつ実験を行い，結果は平均されます．þþþ## Simulation Typesþþþ### HighDþþ高次数エージェントに少数派意見を保持させる条件の実験．simType=0þþ制御変数は，少数派意見を保持させる次数上位エージェントの比率で,[0.0,totalPosRatio]の範囲で動かせます.þþtotalPosRatioは全体に対する少数派の割合なので,制御変数とtotalPosRatioが一致した場合,全ての少数派エージェントが次数上位エージェントとなります．þþþ### BiasedVþþ初期にヴォーカルになるエージェントが少数派意見である条件の実験.simType=1þþ制御変数は,初期ヴォーカルエージェントにおける少数派意見エージェントの割合で,[0,1]の範囲で動かせます.þþþþ### CtrlTHþþ少数派意見エージェントの多数派認識に関する閾値を下げる条件の実験.simType=3þþ制御変数は,「周囲のヴォーカルエージェントのうち，自身と一致する意見の割合が多数派と認識する閾値」の分布上限の下げ幅で，［0,1］の範囲で動かせます．þþ0の時は分布上限を下げないので，閾値は0～1で一様分布し，平常条件です．1の時は少数派エージェントは全て閾値0をもつことになるので，þ自身と一致する意見が周囲に誰もいなくても，ヴォーカルになり（自身の意見が多数派であると認識し）ます．社会的影響に対し頑健である状態です．þþþ### Othersþþ論文に採用しなかった実験的なタイプが残っていますが，そのうちRelief（時間が経つとサイレントになる）はSilentMajorityLTの方には恐らく対応していません．þþSepTHは多数派の閾値を上げてみるという効果を加えたものです．þþþ## Other Classesþþ様々なクラスが含まれていますが，多くはネットワーク生成や可視化，マルチスレッド化のためのクラスです．þþまた，SilentMajority（LTでない）の方には，Independent Cascadeモデルベースのシミュレーション（松澤がM1時に試行していた旧モデル）なども含まれています．

column17: :+1: Android Fingerprint Verification SDK
column43: # FingerprintIdentifyþþThis is an expandable Android fingerprint api compatible lib, which also combine these api:þþAndroid API：minimum support for Android **6.0** [(more detail)](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/support/v4/hardware/fingerprint/FingerprintManagerCompat.html)þþSamSung SDK：minimum support for Android **4.2** [(more detail)](http://developer.samsung.com/galaxy/pass#)þþMeiZu SDK：minimum support for Android **5.1** [(more detail)](http://open-wiki.flyme.cn/index.php?title=%E6%8C%87%E7%BA%B9%E8%AF%86%E5%88%ABAPI)þþApi priority level：Android > Samsung > MeiZuþþ[中文版介绍 -- 传送门](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/blob/master/other/README_ZH.md)þþ[![](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/raw/master/other/QRCode_en.png)](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/raw/master/other/demo.apk)þþ**1. Gradle**þþ    compile 'com.wei.android.lib:fingerprintidentify:1.2.6'þþ**2. AndroidManifest**þþ    <uses-permission android:name="android.permission.USE_FINGERPRINT"/>þ    <uses-permission android:name="com.fingerprints.service.ACCESS_FINGERPRINT_MANAGER"/>þ    <uses-permission android:name="com.samsung.android.providers.context.permission.WRITE_USE_APP_FEATURE_SURVEY"/>þþ**3. FingerprintIdentify api**þþ    mFingerprintIdentify = new FingerprintIdentify(this);       // create objectþ    mFingerprintIdentify.setSupportAndroidL(true);              // support android Lþ    mFingerprintIdentify.setExceptionListener(listener);        // exception callback for developþ    mFingerprintIdentify.init();                                // initþþ    mFingerprintIdentify.isFingerprintEnable();                 // is fingerprint usableþ    mFingerprintIdentify.isHardwareEnable();                    // is hardware usableþ    mFingerprintIdentify.isRegisteredFingerprint();             // is fingerprint collectedþ    mFingerprintIdentify.startIdentify(maxTimes, listener);     // start identifyþ    mFingerprintIdentify.cancelIdentify();                      // cancel identifyþ    mFingerprintIdentify.resumeIdentify();                      // resume identifyþþ**4. startIdentify method**þþ    mFingerprintIdentify.startIdentify(3, new BaseFingerprint.IdentifyListener() {þ        @Overrideþ        public void onSucceed() {þ            // succeed, release hardware automaticallyþ        }þþ        @Overrideþ        public void onNotMatch(int availableTimes) {þ            // not match, try again automaticallyþ        }þþ        @Overrideþ        public void onFailed(boolean isDeviceLocked) {þ            // failed, release hardware automaticallyþ            // isDeviceLocked: is device locked temporarilyþ        }þþ        @Overrideþ        public void onStartFailedByDeviceLocked() {þ            // the first start failed because the device was locked temporarilyþ        }þ    });þþ**5. Proguard**þþ    -ignorewarningsþþ    # MeiZuFingerprintþ    -keep class com.fingerprints.service.** { *; }þ    þ    # SmsungFingerprintþ    -keep class com.samsung.android.sdk.** { *; }þþ**6. Notice**þþ    1. Usually, device will be locked temporarily when read incorrect fingerprints continuously 5 times.þ       And it need to takes about 30 seconds to get back to normal.þ       But it's not standardized, MeiZu SDK has no limit to this.þþ    2. About 'com.android.support:appcompat-v7:25.3.1' versionþ       The class FingerprintManagerCompatApi23 will check the feature FEATURE_FINGERPRINT from version 25.þ       More info：https://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=231939þþ    3. Some manufacturers will transplant standard fingerprint API to the deviceþ       which version less than Android M, such as OPPO.þ       But the API will be modified sometimes and cause calling crash, such as VIVO.þþ    4. We need to check the manufacturers because Meizu's sdk is available on some other devices.þþ    5. MeiZu's SDK runs abnormally on MeiLan Note3 sometimes, it can't switch to mback mode event called release。þþ**7. Version Update**þþ**v1.2.6**　`2018.12.11`　Support AndroidX android.enableJetifier=true.þþ**v1.2.5**　`2018.11.20`　minSdkVersion 21 -> 14.þþ**v1.2.4**　`2018.11.16`　cancelIdentify will not call onFailed.þþ**v1.2.3**　`2018.11.15`　Migrate to AndroidX. Support Android L. Support custom identify implementation.þþ**v1.2.1**　`2017.07.25`　Add new callback onStartFailedByDeviceLocked.þþ**v1.2.0**　`2017.07.10`　Add android M limit. Add new callback parameter to notice is that device locked temporarily。þþ**v1.1.5**　`2017.06.14`　~~FingerprintIdentify(Activity)~~ --> FingerprintIdentify(Context).þþ**v1.1.4**　`2017.05.24`　Remove android M limit, add MeiZu manufacturer verify. See [ISSUE#12](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/issues/12)þþ**v1.1.3**　`2017.05.22`　Update the method getFingerprintManager. See [ISSUE#11](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/issues/11)þþ**v1.1.2**　`2017.04.25`　Modify AOSP's code，avoid the PackageManager.FEATURE_FINGERPRINT limit.þþ**v1.1.1**　`2017.03.20`　Modify gradle AppCompat lib version.þþ**v1.1.0**　`2017.03.16`　Modify package name and bug fixed.þþ**v1.0.2**　`2017.02.17`　Add exception callback.þþ**v1.0.1**　`2017.02.15`　Bug fixed.þþ**v1.0.0**　`2017.02.10`　Release v1.þþ## License ##þþLicensed under the MIT License, see the [LICENSE](https://github.com/uccmawei/FingerprintIdentify/blob/master/LICENSE) for copying permission.

# LetItJumpþþ#Corresponding Android Repository: [https://github.com/BilalHubani/Letitjump]þþThis application was generated using JHipster 3.12.2, you can find documentation and help at [https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2](https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2).þþ## DevelopmentþþBefore you can build this project, you must install and configure the following dependencies on your machine:þ1. [Node.js][]: We use Node to run a development web server and build the project.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Node either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þþAfter installing Node, you should be able to run the following command to install development tools (likeþ[Bower][] and [BrowserSync][]). You will only need to run this command when dependencies change in package.json.þþ    npm installþþWe use [Gulp][] as our build system. Install the Gulp command-line tool globally with:þþ    npm install -g gulp-cliþþRun the following commands in two separate terminals to create a blissful development experience where your browserþauto-refreshes when files change on your hard drive.þþ    ./mvnwþ    gulpþþBower is used to manage CSS and JavaScript dependencies used in this application. You can upgrade dependencies byþspecifying a newer version in `bower.json`. You can also run `bower update` and `bower install` to manage dependencies.þAdd the `-h` flag on any command to see how you can use it. For example, `bower update -h`.þþFor further instructions on how to develop with JHipster, have a look at [Using JHipster in development][].þþ## Building for productionþþTo optimize the LetItJump application for production, run:þþ    ./mvnw -Pprod clean packageþþThis will concatenate and minify the client CSS and JavaScript files. It will also modify `index.html` so it references these new files.þTo ensure everything worked, run:þþ    java -jar target/*.warþþThen navigate to [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080) in your browser.þþRefer to [Using JHipster in production][] for more details.þþ## TestingþþTo launch your application's tests, run:þþ    ./mvnw clean testþþ### Client testsþþUnit tests are run by [Karma][] and written with [Jasmine][]. They're located in `src/test/javascript/` and can be run with:þþ    gulp testþþþþFor more information, refer to the [Running tests page][].þþ## Using Docker to simplify development (optional)þþYou can use Docker to improve your JHipster development experience. A number of docker-compose configuration are available in the `src/main/docker` folder to launch required third party services.þFor example, to start a mysql database in a docker container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml up -dþþTo stop it and remove the container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml downþþYou can also fully dockerize your application and all the services that it depends on.þTo achieve this, first build a docker image of your app by running:þþ    ./mvnw package -Pprod docker:buildþþThen run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/app.yml up -dþþFor more information refer to [Using Docker and Docker-Compose][], this page also contains information on the docker-compose sub-generator (`yo jhipster:docker-compose`), which is able to generate docker configurations for one or several JHipster applications.þþ## Continuous Integration (optional)þþTo set up a CI environment, consult the [Setting up Continuous Integration][] page.þþ[JHipster Homepage and latest documentation]: https://jhipster.github.ioþ[JHipster 3.12.2 archive]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2þþ[Using JHipster in development]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2/development/þ[Using Docker and Docker-Compose]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2/docker-composeþ[Using JHipster in production]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2/production/þ[Running tests page]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2/running-tests/þ[Setting up Continuous Integration]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v3.12.2/setting-up-ci/þþþ[Node.js]: https://nodejs.org/þ[Bower]: http://bower.io/þ[Gulp]: http://gulpjs.com/þ[BrowserSync]: http://www.browsersync.io/þ[Karma]: http://karma-runner.github.io/þ[Jasmine]: http://jasmine.github.io/2.0/introduction.htmlþ[Protractor]: https://angular.github.io/protractor/

column43: OneApi Java clientþ============================þþBasic messaging exampleþ-----------------------þþFirst initialize the messaging client using your username and password:þþ    Configuration configuration = new Configuration(USERNAME, PASSWORD);þ    SMSClient smsClient = new SMSClient(configuration);þþþAn exception will be thrown if your username and/or password are incorrect.þþPrepare the message:þþ    SMSRequest smsRequest = new SMSRequest(SENDER, MESSAGE, DESTINATION);þþþSend the message:þþ    // Store request id because we can later query for the delivery status with it:þ    SendMessageResult sendMessageResult = smsClient.getSMSMessagingClient().sendSMS(smsRequest);þþþLater you can query for the delivery status of the message:þþ    DeliveryInfoList deliveryInfoList = smsClient.getSMSMessagingClient().queryDeliveryStatus(SENDER, sendMessageResult.getClientCorrelator());þ    String deliveryStatus = deliveryInfoList.getDeliveryInfo().get(0).getDeliveryStatus();þþþPossible statuses are: **DeliveredToTerminal**, **DeliveryUncertain**, **DeliveryImpossible**, **MessageWaiting** and **DeliveredToNetwork**.þþMessaging with notification push exampleþ-----------------------þþSame as with the standard messaging example, but when preparing your message:þþ    SMSRequest smsRequest = new SMSRequest(SENDER, MESSAGE, DESTINATION);þ    // The url where the delivery notification will MESSAGE pushed:þ    smsRequest.setNotifyURL(NOTIFY_URL);þþþWhen the delivery notification is pushed to your server as a HTTP POST request, you must process the body of the message with the following code:þþ    DeliveryInfoNotification deliveryInfoNotification = smsClient.getSMSMessagingClient().convertJsonToDeliveryInfoNotification(JSON);þþSending message with language specific characters exampleþ-----------------------------------------------þþIf you want to send message with special characters, this is how you prepare your message:þþ SMSRequest smsRequest = new SMSRequest(SENDER, MESSAGE, DESTINATION);þ    // Create Language object with specific language code, use single shift table and use locking shift table for specific language as parametersþ    Language language = new Language(LanguageCode.TR, true, false);þ    // Set languageþ    smsRequest.setLanguage(language);þþCurrently supported languages (with their language codes) are: `Spanish - "SP"`, `Portuguese - "PT"`, `Turkish - "TR"`.þþþNumber Context exampleþ-----------------------þþInitialize and login the data connection client:þþ    Configuration configuration = new Configuration(USERNAME, PASSWORD);þ    SMSClient smsClient = new SMSClient(configuration);þþþRetrieve the roaming status (Number Context):þþ    Roaming roaming = smsClient.getHLRClient().queryHLR(DESTINATION);þþþNumber Context with notification push exampleþ-----------------------þþSimilar to the previous example, but this time you must set the notification url where the result will be pushed:þþ    smsClient.getHLRClient().queryHLR(DESTINATION, NOTIFY_URL);þþþWhen the roaming status notification is pushed to your server as a HTTP POST request, you must process the body of the message with the following code:þþ    RoamingNotification roamingNotification = smsClient.getHLRClient().convertJsonToHLRNotificationExample(JSON);þþþRetrieve inbound messages exampleþ-----------------------þþWith the existing sms client (see the basic messaging example to see how to start it):þþ    InboundSMSMessageList inboundSMSMessageList =  smsClient.getSMSMessagingClient().getInboundMessages();þþþInbound message push exampleþ-----------------------þþThe subscription to recive inbound messages can be set up on our site.þWhen the inbound message notification is pushed to your server as a HTTP POST request, you must process the body of the message with the following code:þþ    InboundSMSMessageList inboundSMSMessageList = smsClient.getSMSMessagingClient().convertJsonToInboundSMSMessageNotificationExample(JSON);þþþLicenseþ-------þþThis library is licensed under the [Apache License, Version 2.0](http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0)

column43: # androidþAndroid Dev

This project was bootstrapped with [Create React Native App](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app).þþBelow you'll find information about performing common tasks. The most recent version of this guide is available [here](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/react-native-scripts/template/README.md).þþ## Table of Contentsþþ* [Updating to New Releases](#updating-to-new-releases)þ* [Available Scripts](#available-scripts)þ  * [npm start](#npm-start)þ  * [npm test](#npm-test)þ  * [npm run ios](#npm-run-ios)þ  * [npm run android](#npm-run-android)þ  * [npm run eject](#npm-run-eject)þ* [Writing and Running Tests](#writing-and-running-tests)þ* [Environment Variables](#environment-variables)þ  * [Configuring Packager IP Address](#configuring-packager-ip-address)þ* [Adding Flow](#adding-flow)þ* [Customizing App Display Name and Icon](#customizing-app-display-name-and-icon)þ* [Sharing and Deployment](#sharing-and-deployment)þ  * [Publishing to Expo's React Native Community](#publishing-to-expos-react-native-community)þ  * [Building an Expo "standalone" app](#building-an-expo-standalone-app)þ  * [Ejecting from Create React Native App](#ejecting-from-create-react-native-app)þ    * [Build Dependencies (Xcode & Android Studio)](#build-dependencies-xcode-android-studio)þ    * [Should I Use ExpoKit?](#should-i-use-expokit)þ* [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)þ  * [Networking](#networking)þ  * [iOS Simulator won't open](#ios-simulator-wont-open)þ  * [QR Code does not scan](#qr-code-does-not-scan)þþ## Updating to New ReleasesþþYou should only need to update the global installation of `create-react-native-app` very rarely, ideally never.þþUpdating the `react-native-scripts` dependency of your app should be as simple as bumping the version number in `package.json` and reinstalling your project's dependencies.þþUpgrading to a new version of React Native requires updating the `react-native`, `react`, and `expo` package versions, and setting the correct `sdkVersion` in `app.json`. See the [versioning guide](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/VERSIONS.md) for up-to-date information about package version compatibility.þþ## Available ScriptsþþIf Yarn was installed when the project was initialized, then dependencies will have been installed via Yarn, and you should probably use it to run these commands as well. Unlike dependency installation, command running syntax is identical for Yarn and NPM at the time of this writing.þþ### `npm start`þþRuns your app in development mode.þþOpen it in the [Expo app](https://expo.io) on your phone to view it. It will reload if you save edits to your files, and you will see build errors and logs in the terminal.þþSometimes you may need to reset or clear the React Native packager's cache. To do so, you can pass the `--reset-cache` flag to the start script:þþ```þnpm start --reset-cacheþ# orþyarn start --reset-cacheþ```þþ#### `npm test`þþRuns the [jest](https://github.com/facebook/jest) test runner on your tests.þþ#### `npm run ios`þþLike `npm start`, but also attempts to open your app in the iOS Simulator if you're on a Mac and have it installed.þþ#### `npm run android`þþLike `npm start`, but also attempts to open your app on a connected Android device or emulator. Requires an installation of Android build tools (see [React Native docs](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html) for detailed setup). We also recommend installing Genymotion as your Android emulator. Once you've finished setting up the native build environment, there are two options for making the right copy of `adb` available to Create React Native App:þþ##### Using Android Studio's `adb`þþ1. Make sure that you can run adb from your terminal.þ2. Open Genymotion and navigate to `Settings -> ADB`. Select “Use custom Android SDK tools” and update with your [Android SDK directory](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/25176594/android-sdk-location).þþ##### Using Genymotion's `adb`þþ1. Find Genymotion’s copy of adb. On macOS for example, this is normally `/Applications/Genymotion.app/Contents/MacOS/tools/`.þ2. Add the Genymotion tools directory to your path (instructions for [Mac](http://osxdaily.com/2014/08/14/add-new-path-to-path-command-line/), [Linux](http://www.computerhope.com/issues/ch001647.htm), and [Windows](https://www.howtogeek.com/118594/how-to-edit-your-system-path-for-easy-command-line-access/)).þ3. Make sure that you can run adb from your terminal.þþ#### `npm run eject`þþThis will start the process of "ejecting" from Create React Native App's build scripts. You'll be asked a couple of questions about how you'd like to build your project.þþ**Warning:** Running eject is a permanent action (aside from whatever version control system you use). An ejected app will require you to have an [Xcode and/or Android Studio environment](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html) set up.þþ## Customizing App Display Name and IconþþYou can edit `app.json` to include [configuration keys](https://docs.expo.io/versions/latest/guides/configuration.html) under the `expo` key.þþTo change your app's display name, set the `expo.name` key in `app.json` to an appropriate string.þþTo set an app icon, set the `expo.icon` key in `app.json` to be either a local path or a URL. It's recommended that you use a 512x512 png file with transparency.þþ## Writing and Running TestsþþThis project is set up to use [jest](https://facebook.github.io/jest/) for tests. You can configure whatever testing strategy you like, but jest works out of the box. Create test files in directories called `__tests__` or with the `.test` extension to have the files loaded by jest. See the [the template project](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/react-native-scripts/template/App.test.js) for an example test. The [jest documentation](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/getting-started.html) is also a wonderful resource, as is the [React Native testing tutorial](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/tutorial-react-native.html).þþ## Environment VariablesþþYou can configure some of Create React Native App's behavior using environment variables.þþ### Configuring Packager IP AddressþþWhen starting your project, you'll see something like this for your project URL:þþ```þexp://192.168.0.2:19000þ```þþThe "manifest" at that URL tells the Expo app how to retrieve and load your app's JavaScript bundle, so even if you load it in the app via a URL like `exp://localhost:19000`, the Expo client app will still try to retrieve your app at the IP address that the start script provides.þþIn some cases, this is less than ideal. This might be the case if you need to run your project inside of a virtual machine and you have to access the packager via a different IP address than the one which prints by default. In order to override the IP address or hostname that is detected by Create React Native App, you can specify your own hostname via the `REACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME` environment variable:þþMac and Linux:þþ```þREACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME='my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname' npm startþ```þþWindows:þ```þset REACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME='my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname'þnpm startþ```þþThe above example would cause the development server to listen on `exp://my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname:19000`.þþ## Adding FlowþþFlow is a static type checker that helps you write code with fewer bugs. Check out this [introduction to using static types in JavaScript](https://medium.com/@preethikasireddy/why-use-static-types-in-javascript-part-1-8382da1e0adb) if you are new to this concept.þþReact Native works with [Flow](http://flowtype.org/) out of the box, as long as your Flow version matches the one used in the version of React Native.þþTo add a local dependency to the correct Flow version to a Create React Native App project, follow these steps:þþ1. Find the Flow `[version]` at the bottom of the included [.flowconfig](.flowconfig)þ2. Run `npm install --save-dev flow-bin@x.y.z` (or `yarn add --dev flow-bin@x.y.z`), where `x.y.z` is the .flowconfig version number.þ3. Add `"flow": "flow"` to the `scripts` section of your `package.json`.þ4. Add `// @flow` to any files you want to type check (for example, to `App.js`).þþNow you can run `npm run flow` (or `yarn flow`) to check the files for type errors.þYou can optionally use a [plugin for your IDE or editor](https://flow.org/en/docs/editors/) for a better integrated experience.þþTo learn more about Flow, check out [its documentation](https://flow.org/).þþ## Sharing and DeploymentþþCreate React Native App does a lot of work to make app setup and development simple and straightforward, but it's very difficult to do the same for deploying to Apple's App Store or Google's Play Store without relying on a hosted service.þþ### Publishing to Expo's React Native CommunityþþExpo provides free hosting for the JS-only apps created by CRNA, allowing you to share your app through the Expo client app. This requires registration for an Expo account.þþInstall the `exp` command-line tool, and run the publish command:þþ```þ$ npm i -g expþ$ exp publishþ```þþ### Building an Expo "standalone" appþþYou can also use a service like [Expo's standalone builds](https://docs.expo.io/versions/latest/guides/building-standalone-apps.html) if you want to get an IPA/APK for distribution without having to build the native code yourself.þþ### Ejecting from Create React Native AppþþIf you want to build and deploy your app yourself, you'll need to eject from CRNA and use Xcode and Android Studio.þþThis is usually as simple as running `npm run eject` in your project, which will walk you through the process. Make sure to install `react-native-cli` and follow the [native code getting started guide for React Native](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html).þþ#### Should I Use ExpoKit?þþIf you have made use of Expo APIs while working on your project, then those API calls will stop working if you eject to a regular React Native project. If you want to continue using those APIs, you can eject to "React Native + ExpoKit" which will still allow you to build your own native code and continue using the Expo APIs. See the [ejecting guide](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/EJECTING.md) for more details about this option.þþ## Troubleshootingþþ### NetworkingþþIf you're unable to load your app on your phone due to a network timeout or a refused connection, a good first step is to verify that your phone and computer are on the same network and that they can reach each other. Create React Native App needs access to ports 19000 and 19001 so ensure that your network and firewall settings allow access from your device to your computer on both of these ports.þþTry opening a web browser on your phone and opening the URL that the packager script prints, replacing `exp://` with `http://`. So, for example, if underneath the QR code in your terminal you see:þþ```þexp://192.168.0.1:19000þ```þþTry opening Safari or Chrome on your phone and loadingþþ```þhttp://192.168.0.1:19000þ```þþandþþ```þhttp://192.168.0.1:19001þ```þþIf this works, but you're still unable to load your app by scanning the QR code, please open an issue on the [Create React Native App repository](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app) with details about these steps and any other error messages you may have received.þþIf you're not able to load the `http` URL in your phone's web browser, try using the tethering/mobile hotspot feature on your phone (beware of data usage, though), connecting your computer to that WiFi network, and restarting the packager. If you are using a VPN you may need to disable it.þþ### iOS Simulator won't openþþIf you're on a Mac, there are a few errors that users sometimes see when attempting to `npm run ios`:þþ* "non-zero exit code: 107"þ* "You may need to install Xcode" but it is already installedþ* and othersþþThere are a few steps you may want to take to troubleshoot these kinds of errors:þþ1. Make sure Xcode is installed and open it to accept the license agreement if it prompts you. You can install it from the Mac App Store.þ2. Open Xcode's Preferences, the Locations tab, and make sure that the `Command Line Tools` menu option is set to something. Sometimes when the CLI tools are first installed by Homebrew this option is left blank, which can prevent Apple utilities from finding the simulator. Make sure to re-run `npm/yarn run ios` after doing so.þ3. If that doesn't work, open the Simulator, and under the app menu select `Reset Contents and Settings...`. After that has finished, quit the Simulator, and re-run `npm/yarn run ios`.þþ### QR Code does not scanþþIf you're not able to scan the QR code, make sure your phone's camera is focusing correctly, and also make sure that the contrast on the two colors in your terminal is high enough. For example, WebStorm's default themes may [not have enough contrast](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/issues/49) for terminal QR codes to be scannable with the system barcode scanners that the Expo app uses.þþIf this causes problems for you, you may want to try changing your terminal's color theme to have more contrast, or running Create React Native App from a different terminal. You can also manually enter the URL printed by the packager script in the Expo app's search bar to load it manually.þ# React-Native

[Node.js][]: We use Node to run a development web server and build the project.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Node either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þ2. [Yarn][]: We use Yarn to manage Node dependencies.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Yarn either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þþAfter installing Node, you should be able to run the following command to install development tools.þYou will only need to run this command when dependencies change in [package.json](package.json).þþ    yarn installþþWe use yarn scripts and [Webpack][] as our build system.þþþRun the following commands in two separate terminals to create a blissful development experience where your browserþauto-refreshes when files change on your hard drive.þþ    ./mvnwþ    yarn startþþ[Yarn][] is also used to manage CSS and JavaScript dependencies used in this application. You can upgrade dependencies byþspecifying a newer version in [package.json](package.json). You can also run `yarn update` and `yarn install` to manage dependencies.þAdd the `help` flag on any command to see how you can use it. For example, `yarn help update`.þþThe `yarn run` command will list all of the scripts available to run for this project.þþ### Service workersþþService workers are commented by default, to enable them please uncomment the following code.þþ* The service worker registering script in index.htmlþþ```htmlþ<script>þ    if ('serviceWorker' in navigator) {þ        navigator.serviceWorkerþ        .register('./sw.js')þ        .then(function() { console.log('Service Worker Registered'); });þ    }þ</script>þ```þþNote: workbox creates the respective service worker and dynamically generate the `sw.js`þþ### Managing dependenciesþþFor example, to add [Leaflet][] library as a runtime dependency of your application, you would run following command:þþ    yarn add --exact leafletþþTo benefit from TypeScript type definitions from [DefinitelyTyped][] repository in development, you would run following command:þþ    yarn add --dev --exact @types/leafletþþThen you would import the JS and CSS files specified in library's installation instructions so that [Webpack][] knows about them:þEdit [src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts](src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts) file:þ~~~þimport 'leaflet/dist/leaflet.js';þ~~~þþEdit [src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css](src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css) file:þ~~~þ@import '~leaflet/dist/leaflet.css';þ~~~þNote: there are still few other things remaining to do for Leaflet that we won't detail here.þþFor further instructions on how to develop with JHipster, have a look at [Using JHipster in development][].þþ### Using angular-cliþþYou can also use [Angular CLI][] to generate some custom client code.þþFor example, the following command:þþ    ng generate component my-componentþþwill generate few files:þþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.htmlþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.tsþ    update src/main/webapp/app/app.module.tsþþþ## Building for productionþþTo optimize the jhipsterSampleApplication application for production, run:þþ    ./mvnw -Pprod clean packageþþThis will concatenate and minify the client CSS and JavaScript files. It will also modify `index.html` so it references these new files.þTo ensure everything worked, run:þþ    java -jar target/*.warþþThen navigate to [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080) in your browser.þþRefer to [Using JHipster in production][] for more details.þþ## TestingþþTo launch your application's tests, run:þþ    ./mvnw clean testþþ### Client testsþþUnit tests are run by [Karma][] and written with [Jasmine][]. They're located in [src/test/javascript/](src/test/javascript/) and can be run with:þþ    yarn testþþþþFor more information, refer to the [Running tests page][].þþ## Using Docker to simplify development (optional)þþYou can use Docker to improve your JHipster development experience. A number of docker-compose configuration are available in the [src/main/docker](src/main/docker) folder to launch required third party services.þþFor example, to start a mysql database in a docker container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml up -dþþTo stop it and remove the container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml downþþYou can also fully dockerize your application and all the services that it depends on.þTo achieve this, first build a docker image of your app by running:þþ    ./mvnw verify -Pprod dockerfile:buildþþThen run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/app.yml up -dþþFor more information refer to [Using Docker and Docker-Compose][], this page also contains information on the docker-compose sub-generator (`jhipster docker-compose`), which is able to generate docker configurations for one or several JHipster applications.þþ## Continuous Integration (optional)þþTo configure CI for your project, run the ci-cd sub-generator (`jhipster ci-cd`), this will let you generate configuration files for a number of Continuous Integration systems. Consult the [Setting up Continuous Integration][] page for more information.þþ[JHipster Homepage and latest documentation]: http://www.jhipster.techþ[JHipster 4.14.3 archive]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3þþ[Using JHipster in development]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3/development/þ[Using Docker and Docker-Compose]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3/docker-composeþ[Using JHipster in production]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3/production/þ[Running tests page]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3/running-tests/þ[Setting up Continuous Integration]: http://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v4.14.3/setting-up-ci/þþUsing travis CI for Continuous integrationþþþ[Node.js]: https://nodejs.org/þ[Yarn]: https://yarnpkg.org/þ[Webpack]: https://webpack.github.io/þ[Angular CLI]: https://cli.angular.io/þ[BrowserSync]: http://www.browsersync.io/þ[Karma]: http://karma-runner.github.io/þ[Jasmine]: http://jasmine.github.io/2.0/introduction.htmlþ[Protractor]: https://angular.github.io/protractor/þ[Leaflet]: http://leafletjs.com/þ[DefinitelyTyped]: http://definitelytyped.org/
