column43: # Spring FrameworkþþThis is the home of the Spring Framework: the foundation for all [Spring projects](https://spring.io/projects). Collectively the Spring Framework and the family of Spring projects is often referred to simply as "Spring". þþSpring provides everything required beyond the Java programming language for creating enterprise applications for a wide range of scenarios and architectures. Please read the [Overview](https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/spring-framework-reference/overview.html#spring-introduction) section as reference for a more complete introduction.þþ## Code of ConductþþThis project is governed by the [Spring Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.adoc). By participating, you are expected to uphold this code of conduct. Please report unacceptable behavior to spring-code-of-conduct@pivotal.io.þþ## Access to BinariesþþFor access to artifacts or a distribution zip, see the [Spring Framework Artifacts](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/wiki/Spring-Framework-Artifacts) wiki page.þþ## DocumentationþþThe Spring Framework maintains reference documentation ([published](http://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/spring-framework-reference/) and [source](src/docs/asciidoc)), Github [wiki pages](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/wiki), and anþ[API reference](http://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/). There are also [guides and tutorials](https://spring.io/guides) across Spring projects.þþ## Build from SourceþþSee the [Build from Source](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/wiki/Build-from-Source) Wikipedia page and the [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) file.þþ## Stay in TouchþþFollow [@SpringCentral](https://twitter.com/springcentral), [@SpringFramework](https://twitter.com/springframework), and its [team members](https://twitter.com/springframework/lists/team/members) on Twitter. In-depth articles can be found at [The Spring Blog](http://spring.io/blog/), and releases are announced via our [news feed](http://spring.io/blog/category/news).þþ## LicenseþþThe Spring Framework is released under version 2.0 of the [Apache License](http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0).

column17: A small java app which reads a whole filesystem, writing it to a local db (h2) and extracting its metadata (apache tika) into a solr-index, finally allowing metadata searching/comparing files using the power of solr.
column43: file-metadata-solr-indexerþ==========================þþA small java app which reads a whole filesystem, writing it to a local db (h2) and extracting its metadata (tika) into a solr-index, finally allowing metadata searching/comparing files using the power of solr.þFeatures:þ- Allows updates to the solr-index if files on the filesystem have changed. This feature has currently trouble on  large filesystems... :(þþ**enviroment, depencies, installation, interface, usage...**þþ**Enviroment:**þThis app has only been tested on a gentoo linux x64 machine with orcale java jdk 1.8 x64 and solr 4.9.0 running on the same machine through tomcat7. þþ**Depencies:** þAt least Java 1.7þand the following libraries (this list may getting shorter due to unneeded libraries):þ(from solr 4.9.0): commons-io-2.3.jar, httpclient-4.3.1.jar, httpcore-4.3.jar, httpmime-4.3.1.jar, noggit-0.5.jar, slf4j-api-1.7.6.jar, solr-solrj-4.9.0.jar, wstx-asl-3.2.7.jar, zookeeper-3.4.6.jarþ(from h2): h2-1.4.179.jarþ(from tika): tika-app-1.5.jarþYou have to obtain these jars from external sites (apache tika, apache solr, h2)þþ**Installation:**þSetting up the app using eclispe:þThis is maybe a weird way but the only one I used to setup this app:þ- Create a new java-project in eclipse (v.432 in my case)þ- Add my three java classes (Fileadder.java, FIMcli.java, TikaMetadata.java) to the default packageþ- Set JRE System Library to JavaSE 1.7þ- Add all the .jar files from above as referenced libraries to this projectþ- Now, right click on the project inside eclipse and choose "Export" -> Java->Runnable JAR Fileþ- Launch configuration: FIMcli must be used for main, "Extract required libraries into generated jar"þþSetting up the enviroment:þThis section is not ready yet. Planned is a setup for solr on gentoo linux using tomcat. However, all configuration-files needed to setup the right solr-core for this app are included in the repo. þþ**Interface, usage:**þCommand-line based. This java app is executed and controlled through parameters from the command-line.þParameters are:þ--path "/var/data/files" þ--solrurl "http://localhost:8080/solr-example/testcore/"þExplanation: þ--path has to contain the source-path from where to read recursivly all the files þ--solrurl has to be an url to a solr-core with a special config (see solr-config in this repo)þþexample: java -jar fileindexmanager.jar --path "/var/data/Backups" --solrurl "http://localhost:8080/solr-example/testcore/"

BigBlueButtonþ=============þBigBlueButton is an open source web conferencing system for on-line learning.  We believe that every student with a web browser should have access to a high-quality on-line learning experience.  We intend to make that possible with BigBlueButton. þþBigBlueButton supports real-time sharing of slides (PDF and any document readable by OpenOffice), webcams, whiteboard, chat, voice over IP (using FreeSWITCH), and desktop. It can record and playback all content shared in a session.  The BigBlueButton project is is supported by a [community of developers] (http://www.bigbluebutton.org/support/) that care about good design and a streamlined user experience. þþThe use cases for BigBlueButton areþ  * One-to-one on-line tutoringþ  * Small group collaboration þ  * On-line classes (25 or less)þþBigBlueButton is built on the [shoulders of giants] (http://www.bigbluebutton.org/components/).þþGetting Startedþ===============þAll the core information is at the [Google Code project page] (http://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/).  Here are a few quick linksþþIf you want to see how BigBlueButton works, check out these two videosþ  * [presenter] (http://www.bigbluebutton.org/videos/)þ  * [viewer] (http://www.bigbluebutton.org/videos/)þþAfter watching the videos, if you want to immediately try out BigBlueButton, the project maintains a live [demo server] (http://demo.bigbluebutton.org) that anyone can join.  þþTo quickly get started running your own BigBlueButton serverþ  * [Install on Ubunt 10.04 64-bit] (http://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/wiki/InstallationUbuntu)þ  * [Download the BigBlueButton 0.81 Virtual Machine] (http://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/wiki/BigBlueButtonVM)þþSee also [history of project] (http://www.bigbluebutton.org/history/).þþIf you like the work we've done with BigBlueButton and would like to contribute improvemets to the project, see [Contribute to BigBlueButton] (http://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/wiki/FAQ#Contributing_to_BigBlueButton).þþLicenseþ=======þBigBlueButton is licensed under the LGPL 3.0.þþBigBlueButton and the BigBlueButton Logo are trademarks of [BigBlueButton Inc] (http://bigbluebutton.org) .

## Design Docþþ### Install PostgreSQL in DockerþþBuild an image from the Dockerfile and assign it a name.þþ```bashþdocker build -t eg_postgresql .þ```þþRun the PostgreSQL server container (in the background):þþ```bashþdocker run -d -p 5432:5432 --name pg_test eg_postgresqlþ# PORT=$(docker ps -f name=pg_test --format "{{.Ports}}" | sed -e 's/.*://' | awk -F'[->]' '{print $1}')þ```þþþ### Build Hadoop in another Dockerþþ1. Build Hadoop Development Environment Dockerþþ```bashþ# Install Dockerþ# https://docs.docker.com/docker-for-mac/install/þþ# Build Hadoop Build Environment [Docker]þ./start-build-env.shþþ# Jump into containerþdocker exec -it hadoop-dev bashþ```þþþ2. Interact with Postgres via Hadoop containerþþ```bashþpsql -h localhost -p 5432 -d docker -U dockerþ# passwordþþdocker=# CREATE TABLE cities (name            varchar(80),location        point);þdocker=# INSERT INTO cities VALUES ('San Francisco', '(-194.0, 53.0)');þdocker=# select * from cities;þþ     name      | locationþ---------------+-----------þ San Francisco | (-194,53)þ(1 row)þ```þþþ3. Build HDFS Source Code via Hadoop containerþþ```þ# Build Hadoop in DockerþUSER=$(ls /home/)þchown -R $USER /home/$USER/.m2þcd hadoop-hdfs-projectþþ# Compile HDFSþmvn clean install -DskipTestsþ# Resume buildþmvn clean install -DskipTests -rf :hadoop-hdfsþ# mvn package -Pdist -Pnative -Dtar -DskipTestsþ```þþ### Benchmarkþþ1. add hostname as an **alias** of localhost in `/etc/hosts`þþ```bashþ# set passwordþ$ sudo passwd ganglþ$ sudo passwd rootþþ$ cat /etc/hostnameþþ$ sudo vim /etc/hosts þ127.0.0.1       localhost linuxkit-025000000001þ```þþ2. change the `core_site.xml` and `hdfs_site.xml` in `$HADOOP_HOME/etc/`þþ```bashþ# check ipþ/sbin/ifconfig eth0 | grep 'inet addr' | cut -d: -f2 | awk '{print $1}'þ```þþ```bashþ# mkdir name dataþmkdir -p $HOME/hadoop/tmpþmkdir -p $HOME/hadoop/nameþmkdir -p $HOME/hadoop/dataþ```þþ```bashþ# core_site.xmlþ <configuration>þ     <property>þ         <name>fs.defaultFS</name>þ         <value>hdfs://192.168.65.3:9000</value>þ     </property>þ     þ     <property>þ         <name>hadoop.tmp.dir</name>þ         <value>/home/gangl/hadoop/tmp</value>þ     </property>þ </configuration>þ```þþ```bashþ <configuration>þ  <property>þ   <name>dfs.replication</name>þ   <value>1</value>þ  </property>þþ  <property>þ   <name>dfs.namenode.name.dir</name>þ   <value>/home/gangl/hadoop/name</value>þ  </property>þþ  <property>þ   <name>dfs.datanode.data.dir</name>þ   <value>/home/gangl/hadoop/data</value>þ  </property>þ  <property>þ    <name>dfs.namenode.fs-limits.min-block-size</name>þ    <value>10</value>þ  </property>þ  <property>þ         <name>dfs.webhdfs.enabled</name>þ         <value>true</value>þ         <description>提供web访问hdfs的权限</description>þ     </property>þ </configuration>þ```þþ3. sshþþ```bashþssh-keygen -t rsa -f ~/.ssh/id_dsa  þcat ~/.ssh/id_dsa.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys  þchmod 0600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keysþ```þþ4. start namenodeþþ```bashþcd $HADOOP_HOMEþþ# add env variables into hadoop-env.shþexport HADOOP_ROOT_LOGGER=INFO,consoleþexport HADOOP_CLASSPATH="/home/gangl/java/postgresql-42.2.5.jar:"þþ./bin/hdfs namenode -formatþ# add JAVA_HOME to sudo vim /etc/environmentþsudo vim /etc/environmentþJAVA_HOME="/usr/lib/jvm/java-1.8.0-openjdk-amd64"þþsudo vim ./etc/hadoop/hadoop-env.shþexport JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-1.8.0-openjdk-amd64þþservice ssh restartþþkill $(jps | grep '[NameNode,DataNode]' | awk '{print $1}')þ./sbin/start-dfs.shþþþIP=$(/sbin/ifconfig eth0 | grep 'inet addr' | cut -d: -f2 | awk '{print $1}')þ./bin/hadoop org.apache.hadoop.hdfs.server.namenode.NNThroughputBenchmark -fs hdfs://${IP}:9000 -op open -threads 1 -files 1 -keepResults -logLevel INFOþ```þþ### Simplify Compiling Processþþ```bashþcd ~/hadoop/hadoop-hdfs-project/hadoop-hdfs/þmvn package -Pdist -DskipTestsþþcd ..þcp  hadoop-hdfs/target/hadoop-hdfs-3.3.0-SNAPSHOT.jar ../hadoop-dist/target/hadoop-3.3.0-SNAPSHOT/share/hadoop/hdfs/þþcp  hadoop-hdfs/target/hadoop-hdfs-3.3.0-SNAPSHOT-tests.jar ../hadoop-dist/target/hadoop-3.3.0-SNAPSHOT/share/hadoop/hdfs/þ```þþ### Restartþþ```bashþcd $HADOOP_HOMEþrm -rf ~/hadoop/data/*þrm -rf ~/hadoop/name/*þrm -rf ~/hadoop/tmp/*þrm -rf logs/*þþkill $(jps | grep '[NameNode,DataNode]' | awk '{print $1}')þþþ./bin/hdfs namenode -formatþ./sbin/start-dfs.shþþ./bin/hadoop org.apache.hadoop.hdfs.server.namenode.NNThroughputBenchmark -fs hdfs://${IP}:9000 -op open -threads 1 -files 100000 -keepResults -logLevel INFOþþþ# open  *þ./bin/hadoop org.apache.hadoop.hdfs.server.namenode.NNThroughputBenchmark -fs hdfs://${IP}:9000 -op open -threads 100 -files 100 -keepResults -logLevel INFOþþ# create *þ./bin/hadoop column43: # Netty ProjectþþNetty is an asynchronous event-driven network application framework for rapid development of maintainable high performance protocol servers & clients.þþ## Linksþþ* [Web Site](http://netty.io/)þ* [Downloads](http://netty.io/downloads.html)þ* [Documentation](http://netty.io/wiki/)þ* [@netty_project](https://twitter.com/netty_project)þþ## How to buildþþFor the detailed information about building and developing Netty, please visit [the developer guide](http://netty.io/wiki/developer-guide.html).  This page only gives very basic information.þþYou require the following to build Netty:þþ* Latest stable [Oracle JDK 7](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/)þ* Latest stable [Apache Maven](http://maven.apache.org/)þ* If you are on Linux, you need [additional development packages](http://netty.io/wiki/native-transports.html) installed on your system, because you'll build the native transport.þþNote that this is build-time requirement.  JDK 5 (for 3.x) or 6 (for 4.0+) is enough to run your Netty-based application.þþ## Branches to lookþþDevelopment of all versions takes place in each branch whose name is identical to `<majorVersion>.<minorVersion>`.  For example, the development of 3.9 and 4.0 resides in [the branch '3.9'](https://github.com/netty/netty/tree/3.9) and [the branch '4.0'](https://github.com/netty/netty/tree/4.0) respectively.þþ## Usage with JDK 9þþNetty can be used in modular JDK9 applications as a collection of automatic modules. The module names follow theþreverse-DNS style, and are derived from subproject names rather than root packages due to historical reasons. Theyþare listed below:þþ * `io.netty.all`þ * `io.netty.buffer`þ * `io.netty.codec`þ * `io.netty.codec.dns`þ * `io.netty.codec.haproxy`þ * `io.netty.codec.http`þ * `io.netty.codec.http2`þ * `io.netty.codec.memcache`þ * `io.netty.codec.mqtt`þ * `io.netty.codec.redis`þ * `io.netty.codec.smtp`þ * `io.netty.codec.socks`þ * `io.netty.codec.stomp`þ * `io.netty.codec.xml`þ * `io.netty.common`þ * `io.netty.handler`þ * `io.netty.handler.proxy`þ * `io.netty.resolver`þ * `io.netty.resolver.dns`þ * `io.netty.transport`þ * `io.netty.transport.epoll` (`native` omitted - reserved keyword in Java)þ * `io.netty.transport.kqueue` (`native` omitted - reserved keyword in Java)þ * `io.netty.transport.unix.common` (`native` omitted - reserved keyword in Java)þ * `io.netty.transport.rxtx`þ * `io.netty.transport.sctp`þ * `io.netty.transport.udt`þþþþAutomatic modules do not provide any means to declare dependencies, so you need to list each used module separatelyþin your `module-info` file.

column17: Java DSL for easy testing of REST services
column43: ![REST Assured](rest-assured-logo-green.png)þþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/rest-assured/rest-assured.svg)](https://travis-ci.org/rest-assured/rest-assured)þ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/badge.svg)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/io.rest-assured/rest-assured)þ[![Javadoc](https://javadoc-badge.appspot.com/io.rest-assured/rest-assured.svg)](http://www.javadoc.io/doc/io.rest-assured/rest-assured)þþþTesting and validation of REST services in Java is harder than in dynamic languages þsuch as Ruby and Groovy. REST Assured brings the simplicity of using these þlanguages into the Java domain.þþþ## News þ* 2019-01-11: REST Assured [3.3.0](http://dl.bintray.com/johanhaleby/generic/rest-assured-3.3.0-dist.zip) is released. This release introduces better support for [de-serializing with generics](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Usage#deserialization-with-generics), [Java 9 split packages](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/GettingStarted#java-9), [ResponseValidationListeners](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Usage#failure-config) as well as bug fixes and various improvements. Please see [release notes](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/ReleaseNotes33) and [change log](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/master/changelog.txt) for more details.þ* 2018-10-19: REST Assured [3.2.0](http://dl.bintray.com/johanhaleby/generic/rest-assured-3.2.0-dist.zip) is released. This release adds support for Java 11 and OSGi. It also includes support for [Spring Webflux](https://docs.spring.io/spring/docs/current/spring-framework-reference/web-reactive.html) by using the new [spring-web-test-client](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Usage#spring-web-test-client-module) module. Please see [release notes](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/ReleaseNotes32) and [getting started guide](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/GettingStarted) for more details.þ* 2018-10-05: Johan blogs on how to configure REST Assured to log to disk instead of to the console. You can find the blog post [here](http://code.haleby.se/2018/10/05/logging-to-disk-with-rest-assured/). Also added info about this to the [FAQ](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/FAQ#4-logging-rest-assured-logs-to-disk). þþ[Older News](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/OldNews)þþþ## ExamplesþHere's an example of how to make a GET request and validate the JSON or XML response:þþ```javaþget("/lotto").then().assertThat().body("lotto.lottoId", equalTo(5));þ```þþGet and verify all winner ids:þþ```javaþget("/lotto").then().assertThat().body("lotto.winners.winnerId", hasItems(23, 54));þ```þþUsing parameters:þþ```javaþgiven().þ    param("key1", "value1").þ    param("key2", "value2").þwhen().þ    post("/somewhere").þthen().þ    body(containsString("OK"));þ```þþUsing X-Path (XML only):þþ```javaþgiven().þ    params("firstName", "John", "lastName", "Doe").þwhen().þ    post("/greetMe").þthen().þ    body(hasXPath("/greeting/firstName[text()='John']")).þ```þþNeed authentication? REST Assured provides several authentication mechanisms:þþ```javaþgiven().auth().basic(username, password).when().get("/secured").then().statusCode(200);þ```þþGetting and parsing a response body:þþ```javaþ// Example with JsonPathþString json = get("/lotto").asString()þList<String> winnderIds = from(json).get("lotto.winners.winnerId");þ    þ// Example with XmlPathþString xml = post("/shopping").andReturn().body().asString()þNode category = from(xml).get("shopping.category[0]");þ```þþREST Assured supports any HTTP method but has explicit support for *POST*, *GET*, *PUT*, *DELETE*, *OPTIONS*, *PATCH* and *HEAD* and includes specifying and validating e.g. parameters, headers, cookies and body easily.þþþ## Documentationþþ* [Getting started](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/GettingStarted)þ* [Downloads](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Downloads)þ* [Usage Guide](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Usage) (click [here](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/Usage_Legacy) for legacy documentation)þ* [Javadoc](http://www.javadoc.io/doc/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/3.3.0)þ* [Rest Assured Javadoc](http://static.javadoc.io/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/3.3.0/io/restassured/RestAssured.html)þ* [Rest AssuredMockMvc Javadoc](http://static.javadoc.io/io.rest-assured/spring-mock-mvc/3.1.1/io/restassured/module/mockmvc/RestAssuredMockMvc.html)þ* [XmlPath Javadoc](http://static.javadoc.io/io.rest-assured/xml-path/3.3.0/io/restassured/path/xml/XmlPath.html)þ* [JsonPath Javadoc](http://static.javadoc.io/io.rest-assured/json-path/3.3.0/io/restassured/path/json/JsonPath.html)þ* [Release Notes](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/ReleaseNotes)þ* [FAQ](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/wiki/FAQ)þþ## Support and discussionþJoin the mailing list at our [Google group](http://groups.google.com/group/rest-assured). þþ## Linksþ* [Change log](https://github.com/rest-assured/rest-assured/raw/master/changelog.txt)þ* REST Assured on [openhub](https://www.openhub.net/p/rest-assured)þ* [Mailing list](http://groups.google.com/group/rest-assured) for questions and support

column17: Rich Criteria API for JPA providers
column43: þþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.com/Blazebit/blaze-persistence.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.com/Blazebit/blaze-persistence)þþ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-core-impl/badge.svg)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-core-impl)þ[![Slack Status](https://blazebit.herokuapp.com/badge.svg)](https://blazebit.herokuapp.com)þþ[![Javadoc - Core](https://www.javadoc.io/badge/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-core-api.svg?label=javadoc%20-%20core-api)](http://www.javadoc.io/doc/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-core-api)þ[![Javadoc - Entity-View](https://www.javadoc.io/badge/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-entity-view-api.svg?label=javadoc%20-%20entity-view-api)](http://www.javadoc.io/doc/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-entity-view-api)þ[![Javadoc - JPA-Criteria](https://www.javadoc.io/badge/doc/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-jpa-criteria-api.svg?label=javadoc%20-%20jpa-criteria-api)](http://www.javadoc.io/doc/com.blazebit/blaze-persistence-jpa-criteria-api)þþBlaze-Persistenceþ==========þBlaze-Persistence is a rich Criteria API for JPA providers.þþWhat is it?þ===========þþBlaze-Persistence is a rich Criteria API for JPA providers that aims to be betterþthan all the other Criteria APIs available.þIt provides a fluent API for building queries and removes common restrictionsþencountered when working with JPA directly.þIt offers rich pagination support and also supports keyset pagination.þþThe Entity-View module can be used to create views for JPA entites.þYou can roughly imagine an entity view is to an entity, what a RDBMS view is to a table.þþThe JPA-Criteria module implements the Criteria API of JPA but is backed by the Blaze-Persistence Core APIþso you can get a query builder out of your CriteriaQuery objects.þþWith Spring Data or DeltaSpike Data integrations you can make use of Blaze-Persistence easily in your existing repositories.þþFeaturesþ==============þþBlaze-Persistence is not only a Criteria API that allows to build queries easier,þbut it also comes with a lot of features that are normally not supported by JPA providers.þþHere is a rough overview of new features that are introduced by Blaze-Persistence on top of the JPA modelþþ* Use CTEs and recursive CTEsþ* Use modification CTEs aka DML in CTEsþ* Make use of the RETURNING clause from DML statementsþ* Use the VALUES clause for reporting queries and soon make use of table generating functionsþ* Create queries that use SET operations like UNION, EXCEPT and INTERSECTþ* Manage entity collections via DML statements to avoid reading them in memoryþ* Define functions similar to Hibernates SQLFunction in a JPA provider agnostic wayþ* Use many built-in functions like GROUP_CONCAT, date extraction, date arithmetic and many moreþ* Easy pagination and simple API to make use of keyset paginationþþIn addition to that, Blaze-Persistence also works around some JPA provider issues in a transparent way.þþHow to use it?þ==============þþBlaze-Persistence is split up into different modules. We recommend that you define a version property in your parent pom that you can use for all artifacts. Modules are all released in one batch so you can safely increment just that property. þþ```xmlþþ 1.5.0-Alpha5þþ```þþAlternatively you can also use our BOM in the `dependencyManagement` section.þþ```xmlþþ þ þ com.blazebitþ blaze-persistence-bomþ ${blaze-persistence.version}þ pomþ importþ þ þþ```þþ## QuickstartþþIf you want a sample application with everything setup where you can poke around and try out things, just go with our archetypes!þþCore-only archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-core-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþEntity view archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-entity-view-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþSpring-Data archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-spring-data-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþSpring-Boot archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-spring-boot-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþDeltaSpike Data archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-deltaspike-data-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþJava EE archetype:þþ```bashþmvn archetype:generate "-DarchetypeGroupId=com.blazebit" "-DarchetypeArtifactId=blaze-persistence-archetype-java-ee-sample" "-DarchetypeVersion=1.5.0-Alpha5"þ```þþ## Supported Java runtimesþþAll projects are built for Java 7 except for the ones where dependencies already use Java 8 like e.g. Hibernate 5.2, Spring Data 2.0 etc.þSo you are going to need a JDK 8 for building the project.þþWe also support building the project with JDK 9 and try to keep up with newer versions.þIf you want to run your application on a Java 9 JVM you need to handle the fact that JDK 9+ doesn't export the JAXB and JTA APIs anymore.þIn fact, JDK 11 will even remove the modules so the command line flags to add modules to the classpath won't work.þþSince libraries like Hibernate and others require these APIs you need to make them available. The easiest way to get these APIs back on the classpath is to package them along with your application.þThis will also work when running on Java 8. We suggest you add the following dependencies.þþ```xmlþþ javax.xml.bindþ jaxb-apiþ 2.2.11þþþ com.sun.xml.bindþ jaxb-coreþ 2.2.11þþþ com.sun.xml.bindþ jaxb-implþ 2.2.11þþþ javax.transactionþ javax.transaction-apiþ 1.2þ þ providedþþþ javax.activationþ activationþ 1.1.1þ þ providedþþþ javax.annotationþ javax.annotation-apiþ 1.3.2þ þ providedþþ```þþThe `javax.transaction` and `javax.activation` dependencies are especially relevant for the JPA metamodel generation.þþ## Supported environments/librariesþþThe bare minimum is JPA 2.0. If you want to use the JPA Criteria API module, you will also have to add the JPA 2 compatibility module.þGenerally, we support the usage in Java EE 6+ or Spring 4+ applications.þþSee the following table for an overview of supported versions.þþModule | Minimum version | Supported versionsþ---------------------------------|--------------------------------------|--------------------þHibernate integration | Hibernate 4.2 | 4.2, 4.3, 5.0, 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.4 (not all features are available in older versions)þEclipseLink integration | EclipseLink 2.6 | 2.6 (Probably 2.4 and 2.5 work as well, but only tested against 2.6)þDataNucleus integration | DataNucleus 4.1 | 4.1, 5.0þOpenJPA integration | N/A | (Currently not usable. OpenJPA doesn't seem to be actively developed anymore and no users asked for support yet)þEntity View CDI integration | CDI 1.0 | 1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 2.0þEntity View Spring integration | Spring 4.3 | 4.3, 5.0, 5.1, 5.2þDeltaSpike Data integration | DeltaSpike 1.7 | 1.7, 1.8, 1.9þSpring Data integration | Spring Data 1.11 | 1.11, 2.0, 2.1, 2.2, 2.3þSpring Data WebMvc integration | Spring Data 1.11, Spring WebMvc 4.3 | Spring Data 1.11 - 2.3, Spring WebMvc 4.3 - 5.2þSpring Data WebFlux integration | Spring Data 2.0, Spring WebFlux 5.0 | Spring Data 2.0 - 2.3, Spring WebFlux 5.0 - 5.2þSpring HATEOAS WebMvc integration| Spring Data 2.2, Spring WebMvc 5.2 | Spring Data 2.3, Spring WebMvc 5.2, Spring HATEOAS 1.0+þJackson integration | 2.8.11 | 2.8.11+þGraphQL integration | 5.2 | 5.2+þJAX-RS integration | Any JAX-RS version | Any JAX-RS versionþQuarkus integration | 1.4.2 | 1.4+þþ## Manual setupþþFor compiling you will only need API artifacts and for the runtime you need impl and integration artifacts.þþSee the [core documentation](https://persistence.blazebit.com/documentation/core/manual/en_US/index.html#maven-setup) for the necessary dependencies needed to setupþBlaze-Persistence. If you want to use entity views, the [entity view documentation](https://persistence.blazebit.com/documentation/entity-view/manual/en_US/index.html#maven-setup) þcontains a similar setup section describing the necessary dependencies.þþDocumentationþ=========þþThe current documentation is a reference manual and is split into a reference for the [core module](https://persistence.blazebit.com/documentation/core/manual/en_US/index.html) and for the [entity-view module](https://persistence.blazebit.com/documentation/entity-view/manual/en_US/index.html).þAt some point we might introduce topical documentation, but for now you can find articles on the [Blazebit Blog](https://blazebit.com/blog.html)þþCore quick-startþ=================þþFirst you need to create a `CriteriaBuilderFactory` which is the entry point to the core api. þþ```javaþCriteriaBuilderConfiguration config = Criteria.getDefault();þ// optionally, perform dynamic configurationþCriteriaBuilderFactory cbf = config.createCriteriaBuilderFactory(entityManagerFactory);þ```þþNOTE: The `CriteriaBuilderFactory` should have the same scope as your `EntityManagerFactory` as it is bound to it.þþFor demonstration purposes, we will use the following simple entity model.þþ```javaþ@Entityþpublic class Cat {þ @Idþ private Integer id;þ private String name;þ @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)þ private Cat father;þ @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)þ private Cat mother;þ @OneToManyþ private Set kittens;þ // Getter and setters omitted for brevityþ}þ```þþIf you want to select all cats and fetch their kittens as well as their father you do the following.þþ```javaþcbf.create(em, Cat.class).fetch("kittens.father").getResultList();þ```þþThis will create quite a query behind the scenes:þþ```sqlþSELECT cat FROM Cat cat LEFT JOIN FETCH cat.kittens kittens_1 LEFT JOIN FETCH kittens_1.father father_1þ```þþAn additional bonus is that the paths and generally every expression you write will get checked against the metamodel so you can spot typos very early.þþJPA Criteria API quick-startþ=================þþBlaze-Persistence provides an implementation of the JPA Criteria API what allows you to mostly code against the standard JPA Criteria API,þbut still be able to use the advanced features Blaze-Persistence provides.þþAll you need is a `CriteriaBuilderFactory` and when constructing the actual query, an `EntityManager`.þþ```javaþ// This is a subclass of the JPA CriteriaBuilder interfaceþBlazeCriteriaBuilder cb = BlazeCriteria.get(criteriaBuilderFactory);þ// A subclass of the JPA CriteriaQuery interfaceþBlazeCriteriaQuery query = cb.createQuery(Cat.class);þþ// Do your JPA Criteria query logic with cb and queryþRoot root = query.from(Cat.class);þquery.where(cb.equal(root.get(Cat_.name), "Felix"));þþ// Finally, transform the BlazeCriteriaQuery to the Blaze-Persistence Core CriteriaBuilderþCriteriaBuilder builder = query.createCriteriaBuilder(entityManager);þ// From here on, you can use all the power of the Blaze-Persistence Core APIþþ// And finally fetch the resultþList resultList = builder.getResultList();þ```þþThis will create a query that looks just about what you would expect:þþ```sqlþSELECT cat FROM Cat cat WHERE cat.name = :param_0þ```þþThis alone is not very spectacular. The interesting part is that you can use the Blaze-Persistence `CriteriaBuilder` then to do your advanced SQL thingsþor consume your result as entity views as explained in the next part. þþEntity-view usageþ=================þþEvery project has some kind of DTOs and implementing these properly isn't easy. Based on the super quick-start model we will show how entity views come to the rescue!þþTo make use of entity views, you will need a `EntityViewManager` with entity view classes registered. In a CDI environment you can inject a `EntityViewConfiguration` that has all discoverable entity view classes registered, but in a normal Java application you will have to register the classes yourself like this:þþ```javaþEntityViewConfiguration config = EntityViews.createDefaultConfiguration();þconfig.addEntityView(CatView.class);þEntityViewManager evm = config.createEntityViewManager(criteriaBuilderFactory);þ```þþNOTE: The `EntityViewManager` should have the same scope as your `EntityManagerFactory` and `CriteriaBuilderFactory` as it is bound to it.þþAn entity view itself is a simple interface or abstract class describing the structure of the projection that you want. It is very similar to defining an entity class with the difference that it is based on the entity model instead of the DBMS model.þþ```javaþ@EntityView(Cat.class)þpublic interface CatView {þ @IdMappingþ public Integer getId();þþ @Mapping("CONCAT(mother.name, 's kitty ', name)")þ public String getCuteName();þþ public SimpleCatView getFather();þþ}þ```þþ```javaþ@EntityView(Cat.class)þpublic interface SimpleCatView {þ @IdMappingþ public Integer getId();þþ public String getName();þþ}þ```þþThe `CatView` has a property `cuteName` which will be computed by the JPQL expression `CONCAT(mother.name, 's kitty ', name)` and a subview for `father`. Note that although not required in this particular case,þevery entity view for an entity type should have an id mapping if possible. Entity views without an id mapping will by default have equals and hashCode implementations that consider all attributes, whereas with an id mapping, only the id is considered.þThe `SimpleCatView` is the projection which is used for the `father` relation and only consists of the `id` and the `name` of the `Cat`.þþYou just created two DTO interfaces that contain projection information. Now the interesting part is that entity views can be applied on any query, so you can define a base query and then create the projection like this:þþ```javaþCriteriaBuilder cb = criteriaBuilderFactory.create(entityManager, Cat.class);þcb.whereOr()þ .where("father").isNull()þ .where("father.name").like().value("Darth%").noEscape()þ.endOr();þCriteriaBuilder catViewBuilder = evm.applySetting(EntityViewSetting.create(CatView.class), cb);þList catViews = catViewBuilder.getResultList();þ```þþThis will behind the scenes execute the following optimized query and transparently build your entity view objects based on the results.þþ```sqlþSELECTþ cat.id,þ CONCAT(mother_1.name, 's kitty ', cat.name),þ father_1.id,þ father_1.nameþFROM Cat catþLEFT JOIN cat.father father_1þLEFT JOIN cat.mother mother_1þWHERE father_1 IS NULLþ OR father_1.name LIKE :param_0þ```þþSee the left joins created for relations used in the projection? These are implicit joins which are by default what we call "model-aware". If you specified that a relation is `optional = false`, we would generate an inner join instead.þThis is different from how JPQL path expressions are normally interpreted, but in case of projections like in entity views, this is just what you would expect!þYou can always override the join type of implicit joins with `joinDefault` if you like.þþQuestions or issuesþ===================þþDrop by on [![Slack Status](https://blazebit.herokuapp.com/badge.svg)](https://blazebit.herokuapp.com) and ask questions any time or just create an issue on [GitHub](https://github.com/Blazebit/blaze-persistence/issues/new) or ask on [Stackoverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/ask?tags=java+blaze-persistence).þþSetup local developmentþ=======================þþHere some notes about setting up a local environment for testing.þþ## Setup general build environmentþþAlthough Blaze-Persistence still supports running on Java 7, the build must be run with at least JDK 8.þWhen doing a release at least a JDK 9 is required as we need to build some Multi-Release or MR JARs.þSince we try to support the latest JDK versions as well, we require developers that want to build the project with JDK 11+ to define a system property for a release build.þþThe system property `jdk8.home` should be set to the path to a Java 7 or 8 installation that contains either `jre/lib/rt.jar` or `jre/lib/classes.jar`.þThis property is necessary when using JDK 11+ because `sun.misc.Unsafe.defineClass` was removed.þþ## Building the website and documentationþþYou have to install [GraphViz](http://www.graphviz.org/Download.php) and make it available in your PATH.þþAfter that, it's easiest to just invoke `./serve-website.sh` which builds the documentation, website and starts an embedded server to serve at port 8820.þþ## Checkstyle in IntelliJþþ1. Build the whole thing with `mvn clean install` once to have the checkstyle-rules jar in your M2 repositoryþ2. Install the CheckStyle-IDEA Pluginþ3. After a restart, go to Settings > Other Settings > Checkstyleþ4. Add a _Third party check_ that points to the _checkstyle-rules.jar_ of your M2 repositoryþ5. Add a configuration file named *Blaze-Persistence Checkstyle rules* pointing to `checkstyle-rules/src/main/resources/blaze-persistence/checkstyle-config.xml`þ6. Use `target/checkstyle.cache` for the property `checkstyle.cache.file`þþNow you should be able to select *Blaze-Persistence Checkstyle rules* in the dropdown of the CheckStyle window. +þClick on *Check project* and checkstyle will run once for the whole project, then it should do some work incrementally.þþ## Testing a JPA provider and DBMS combinationþþBy default, a Maven build `mvn clean install` will test against H2 and Hibernate 5.2 but you can activate different profiles to test other combinations.þTo test a specific combination, you need to activate at least 4 profilesþþ* One of the JPA provider profilesþ * `hibernate-5.4`þ * `hibernate-5.3`þ * `hibernate-5.2`þ * `hibernate-5.1`þ * `hibernate-5.0`þ * `hibernate-4.3`þ * `hibernate`þ * `eclipselink`þ * `datanucleus-5.1`þ * `datanucleus-5`þ * `datanucleus-4`þ * `openjpa`þ* A DBMS profileþ * `h2`þ * `postgresql`þ * `mysql`þ * `mysql8`þ * `oracle`þ * `db2`þ * `mssql`þ * `firebird`þ * `sqllite`þ* A Spring data profileþ * `spring-data-2.3.x`þ * `spring-data-2.2.x`þ * `spring-data-2.1.x`þ * `spring-data-2.0.x`þ * `spring-data-1.11.x`þ* A DeltaSpike profileþ * `deltaspike-1.7`þ * `deltaspike-1.8`þ * `deltaspike-1.9`þþThe default DBMS connection infos are defined via Maven properties, so you can override them in a build by passing the properties as system properties.þþ* `jdbc.url`þ* `jdbc.user`þ* `jdbc.password`þ* `jdbc.driver`þþThe values are defined in e.g. `core/testsuite/pom.xml` in the respective DBMS profiles.þþ## Switching JPA provider profiles in IntelliJþþWhen switching between Hibernate and other JPA provider profiles, IntelliJ does not unmark the `basic` or `hibernate` source directories in *core/testsuite*.þIf you encounter errors like _duplicate class file found_ or something alike, make sure thatþþ* With a Hibernate profile you unmark the *core/testsuite/src/main/basic* directory as source rootþ* With a non-Hibernate profile you unmark the *core/testsuite/src/main/hibernate* and *core/testsuite/src/test/hibernate* directory as source rootþþUnmarking as source root can be done by right clicking on the source directory, going to the submenu _Mark directory as_ and finally clicking _Unmark as Sources Root_.þþ## Using DataNucleus profiles in IntelliJþþDataNucleus requires bytecode enhancement to work properly which requires an extra step to be able to do testing within IntelliJ.þUsually when switching the JPA provider profile, it is recommended to trigger a _Rebuild Project_ action in IntelliJ to avoid strange errors causes by previous bytecode enhancement runs.þAfter that, the entities in the project *core/testsuite* have to be enhanced. This is done through a Maven command.þþ* DataNucleus 4: `mvn -P "datanucleus-4,h2,deltaspike-1.8,spring-data-2.0.x,eclipselink" -pl core/testsuite,integration/spring-data/testsuite datanucleus:enhance`þ* DataNucleus 5: `mvn -P "datanucleus-5,h2,deltaspike-1.8,spring-data-2.0.x,eclipselink" -pl core/testsuite,integration/spring-data/testsuite datanucleus:enhance`þ* DataNucleus 5.1: `mvn -P "datanucleus-5.1,h2,deltaspike-1.8,spring-data-2.0.x,eclipselink" -pl core/testsuite,integration/spring-data/testsuite datanucleus:enhance`þþAfter doing that, you should be able to execute any test in IntelliJ.þþNote that if you make changes to an entity class or add a new entity class you might need to redo the rebuild and enhancement. þþ## MySQLþþWhen using the MySQL docker container via `docker_db.sh mysql_5_7` or `docker_db.sh mysql_8_0` you might want to specify the following properties when executing tests `-Djdbc.url=jdbc:mysql://192.168.99.100:3306/test?useUnicode=true&characterEncoding=utf8`þþ## FirebirdþþWhen installing the 3.x version, you also need a 3.x JDBC driver.þAdditionally you should add the following to the firebird.confþþ```þWireCrypt = Enabledþ```þþAfter creating the DB with `create database 'localhost:test' user 'sysdba' password 'sysdba';`, you can connect with JDBC with `jdbc:firebirdsql:localhost:test?charSet=utf-8`þþ## OracleþþWhen setting up Oracle locally, keep in mind that when you connect to it, you have to set the NLS_SORT to BINARY.þSince the JDBC driver derives values from the locale settings of the JVM, you should set the default locale settings to en_US.þIn IntelliJ when defining the Oracle database, go to the Advanced tab an specify the JVM options `-Duser.country=us -Duser.language=en`. þþWhen using the Oracle docker container via `docker_db.sh oracle` you might want to specify the following properties when executing tests `-Djdbc.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@192.168.99.100:1521/xe -Djdbc.user=SYSTEM -Djdbc.password=oracle`þþ### JDBC DriverþþYou have to install the JDBC driver manually. If you install Oracle XE locally, you can take it from $ORACLE_HOME/jdbc otherwise download it from http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/features/jdbc/index-091264.htmlþCopy the jar to $M2_HOME/com/oracle/ojdbc14/10.2.0.4.0/ojdbc14-10.2.0.4.0.jar and you should be good to go.þþIf you use the docker container, extract the jdbc driver from the container via `docker cp oracle:/u01/app/oracle/product/11.2.0/xe/jdbc/lib/ojdbc6.jar ojdbc.jar`þþ`mvn -q install:install-file -Dfile=ojdbc.jar -DgroupId=com.oracle -DartifactId=ojdbc14 -Dversion=10.2.0.4.0 -Dpackaging=jar -DgeneratePom=true`þþ### Install Oracle locallyþþDownload Oracle XE from http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/database-technologies/express-edition/downloads/index.htmlþDuring installation use the password "oracle" which is also the default password for the docker image.þþ## DB2þþWhen using the DB2 docker container via `docker_db.sh db2` you might want to specify the following properties when executing tests `-Djdbc.url=jdbc:db2://192.168.99.100:50000/test -Djdbc.user=db2inst1 -Djdbc.password=db2inst1-pwd`þþ### JDBC DriverþþYou have to install the JDBC driver manually. If you install DB2 Express locally, you can take it from $DB2_HOME/sqllib/java otherwise download it from http://www-01.ibm.com/support/docview.wss?uid=swg21363866þþWhen using the docker container, you can find in the copy script to extract the JDBC driver from the container in `docker_db.sh`.þInstall via the following commands.þþ`mvn -q install:install-file -Dfile=db2jcc4.jar -DgroupId=com.ibm.db2 -DartifactId=db2jcc4 -Dversion=9.7 -Dpackaging=jar -DgeneratePom=true`þþ`mvn -q install:install-file -Dfile=db2jcc_license_cu.jar -DgroupId=com.ibm.db2 -DartifactId=db2jcc_license_cu -Dversion=9.7 -Dpackaging=jar -DgeneratePom=true`þþ## SQL ServerþþWhen using the DB2 docker container via `docker_db.sh mssql` you might want to specify the following properties when executing tests `-Djdbc.url=jdbc:sqlserver://192.168.99.100:1433`þþ### JDBC DriverþþSince the JDBC driver is officially available in Maven central, you don't have to separately install it.þþ## GraalVM for native images with QuarkusþþThe general setup required for building native images with GraalVM is described in https://quarkus.io/guides/building-native-image.þþ* Install GraalVM 20.0.0 and make sure you install the native-image tool and set `GRAALVM_HOME` environment variableþ* Install required packages for a C development environmentþ * Under Windows, install [Visual Studio 2017 Visual C++ Build Tools](https://aka.ms/vs/15/release/vs_buildtools.exe)þþFor example, run the following maven build to execute native image tests for H2:þþ```þmvn -pl examples/quarkus/testsuite/native/h2 -am integration-test -Ph2 -Pnativeþ```þþUnder Windows, make sure you run maven builds that use native image from the VS2017 native tools command line.þþ## Website deploymentþþYou can use `build-deploy-website.sh` to deploy to the target environment but need to configure in ~/.m2/settings.xml the following servers.þþId: staging-persistence.blazebit.comþUser/Password: user/****þþId: persistence.blazebit.comþUser/Password: user/****þþLicensingþ=========þþThis distribution, as a whole, is licensed under the terms of the ApacheþLicense, Version 2.0 (see LICENSE.txt).þþReferencesþ==========þþProject Site: https://persistence.blazebit.com
androidþ=======

column17: Control System Studio is an Eclipse-based collections of tools to monitor and operate large scale control systems, such as the ones in the accelerator community.
column43: # cs-studio [![Build Status](https://travis-ci.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio) [![CII Best Practices](https://bestpractices.coreinfrastructure.org/projects/541/badge)](https://bestpractices.coreinfrastructure.org/projects/541)þþControl System Studio is a collections of tools to monitor and operate large scale control systems, such as the ones in the accelerator community.þþThis repository is for the original, Eclipse-based implementation of CS-Studio.þA newer development provides most of the key CS-Studio componentsþwithout any Eclipse dependencies, see https://github.com/shroffk/phoebusþIt generally offers faster startup, and also dramatically simplifies theþbuild process.þþþ* [Webpage](http://controlsystemstudio.github.io/) - general informationþ* [Github wiki](https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio/wiki/) - notes for developersþ* [Tech-talk](http://aps.anl.gov/epics/tech-talk/index.php) (the EPICS mailing list) - for user queries and discussionþ* [Download page](http://controlsystemstudio.org/download.html)þþ### How to contributeþþUser feedback, feature requests and code contributions are all welcome.þþTo get started, see the following Wiki pages:þþ* [How to contribute](https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio/wiki/HowToContribute)þ* [Coding guidelines](https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio/wiki/CodingGuidelines)þþþ### Building CS-StudioþþThis repository contains all the code for building CS-Studio. However, there is a two-stepþbuild process.þþ```þ# Build maven-osgi-bundles to ensure all bundles are available for Tycho resolution.þmvn -f maven-osgi-bundles/pom.xml clean verifyþ# Build everything else.þmvn clean verify -Dcsstudio.composite.repo=$(pwd)/p2repoþ```þþYou can use `-DskipTests=true` to speed up the build process.

column17: Display PDF in a HTML file using images and JavaScript
column43: /************** License stuff **************/þI have used Apache License v2.0, so the same license probably apply.þþþþþþ/************** About the code **************/þThere is two parts in this project.þþ1/ The first one is the back end processing. It's done with Java, takes a PDF and do two things:þ- Extract all the words with their position and save it in a .txt file with a JSON format.þ- Convert the background (PDF without the text) in images with ImageMagick (because it's faster than with PDFBox).þþIt's almost the original source code.þThis project used to crawl through directories, find pdf and convert them and save the publications converted in a MySQL database. I have removed all the code related to this. I have removed all the unuse classes (things I tried). If you are interested in, just mail me (it's free).þþI'm saving everything in a file, but it would be better to store it in a proper database.þForget about saving it in a MySQL database with one word per entry, your database won't scale.þþþþ2/ The second part is the interface. I have rewrote the core of the interface to display the images and let the user make selection.þCompare to the original version, the tree of HTML element is better balanced, the user experience is slightly better (I have spotted some bugs that I have corrected) and the sources are way more clean.þThere is just the core, so it's easier if you want to adapt it. I have remove all the things like export to the clipboard, add comments etc. If you are interested in the old sources, again mail me (it's free).þþþþ/************** To come **************/þI plan to fork this project and try something more scalable.þThe idea is to to convert PDF files on the fly. For that I plan to use something like Node.js, and convert one page at a time. One of the reason I have rewrote the interface is that it's going to be easier to do it now.þþIf you are interested/need it, contact me, it could be interesting.þþþ/************** Contact **************/þMichel Tuþorphee@gmail.comþhttp://www.neumino.com

column17: Zero后端重置框架：http://www.vertxup.cn
column43: # Zero Epic Fabricþþ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/cn.vertxup/vertx-zero/badge.svg?style=plastic)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/cn.vertxup/vertx-zero/)  [![Apache License 2](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-ASF2-blue.svg)](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.txt)  [![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/silentbalanceyh/vertx-zero.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/silentbalanceyh/vertx-zero) [![Gitter](https://badges.gitter.im/Join Chat.svg)](https://gitter.im/vertx-up/Lobby) þþThis project is based on Vert.x, the idea came from Spring-Boot framework. It could help developers focus on business requirements instead of more details of Vert.x. The project contains two parts "Up" and "Zero". "Up" means running up, "Zero" means no more workload for high producation, you could run your project with default configuration only.þþMicro Service architecture is a future focused method to design and build mature system and help more companies to implement project faster, based on this idea, `Zero Framework` came out. It's micro-service oriented framework and will be verified by real projects. Also it provide a tool set to help developers to do correct things. Now there are two enterprise application cases those are implemented by `Zero`, although the number is small, but the cases could verify that `Zero` can be used in production environment instead of tool, demo or good looks. þþThis framework contains four sub-projects, all these projects are located under `vertx-gaia` sub-project. þþ* `vertx-gaia/vertx-co`: Core Library of Zero Frameworkþ* `vertx-gaia/vertx-tp`: Third part integration components in Zero Frameworkþ* `vertx-gaia/vertx-ifx`：Useful plug-ins that could be supported in Zero Framework with **Infix Structure**þ* `vertx-gaia/vertx-up`: Zero Up Engine with nested vert.x web containerþ* `vertx-gaia/vertx-rx`: Zero Up Engine with nested rxjava web container instead of web container ( Experimental Version for future ) þ* `vertx-import`: Zero Usage dependency project to perform development, provide uniform dependency for your projects.þþIn latest version, examples have been moved to [https://github.com/silentbalanceyh/vertx-zero-example](https://github.com/silentbalanceyh/vertx-zero-example)þþ* `vertx-zeus/*`: Zero Examples, it contains all the code tutorials of this frameworkþþ> If your wan't to study vert.x development skill, you can refer chinese tutorial:[《Vert.x逐陆记》](https://silentbalanceyh.gitbooks.io/vert-x/content/). ( In Progress )þþ![](doc/image/zero-up.png)þþ## 0. Features þþIn 2019, Zero Framework has been re-factor to new version `0.5.x` and here I provide the feature list to let developers know more details in Zero Framework: [Feature List](FEATURES.md). þþ## 1. Documentationþþ### 1.1. Official Documentþþ* You can refer the link to see documents of Zero Framework: [Offical Document](DOCUMENT.md)þ* For all module api documents you can refere [Api Document](DOCUMENT-API.md)þþ### 1.2. Relatedþþ* You can refer [Zero UI](http://www.vertxui.cn) to visit front-end framework, it runs 3 production cases ( CN ).þ* You can refer [Spring Up](http://www.spring-up.cn) to visit spring framework bridged component ( Experimental Version ), it runs one production cases ( CN ).þ* You can refer [Origin X](http://www.origin-x.cn) to visit knowledge management of all documents, it act as entry of documentation ( CN ).þþ## 2. Envrionmentþþ### 2.1. Configuration in pom.xmlþþIf you want to use Zero framework, you can add following dependency into you `pom.xml` to use Zero:þþ```xmlþ    <parent>þ        <artifactId>vertx-import</artifactId>þ        <groupId>cn.vertxup</groupId>þ        <version>0.5.2</version>þ    </parent>þ```þþ### 2.2. Start UpþþIn your project, you can provide main entry only as following to run Zero \( Annotated with `@Up` \) .þþ```javaþimport io.vertx.up.VertxApplication;þimport io.vertx.up.annotations.Up;þþ@Upþpublic class Driver {þþ    public static void main(final String[] args) {þ        VertxApplication.run(Driver.class);þ    }þ}þ```þþOnce the Zero is up, you can see following logs in your console \( The default port is `6083` \):þþ```þ[ ZERO ] ZeroHttpAgent Http Server has been started successfully. \þ    Endpoint: http://0.0.0.0:6083/þ```þþ### 2.3. Tipsþþ#### 2.3.1. Data SpecificationþþIn zero framework, we designed uniform data specification as following response data format for business usage:þþ```jsonþ{þ    "data": þ}þ```þþAfter `0.5.2`, it could support freedom data format response as you wanted such as:þþ```shellþHello Worldþ1þ...þ```þþIf you want to switch to freedom mode, you can set the configuration in `vertx.yml` file:þþ```yamlþzero:þ    freedom: true     # The default value of `freedom` is false.þ```þþ#### 2.3.2. Logging in ZeroþþYou can use following function in your coding to get Logger component instead of `log4j` because we have re-designed the detail implementation of logging system.þþ```javaþ// Zero Logger initialized, connect to vert.x logging system directly but uniform managed by zero.þimport io.vertx.up.log.Annal;þþ// Then in your classþpublic final class Statute {þþ    private static final Annal LOGGER = Annal.get(Statute.class);þ    ......þ}þ```þþ## 3. Other Informationþþ### 3.1. Case Actionsþþ1. TLK Video Mobile System ( 0.4.6 )þ2. Micro Hotel Platformþ3. CMDB/ITSM Platformþþ### 3.2. WeChat GroupþþYou can send request to group leader: `445191171` to contact with the author team of zero.þþ![](./_image/2020-04-10/2020-04-18-11-26-20.jpg)þþFor china people, because of network limitation, you can join `BearyChat` with below:þþ[![](./_image/2020-04-10/char-4.png)](https://vertx-zero.bearychat.com/signup/f453ec0b240b5eadcafb54f9303b16a6?inviter_id==bwUDB)þþ## DESIGNED IN CHINA
