All other trademarks are the property of their respective owners.þþ-->þ# Sonatype Nexus Repository Open Source Codebase þþ[![CircleCI Build Status](https://circleci.com/gh/sonatype/nexus-public.svg?style=shield "CircleCI Build Status")](https://circleci.com/gh/sonatype/nexus-public) [![Join the chat at https://gitter.im/sonatype/nexus-developers](https://badges.gitter.im/sonatype/nexus-developers.svg)](https://gitter.im/sonatype/nexus-developers?utm_source=badge&utm_medium=badge&utm_campaign=pr-badge&utm_content=badge)þþ## Downloadable Bundlesþþ See: https://www.sonatype.com/download-oss-sonatypeþ þ## Requirementsþþ* Apache Maven 3.3.3+þ* Java 8þ* Network access to https://repository.sonatype.org/content/groups/sonatype-public-gridþþ## BuildingþþTo build the project and generate the template assembly use the included Maven wrapper:þþ    ./mvnw clean installþþ## RunningþþTo run Nexus Repository, after building, unzip the assembly and start the server:þþ    unzip -d target assemblies/nexus-base-template/target/nexus-base-template-*.zipþ    ./target/nexus-base-template-*/bin/nexus consoleþþThe `nexus-base-template` assembly is used as the basis for the official Sonatype Nexus distributions.þþ## LicenseþþThis project is licensed under the Eclipse Public License - v 1.0, you can read the full text [here](LICENSE.txt)þþ## Getting helpþþLooking to contribute to our code but need some help? There's a few ways to get information or our attention:þþ* File an issue in [our public JIRA](https://issues.sonatype.org/browse/NEXUS)þ* Check out the [Nexus3](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/nexus3) tag on Stack Overflowþ* Check out the [Nexus Repository User List](https://groups.google.com/a/glists.sonatype.com/forum/?hl=en#!forum/nexus-users)þ* Connect with [@sonatypeDev](https://twitter.com/sonatypeDev) on Twitter

column17: A practice repo of basic physics for testing Maven, Travis CI, JUnit, SpotBugs, and Codecov.
column43: # newtonian-gravity [![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/naharrison/newtonian-gravity.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/naharrison/newtonian-gravity) [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/naharrison/newtonian-gravity/branch/master/graph/badge.svg)](https://codecov.io/gh/naharrison/newtonian-gravity)þA practice repo of basic physics for testing Maven, Travis CI, JUnit, SpotBugs, and code coverage tools.þþ## ExampleþBuild, test, and debug with:þ```tcshþ./build-test-debug.cshþ```þThen run:þ```tcshþ./example1.cshþ```þ

# Syndesis QEþþ##### Table of Contentsþþ* [Structure](#structure)þ* [Prerequisites](#prerequisites)þ* [Scenarios](#scenarios)þ* [Configuration](#configuration)þ* [Execution](#execution)þ  * [Most common problems](#most-common-problems)þ* [Contributing](#contributing)þ  * [Checkstyle](#checkstyle)þ  * [Creating a Pull Request](#creating-a-pull-request)þ* [Advanced debugging](#advanced-debugging)þ* [List of scenarios](#list-of-scenarios)þþ### Structureþþ```bashþ├── checkstyleþ├── dockerþ├── docsþ├── endpointsþ├── hooksþ├── operator-testsþ├── rest-commonþ├── rest-testsþ├── ui-commonþ├── ui-testsþ├── upgrade-testsþ├── utilitiesþ└── validationþ```þ#### checkstyleþContains checkstyle configuration used in this project and intellij settings for this configuration.þþ#### dockerþDockerfile for containerized test suite that is capable of running the test suite in a docker container.þþ#### docsþOn-going initiative to provide comprehensive guide to current code structure.þContains a script `generateDocs.py` which produces list of all defined steps in this project and a link to their definition.þþ#### endpointsþCollection of syndesis endpoints used in the test suite.þþ#### hooksþGit hooks that can should be used.þþ#### operator-testsþCucumber scenarios for operator tests.þþ#### rest-commonþCollection of gherkin steps that are shared between all rest-based tests.þþ#### rest-testsþJava based tests that use Cucumber scenarios.þTest actions are executed directly to `syndesis-server` backend.þþ#### ui-commonþGherkin steps shared between all ui tests.þþ#### ui-testsþJava based tests that use Selenide and Cucumber BDD scenarios.þTest actions are mainly UI driven with additional 3rd party validation like Salesforce, Twitter etc.þþ#### upgrade-testsþCucumber scenarios for upgrade tests.þþ#### utilitiesþUtility classes.þþ#### validationþGherkin steps for validating expected output in the tests.þþ### Prerequisites:þ- OpenShift cluster with at least 1 admin and 1 regular userþþ- Cloned [Syndesis](https://github.com/syndesisio/syndesis)þþ- Cloned this repo with [syndesis-extension](https://github.com/syndesisio/syndesis) submodule (*git clone --recurse-submodules*)þþ- Correctly set test.properties and credentials.json (described later) þþ- Syndesis with test support endpoint enabled or sudoless docker access (either by being in the `docker` group or using `podman` instead) to install Syndesis with `deploy` profileþþThere are some dependencies that are not publicly available and require a special maven repository in maven settings. These are disabled by default and will cause some tests to fail. You can enable them with `-DallDeps` system property.þþBefore you import maven project to the IDE, you have to installþ**Lombok** andþ**Cucumber** plugins to your IDE.þþFor IntelliJ Idea you can use these plugins:þþ- [Lombok](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/6317-lombok-plugin)þ- [Cucumber](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/7212-cucumber-for-java)þþFor more information ask `mcada@redhat.com` or `avano@redhat.com` or `tplevko@redhat.com`þþ#### Make static route availableþIf you wish to run OAuth tests, we are using a static route for all oauth callbacks, so you will need to make it accessible, for example adding following entries to your /etc/hosts file:þ```þ<OpenShift cluster IP> syndesis.my-minishift.syndesis.ioþ<OpenShift cluster IP> todo-syndesis.my-minishift.syndesis.ioþ```þþDue to --route option when installing syndesis and updated /etc/hosts file we don'tþhave to update all third party applications and their callbacks for every minishift/openshift IP.þþ#### Adding users to openshift clustersþIf you are using minishift, you can use following commands to create an admin user:þ```þoc create --as system:admin user adminþoc create --as system:admin identity anypassword:adminþoc create --as system:admin useridentitymapping anypassword:admin adminþoc adm policy --as system:admin add-cluster-role-to-user cluster-admin adminþ```þþIf you have some dedicated 3.11 cluster, you can add a new htpasswd entry to the `/etc/origin/master/htpasswd` file and then add the cluster-admin role to the userþþIf you have 4.x cluster, you can follow the docs for [configuring htpasswd](https://docs.openshift.com/container-platform/4.1/authentication/identity_providers/configuring-htpasswd-identity-provider.html)þþIf you for some reason can't have 2 users (1 admin, 1 regular) - for example on eval clusters when the Syndesis is installed for you, you can use property `syndesis.config.one.user=true` to use only the regular user (specified by the config property `syndesis.config.ui.username`)þþ### ScenariosþTest scenarios are provided in Gherkin language in a BDD fashion. Located in `./resources`þdirectory of `*-tests` module, e.g. [UI scenarios](https://github.com/syndesisio/syndesis-qe/tree/master/ui-tests/src/test/resources/features).þþEvery scenario is wrapped with appropriate tags to target specific execution on demand.þþIf you want to execute tests for specific component - both UI and REST, you can use components tags, for example `@salesforce`, otherwise you can specify multiple tags using cucumber notation like `'@datamapper and @rest'` .þThe list of all scenarios(tags) is in the [List of scenarios](#list-of-scenarios) chapter.þþþ#### GitHub and ENTESB Jira issue tagsþþA scenario may optionally be tagged with one or more tags in the form `@gh-<issue-number>` or `@ENTESB-<issue-number>`þIf such a scenario fails, the relevant GitHub or Jira issues are checked and a summary is written in the cucumber report.þSee javadoc of the OnFailHooks class for more info.þþ##### Skipping tests with open issuesþIn some cases you might want to skip tests which you know are going to fail, because they are tagged with open issues.þYou can do that by setting the property `syndesis.skip.open.issues` to `true` (defaults to `false`).þþ### ConfigurationþNOTE: Successful execution of tests requires fully configured credentials.þAll the callback URLs, Oauth tokens, etc. for Salesforce and Twitter accounts.þþ#### Example of test.properties to run on minishiftþFile `test.properties` should be located in the root of syndesis-qe folder.þWorking example can be found in jenkins nightly build run logs.þþFor more information ask `mcada@redhat.com` or `avano@redhat.com` or `tplevko@redhat.com`þþMinimal test.properties file (will work with most of the tests, some require more configuration)þ```þsyndesis.config.openshift.url=https://192.168.64.2:8443þsyndesis.config.openshift.namespace=syndesisþsyndesis.config.ui.url=https://syndesis.my-minishift.syndesis.ioþsyndesis.config.admin.username=adminþsyndesis.config.admin.password=adminþsyndesis.config.ui.username=developerþsyndesis.config.ui.password=developerþsyndesis.config.ui.browser=firefoxþ```þIf you want to use the default route for your tests, the only thing you need to specify is the `syndesis.config.openshift.url`.þIf you want to use your custom route, you need to specify `syndesis.config.openshift.url` and `syndesis.config.ui.url`. þþYou can also use the `syndesis.config.test.properties` system property to specify a different location of the `test.properties` file, relative to the repo root. This can be useful in case you want to quickly switch between e.g. a local minishift instance and a remote openshift instance.þþ#### Use correct webdriver version for selected browserþBy default the testsuite will not download any drivers when running tests. To download drivers, you need to use profile `download-drivers`, for example `mvn clean install -DskipTests -Pdownload-drivers`.þþBy default the testsuite will download latest drivers which may not work with older browsers.þTo use older webdriver, find supported version for your browser and set the system property `chrome.driver.version` or `firefox.driver.version` depending the browser of your choice.þþ##### ChromeþFind supported driver version for chrome browser here: http://chromedriver.chromium.org/downloadsþþUse following maven parameter when starting the tests: `-Dchrome.driver.version=<selected_version>`þþFor Chrome version 75, the parameter would be `75.0.3770.8`þþFor Chrome version 74, the parameter would be `74.0.3729.6`þþFor Chrome version 73, the parameter would be `73.0.3683.68`þþ##### FirefoxþFind supported driver version for your firefox browser here: https://firefox-source-docs.mozilla.org/testing/geckodriver/geckodriver/Support.htmlþþUse following maven parameter when starting the tests: `-Dfirefox.driver.version=<selected_version>`þþFor firefox 57 the parameter would be `0.24.0`þþ#### Example of credentials.jsonþFile `credentials.json` should be located in root of syndesis-qe folder.þWorking example on demand.þþFor more information ask `mcada@redhat.com` or `avano@redhat.com` or `tplevko@redhat.com`þþcredentials.jsonþ```jsonþ{þ  "twitter_listener": {þ    "service": "twitter",þ    "properties": {þ      "screenName": "****",þ      "accessToken": "****",þ      "accessTokenSecret": "****",þ      "consumerKey": "****",þ      "consumerSecret": "*****",þ      "login": "****",þ      "password": "****"þ    }þ  },þ  "twitter_talky": {þ    "service": "twitter",þ    "properties": {þ      "screenName": "****",þ      "consumerKey": "****",þ      "consumerSecret": "****",þ      "accessToken": "****",þ      "accessTokenSecret": "****",þ      "login": "****",þ      "password": "****"þ    }þ  },þ  "salesforce": {þ    "service": "salesforce",þ    "properties": {þ      "instanceUrl": "https://developer.salesforce.com",þ      "loginUrl": "https://login.salesforce.com",þ      "clientId": "****",þ      "clientSecret": "****",þ      "userName": "****",þ      "password": "****"þ    }þ  },þ  ...þ}þ```þþ### Executionþþ#### Before executionþFor the test execution at least `io.syndesis.common:common-model` and `io.syndesis.server:server-endpoint` modules are required in current version.þþ```þcd <syndesis-project-dir>þmvn clean install -f app/pom.xml -P flash --projects :common-model,:server-endpoint -amþ```þþWorking with extensions requires syndesis-extensions submodule compiled.þ**NOTE** If you didn't clone syndesis-qe repository with *--recurse-submodules* option as mentioned before, you have run following commands:þ```þcd <syndesis-qe-project-dir>þgit submodule update --init --recursiveþcd syndesis-extensionsþmvn clean installþ```þþ#### Test suite executionþþThere are separate maven profiles that can be used to build and execute tests. For each *-tests module there is a profile named after the part that is being tested in given module.þþ```þmvn clean test -P operatorþmvn clean test -P restþmvn clean test -P uiþmvn clean test -P upgradeþ```þþ#### Particular test executionþþWhen you want to run only the particular tests or scenarios, just use their **tags**. The following example runs `@integration-ftp-ftp` and `@integration-s3-ftp` scenarios from the rest suiteþþ```þmvn clean test -P rest -Dtags="@integration-ftp-ftp or @integration-s3-ftp"þ```þþ#### Additional parametersþþ##### Deploying Syndesis via the testsuiteþYou can use profile `-P deploy` **with some other profile** (ie. mvn clean test -P deploy,ui) that sets the required parameters to clean the namespace and deploy Syndesis.þþ```þmvn clean test -P deploy,rest -Dtags="@integration-ftp-ftp"þ```þþis the same asþþ```þmvn clean test -P rest -Dtags="@integration-ftp-ftp" -Dsyndesis.config.openshift.namespace.cleanup=trueþ```þþTo select syndesis version, add another maven parameter:þþ -Dsyndesis.config.install.version=<version>þþTo install syndesis using a particular operator image, use the following parameter:þþ -Dsyndesis.config.operator.image="[registry/]<namespace>/<syndesis|fuse-online>-operator:<version>"þþYou can also use the property `syndesis.config.build.properties.url` to specify a URL to a properties file, that will be sourced, so if you prefer, you can "hide" all command-line properties into one file and use only one parameter for the configuration.þþ##### Using maven central proxyþMaven central is used when building integrations in minishift. That can occasionally fail, because a request limit is reached.þIn such a case (and perhaps in any case), you can add the following test property to use your own maven central proxy:þ```þsyndesis.config.upstream.repository=<your maven central proxy>þ```þþ##### Pulling from private registriesþIf the images are deployed to a registry that requires authentication, you can use the *syndesis.config.pull.secret* property to specify the base64 encoded content of the docker config to use.þOptionally you can also use *syndesis.config.pull.secret.name* to specify the name of the created secret - if not present, it will default to *syndesis-pull-secret*.þThis secret will be linked to *syndesis-operator* service account automatically.þþþ##### Most common problemsþ* If tests failed at ***java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: bound must be positive***, probably the Syndesis isn't deployed in your namespace, so try again with `deploy` profile.þþ* When you start minishift, you might receive a 403 forbidden status from GitHub if your request exceeds the rate limit for your IP address. In this case, the command will fail and you will receive an error message. You need to create a personal API token from your GitHub account at https://github.com/settings/tokens. After you generate the API token, you need to set the MINISHIFT_GITHUB_API_TOKEN environment variable by running: `export MINISHIFT_GITHUB_API_TOKEN=<token_ID>` .þþ#### DebuggingþþWhen you want to debug code, just add following commandþ```þ"-Dmaven.failsafe.debug=-Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=y,address=8000 -Xnoagent -Djava.compiler=NONE"þ```þto the maven run command.þþE.g. for debugging slack tests:þ```þmvn "-Dmaven.failsafe.debug=-Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=y,address=8000 -Xnoagent -Djava.compiler=NONE" \þ        clean test -P ui -Dtags="@slack" \þ        -Dsyndesis.config.openshift.namespace.cleanup=true \þ```þþAfter that, the project will be waiting for a connection. After that, you can connect to remote debug in IDE. For more information [look here](http://jtuts.com/2016/07/29/how-to-set-up-remote-debugging-in-intellij-idea-for-a-webapp-that-is-run-by-tomcat-maven-plugin/).þþ### Contributingþþ#### CheckstyleþBefore you start contributing, please set up checkstyle in your IDE.þFor IntelliJ Idea, you have to install *[CheckStyle-IDEA](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/1065-checkstyle-idea)* plugin.þAfter that, open Settings > Editor > CodeStyle and click on cogwheel, select Import Scheme > CheckStyle configuration andþchoose checkstyle/checkstyle.xml file from this repository. Currently we use 8.20 version of the checkstyle, so select the version in the checkstyle plugin accordingly.þþSecond, import the code style settings into the IntelliJ from checkstyle/intellij-settings.jar (File -> Import settings). This provides all necessary configuration that conforms the checkstyle ruleset.þþAfter importing the jar file, verify that you have _Scheme: Syndesis_ in Settings -> Editor -> Code Style -> JavaþþIf you don't use IntelliJ IDEA, you will need to configure the code style manually, the basic settings are:þþ- Use spaces instead of tabsþ- Tab size 4, indent 4, continuation indent 4þ- Import order (new line between each group): static io.syndesis.\*, org.junit.\*, org.\*, javax.\*, java.\*, all other and then non-static imports following the same orderþþ**NOTE** IntelliJ Idea doesn't provide auto-format code after saving (because it provides auto-saving) by default. When you want toþreformat your code, you can use shortcut **CTRL+ALT+L** or you can install and configure **[Save Actions](https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/7642-save-actions)**.þPlease note that **CTRL+ALT+L** only reformat the code but it doesn't change the ordering of imports so you have to use also **CTRL+ALT+O** for optimizing imports.þþYou can also use *Reformat Code* checkbox in *Commit Changes*þdialog before you commit changes.þþ**Commit changes** dialog provides a useful view of your changes before commit. There, you can see the diff betweenþoriginal and changed file. So you can make sure that you commit only changes which you want. Also, you can set commit messageþand commit changes via this dialog.þþ![Commit changes](docs/readme_images/idea_commit_changes.png)þþCheckstyle can be also run automatically on each commit, see [Git hooks](#git-hooks) below.þþ#### Git hooksþYou can find the git hooks in the _hooks_ directory in the root of the project. You can enable them using following command in the root directory of this repository:þþ```þfor f in hooks/*; do ln -srf $f .git/hooks/; doneþ```þþCurrently there are two hooks:þ- _pre-push_ - if you want additional control that you are not pushing directly to upstreamþ- _prepare-commit-msg_ - runs checkstyle before each commit. Checkstyle verification can be temporarily disabled if the commit message starts with "tmp"þþ#### Creating a Pull RequestþWhen you create a PR on GitHub a new Jenkins job is scheduled. This job runs on Fuse QE Jenkins instance and runs a basic subset of tests (annotated with @smoke tag).þþIf you want to run a different subset of tests, you can use **//test: \`@mytag1 or @mytag2\`** in your PR description to trigger specific tests annotated by given tags.þþIf you don't want to run the job for your PR at all (for example when you are changing small things in README file), you can use `//skip-ci` in your PR description.þþWhen the PR job fails because of test failures and you believe that you didn't cause the error, you can try to trigger the job once again. For this just comment `retest this please` in the PR and a new build will be triggered in few minutes.þþPlease remember that each time you push something new (or amend something old) in the PR, a new build is triggered automatically, so you don't need to do anything else to get your PR rebuilt.þþ### Advanced debuggingþþ#### HotSwapþHotSwap is a very useful technique on how to change the code during debugging. It saves a lot of times. þEspecially in UI testing. You can stop debugger to the point where the test fails due to þtest mistakes (e.g. label was changed), look into the debbuger for the correct value, drop frame and run method again þwithout restart all tests.þþThe following steps show how to debug and use it in the IntelliJ Idea.þþ* In the UI project, right-click on the CucumberTest class and click Run. It fails, but it created JUnit configurationþ* Edit JUnit configuration and add parameters to the VM Options.þ *cucumber.options* and *syndesis.version* are mandatory!þ    e.g.þ    ```þ    -eaþ    -Dtags="@slack-to-db"þ    -Dsyndesis.config.openshift.namespace.cleanup=trueþ    -Dsyndesis.version=masterþ    ```þ    As you can see, the running scenario is specified in the cucumber.options tag.þ* Add breakpoint where you want and run debug (Shift-F9).þ* When you change something, you have to recompile the particular class. *(Build -> Recompile Ctrl+Shift+F9)*þ* After that, you have to drop frame. In the Debugger view, right-click on the top frame and select *Drop Frame*.þ    It causes that last frame (e.g. function) will be running again with the changed code.þþ[Video with example](https://drive.google.com/file/d/16G-UDrRGLE-YvuRJUMlVpGi1z5vkjc4r/view?usp=sharing)þþ* In some cases, after step to the next line, the code throws exception and you lose the frame stack. When you want toþignore exception, in the debugger view click on *View Breakpoints* (Ctrl+Shift+F8) and select that you want to stop programþon Java Exception Breakpoints and specify particular exception. After that, program stop beforeþthrowing an exception and you just drop frames which are on the frame with your method.þþ* In some cases, you want to try find UI label with **Trial and Error** method.þIt means that you are changing the name unless you find the correct one. But, of course, you don't want toþthrow exception every time when you set incorrect name. For this, just stop debugger in code, open debuggerþand in the variables view you can add and edit any variables you want.þWhen variables throws exception, it will not affect tests (main) executions.þþ[Video with example of *Exception Breakpoints* and *Trial and Error*](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1baPJx7YncTn36B6N-VFy85lZciskC1NE)þþþFor more information see [Altering the program's execution flow](https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/altering-the-program-s-execution-flow.html#reload_classes)þþ### List of scenariosþþ```þ------MAIN CATEGORIES------þ@doc-tutorial (documentation tutorials tests)þ@quickstart (tests for quickstarts: https://github.com/syndesisio/syndesis-quickstarts)þ@reproducer (tests which are related to the particular issue)þ@restþ@uiþ------TECHNOLOGIES------þ@activemqþ@amqpþ@api-providerþ@apicurioþ@concurþ@dropboxþ@ftpþ@gmailþ@google-calendarþ@httpþ@kafkaþ@mqttþ@mysqlþ@oracle12þ@s3þ@salesforceþ@servicenowþ@slackþ@sqsþ@twitterþ@webhookþ------FUNCTIONS------þ@3scaleþ@activityþ@amqbrokerþ@api-connectorþ@databaseþ@datamapperþ@exportþ@extensionþ@importþ@logþ@metricsþ@swaggerþ@timerþ@todo-appþ@publicapiþ------QUICKSTARTS------þ@quickstart-solution (tests for importing and testing the quickstart's solutions)þ@quickstart-video (tests for testing process which is described in the quckstart's videos)þ```

column17: Fess is very powerful and easily deployable Enterprise Search Server.
column43: Fess Enterprise Search Server [![Tweet](https://img.shields.io/twitter/url/http/shields.io.svg?style=social)](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Fess+is+very+powerful+and+easily+deployable+Enterprise+Search+Server.&url=https://github.com/codelibs/fess)þ====þ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/codelibs/fess.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/codelibs/fess) þ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/org.codelibs.fess/fess/badge.svg)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/org.codelibs.fess/fess)þ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-blue.svg)](https://github.com/gitbucket/gitbucket/blob/master/LICENSE)þþ## OverviewþþFess is a very powerful and easily deployable Enterprise Search Server. You can quickly install and run Fess on any platform where you can run the Java Runtime Environment. Fess is provided under the [Apache License 2.0](LICENSE).þþFess is based on [Elasticsearch](https://www.elastic.co/products/elasticsearch), but knowledge/experience about Elasticsearch is _not_ required. Fess provides an easy to use Administration GUI to configure the system via your browser.þFess also contains a Crawler, which can crawl documents on a [web server](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/admin/webconfig-guide.html), [file system](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/admin/fileconfig-guide.html), or [Data Store](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/admin/dataconfig-guide.html) (such as a CSV or database). Many file formats are supported including (but not limited to): Microsoft Office, PDF, and zip.þþ*[Fess Site Search](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-site-search)* is a free alternative to [Google Site Search](https://enterprise.google.com/search/products/gss.html). For more details, see the [FSS JS Generator documentation](https://fss-generator.codelibs.org/docs/manual).þþ## Websiteþþ[fess.codelibs.org](https://fess.codelibs.org/)þþ## Issues/Questionsþþ[discuss.codelibs.org](https://discuss.codelibs.org/c/FessEN/)þþ## Getting StartedþþThere are 2 ways to try Fess. The first is to download and install yourself. The second is to use [Docker](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-engine).þþ### Download and Install/RunþþFess 13.8 is now available and can be downloaded on the [Releases page](https://github.com/codelibs/fess/releases "download"). Downloads come in 3 flavors: deb, rpm, zip.þþThe following commands show how to use the zip download:þþ    $ unzip fess-13.8.x.zipþ    $ cd fess-13.8.xþ    $ ./bin/fessþþFor more details, see the [Installation Guide](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/install/index.html).þþ### DockerþþWe provide Docker images on [Docker Hub](https://hub.docker.com/r/codelibs/fess/). We also provide a Docker Compose (YAML) file in [this repository](https://github.com/codelibs/docker-fess/tree/master/compose). þþ### Browser UIþþ- Search UI: http://localhost:8080/þþ![Search UI](https://fess.codelibs.org/_images/fess_search_result1.png)þþ- Admin UI: http://localhost:8080/admin/ (default username/password is admin/admin)þþ![Admin UI](https://fess.codelibs.org/_images/fess_admin_dashboard.png)þþYou can register crawling targets in the Admin UI on the (Web, File, Data Store) crawler configuration pages, and then start the Crawler manually on the [Scheduler page](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/admin/scheduler-guide.html).þþ## Migration from another search providerþþPlease see [MIGRATION.md](MIGRATION.md).þþ## Data StoreþþCurrently, Fess supports crawling the following [storage locations and APIs](https://fess.codelibs.org/13.8/admin/dataconfig-guide.html):þþ - [Confluence/Jira](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-atlassian)þ - [Box](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-box)þ - [CSV](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-csv)þ - [Database](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-db)þ - [Dropbox](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-dropbox)þ - [Elasticsearch](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-elasticsearch)þ - [Git](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-git)þ - [Gitbucket](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-gitbucket)þ - [G Suite](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-gsuite)þ - [JSON](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-json)þ - [Office 365](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-office365)þ - [S3](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-s3)þ - [Salesforce](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-salesforce)þ - [SharePoint](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-sharepoint)þ - [Slack](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ds-slack)þþ## Themeþþ - [Simple](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-theme-simple)þ - [Classic](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-theme-classic)þþ## Ingestþþ - [Logger](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ingest-logger)þ - [NDJSON](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-ingest-ndjson)þþ## Localizationþþ### Japaneseþþ - [Website](https://fess.codelibs.org/ja/)þþ### Koreanþþ - [Forum](https://github.com/nocode2k/fess-kr-forum)þþ## Development Informationþþ### Get Source Codeþþ1. Clone Fess's repository:þ    ```þ    $ cd ~/workspaceþ    $ git clone https://github.com/codelibs/fess.gitþ    ```þ    þ2. Import the cloned repository as a [Maven](https://maven.apache.org/) project on [Eclipse](https://www.eclipse.org/eclipseide/) or another IDE.þþ### Setup for Elasticsearch PluginsþþRun antrun:run to download plugins into the plugins directory:þþ    $ mvn antrun:runþþ### Run FessþþRun or debug org.codelibs.fess.FessBoot on your IDE, and then access http://localhost:8080/þþ### Build PackageþþRun the `package` goal and then the release file will be created in target/releases.þþ    $ mvn packageþ    $ mvn rpm:rpm   # .rpm packageþ    $ mvn jdeb:jdeb # .deb packageþþ### Generate Source Codeþþ    $ mvn dbflute:download # (one time command)þ    $ mvn dbflute:freegenþ    $ mvn license:formatþþ### Integration TestsþþLaunch Fess Server and run the following command:þþ    $ mvn test -P integrationTests -Dtest.fess.url="http://localhost:8080" -Dtest.es.url="http://localhost:9201"þþTo run a single test case, you can use:þþ    $ mvn test -P integrationTests -Dtest.fess.url="http://localhost:8080" -Dtest.es.url="http://localhost:9201" -Dtest=SearchApiTestsþþ### Translate In Your LanguageþþFess is internationalized software.þþIf you want to add labels/messages for your language, please translate properties file and then rename to fess\_\*\_[lang].properties.þþ* [fess_label_en.properties](https://github.com/codelibs/fess/blob/master/src/main/resources/fess_label_en.properties)þ* [fess_message_en.properties](https://github.com/codelibs/fess/blob/master/src/main/resources/fess_message_en.properties)þþFor search/index analyzer, if [doc.json](https://github.com/codelibs/fess/blob/master/src/main/resources/fess_indices/fess/doc.json) contains lang\_[lang] for your language, please modify the analyzer for your language. For more details about Analyzers, see the [Elasticsearch documentation](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/analysis-analyzers.html).þþWe welcome pull requests for your language.þþ## Powered Byþþ* [Lasta Di](https://github.com/lastaflute/lasta-di "Lasta Di"): DI Containerþ* [LastaFlute](https://github.com/lastaflute/lastaflute "LastaFlute"): Web Frameworkþ* [Lasta Job](https://github.com/lastaflute/lasta-job "Lasta Job"): Job Schedulerþ* [Fess Crawler](https://github.com/codelibs/fess-crawler "Fess Crawler"): Web Crawlerþ* [Elasticsearch](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch "Elasticsearch"): Search Engine

column17: Fault-tolerant Distributed Store providing strict serializable transactions using inconsistent replication
column43: # AminoStoreþþThis repository includes code implementing AminoStore -- A fault-tolerant, transactional data store. þThis code is based on the research described in þthe SOSP 2015 paper, ["Building Consistent Transactions withþInconsistent Replication."](http://dl.acm.org/authorize?N93281)þþAminoStore incorporates TAPIR, a new protocol for linearizable distributed transactionsþbuilt using replication with no consistency guarantees. By enforcingþconsistency only at the transaction layer,þcoordination at the replication layer is eliminated, enabling theþsame transaction model and consistency guarantees as existing systems,þlike Spanner, with better latency and throughput.þþIn addition to TAPIR, this repo includes several other usefulþimplementations of distributed systems, including:þþ1. An implementation of a lock server designed to work withþ   inconsistent replication (IR), our high-performance, unorderedþ   replication protocol.þþ2. An implementation of Viewstamped Replication (VR), detailed in thisþ   [older paper](http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=62549) and thisþ   [more recent paper](http://18.7.29.232/handle/1721.1/71763).þþ3. An implementation of a scalable, distributed storage systemþ   designed to work with VR that uses two-phase commit to supportþ   distributed transactions and supports both optimistic concurrencyþ   control and strict two-phase locking.þþThe repo is structured as follows:þþ- /lib - the transport library for communication between nodes. Thisþ  includes UDP based network communcation as well as the ability toþ  simulate network conditions on a local machine, including packetþ  delays and reorderings.þþ- /replication - replication library for the distributed storesþ  - /vr - implementation of viewstamped replication protocolþ  - /ir - implementation of inconsistent replication protocolþþ- /store - partitioned/sharded distributed storeþ  - /common - common data structures, backing stores and interfaces for all of storesþ  - /tapirstore - implementation of TAPIR designed to work with IRþ  - /strongstore - implementation of both an OCC-based and locking-based 2PC transactionalþ  storage system, designed to work with VRþ  - /weakstore - implementation of an eventually consistent storageþ    system, using quorum writes for replicationþþ- /lockserver - a lock server designed to be used with IRþþ## Compiling & RunningþYou can compile all of the executables by running make in the root directoryþþAminoStore depends on protobufs and libevent, so you will need those development libraries installed on your machine. On Linux, this can be done through apt.þþ## Contact and QuestionsþPlease email Quinton at quinton.hoole@huawei.com, Irene at iyzhang@cs.washington.edu, Dan at drkp@cs.washington.edu

That file also lists supported operating systems andþhardware platforms and contains information regarding any otherþsoftware packages that are required to build or run the PostgreSQLþsystem.  Copyright and license information can be found in theþfile COPYRIGHT.  A comprehensive documentation set is included in thisþdistribution; it can be read as described in the installationþinstructions.þþThe latest version of this software may be obtained atþhttps://www.postgresql.org/download/.  For more information look at ourþweb site located at https://www.postgresql.org/.

column43: # Skungeeþ[![Discord](https://img.shields.io/discord/138464183946575874.svg?label=skript-chat%20discord)](https://discord.gg/7rk74Pg)þ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-red.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0)þ![Commit](https://img.shields.io/github/last-commit/Skungee/Skungee.svg)þ[![](https://jitpack.io/v/Skungee/Skungee.svg)](https://jitpack.io/#Skungee/Skungee)þþSpigot Socket API and Bungeecord Skript Addon.þþ## BuildingþOpen a command promptþþThe following will clone Skungee to your current directory location. To change the current directory as to where you want it cloned, type `cd PATH` replace PATH with the directory path location.þþThen type the clone commandþ`git clone https://github.com/TheLimeGlass/Skungee.git`þþNow to build Skungee you simply need to run the `gradle build` command. You can find the compiled JAR file in `./build/libs` of the gradle folder when complete.þþ__Note:__ If you do not have [Gradle] installed then use ./gradlew for Unix systems or Git Bash and windows systems have executable gradlew.bat.þþ## APIþYou can use Skungee without Skript being required. You can use Skungee as an advanced socket protocol between Bungeecord and Spigot.þCheck out the tutorial here https://github.com/Skungee/Skungee/wiki/Using-the-Skungee-APIþþ## ContributingþThe only guideline we have is to follow Google's Java coding style https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.htmlþPull requests and contributions are welcome.

column43: Protptype Projectþ================þ## Overviewþ### フォルダ構成þ* adk : ADKを利用するAndroidアプリ（ライブラリとしてforMegaAdkLibを指定する）þ* forMegaAdkLib : adkを使うAndroidアプリのライブラリþ* Arduino : Arduinoアプリþ* Node : Node.js学習用サンプルコードþ* SampleSockeIO : express, ejs, Socket.IOを使ったチャットサンプルþ* NodeServer : プロトタイプ作成用のサーバサイドとブラウザクライアント(/chat と /webcommand のエントリポイント)þþ### 動作確認済みバージョンþ* Node.js : v0.8.16（nvm lsで確認可能）þþ        Macでv0.8系をインストールするにはXcodeが必要þ* Socket.IO : v0.9（SampleSocketIOおよびNodeServerのディレクトリでnpm listで確認可能）þ* express 3.0.0rc3þþ### Node.jsのインストールþþ#### nvmþþ```þ$ git clone https://github.com/creationix/nvm.git .nvmþ// .bashrcに以下を追加しておくとターミナル起動時にnvmが使える(Macの場合は.bash_profile)þsource ~/.nvm/nvm.shþ// スクリプト実行þ$ source .nvm/nvm.shþ// Node.jsをインストールþ$ nvm install v0.8.16þ$ nvm lsþ$ nvm use v0.8.16þ$ node --versionþþ```þþ#### nodebrewþ```þ$ curl https://raw.github.com/hokaccha/nodebrew/master/nodebrew | perl - setupþ// .bashrcに以下を追加しておくと起動時にnodeが使える(Macの場合は.bash_profile)þexport PATH=$HOME/.nodebrew/current/bin:$PATHþ// 読み直しþ$ source .bashrcþ// Node.jsをインストールþ$ nodebrew install-binary v0.8.16þ$ nodebrew lsþ$ nodebrew use v0.8.16þ$ node --versionþ```

column17: MIT App Inventor Public Open Source
column43: # Welcome to MIT App Inventorþþ## IntroductionþþLearn more about [MIT App Inventor](http://appinventor.mit.edu).þþThis code is designed to be run in Google's App Engine. MIT runs aþpublic instance that all are welcome to use to build App InventorþApplications. You do not need to compile or use this code if you wishþto build MIT App Inventor applications.þþWe provide this code for reference and for experienced people who wishþto operate their own App Inventor instance and/or contribute to the project.þþThis code is tested and known to work with Java 8.þþ## ContributorsþThe best way to go about integrating changes in App Inventor is to start a conversation in the [Open Source forum](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/app-inventor-open-source-dev) about whatever you intend to change or add.þþWe use ***very brief and informal*** design documents with descriptions of the proposed changes and screenshots of how the functionality would look like and behave, in order to gather as much feedback from the community, as early as possible. We generally use shared Google docs for this (with permissions to add comments), but any format that is accessible from a web browser (and allows comments) would do.þþIf you have skipped this step and have gone ahead and made your changes already, feel free to open a pull request, but don't be too surprised if we ask you to go back and document it in a design document. Remember that the main goal of doing this is ***to gather as much feedback, as early as possible***. We will also possibly ask you to put an instance with your changes on [appspot](http://appspot.com), and provide a modified Companion app (if that applies) so that reviewers can play with the changes before looking at the source.þþCheck out our open source [site](http://appinventor.mit.edu/appinventor-sources/) to find a lot more information about the project and how to contribute to it.þþ## Setup instructions (Vagrant)þþThe easiest way to get a development environment up and running is to use the provided Vagrantfile. Install [Vagrant](https://vagrantup.com) and open a terminal in the root directory of this repository. Run the following commandsþþ```bashþvagrant plugin install vagrant-vbguest  # optionally for virtualbox users, and only onceþvagrant up                              # initializes the VMþ```þþIt may take a few minutes for Vagrant to initialize as it will pull down a virtual machine image from the Internet and configure it with all of the App Inventor dependencies. Subsequent start-ups will be faster. Next, enter the virtual machine by running:þþ```bashþvagrant sshþ```þþThis should open up a terminal within the virtual machine in the directory `/vagrant/appinventor`. This directory is the same as the `appinventor` directory in this repository, shared between your host machine and the virtual machine. Any changes made on one side will be visible in the other. This allows you to edit files on your host machine with your preferred editor, while keeping the build environment relegated to the virtual machine. To build App Inventor, you may now run:þþ```bashþantþ```þþand to run App Inventor:þþ```bashþstart_appinventorþ```þþPress Ctrl+C to quit the server. Enter exit at the prompt to leave the virtual machine. To reclaim resources when you are not actively developing, you can run `vagrant halt` to stop the virtual machine. To completely remove the virtual machine, run `vagrant destroy`. If you destroy the VM, you will need to start these instructions from the top.þþNote 1: For macOS users, if you are using VirtualBox and get any error while initializing the VM it may be due to security restrictions in System Preferences, consider reading [this](https://medium.com/@Aenon/mac-virtualbox-kernel-driver-error-df39e7e10cd8) article. þþNote 2: If it seems like none of the dependencies are installed in the VM, run ```vagrant provision```.þþFor better performance, consider using the manual instructions.þþ## Setup instructions (manual)þþThis is a quick guide to get started with the sources. More detailed instructions can be found [here](https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=1Xc9yt02x3BRoq5m1PJHBr81OOv69rEBy8LVG_84j9jc), a slide show can be seen [here](http://josmas.github.io/contributingToAppInventor2/#/), and all the [documentation](http://appinventor.mit.edu/appinventor-sources/#documentation) for the project is available in our [site](http://appinventor.mit.edu/appinventor-sources/).þþ### DependenciesþYou will need a full Java JDK (version 8, OpenJDK preferred; JRE is not enough) and Python to compile and run the servers.þþYou will also need a copy of the [Google Cloud SDK](https://cloud.google.com/appengine/docs/standard/java/download) for Java and [ant](http://ant.apache.org/).þþIf you want to make changes to the source, you are going to need to run an automated test suite, and for that you will also need [phantomjs](http://phantomjs.org/). Have a look at the testing section for more information.þþNote 1: If you are working on a 64-bit linux system, you need to install 32-bit version of: glibc(to get a 32-bit version of ld-linux.so), zlib and libstdc++.þþIf you are on a Debian-based distribution(Ubuntu), use:þþ    $ sudo apt-get install libc6:i386 zlib1g:i386 libstdc++6:i386þþIf you are on an RPM-based distribution(Fedora), use:þþ    $ sudo dnf install glibc.i686 zlib.i686 libstdc++.i686þþNote 2: Certain Java 8 features, such as lambda expressions, are not supported on Android, so please don't use them in your changes to the source code.þþ### Forking or cloningþConsider ***forking*** the project if you want to make changes to the sources. If you simply want to run it locally, you can simply ***clone*** it.þþ#### ForkingþIf you decide to fork, follow the [instructions](https://help.github.com/articles/fork-a-repo) given by github. After that you can clone your own copy of the sources with:þþ    $ git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USER_NAME/appinventor-sources.gitþþMake sure you change *YOUR_USER_NAME* to your user name.þþConfiguring a remote pointing to this repository is also a good idea if you are forking:þþ    $ cd appinventor-sourcesþ    $ git remote add upstream https://github.com/mit-cml/appinventor-sources.gitþþFinally, you will also have to make sure that you are ignoring files that need ignoring:þþ    $ cp sample-.gitignore .gitignoreþþ### Checkout dependenciesþApp Inventor uses Blockly, the web-based visual programming editor from Google, as a core part of its editor. Blockly core is made available to App Inventor as a git submodule. The first time after forking or cloning the repository, you will need to perform the following commands:þþ    $ git submodule update --initþþFor developers who will be working on Blocky within the context of App Inventor, the preferred checkout procedure is to perform a `git submodule init`, edit the `.git/config` file to use the read/write SSH URL for [MIT CML's Blockly fork](https://github.com/mit-cml/blockly) instead of the public read-only HTTPS URL assumed by default (to support pushing changes). After changing `.git/config`, a `git submodule update` will pull the repository.þþIf you need to switch back to a branch that does contains the Blockly and Closure Library sources in the tree, you will need to run the command:þþ    $ git submodule deinit --allþþto clear out the submodules ___before switching branches___. When switching back, you will need to repeat the initialization and update procedure above.þþ### CompilingþBefore compiling the code, an [auth key](https://docs.google.com/document/pub?id=1Xc9yt02x3BRoq5m1PJHBr81OOv69rEBy8LVG_84j9jc#h.yikyg2e1rfut) is needed. You can create one by running the following commands:þþ    $ cd appinventorþ    $ ant MakeAuthKeyþþOnce the key is in place, type the following to compile (from the appinventor folder):þþ    $ antþþYou will see a lot of stuff in the terminal and after a few minutes (it can take from 2 to 10 minutes, depending on your machine specs) you should see a message saying something like *Build Successful*.þþ### Running the server(s)þThere are two servers in App Inventor, the main server that deals with project information, and the build server that creates apk files. More detailed information can be found in the [App Inventor Developer Overview](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hIvAtbNx-eiIJcTA2LLPQOawctiGIpnnt0AvfgnKBok/pub) document.þþ#### Running the main serverþþ    $ your-google-cloud-SDK-folder/bin/java_dev_appserver.shþ            --port=8888 --address=0.0.0.0 appengine/build/war/þþMake sure you change *your-google-cloud-SDK-folder* to wherever in your hard drive you have placed the Google Cloud SDK.þþ#### Running the build serverþThe build server can be run from the terminal by typing:þþ    $ cd appinventor/buildserverþ    $ ant RunLocalBuildServerþþNote that you will only need to run the build server if you are going to build an app as an apk. You can do all the layout and programming without having the build server running, but you will need it to download the apk.þþ### Accessing your local serverþYou should now be up and running; you can test this by pointing your browser to:þþ    http://localhost:8888þþBefore entering or scanning the QR code in the Companion, check the box labeled "Use Legacy Connection".þþ### Running testsþThe automated tests depend on [Phantomjs](http://phantomjs.org/). Make sure you install it and add it to your path. After that, you can run all tests by typing the following in a terminal window:þþ    $ ant testsþ    þ### Hot-reloading GWT code with 'Super Dev Mode'þ1. Run `ant devmode`þ2. [Run the main server](#running-the-main-server).þ3. Open http://localhost:9876 (*GWT CodeServer*) and drag the two bookmarklets (*Dev Mode On & Off*) to the bookmarks bar.þ4. Open http://localhost:8888 (*App Engine server*)þ5. To see changes "live":þ   1. Save your changes in file.þ   2. Click on the *"Dev Mode On"* bookmarklet.þ   3. A popup will be shown with a button to compile `ode` module.þ   4. Press that button to compile. (That button is actually a bookmarklet. So you can drag this button to the bookmarks bar as well. This will come handy for subsequent compilations)þ   5. After that, *GWT CodeServer* will compile the module incrementally.þ   6. Refresh the page and that's it! The changes are live.þþLogs can be found at http://localhost:9876/log/ode and SourceMaps at http://localhost:9876/sourcemaps/odeþþ## Need help?þJoin [our community](https://community.appinventor.mit.edu/).

[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/jbehave/jbehave-core.png)](https://travis-ci.org/jbehave/jbehave-core)þþ# JBehaveþþJBehave is a BDD framework for Java and all JVM languages (Groovy, Ruby, Scala).þþþþ## UsingþþCanonical information for JBehave:þþ1. [Web Site](http://jbehave.org).þ2. [Stable Reference](http://jbehave.org/reference/stable/).þ3. [User mailing list](http://jbehave.org/mailing-lists.html)þ4. [Search Maven](http://search.maven.org/#search|ga|1|jbehave)þþ## Contributing and DevelopingþþPlease report issues, feature requests on [JIRA](http://jbehave.org/issue-tracking.html) or discuss them on theþ[dev mailing list](http://jbehave.org/mailing-lists.html).þþKeep an eye on the [Travis CI](http://travis-ci.org/jbehave) server for JBehave builds.þþ### JDKþþJDK version required: þþ1.8 or above at build and runtime (tested with Oracle JDK on different platforms)þþ### Maven þþ[Maven](http://maven.apache.org) version required to build: 3.5 or above þ(while tested with 3.5.x it may also work with previous 3.x versions)þþ### EncodingþþConfigure IDE to use UTF-8 for all filesþConfigure Maven by adding "-Dfile.encoding=UTF-8" to $MAVEN_OPTSþþ### IDE IntegrationþþMaven is supported in Intellij IDEA out-of-the-boxþMaven is supported in Eclipse via [m2e plugin](http://eclipse.org/m2e), included out-of-the-box in some Eclipse distributions.þEclipse users may also want to load the ides/eclipse/lifecycle-mapping-metadata.xml or ignore the m2e lifecycle mappings manually.þþ### BuildingþþThe first time you run the Maven build, do:þþ mvn install -s settings.xmlþþAfter that, it is necessary to only do the following:þþ mvn installþþ### Maven Build Profilesþþ- default: builds all releasable modulesþ- examples: builds all headless examplesþ- gui: builds examples that require a GUI (i.e. non-headless) mode (separated as they do not run on CI.þ- nt: no-test, builds skipping unit-test behaviorsþþ#### Maven Build Profiles used during release cycleþþ- reporting: builds reportsþ- distribution: builds distribution (documentation)þþNote: profiles are additive and the default profile is always active.þþ### Example Profile Usagesþþ#### Build Core and all Examplesþþ mvn install -Pexamplesþþ#### Build with Reporting and Distributionþþ mvn install -Preporting,distributionþþ#### Building a Release with Mavenþþ mvn release:prepare -Preporting,distributionþ mvn release:perform -Preporting,distributionþþ## Related JBehave projectsþþSee also: þþ- [jbehave-pom](https://github.com/jbehave/jbehave-pom) JBehave POMþ- [jbehave-web](https://github.com/jbehave/jbehave-web) web extensions to JBehaveþ- [jbehave-osgi](https://github.com/jbehave/jbehave-osgi) OSGi extensions to JBehaveþ- [jbehave-eclipse](https://github.com/jbehave/jbehave-eclipse) Eclipse integration for JBehaveþ- [jbehave-tutorial](https://github.com/jbehave/jbehave-tutorial) for an example of JBehave testing of a real web application.þþ## LicenseþþSee LICENSE.txt in the source root (BSD).

column17: Blockchain project in Java, WIP
column43: # BlockChainJþþSimple blockchain implementation, in Java, WIPþþ## DescriptionþþThis blockchain implementation has:þþ- Block: with number, parent block and list of transactionsþ- Transaction: send value from sender to receiver accountþ- Account: with balance and optional smart contract codeþ- Virtual Machine: to execute smart contractsþþThe world state keeps the account states. Each account has a balance and smart contract storage.þþ## Referencesþþ- [SpongyCastle](https://rtyley.github.io/spongycastle)þ- [BouncyCastle Java](http://www.bouncycastle.org/java.html)þ- column17: Mirror of Apache Stanbol (incubating)
column43: <!--þ  Licensed to the Apache Software Foundation (ASF) under one or moreþ  contributor license agreements.  See the NOTICE file distributed withþ  this work for additional information regarding copyright ownership.þ  The ASF licenses this file to You under the Apache License, Version 2.0þ  (the "License"); you may not use this file except in compliance withþ  the License.  You may obtain a copy of the License atþþ      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþ  Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþ  distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þ  WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þ  See the License for the specific language governing permissions andþ  limitations under the License.þ-->þþ# Apache StanbolþþApache Stanbol is a modular set of components and HTTP services forþsemantic content management.þþ## Building StanbolþþTo build Stanbol you need a JDK 1.6 and Maven 3.0.3+ installed. You probablyþneedþþ    $ export MAVEN_OPTS="-Xmx1024m -XX:MaxPermSize=256M"þþThe following builds the Apache Stanbol plus available Enhancement Engines and aþdefault set of linked open data for the EntityHub. If you want to have a readyþto use version of Apache Stanbol, this is the way to go.þþIn the Apache Stanbol source directory typeþþ    $ mvn installþþIf you want to skip the tests, use :þþ    $ mvn install -Dmaven.test.skip=trueþ    þþ## Launching the Apache Stanbol ServerþþThe recommended lanchers are packaged under the `launchers/` folder. þþ### Launching the Apache Stanbol runnable jarþþFor running the full launcher you need to execute:þþ    $ java -Xmx1g -jar launchers/full/target/org.apache.stanbol.launchers.full-0.10.0-incubating-SNAPSHOT.jarþþYour instance is then available on <http://localhost:8080>. You can change theþdefault port number by passing a `-p 9090` options to the commandline launcher.þþUpon first startup, a folder named `sling/` is created in the current folder.þThis folder will hold the files for any database used by Stanbol, deploymentþconfiguration and logs.þþIf Stanbol is launched with a FactStore a folder named `factstore` is createdþin the current folder. This folder holds the FactStore database (Apache Derby).þþ### Launching the Apache Stanbol runnable warþþFor running the full war launcher you need to go to the launcher directory:þþ    $ cd launchers/full-warþþand then execute:þþ    $ mvn clean package tomcat7:runþþYour instance is then available on <http://localhost:8080/stanbol>. You can change theþdefault port number by passing `-Pstanbol.port=9090` property to maven.þþ### Running Apache Stanbol on a application containerþþFor running the full war launcher on a external application container, just deployþthere in your usual way the file `launchers/full-war/target/stanbol.war`.þþþ## Importing the source code as Eclipse projectsþþEclipse is the most popular IDE among Stanbol developers. Here areþinstructions to get you started with this IDE. For other IDEs / editors,þplease refer to their documentation and maven integration plugins.þþTo generate the Eclipse project definition files, go to Stanbol sourceþdirectory and type:þþ    $ mvn eclipse:eclipseþþIf you want to recreate already existing Eclipse projects, you have to deleteþthe old ones first by using `eclipse:clean`.þþThen in Eclipse, right click on the `Project Explorer` panel and selectþyour source folder from the following menu / import wizard:þþ    > Import... > General > Import Existing Projects into WorkspaceþþYou will also need to setup the build path variable `M2_REPO` pointing toþ`~/.m2/repository` (where `~` stands for the path to your home folder). To setþup this variable go to:þþ    > Window > Preferences > Java > Build Path > Classpath Variables > New...þþIf you plan to contribute patches to the project, please ensure that your styleþfollow the official sun java guidelines with 4 space indents (no tabs). Toþensure that your files follow the guidelines you can import the formatterþdefinitions avaiable in the `conventions/` folder:þþ    > Window > Preferences > Java > Code Style > Formatter > Import...þþYou can then apply the formatter to a selected area of a Java source code filesþby pressing `Shift+Ctrl+F`.þþþ## Debugging an Apache Stanbol Instance from EclipseþþTo debug a locally running Stanbol instance from eclipse, run the stanbolþlauncher with::þþ    $ java -Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,address=8787,server=y,suspend=n \þ           -jar org.apache.stanbol.some.launcher-[VERSION].jar -p 8080þþIn eclipse, you can then create a new "Debug Configuration" with type "RemoteþJava Application" and connect it to localhost on port 8787.þþþ## Build without SNAPSHOTs from Apache RepositoryþþApache Stanbol deployes current SNAPSHOTS of components from the trunk to theþApache SNAPSHOT Maven repository. This is done on each succesful Jenkins buildþat https://builds.apache.org/view/S-Z/view/Stanbol/job/stanbol-trunk/þþTo locally build Stanbol without loading available SNAPSHOTs from the ApacheþSNAPSHOT repository, use can use the 'no-snapshot-dep' profile.þþ    $ mvn clean install -Pno-snapshot-depþþThis profile especially useful if you are preparing a release and want toþensure that there are no dangling SNAPSHOT dependencies that can not beþresolved from within the locally available components.þþþ## License check via the Apache's Release Audit Tool (RAT)þþTo check for license headers within the source code Stanbol uses the RAT Mavenþplugin [1]. You can activate a 'rat:check' by using the 'rat' Maven profile.þþFor example to check the licenses in the Stanbol Framework useþþ    $ mvn install -Pratþþþ## Release Apache StanbolþþYou should read [1,2] before doing any release related actions.þþTo do a release test build, you have to activate the 'apache-release' profile.þFor building Apache Stanbol plus signing the artifacts as it would be done duringþa release you can useþþ    $ mvn install -Papache-releaseþþThe 'apache-release' profile will be automatically activated when the Mavenþrelease plugin [3] is used. For doing official release you start withþþ    $ mvn release:prepareþþ[1] http://www.apache.org/dev/#releasesþ[2] http://incubator.apache.org/guides/releasemanagement.htmlþ[3] http://maven.apache.org/plugins/maven-release-plugin/þþþ## Useful linksþþ  - Documentation will be published and mailing lists info on [the officialþ    Stanbol page](http://incubator.apache.org/stanbol/)þþ  - Please report bugs on the [Apache issue tracker](þ    https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/STANBOL)

column43: = UI Quality Assurance project for eXo Platformþ:toc:þ:toclevels: 4þ:link-chrome-driver: https://chromedriver.storage.googleapis.com/2.28þ:link-chrome-driver-notes: {link-chrome-driver}/notes.txtþ:link-chrome-driver-linux32: {link-chrome-driver}/chromedriver_linux32.zipþ:link-chrome-driver-linux64: {link-chrome-driver}/chromedriver_linux64.zipþ:link-chrome-driver-mac64: {link-chrome-driver}/chromedriver_mac64.zipþ:link-chrome-driver-win32: {link-chrome-driver}/chromedriver_win32.zipþ:link-firefox-driver: https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/releases/download/v0.14.0þ:link-firefox-driver-notes: https://github.com/mozilla/geckodriver/releases/tag/v0.14.0þ:link-firefox-driver-linux32: {link-firefox-driver}/geckodriver-v0.14.0-linux32.tar.gzþ:link-firefox-driver-linux64: {link-firefox-driver}/geckodriver-v0.14.0-linux64.tar.gzþ:link-firefox-driver-mac64: {link-firefox-driver}/geckodriver-v0.14.0-macos.tar.gzþ:link-firefox-driver-win32: {link-firefox-driver}/geckodriver-v0.14.0-win64.zipþþAutomation Process for Functional Tests on eXo Platform.þþ== OverviewþþTechnical stacks required:þþ* Docker & Docker Compose 1.13+þ* JUnit 5þ* Selenide 4.2 (Selenium 3.0.1)þ* Selenium Grid 3.0.1þ* Maven 3.3.9þþ== Getting Startedþþ=== PLF instance and Selenium Gridþþ[NOTE]þ--þActually we use :þþ* *PLF 5.2.0-Mxx*þ* *Selenium Grid 3.11.0*þ--þþ.Start PLF instance, Selenium Grid and MailHogþ[source, shell]þ----þ$ git clone git@github.com:exoplatform/platform-qa-ui.gitþ$ docker-compose -f core/src/main/resources/stack/docker-compose-50-hsqldb.yml -p qa_ui upþþ# Check that the PLF instance is runningþ$ open http://localhost:8080þþ# Check that the Selenium Grid is UPþ$ open http://localhost:4444/grid/consoleþþ# Check that MailHog is UPþ$ open http://localhost:8025/mail/þ----þþþ=== Drivers for Chrome and Firefoxþþ[IMPORTANT]þ--þThose drivers are required only to run UI tests with your local browsers.þIf you want to execute the *tests with Selenium Grid, you can skip this step*.þ--þþ==== Chrome Driversþþ* Download the *Chrome Driver* compatible with your OS ({link-chrome-driver-notes}[notes]):þ** {link-chrome-driver-linux32}[Linux32] / {link-chrome-driver-linux64}[Linux64]þ** {link-chrome-driver-mac64}[Mac64]þ** {link-chrome-driver-win32}[Win32]þ* Unzip it locallyþ** _ie: /tmp/chromedriver_þþ==== Firefox (gecko) Driversþþ* Download the *Firefox Driver* compatible with your OS ({link-chrome-firefox-notes}[notes]):þ** {link-firefox-driver-linux32}[Linux32] / {link-firefox-driver-linux64}[Linux64]þ** {link-firefox-driver-mac64}[Mac64]þ** {link-firefox-driver-win32}[Win32]þ* Unzip it locallyþ** _ie: /tmp/geckodriver_þþ=== Run UI Tests from your IDEþþ==== Configure IntellIJ IDEAþþ[IMPORTANT]þ--þTo be able to execute JUnit5 Tests with IntellIJ, you need at *least IntellIJ 2018.x*þ--þþ. Configure the test to *add the following System properties* in the `Run > Edit configurations... > VM options` input text +þ `-ea -Dwebdriver.chrome.driver=/tmp/chromedriver -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://localhost:8080`þ.. Run the testþþ=== Run UI Tests from Mavenþþ==== Use browsers in a Selenium GridþþTo launch a local Selenium Grid you just need to launch it with the compose file at the root of this repository :þþ[source,shell]þ.Launch Selenium Grid 01þ----þdocker-compose -f docker-compose-selenium-grid01.yml -p grid01 up -dþ----þþThis will launch 1 Selenium Grid on the local port `4401` with 1 Chrome node and 1 Firefox nodeþþYou can then launch your Maven Automated tests on Chrome or Firefox with one of the following command:þþ[source,shell]þ.Maven tests with Chrome through Selenium Grid 01þ----þmvn  clean verify -Prun-its,grid \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://exo:8080 \þ    -Dremote=http://localhost:4401/wd/hub \þ    -Dselenide.browser=chrome  \þ    -Dselenide.timeout=20000þ----þþ[source,shell]þ.Maven tests with Firefox through Selenium Grid 01þ----þmvn  clean verify -Prun-its,grid \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://exo:8080 \þ    -Dremote=http://localhost:4401/wd/hub \þ    -Dselenide.browser=firefox  \þ    -Dselenide.timeout=20000þ----þþ[NOTE]þ----þYou can also launch more Selenium Grid on your local environment to be able to launch more maven tests in parallel.þFor that we provide 3 different Compose files which use different local ports. When started you just have to be careful in your maven launch command to use the good local port in the `-Dremote=http://localhost:<GRID_PORT>/wd/hub`.þ----þþ|===þ|Start Command |Selenium Grid local portþþ|docker-compose -f docker-compose-selenium-hub01.yml -p grid01 upþ| `-Dremote=http://localhost:4401/wd/hub`þþ|docker-compose -f docker-compose-selenium-hub02.yml -p grid02 upþ| `-Dremote=http://localhost:4402/wd/hub`þþ|docker-compose -f docker-compose-selenium-hub03.yml -p grid03 upþ| `-Dremote=http://localhost:4403/wd/hub`þ|===þþþ==== Use your local browsersþþ[IMPORTANT]þ--þBe sure to have your drivers configured, you can override the default path with Maven system variables:þþ* Firefox: `-Dselenium.webdriver.geckodriver.driver.path=<path-to-driver`þ* Chrome: `-Dselenium.webdriver.chrome.driver.path=<path-to-driver`þ--þþ[source,shell]þ.Run with Maven and Local Chromeþ----þmvn  clean verify -Prun-its,chrome \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://localhost:8080þ----þþ[source,shell]þ.Run with Maven and your local Firefoxþ----þmvn  clean verify -Prun-its,firefox \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://localhost:8080þ----þþ=== Debugþþ[source,java]þ----þ@Testþ@Smokeþ@Tag("smoke")þ@Tag("debug") // <1>þpublic void test01_CheckHomePage() {þ  info("Test 1: Check Home page");þ...þ}þ----þ<1> Tag a test with `@Tag("debug")`þþ.Debug one test tagged with @tag("debug")þ[source,shell]þ----þmvn  clean verify -Prun-its,firefox \þ    -Dselenide.test.tags.include=debug \þ    -Dmaven.failsafe.debug="-Xdebug -Xrunjdwp:transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=y,address=8000 -Xnoagent -Djava.compiler=NONE" \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://localhost:8080þ----þþþ=== Run UI Tests from Maven in Containerþþ[IMPORTANT]þ--þ*mvncw* is an alias to run Maven in Docker *connected to the the network qa_ui*þ--þþ[source,shell]þ.Run All in containers: test with Maven and Selenium Gridþ----þmvncw  clean verify -Prun-its,grid \þ    -Dselenide.baseUrl=http://exo:8080 \þ    -Dremote=http://hub:4444/wd/hub \þ    -Dselenide.browser=chrome  \þ    -Dselenide.timeout=20000þ----þþ== Data for sniff testsþþData for sniff tests, such as Office documents or images, are stored in https://github.com/exoplatform/platform-qa-ui-data[a dedicated Github repository].þThese data are included in the project `platform-qa-ui` thanks to https://git-scm.com/docs/git-submodule[Git submodules].þþAll data pushed in the project `platform-qa-ui-data` are available in the folder `platform/src/test/resources/data` of the project `platform-qa-ui`, þwith the same path.þFor example the file `forum/topic_attachment.txt` of the project `platform-qa-ui-data` is available þat `platform/src/test/resources/data/forum/topic_attachment.txt` in the project `platform-qa-ui`.þþ=== Getting startedþþThe first time the submodule is used (after a git clone for example), the submodule must be initialized.þRun the following commands at the root level of the project `platform-qa-ui`:þ[source,shell]þ----þgit submodule initþgit submodule updateþ----þþYou should now see the data files in the folder `platform/src/test/resources/data`.þþ=== How to add new files ?þþThe parent project is not aware of changes done in the submodule project automatically.þEach time new files are pushed in the submodule project, an update must be explicitly done on parent project.þþNOTE: It is important to understand that the link between the parent project and the submodule is based on a *commit id*,þnot on a branch or a tag. And this commit id in stored in the git index files of parent project.þSo if new files are committed and pushed in the submodule project, if nothing is done on parent project andþif you run again a `git submodule update`, new files will not come up.þYou have to add the option `--remote` to fetch the latest changes of the submodule.þþSo here is how you basically add new files and use them:þþ* commit new files in the project `platform-qa-ui-data`þ* in the project `platform-qa-ui`, at the root level, runþ[source,shell]þ----þgit submodule update --remoteþ----þþAt this point, you should see the new files from `platform-qa-ui-data`.þYou will notice that the working dir in not clean anymore, there are some uncommitted changes. Example:þþ$ git statusþOn branch feature/external-data-setsþYour branch is up-to-date with 'origin/feature/external-data-sets'.þ[source,shell]þ----þChanges not staged for commit:þ  (use "git add <file>..." to update what will be committed)þ  (use "git checkout -- <file>..." to discard changes in working directory)þþ modified:   platform/src/test/resources/data (new commits)þþno changes added to commit (use "git add" and/or "git commit -a")þ----þþSince we pulled the latest changes from the branch and not from the linked commit id of the submodule,þthe commits ids are not the same, which explains the status message.þYou must commit these changes (you probably want to do it as part of the fix/improvements you are working on). þþ=== How to add new files in branches/PR ?þþIf you want to add new files as part of new branches/PR, the new branch must be created in both project and the submodule configuration must be updated.þHere are the steps to follow:þþ* in the project `platform-qa-ui-data`, create the new branch and push it:þ[source,shell]þ----þgit checkout -b new-branchþgit push -u origin new-branchþ----þ* create any new files and push themþþ* in the project `platform-qa-ui`, create the new branch and push it:þ[source,shell]þ----þgit checkout -b new-branchþgit push -u origin new-branchþ----þ* update the value of branch attribute in the file `.gitmodules` with the name of the new branch:þ[source,shell]þ----þ[submodule "platform/src/test/resources/data"]þ        path = platform/src/test/resources/dataþ        url = git@github.com:exoplatform/platform-qa-ui-data.gitþ        branch = new-branchþ----þWARNING: do not commit and push that change. It is only used during the branch life and must not be merged in master branch.þ* update the submodule:þ[source,shell]þ----þgit submodule update --remoteþ----

gemoc-studio
column43: -------------þThis repository is part of a serie of repositories related to [GEMOC Studio](http://eclipse.org/gemoc) :þ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studioþ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-modeldebuggingþ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-execution-aleþ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-execution-javaþ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-execution-moccmlþ- https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-moccmlþ-------------þþGemoc Studioþ============þþThis repository contains the code for assembling the [GEMOC Studio](http://gemoc.org/studio.html) hosted in the Eclipse foundation (see [GEMOC project @ Eclipse](http://www.eclipse.org/gemoc)).þþIt can be downloaded from [gemoc.org/download.html](http://gemoc.org/download.html). (Older builds are available).þþGetting helpþ============þThe [contact page](https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/modeling.gemoc/contact) lists all the various ways to interact in the context of the GEMOC Studio. As a user of the GEMOC Studio you'll probably be interested by the [Mattermost GEMOC Users](https://mattermost.eclipse.org/eclipse/channels/gemoc) channel, the GEMOC User mailing list (to be created soon, in the meantime, you can post questions in the [gemoc-dev](https://dev.eclipse.org/mailman/listinfo/gemoc-dev) mailing list) and the Github trackers (see next section: reporting issue for identifying the best tracker).þþReporting issuesþ============þIn case of trouble with the studio, you can use one the issue trackers of the Studio. Since the Studio is an assembly of various tools and components, the precise tracker will depend on the involved component.þA dashboard of all issues is available as a waffle:  [https://waffle.io/eclipse/gemoc-studio](https://waffle.io/eclipse/gemoc-studio).þþ* https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio/issues : Main/Global tracker, use this tracker if this is an assembly problem or if you don't know which precise component is affected.þ* https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio-modeldebugging/issues : Tracker for issues related to the main framework, to the definition of Sequential languages and to the sequential engine.þþ(Please note that some older issues are still in the old repositories in the GEMOC github organization https://github.com/gemoc)þþSome additional trackers may be used on the repositories of the [GEMOC github organization](https://github.com/gemoc) : typically those related to a given example ( [ActitivityDiagram](https://github.com/gemoc/activitydiagram/issues), [ArduinoModeling](https://github.com/gemoc/arduinomodeling/issues), [ardurobotmodeling](https://github.com/gemoc/ardurobotmodeling/issues))þþþContributingþ============þIf you wish to contribute to the project, you'll find some guidance and tip and tricks on the [project github wiki pages](https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio/wiki).þþDevelopmentþ============þ- Instructions about how to build locally the studio are available in this readme page https://github.com/eclipse/gemoc-studio/tree/master/dev_support/full_compilation or in the [studio documentation](http://download.eclipse.org/gemoc/docs/nightly/_contributing.html#_compilation_of_the_complete_gemoc_studio).þ- Continuous integration on [Eclipse CI](https://ci.eclipse.org/gemoc/job/gemoc-studio/)

column17: The Open Source Controller
column43: image::extra/images/logo-mycontroller.org_full.png[MyController.org, link="http://www.mycontroller.org"]þ:source-language: java, angularjsþþ---þþifdef::env-github[]þimage:https://badges.gitter.im/Join%20Chat.svg[link="https://gitter.im/mycontroller-org/mycontroller?utm_source=badge&utm_medium=badge&utm_campaign=pr-badge&utm_content=badge"]{nbsp}þimage:https://www.paypalobjects.com/en_US/CH/i/btn/btn_donateCC_LG.gif[link="https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=CHWAXCBVHTC64"]þendif::[]þþ[link=https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller]þMaster: image:https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller.svg?branch=master["Build Status", link="https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller"]þ[link=https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller]þDevelopment: image:https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller.svg?branch=development["Build Status", link="https://travis-ci.org/mycontroller-org/mycontroller"]þþ====== Project website: http://www.mycontroller.orgþ====== Forum: http://forum.mycontroller.orgþ====== Want to try now? http://demo.mycontroller.org[Demo server] Authentication: demo/demoþþ== Aboutþþ*MyController.org* is an IoT automation controller for home, office or any place.þPrimarly this project was started to support http://www.mysensors.org/[MySensors]. Later it was expanded to support other networks also. MyController.org was designed to run with limited resources. For instance, it can run on the first generation Raspberry Pi.þþ== LocalizationþMyController.org supports multiple languages. If you are interested in providing a translation for your native language, send a request via https://www.transifex.com/mycontrollerorg/multi-locale/[Transifex MyController.org locale project]þþ== System RequirementsþþMyController.org is a very lightweight server. Its resource requirements are modest:þþ  * Disk        : ~100 MB (may require more space, when we store metrics data for long time)þ  * Memory(RAM) : 256 MBþ  * Java        : 1.8 or laterþþ===== Supported Platforms (tested)þMyController.org is a Java-based application server. It can run on any platform where Java support is available.þþ- Linuxþ- Windowsþ- Orange PIþ- Raspberry PI (Oracle Java recommended)þþ== MyController and MySensors Setupþþimage::extra/images/MyController-MySensors-RF.png[MyController  and MySensors setup.]þþ== Installationþþ====== Download(executable bundle),þþ* Visit MyController.org http://www.mycontroller.org/#/downloads[downloads page]þþ====== ConfigurationþþExtract the downloaded bundle in the directory where you want it to run. The configuration files are located in `mycontroller/conf`þþFile: `mycontroller.properties`þþ*Temporary files*þ----þmcc.tmp.location=tmp/ # <1>þ----þ<1> You can change the default location and file name. This directory is used as a temporary location for operations such as backup, restore, etc.þþ*Database Configuration*þ----þmcc.db.h2db.location=../conf/mycontroller # <1>þ----þ<1> You can change the default location and file name. The database file will be stored with the extension `.h2.db`. Do not add file extension to this property.þþ*Web server configuration*þ----þmcc.web.bind.address=0.0.0.0 # <1>þmcc.web.enable.https=true  # <2>þmcc.web.http.port=8443  # <3>þmcc.web.file.location=../www/  # <4>þmcc.web.ssl.keystore.file=../conf/keystore.jks  # <5>þmcc.web.ssl.keystore.password=mycontroller  # <5>þmcc.web.ssl.keystore.type=JKS  # <5>þ----þþ<1> Bind interface address. 0.0.0.0 means it will bind to all available interfaces.þ<2> Enable/disable https. Only one protocol is supported at a time. true - `https`, false - `http`.þ<3> Port number of `http/https` to access MyController.org server.þ<4> Web files location, no need to touch this one.þ<5> If `https` is enabled these fields are mandatory.þþDefault URL: `https://<ip>:8443` (ex: `https://localhost:8443`)þþNOTE: Default username/password: `admin/admin`þþ*Important*: Change default `mcc.web.ssl.keystore.file` and `mcc.web.ssl.keystore.password` and `https` protocol isþrecommendedþþ*MQTT broker configuration*þ----þmcc.mqtt.broker.enable=true # <1>þmcc.mqtt.broker.bind.address=0.0.0.0 # <2>þmcc.mqtt.broker.port=1883 # <3>þmcc.mqtt.broker.websocket.port=7080 # <4>þmcc.mqtt.broker.persistent.store=../conf/moquette/moquette_store.mapdb # <5>þ----þþ<1> Enable/disable builtin MQTT broker. By default it is enabled. `true`- enabled, `false` - disabledþ<2> Bind interface address for the MQTT broker. By default it will bind to all available interfaces.þ<3> MQTT broker portþ<4> Websoicket portþ<5> Internal use. no need to touch this one.þþþ*Logger configuration*þþConfiguration File Name: `logback.xml`þþDefault log file location: `logs/mycontroller.log`þþ====== Start/Stop ServerþExecutable scripts are located in `mycontroller/bin/`þþ* Linuxþ    - Start : `./start.sh`þ    - Stop  : `./stop.sh`þþ* Windowsþ    - Start : Double click on `start.bat`þ    - Stop  : `Ctrl+C`þþ* Other Platformsþþ```þjava -Xms8m -Xmx256m -Dlogback.configurationFile=../conf/logback.xml -Dmc.conf.file=../conf/mycontroller.properties -cp "../lib/*" org.mycontroller.standalone.StartAppþ```

column43: # Buenas prácticas de desarrollo AndroidþþA continuación encontrarán una serie de buenas prácticas a tomar en cuenta para a la hora de programar aplicaciones móvilesþpara las plataformas Android.þComo bien sabemos a la hora de desarrollar aplicaciones nativas para Android, usamos el lenguaje de programación Java y en estaþocación el IDE oficial Android Studio.þSi bien Android Studio nos ofrece de por defecto la estructura general del proyecto, a medida que vayamos profundizando en el desarrolloþde una aplicación o vayamos creando aplicaciones más complejas necesitaremos crear un código entendible por cualquier miembro del equipo,þun código modular que pueda ser escalable fácilmente y por sobre todo un código limpio basándonos en estándares de programación queþsolo los buenos desarrolladores siguen.þþþhttps://github.com/futurice/android-best-practicesþhttps://github.com/futurice/android-best-practices/tree/master/templates/rx-architectureþþþ## Estructura del proyectoþþEsta es la estructura base que nos proporciona Android Studio al crear un proyecto para aplicaciones móviles.þþ```þ├─ appþ│  ├─ libsþ│  ├─ srcþ│  │  ├─ androidTestþ│  │  │  └─ javaþ│  │  │     └─ com/domain/projectþ│  │  └─ mainþ│  │     ├─ javaþ│  │     │  └─ com/domain/projectþ│  │     ├─ resþ│  │     └─ AndroidManifest.xmlþ│  ├─ build.gradleþ│  └─ proguard-rules.proþ├─ build.gradleþ└─ settings.gradleþ```þþþ### Estructura /javaþþ> **Nota:**þ>þ> - El paquete **java** es un contenedor de clases para diferentes fines dentro de la aplicación.þ> - El IDE Android Studio provee por defecto las carpetas bases.þ> - Si un paquete contiene sub carpetas solo valdrá la pena crear las carpetas si estas contienen clases.þ> - Las carpetas debe estar en minuscula y en singular.þþ```þ├─ javaþ│  ├─ com.domain.projectþ│     ├─ activityþ│     ├─ fragmentþ│     ├─ modelþ│     ├─ adapterþ│     ├─ configþ│     ├─ dialogþ│     ├─ networkingþ│     ├─ backgroundþ│     ├─ databaseþ│     ├─ sessionþ│
