R.drawable.gray_round_button : R.drawable.blue_round_button);þ    }þþ    public void setDisable(boolean disable) {þ        setBackgroundResource(disable ? R.drawable.gray_round_button : R.drawable.blue_round_button);þ    }þ}þþ```þþ### Estructura JAVAþþ#### Nomenclatura de paquetesþLos paquetes se nombran en singular y con letras minúsculas.þ```þactivityþfragmentþadapterþmodelþutilþ```þþ#### Nomenclatura de clasesþLas clases java se nombran utilizando el estándar “UpperCamelCase”, es decir utilizandoþuna combinación de palabras que empiezan con mayúscula como “ClasePrincipal”.þ```þMainActivityþLoginActivityþRegisterFragmentþDetailFragmentþ```þþ### Estructura de un layoutþ```xmlþ<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>þ<android.support.constraint.ConstraintLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"þ    xmlns:app="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res-auto"þ    xmlns:tools="http://schemas.android.com/tools"þ    android:layout_width="match_parent"þ    android:layout_height="match_parent"þ    tools:context="com.example.leo.componet.dummy.MainActivity">þþ        <ImageViewþ            android:id="@+id/global_image"þ            android:layout_width="wrap_content"þ            android:layout_height="wrap_content"þ            app:srcCompat="@mipmap/ic_launcher"þ            android:layout_marginRight="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintRight_toRightOf="parent"þ            android:layout_marginLeft="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintLeft_toLeftOf="parent"þ            app:layout_constraintTop_toTopOf="parent"þ            android:layout_marginTop="199dp" />þþ        <TextViewþ            android:id="@+id/inicio_text"þ            android:layout_width="wrap_content"þ            android:layout_height="wrap_content"þ            android:text="TextView"þ            android:textAppearance="@style/TextAppearance.AppCompat.Body2"þ            android:textSize="24sp"þ            android:layout_marginRight="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintRight_toRightOf="parent"þ            android:layout_marginLeft="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintLeft_toLeftOf="parent"þ            android:layout_marginTop="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintTop_toBottomOf="@+id/imageView"þ            app:layout_constraintBottom_toBottomOf="parent"þ            app:layout_constraintHorizontal_bias="0.501"þ            android:layout_marginBottom="8dp"þ            app:layout_constraintVertical_bias="0.0" />þþ</android.support.constraint.ConstraintLayout>þ```þþ### Comentar una clasesþ```javaþ/**þ  * Initializing GUIþ  **/þprivate void init() {þ    Toolbar toolbar = (Toolbar) findViewById(R.id.toolbar);þ    TextView text = (TextView) findViewById(R.id.text);þ}þ```þþ### Estructura RESþþ#### Nomenclatura de paquetesþAl igual que en la sección Java, también se nombran los paquetes en minúsculas peroþno siempre en singular, habrá casos en los que usemos plurales como la carpeta “values”þy otros casos donde se usan guiones como en el caso de crear carpetas para para soporte deþde versiones android como “values-v21”.þ```þdrawableþlayoutþmanuþvaluesþvalues-v21þ```þþ### Definir formato de Colors.xmlþþ```xmlþ<resources>þþ        <color name="colorPrimary">@color/red</color>þ        <color name="colorPrimaryDark">@color/red300</color>þ        <color name="colorAccent">@color/blue</color>þþ        <color name="red">#ff0000</color>þ        <color name="red100">#560033</color>þ        <color name="red300">#560033</color>þ        <color name="red700">#560033</color>þ        <color name="redOpacity40">#711616</color>þ        <color name="redOpacity60">#711616</color>þþ        <color name="blue">#310004ff</color>þ        <color name="blue50">#310004ff</color>þ        <color name="blueOpacity50">#310004ff</color>þþ</resources>þ```þþ### Definir formato de dimens.xmlþþ```xmlþ<resources>þþ    <dimen name="text1">1sp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="text2">2sp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="text3">3sp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="text4">4sp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="text5">5sp</dimen>þþ    <dimen name="size1">1dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="size2">2dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="size3">3dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="size4">4dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="size5">5dp</dimen>þþ    <dimen name="spacing1">1dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="spacing2">2dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="spacing3">3dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="spacing4">4dp</dimen>þ    <dimen name="spacing5">5dp</dimen>þþ</resources>þ```þþ### Definir cadenas estáticas por pantalla en strings.xmlþþ```xmlþ<resources>þþ    <!-- activity login -->þ    <string name="login_title">Titulo del Activity</string>þ    <string name="login_text_descripcion">Descripcion</string>þþ    <!-- Error -->þ    <string name="error_usuario">Error el usuario no esta registrado</string>þþ</resources>þ```þþ#### Nomenclatura de un includeþþAl crear un includ se nombrará de la siguiente formaþCuando la vista contenga un Toolbar - > `app_bar_main.xml` , `app_bar_contact.xml`þþ```xmlþ  <includeþ        layout="@layout/app_bar_main"þ        android:layout_width="match_parent"þ        android:layout_height="match_parent" />þ```þþCuando la vista forma parte de la ventana -> `custom_contact.xml , custom_about.xml`þþ```xmlþ  <includeþ        android:id="@+id/custom_contact"þ        layout="@layout/custom_contact"þ        android:layout_width="match_parent"þ        android:layout_height="match_parent" />þ```þþCuando la vista sea el contenedor de los fragments- > `content_menu.xml`þþ#### Uso de las carpetas “mipmap“ y “drawable”þAndroid Studio nos provee por defecto de ambas carpetas para almacenar los recursos gráficos del proyecto.þþLa carpeta `mipmap`, sirve exclusivamente para almacenar el icon launcher de la aplicación, es decir que soloþalmacenará los archivos `ic_launcher.png` y su distribución será así:þ```þ├─ mipmap-hdpiþ│  ├─ ic_launcher.pngþ│  |þ├─ mipmap-mdpiþ│  ├─ ic_launcher.pngþ│  |þ├─ mipmap-xhdpiþ│  ├─ ic_launcher.pngþ│  |þ├─ mipmap-xxhdpiþ│  ├─ ic_launcher.pngþ│  |þ├─ mipmap-xxxhdpiþ│  ├─ ic_launcher.pngþ│  |þ```þþLa carpeta `drawable`, sirve para almacenar recursos .xml tales como los selector, shape y derivados.þLa carpeta `drawable-hdpi`, `drawable-xhdpi`y demás sirven para almcenar los recursos gráficos de la aplicación, como íconos, logos, imágenes de fondo, etc.þþ#### Utilizar fuentes de textoþSi bien Androi Studio no nos provee de una carpeta por defecto para almacenar archivos .ttf .otf o derivados, podemos optar por crear nuestra propiaþpaquetería para almacenar otros archivos que no sea recursos gráficos.þþCrearemos una carpeta llamanda `assets` y dentro crearemos la carpeta `font`, aquí podremos guardar nuestros archivos .ttf o derivados.þþ```þ─ mainþ   ├─ assetsþ   │  └─ fontþ   ├─ javaþ   │  └─ com/domain/projectþ   ├─ resþ   └─ AndroidManifest.xmlþ```þþ### Librerías a utilizarþþ    Butter Knife -> https://github.com/JakeWharton/butterknife#butter-knifeþ    picasso -> http://square.github.io/picasso/þ    Retrofit -> http://square.github.io/retrofit/þ    mpandroidchart -> https://github.com/PhilJay/MPAndroidChartþ    firebase -> https://firebase.google.com/

column17: xml-doclet imported from http://code.google.com/p/xml-doclet/
column43: This code was cloned from http://code.google.com/p/xml-doclet/þwith minimal modifications. Many tanks to Seth Call for writing it.þþAdditional thanks to lhunath@lyndir.com who provided a patch to adopt þthis code with javadoc tool: http://code.google.com/p/xml-doclet/issues/detail?id=1þþOverviewþ===========þþThis tool uses javadoc to parse java source files. Javadoc providesþan API (doclet), which is being used to drive the generation of XML. Forþa given invocation of this doclet, one monolithic XML file is generatedþwhich is the sum of all clasess, methods, enums, interfaces, exceptions,þand any other documentable entity within Java.þþþStructure of the Generated XMLþ------------------------------þþThe XML file generated by xml-doclet has as top-level entities which areþ1st-class members of Java. Specifically, `class`, `interface`, `enum`,þand `exception` are top-level entities in this file. Methods, fields,þmethod arguments, and other sub-entities occur as child elements of theþtop-level entities, in order to preserve their relationships with theþtop-level entities. These sub-entities usually refer to the typeþinformation of one of the top-level entities; this is accomplishedþsimply be referring to the full type name of that top-level entity.þþþProject Basicsþ--------------þThis project is completely maven-based.  The heart of a maven project isþthe pom.xml file, which defines dependencies, plugins, and otherþproject-related items.þþþBuilding the Projectþ--------------------þTo build the project and run unit tests, one can execute from the projectþroot dir:  þmvn clean test þþþPackaging the Projectþ---------------------þTo package the project using the maven appassembler plugin, execute: þmvn package appassembler:assemble þþIf you run appassembler with the above command, a bat script and shellþscript will be created by this plugin and placed inþproject_root_dir/target/appassembler/bin. This script can be invokedþdirectly with just the command line arguments of xml-doclet.  To seeþhelp on xml-doclet, execute:þproject_root_dir/target/appassembler/xmldoclet --helpþþþRunning the Projectþ-------------------þTo see xml-doclet in action, you could run it against this project:þþproject_root_dir/target/appassembler/bin/xmldoclet -sp project_root_dir/src/main/java -sub comþþNOTE!!!  appassembler changes the working directory to project_root_dir/target/appassemblerþþSo running this example from the project root dir on windows:þþ> ./target/appassembler/bin/xmldoclet.bat -sp ../../src/main/java/ -sub comþþon mac:þþ> sh ./target/appassembler/bin/xmldoclet -sp ../../src/main/java/ -sub comþþThe resulting output file in this case would be at:þ./target/appassembler/javadoc.xmlþþIDE Integration: Intellij IDEAþ------------------------------þTo use with Intellij IDEA, the latest version supports maven-based projectsþnatively.  All you should have to do is open the pom.xml and Intellijþwill create a project for you.þþþIDE Integration: Eclipseþ------------------------þþTo use with Eclipse, you will need a maven plugin, such as m2 or q4e.

column17: Jenkins SourceSafe Journal Plugin
column43: Jenkins SourceSafe Journal Pluginþ=================================þþProvides Jenkins integration with Visual SourceSafe Journal file.þþThe goal of this plugin was to provide a simple monitoring of changes in SourceSafe, þwithout the need of a local SourceSafe installation or COM. It is similar toþthe [FSTrigger Plugin](https://wiki.jenkins-ci.org/display/JENKINS/FSTrigger+Plugin), butþcan also parse the journal file and display that information as change log entries.þþIt can also get the latest versions of files using the [SS command line utility](http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/5ws92cw2%28v=vs.80%29.aspx) [GET command](http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/661w6e3d%28v=vs.80%29.aspx).þþSee also [SourceSafe Plugin](https://wiki.jenkins-ci.org/display/JENKINS/Visual+SourceSafe+Plugin).þþLicenseþ-------þþ (The MIT License)þþ Copyright (c) 2015 Patrick Lauperþþ Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any person obtainingþ a copy of this software and associated documentation files (theþ 'Software'), to deal in the Software without restriction, includingþ without limitation the rights to use, copy, modify, merge, publish,þ distribute, sublicense, and/or sell copies of the Software, and toþ permit persons to whom the Software is furnished to do so, subject toþ the following conditions:þþ The above copyright notice and this permission notice shall beþ included in all copies or substantial portions of the Software.þþ THE SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED 'AS IS', WITHOUT WARRANTY OF ANY KIND,þ EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO THE WARRANTIES OFþ MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE AND NONINFRINGEMENT.þ IN NO EVENT SHALL THE AUTHORS OR COPYRIGHT HOLDERS BE LIABLE FOR ANYþ CLAIM, DAMAGES OR OTHER LIABILITY, WHETHER IN AN ACTION OF CONTRACT,þ TORT OR OTHERWISE, ARISING FROM, OUT OF OR IN CONNECTION WITH THEþ SOFTWARE OR THE USE OR OTHER DEALINGS IN THE SOFTWARE.

column17: A shoddily balanced dumpster-fire of a mod about nuclear weapons, technology, and many, many unfunny jokes.
column43: # Hbm-s-Nuclear-Tech-GITþþhttps://minecraft.curseforge.com/projects/hbms-nuclear-tech-mod?gameCategorySlug=mc-mods&projectID=235439þþFor a 1.12 fork, check this link: https://github.com/Drillgon200/Hbm-s-Nuclear-Tech-GIT/releasesþþ## Installation InstructionsþþTired of waiting until the next version comes out? Here is a tutorial on how to compile the very newest version yourself:þ1. Download minecraft forge 1.7.10 srcþ2. Unpack it somewhereþ3. Download the source and insert it into the same folder. This will overwrite a couple of files, for example build.gradleþ4. Run `gradlew setupDecompWorkspace` on windows or `./gradlew setupDecompWorkspace` on linux (remember: do not take the name of root in vain). Running this command on a blank forge workspace will yield errors, so it's important you insert the mod's source in step 3. The source has corrected versions of guild.gradle and the gradle wrapper, if done correctly it should run just fine.þ5. The `build.gradle` file will reference these following files:þ```þcompile files('lib/CodeChickenCore-1.7.10-1.0.4.29-dev.jar')þcompile files('lib/CodeChickenLib-1.7.10-1.1.3.140-dev.jar')þcompile files('lib/NotEnoughItems-1.7.10-1.0.3.74-dev.jar')þ```þwhich means you need to do one of the following things:þ1) Find these exact versions of the dependencies, download them and put them into a folder called `libs` in your project's root folder. You can download a zip containing all files here: https://bit.ly/3fBxMq0þ2) Find other versions, change the `build.gradle` file to reflect this difference and fix any potential errors this could cause (unlikely but not impossible)þ3) Remove these dependencies from `build.gradle` along with all the API code. Note that this will break NEI-integration.þ7. Open up the CMD in the root directory and run `gradlew build` on windows or `./gradlew build` on linuxþ8. Head over to `build/libs` and get the jar (named modid.jar)þ9. Open the jar file with an archieve manager of your choice and insert the mod's asset folder into the jar's main directoryþþIf you want to do some changes in the code yourself, start here after 6. and continue with 7. once you are done:þ1) Get the IDE of your choice and prepare the workspace (for eclipse, it's `gradlew eclipse` or `./gradlew eclipse`, then use the eclipse folder as workspace directory in eclipse)þ2) Meddle with the code, you can always test the code in the IDE (eclipse has a convenient green play button)þ3) Save changes, close the IDE and continue with 7. of the previous listþþ## Installation Instructions for a non-standard WorkspaceþþI cannot offer any help on compiling the mod in a GregTech-workspace as I never managed to get it to work myself, here's a rough guide on how it might be possible:þ1. Prepare the workspaceþ2. Slap this mod's `src` into the project's root directoryþ3. Prayþþ# LicenseþþThis software is licensed under the GNU Public License version 3. In short: This software is free, you may run the software freely, create modified versions, distribute this software and distribute modified versions, as long as the modified software too has a free software license. You win this round, Stallman. The full license can be found in the `LICENSE` file.

column17: This plugin uses Google's Fused Locations API to provide the user's current location in an energy efficient way. It also allows the user to define geo-tagged areas.
column43: AWARE Plugin: Google Fused Locationþ===================================þþ[![Release](https://jitpack.io/v/denzilferreira/com.aware.plugin.google.fused_location.svg)](https://jitpack.io/#denzilferreira/com.aware.plugin.google.fused_location)þþThis plugin uses Google's Fused Locations API to provide the user's current location in an energy efficient way. It also allows the user to define geo-tagged areas.þþ# SettingsþParameters adjusted on the dashboard and client:þ* **status_google_fused_location**: (boolean) activate/deactivate pluginþ* **frequency_google_fused_location**: (integer) How frequently to fetch user's location (in seconds), default 300 secondsþ* **max_frequency_google_fused_location**: (integer) How fast are you willing to get the latest location (in seconds), default 60 secondsþ* **accuracy_google_fused_location**: (integer) One of the following:þ    * 100 (high power): uses GPS only - works best outdoors, highest accuracyþ    * 102 (balanced): uses GPS, Network and Wifi - works both indoors and outdoors, good accuracy (default)þ    * 104 (low power): uses only Network and WiFi - poorest accuracy, medium accuracyþ    * 105 (no power) - scavenges location requests from other appsþ* **fallback_location_timeout**: (integer) wait X seconds for GPS satellite fix to timeout, default 20 secondsþ* **location_sensitivity**: (integer) move more than X meter(s) to request another location fix, default 5 metersþþ# Broadcastsþ**ACTION_AWARE_LOCATIONS**þBroadcasted when we have a new location, with the following extras:þ- **data**: (Location) latest location informationþþ**ACTION_AWARE_PLUGIN_FUSED_ENTERED_GEOFENCE**þBroadcasted when we are inside a geofence, with the following extras:þ- **label**: (String) geofence labelþ- **location**: (Location) geofence location informationþ- **radius**: (double) geofence radius (in meters)þþ**ACTION_AWARE_PLUGIN_FUSED_EXITED_GEOFENCE**þBroadcasted when we left a geofence, with the following extras:þ- **label**: (String) geofence labelþ- **location**: (Location) geofence location informationþ- **radius**: (double) geofence radius (in meters)þ    þ# Providersþ##  Locations Dataþ> content://com.aware.provider.locations/locationsþþField | Type | Descriptionþ----- | ---- | -----------þ_id | INTEGER | primary key auto-incrementedþtimestamp | REAL | unix timestamp in milliseconds of sampleþdevice_id | TEXT | AWARE device IDþdouble_latitude | REAL | the location’s latitude, in degreesþdouble_longitude | REAL | the location’s longitude, in degreesþdouble_bearing | REAL | the location’s bearing, in degreesþdouble_speed | REAL | the speed if available, in meters/second over groundþdouble_altitude | REAL | the altitude if available, in meters above sea levelþprovider | TEXT | gps, network, fusedþaccuracy | INTEGER | the estimated location accuracyþlabel | TEXT | Customizable label. Useful for data calibration and traceabilityþþ##  Geofencesþ> content://com.aware.plugin.google.fused_location.provider.geofences/fused_geofencesþþField | Type | Descriptionþ----- | ---- | -----------þ_id | INTEGER | primary key auto-incrementedþtimestamp | REAL | unix timestamp in milliseconds of sampleþdevice_id | TEXT | AWARE device IDþgeofence_label | TEXT | user-defined label for this geofenceþdouble_latitude | REAL | the location’s latitude, in degreesþdouble_longitude | REAL | the location’s longitude, in degreesþdouble_radius | REAL | the geofence radius (in meters)þþ##  Geofences Dataþ> content://com.aware.plugin.google.fused_location.provider.geofences/fused_geofences_dataþþField | Type | Descriptionþ----- | ---- | -----------þ_id | INTEGER | primary key auto-incrementedþtimestamp | REAL | unix timestamp in milliseconds of sampleþdevice_id | TEXT | AWARE device IDþgeofence_label | TEXT | user-defined label for this geofenceþdouble_latitude | REAL | the location’s latitude, in degreesþdouble_longitude | REAL | the location’s longitude, in degreesþdouble_distance | REAL | distance between current location and geofence center (in kilometers)þstatus | INTEGER | 1 = entered, 0 = exited geofence

column17: Java library that is able to parse EBNF Syntax and automatically generate a finite state machine for the specified formal language.
column43: This parser is able to parse EBNF (Backus-Naur) grammar rules of any formal language and automatically build a finite state machine out of these rules that can verify any String input of that language and determine the next legal inputs.þþþQuick Documentation:þ*  Parser is your API Interface for inputting backus-naur rules and retrieve a "LanguageVerificationDevice" back.þ*  LanguageVerificationDevice is an interface atm only implemented by FiniteStateMachine that allows you to verify language input and determine the next legal inputsþþSee examples provided within the Main class for further info on how to use this code.þþþ# NOTE:þ* I now know a a lot more about theoretical computer science to understand, that this approach will only work for a narrow subset of all formal languages. This project won't be deleted because it still is a part of my past work efforts.

column43: # Gluon Attach #þþGluon [Attach](http://gluonhq.com/products/mobile/attach/) is the component that addresses the integration with low-level platform APIs in an end-to-end Java Mobile solution.þþAttach provides an uniform, platform-independent API to access device and hardware features. þAt runtime, the appropriate implementation (attach:desktop, attach:android, attach:ios) makes sure the platform specific code is þused to deliver the functionality.þþAttach is open source, and it is freely licensed under the GPL license.þ[Gluon](http://gluonhq.com) can provide [custom consultancy](http://gluonhq.com/services/consulting/) and [training](http://gluonhq.com/services/training/), commercial licenses, and open source [commercial support](http://gluonhq.com/services/commercial-support/), including daily and monthly releases.þþ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.gluonhq.attach/util)](https://search.maven.org/search?q=g:com.gluonhq.attach%20AND%20a:util)þ[![Travis CI](https://api.travis-ci.com/gluonhq/attach.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.com/gluonhq/attach)þ[![License: GPL v3](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-GPLv3-blue.svg)](https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0)þþþ## Getting started ##þþThe best way to get started with Gluon Attach is using the [Gluon Client Maven archetype from your IDE](https://github.com/gluonhq/client-maven-archetypes)þand creating a [Gluon Mobile](http://gluonhq.com/products/mobile) project.þþThe [Gluon Client samples](https://github.com/gluonhq/client-samples) are a good way to find out how Attach is used.þþSee the [documentation](https://docs.gluonhq.com/client/#_attach_configuration) on how to add Attach with the Client Plugin.þþThe list of available services at Attach can be found [here](http://gluonhq.com/products/mobile/attach/).þþþ## Issues and Contributions ##þþIssues can be reported to the [Issue tracker](https://github.com/gluonhq/attach/issues)þþContributions can be submitted via [Pull requests](https://github.com/gluonhq/attach/pulls), þ providing you have signed the [Gluon Individual Contributor License Agreement (CLA)](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/16aoFTmzs8lZTfiyrEm8YgMqMYaGQl0J8wA0VJE2LCCY) þ (See [What is a CLA and why do I care](https://www.clahub.com/pages/why_cla) in case of doubt).þþþ## Building Attach ##þþGluon Attach is frequently released, and this is only required in case you want to fork and build your local version of Attach.þþ### Requisites ###þþThese are the requisites:þþ* A recent version of [JDK 11](http://jdk.java.net/11/)þ* Gradle 5.0 or superior. þþTo build the iOS Services:þ þ* A Mac with with MacOS X 10.11.5 or superiorþ* XCode 9.x or superiorþþ### How to build and install Attach ###þþTo build the Attach services on the project's root, run:þþ`./gradlew clean build`þþIf you want to install them, run:þþ`./gradlew  clean publishToMavenLocal`þþWhen the process finishes successfully, the different services can be added to a Gluon Mobile project.þþFor instance, the Display service for desktop can be added to the project like:þþ```þ<!-- dependencies -->þ<dependency>þ    <groupId>com.gluonhq.attach</groupId>þ    <artifactId>display</artifactId>þ    <version>4.0.6-SNAPSHOT</version>þ</dependency>þþ<!-- plugin -->þ<configuration>þ    <attachList>þ        <list>display</list>þ    </attachList>þ</configuration>þ```

column17: A classic game of chess with a hint of artificial intelligence
column43: # Chess [![MIT license](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue.svg)](https://lbesson.mit-license.org/)þA classic game of chess with a hint of artificial intelligence þ þþþ### Under DevelopmentþþThis is a *mostly* functional game of chess written in java. The project is beingþdeveloped under the *Model-View-Controller (MVC)* design pattern. There are alsoþsome uses of the *factory* design pattern. The goal is to hopefully use machine learning algorithms to þplay chess instead of using the traditional brute force method þof searching a decision tree. þþ### Currrent Structureþ![UML](Chess_UML.png)þþ## Goalsþ> The primary goal of this project is to create well organized and well documented software.  þþ### To Be Implemented:þ* ~~castling~~þ* ~~pawn on pawn en passante~~þ* players, ~~clocks~~, ~~movelogs~~þ* pawn promotionþ* ~~player turns~~þ* a brute force engineþ* a more aesthetic guiþ* ability to play onlineþ* a machine learning algorithm  þþ## Getting Started  þþ### CloningþþTo import this chess software, execute the following line of code in your command consoleþþ```þ git clone https://github.com/haxdds/Chess.gitþ```þþ### Running  þþTo run the current version of this chess software, execute the following lines of codeþin your command console in the .../Chess/src/chess directory:þ```þ javac Test.javaþ java Testþ```þThis should cause the chess gui to pop up. þþ### If using bash  þþin your terminal runþþ`make`þþfrom this projects root directory.þthen it should be compiled then the gui should show up.þþIf your on windows checkout:þþhttps://gist.github.com/evanwill/0207876c3243bbb6863e65ec5dc3f058þþto install make for git bash.þþ## Release History  þþ* 0.0.1þ    * Work in progress  þþ## ContributingþþWe love your input! We want to make contributing to this project as easy and transparent as possible, whether it's:þþ- Reporting a bugþ- Discussing the current state of the codeþ- Submitting a fixþ- Proposing new featuresþ- Becoming a maintainerþþ## Authorsþþ* **Rahul Chowdhury** - [haxdds](https://github.com/haxdds)þ* **Stephon Lawrence** - [stephonlawrence](https://github.com/stephonlawrence)

load the demo data (strongly advised if you are new toþOFBiz) with the following command on the command lineþfrom the OFBiz home folder (in Unix-like operating systemsþtype "./ant" rather than "ant" to use the embed ant versionþ if you haven't installed it on your system) :þþant load-demoþþThen start OFBiz:þþant startþþ(or "java -Xms128M -Xmx512M -jar ofbiz.jar")þ(you can also run directly "ant load-demo start")þþOnce OFBiz starts, you can look at the demo storefront at:þhttp://localhost:8080/ecommerceþþthe back office at:þhttps://localhost:8443/ordermgrþþand the administration interface platform dependent scripts in theþ"tools" folder (for example for Windows and Unix-like operatingþsystems, the startup scripts are startofbiz.bat and startofbiz.sh).þþNote that the default column17: Apache Archiva
column43: Archiva Redback - Documentationþ===============================þ:toc:þþþ== How to build and publish the pages for the archiva web contentþþThis module and the children contain web content and project reports that can be published to the þarchiva web site: https://archiva.apache.orgþþThe web content parts of this module and submodules are published to the path þþ  /redback/coreþþ=== Use the scriptþþThere is a shell script +deploySite.sh+ which you can run to generate the site check and publish to þthe remote repository. It works only on Linux, on other platforms you have to go the next section.þþThe script is interactive, it asks you to confirm the publish after generation of the staging part.þþ.Executeþþ  ./deploySite.sh þþAll arguments are appended to the mvn calls.þþ=== Run the mvn steps manuallyþþ==== Building the pagesþþYou need enough free disk space to publish the web content. The archiva web site repository is big, þbut the maven build will only checkout the necessary directories for this build (sparse checkout).þþFor all the commands you have to change to this archiva-modules directory:þþ  cd archiva/archiva-modulesþþ.The following creates the site to the staging folderþþ  mvn clean site site:stageþþThe result can be checked in þþ  archiva-modules/target/staging/ref/${project.version}þþwith your browser.þþIf you would like the use a local checkout of the archiva-web-content.git repository and not push directlyþto the remote repository, you may add this parameter:þþ  -DsiteRepositoryUrl=scm:git:file:///${path-to-your-local-archiva}/archiva-web-content.gitþþwhere +${path-to-your-local-archiva}+ is the path where a bare clone of the archiva-web-content.git is stored.þþNOTE: You cannot use +mvn site:run+ because this will place the submodules into the same folder and þ      overwrite each other.þþ==== Publish the pagesþþ.This command publishes to the git repositoryþþ  mvn scm-publish:publish-scmþþAfter publishing to the git repository the gitpubsub mechanism is transferring it to the HTTP server.þþIf you would like the use a local checkout of the archiva-web-content.git repository and not push directlyþto the remote repository, you may add this parameter:þþ  -DsiteRepositoryUrl=scm:git:file:///${path-to-your-local-archiva}/archiva-web-content.gitþþþ=== Some notes about the build processþþA sparse checkout of the git repository will be created in þþ .site-contentþþbut only, if the directory +.site-content/.git+ does not exist.

# Alkomat 3000þþ![Android Build](https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp/workflows/Android%20Build/badge.svg?branch=master)þþþ![](screenshots/mainscreen.png)þ![](screenshots/adddrink.png)þþ### Installing the appþDownload the [app as .apk](https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp/releases) and copy it to your android phone.þOpen the file browser and navigate to the apk file. To install it, click on it and accept the warning. Enjoy the app :)þþ### Fork & Clone the repoþIf you haven't already, fork [this repo](https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp/fork).þþ#### Android StudioþClone the **alcoholtestapp app** in Android Studio:þþ1. Choose **VCS > Checkout from Version Control > GitHub** on the main menu.þ2. From the **Repository** drop-down list, select the source repository to clone the data from.þ3. In the **Folder** text box, specify the directory where the local repository for cloned sources will be set up.þ4. Click the Clone button to start cloning the sources from the specified remote repository.þþ#### Command line Gitþ[Clone the alcoholtestapp](https://help.github.com/articles/fork-a-repo#step-2-clone-your-fork)þþOpen your terminal, navigate to your working directory, use `git clone` to get a local copy of the repo.þþ```þ# Clones your fork of the repository into the current directory in terminalþ$ git clone https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/alcoholtestapp.gitþ```þþ### Configure remote upstream for your forkþTo sync changes you make in a fork with this repository, you must configure a remote that points to the upstream repository in Git.þþ- Open a terminal or command promptþ- List the current configured remote repository for your forkþþ```þ$ git remote -vþorigin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/alcoholtestapp.git (fetch)þorigin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/alcoholtestapp.git (push)þ```þþ- Specify a new remote upstream repositoryþþ```þ$ git remote add upstream https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp.gitþ```þþ- Verify the new upstream repositoryþþ```þ$ git remote -vþþorigin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/alcoholtestapp.git (fetch)þorigin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/alcoholtestapp.git (push)þupstream https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp.git (fetch)þupstream https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp.git (push)þ```þþ#### Sync your forkþOnce you have set up a remote upstream, you can keep your fork up to date with our repository by syncing your fork.þþ- Open a terminal or command promptþ- Change to the current working directory of your local repositoryþ- Fetch the branches and commits from the upstream repository.  Commits to `master` will be stored in a local branch, `upstream/master`.þþ```þ$ git fetch upstreamþ```þþ- Check out your forks local `master` branchþþ```þ$ git checkout masterþ```þþ- Merge changes from `upstream/master` into  your local `master` branch which syncs your forks `master` branch with our repository.þþ```þ$ git merge upstream/masterþ```þþ#### Import Gradle project into Android StudioþOnce the project is cloned to disk you can import into Android Studio:þþ* From the toolbar select **File > Import Project**, or **Import Non-Android Studio project** from the Welcome Quick Start.þ* Navigate to the root project folder, **alcoholtestapp** directory and click **OK**þþ### Build the feedback serverþþThe feedback server is used by the feedback feature in the app, which allows users toþsend a message and general device diagnostics to the developer. It is an HTTPS serverþwritten in [Go](https://golang.org/). It takes messages in JSON (see [below](https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp#feedback) for the format) and forwards them to the specified e-mail address.þþFirst, install the `gomail` package to compile the feedback server.þþ```þgo get gopkg.in/gomail.v1þ```þþYou need a new file called `config.go` in the `feedback` directory. The file is .gitignoredþsince it holds the password for the feedback server's mail account.þþ```goþpackage mainþþconst (þ        // address of the feedback botþ        FromAddr = "foo@bar.de"þþ        // Password of the feedback botþ        Passwd = "secretpassword"þþ        // SMTP server of the feedback botþ        SMTPSrv = "smtp-mail.bar.com"þ        SMTPPort = "587"þþ        // your mail addressþ        ToAddr = "cryonme@nobodycares.com"þþ        // default subject line; fixed at the momentþ        Subject = "Alkomat 3000 Feedback"þþ        // port used by this server (should be the same as used in the app)þ        Port = "9444"þþ        CertificatePath = "certificate.pem"þ        PrivateKeyPath = "privatekey.pem"þþ)þ```þþ## App structureþþ### Terminologyþþ|term|description|þ|----|-----------|þ|`User`| Can consume `Mixture`s as `Drink`s which are stored in a `Drink`-Array|þ|`Drink`|A consumed `Mixture` with additional data (time of consume, ...)|þ|`Mixture`|A `Mixture` has one or more `Content`s and can be consumed by a `User`|þ|`Content`|A base content of a `Mixture` (e.g. beer, vodka, water, ...)|þþ### Data saved by the app on your phoneþþPath: `/data/data/AhiruSoftwareCompany.breathalyzer/shared_prefs/data.xml`þþ#### Users-ArrayþþAn array with every user currently existing including its drinks (updated on startup/resume/refresh button press)þþ```javascriptþ[þ  {þ    name:String,þ    isMale:boolean,þ    age:int,þ    weight:int,þ    height:int,þ    created:long,þ    drinks: [þ      {þ        name:String,þ        description:String,þ        consumePoint:long,þ        mixtureImage:String,þ        content: [þ          {þ            name:String,þ            alcContent:double,þ            amount:doubleþ          }þ        ]þ      }þ    ]þ    depletedDrinks: [þ      {þ        name:String,þ        description:String,þ        consumePoint:long,þ        mixtureImage:String,þ        content: [þ          {þ            name:String,þ            alcContent:double,þ            amount:doubleþ          }þ        ]þ      }þ    ]þ  }þ]þ```þþIn addition to that: `lastUser` as `long` (simply the creation date (with milliseconds)) from the last selected userþþþ#### Recipe-Arrayþþ`MixtureImage` represents a image (as string). See [source](https://github.com/AhiruSoftwareCompany/alcoholtestapp/blob/master/app/src/main/java/de/ahirusoftware/breathalyzer/model/MixtureImage.java) for more information.þþFor custom recipes saved by the user:þþ```þ[þ  {þ    name:String,þ    text:String,þ    imgString:String,þ    ingredients:[þ      {þ        name:String,þ        alcContent:double,þ        quantity:doubleþ      }þ    ]þ  }þ]þ```þþ### Send Feedbackþþ#### FeedbackþþExample of the string sent by the app:þþ```þ{þ  Device:{þ    OsVer:"3.0.31-novafusion(6452af36f2)",þ    OsApiLvl:22,þ    Device:"golden (samsung, GT-I8190)",þ    Model:"GT-I8190 (cm_golden)"þ   },þ  AppInfo:"Friendly name: 1.1, version code: 1",þ  LogTrace:"",þ  Sender:"Francis alias Ajax",þ  SenderMail:"foo@bar.cool",þ  Message:"Hi, I have a problem! Can you help me??"þ}þ```þþThe `LogTrace` is for future use: Logging every exception into a file.þþDisclaimer for the sake of the EU-GDPRþþ```þBy pressing the "send message" button in the "Send Feedback" form you agree that the data entered above,þinformation about your device (manufacturer, model, operating system and its version), your currentþIP-Address and the opt-in date as well as information about the app (version number, log files, storedþmixtures/recipes) will be sent securely. Data beyond the one provided by you optional (Name,þE-Mail-Address, Message) is used to ensure a better problem solving process and are stored untilþrevocation and are deleted after 10 years (except there are other valid lawfully retention periods).þþNo other personal data (photos, videos, etc.) are sent!þþThe name and the e-mail address are optional, but useful for inquiries/feedback.þþYou can always contact us via e-mail (privacy-duck@outlook.com) about your saved data and request a copy,þcancellation or rectification. In addition, you have the right to contact the data protection authorityþresponsible for you (for example your national data protection officer).þ```þþ## IssuesþFound a bug? Want to request a new feature?  Please let us know by submitting an issue or use the in-app feedback function (in the options menu).þþ## LicensingþThis project stands unter the MIT-License. Bear in mind that the pictures used in this project have their own license!þþ## Sources/AdaptionsþReadme adapted from [Esri](https://github.com/Esri/arcgis-runtime-samples-android)þþ[Emoji icons provided free by EmojiOne](http://emojione.com/)

column17: Pipelines for data processing (GBIF and LivingAtlases)
column43: [![Build Status](https://builds.gbif.org/job/pipelines/badge/icon?style=flat-square)](https://builds.gbif.org/job/pipelines/)þ[![Coverage](https://sonar.gbif.org/api/project_badges/measure?project=org.gbif.pipelines%3Apipelines-parent&metric=coverage)](https://sonar.gbif.org/dashboard?id=org.gbif.pipelines%3Apipelines-parent)þþ# Table of Contentsþþ- [**About the project**](#about-the-project)þ- [**Architecture**](#architecture)þ    - [**Ingress**](#ingress)þ    - [**Interpretation**](#interpretation)þ    - [**Indexing**](#indexing)þ- [**Structure**](#structure)þ- [**How to build the project**](#how-to-build-the-project)þ- [**Contributions**](#contributions)þþ# About the projectþþ**REMEMBER, YOU HAVE TO USE JAVA VERSION 8**þþ**Pipelines for data processing and indexing of biodiversity data**þþ_Status: IN PRODUCTION_þþVision: Consistent data processing pipelines (parsing, interpretation and quality flagging) for use in GBIF, the Living Atlases project and beyond.þBuilt to scale from laptop to GBIF volumes. Deployable on JVM, Spark, Google Cloud, <insert your favourite cloud provider here>.þþ# ArchitectureþþThe project provides vanilla JVM-based parsing and interpretation libraries, and pipelines for indexing into SOLR and ElasticSearch, built using Apache Beam.þþ> Apache Beam provides a high level abstraction framework ideal for this purpose with the ability to deploy across target environments (e.g. Spark, local JVM) and with many built in connectors for e.g. HBase, SOLR, ElasticSearch etc.þþ## IngressþþIngress is from [Darwin Core Archive](https://www.tdwg.org/standards/dwc/) (zip files of one or more delimited text files) or ABCD Archives (compressed XML) only[1].þDuring ingress data is converted from its native format and stored as [Avro](https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/) files containing Darwin Core compliant data.þþThis is depicted below:þþ![Ingress](./docs/images/ingress.svg)þþ> Avro is chosen as a storage and interchange format exclusively in this project because a) it is splittable with each split compressed independently, b) it holds the data schema with the data, c) is well supported in the Hadoop ecosystem (e.g. Hive, Spark) and many other tools (e.g. Google Cloud) d) is very robust in serialization and e) reduces boiler plate code thanks to schema to code generators. Darwin Core Archives and JSON for example do not exhibit all these traits.þþ[1] Other protocols (e.g. DiGIR, TAPIR) are supported by GBIF but are converted by crawling code upstream of this project.þþ## InterpretationþþDuring interpretation the verbatim data is parsed, normalised and tested against quality control procedures.þþTo enable extensibility data is interpreted into separate [`avro`](https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/) files where a separate file per category of information is used.  Many interpretations such as `date / time` formatting are common to all deployments, but not all.þFor example, in the [GBIF.org](https://www.gbif.org) deployment the scientific identification is normalised to the GBIF backbone taxonomy and stored in `/interpreted/taxonomy/interpreted*.avro` which might not be applicable to everyone.þSeparating categories allows for extensibility for custom deployments in a reasonably modular fashion.þþInterpretation is depicted below:þþ![Ingress](./docs/images/interpret.svg)þþ> Note that all pipelines are designed and tested to run with the `DirectRunner` and the `SparkRunner` at a minimum.  This allows the decision to be taken at runtime to e.g. opt to interpret a small dataset in the local JVM without needing to use cluster resources for small tasks.þþ> It is a design decision to ensure that all the underlying parsers are as reusable as possible for other projects with careful consideration to not bring in dependencies such as Beam or Hadoop.þþ## IndexingþþInitial implementations will be available for both SOLR and for ElasticSearch to allow for evaluation of both at GBIF.þDuring indexing the categories of interpreted information of use are merged and loaded into the search indexes:þþ![Ingress](./docs/images/index.svg)þþ> Note that GBIF target 10,000 records/sec per node indexing speed (i.e. 100,000 records/sec on current production cluster).  This will allow simplified disaster recovery and rapid deployment and of new features.þþ# StructureþþThe project is structured as:þþ- [**.buildSrc**](./.buildSrc) - Tools for building the projectþ- [**docs**](./docs) - Documents related to the projectþ- [**examples**](./examples) - Examples of using project API and base classesþ    - [**transform**](./examples/transform) - Transform example demonstrates how to create Apache Beam pipeline, create the new transformation and use it together with GBIF transforms and core classesþ    - [**metrics**](./examples/metrics) - The example demonstrates how to create and send Apache Beam SparkRunner metrics to ELK and use the result for Kibana dashboardsþ- [**gbif**](./gbif) - GBIF moduleþ    - [**coordinator**](./gbif/coordinator) - The main module which controls the interpretation process, through RabbitMQþ    - [**keygen**](./gbif/keygen) - The library to generate GBIF identifiers, to support backward compatibility the codebase (with minimum changes) was copied from the occurrence/occurrence-persistence projectþ    - [**pipelines**](./gbif/pipelines) - Main pipelines moduleþ        - [**export-gbif-hbase**](./gbif/pipelines/export-gbif-hbase) - The pipeline to export the verbatim data from the GBIF HBase tables and save as `ExtendedRecord` avro filesþ        - [**ingest-gbif-beam**](./gbif/pipelines/ingest-gbif-beam) - Main GBIF pipelines for ingestion of biodiversity dataþ        - [**ingest-gbif-fragmenter**](./gbif/pipelines/ingest-gbif-fragmenter) - Writes raw archive's data to HBase storeþ        - [**ingest-gbif-java**](./gbif/pipelines/ingest-gbif-java) - Main GBIF pipelines for ingestion of biodiversity data, Java versionþ- [**sdks**](./sdks) - Main module contains common classes, such as data models, data format interpretations, parsers, web services clients etc.þ    - [**beam-common**](./sdks/beam-common) - Classes and API for using with Apache Beamþ    - [**beam-transforms**](./sdks/beam-transforms) - Transformations for ingestion of biodiversity dataþ    - [**core**](./sdks/core) - Main API classes, such as data interpretations, converters, [DwCA](https://www.tdwg.org/standards/dwc/) reader etc.þ    - [**models**](./sdks/models) - Data models represented in Avro binary format, generated from [Avro](https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/) schemasþ    - [**variables**](./sdks/variables) - Only static string variablesþ- [**tools**](./tools) - Module for different independent toolsþ    - [**archives-converters**](./tools/archives-converters) - Converters from [DwCA/DWC 1.0/DWC 1.4](https://www.tdwg.org/standards/dwc/)/ABCD 1.2/ABCD 2.06 to *.[avro](https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/) formatþ    - [**elasticsearch-tools**](./tools/elasticsearch-tools) - Tool for creating/deleting/swapping Elasticsearch indexesþ    - [**pipelines-maven-plugin**](./tools/pipelines-maven-plugin) - Maven plugin adds new annotations and interface to [avro](https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/) generated classesþþ# How to build the projectþþThe project uses [Apache Maven](https://maven.apache.org/) for building. The project contains a Maven wrapper script for Linux and MacOS systems, you just can run the **`build.sh`** script:þþ```shellþ./build.shþ```þþPlease read the [Apache Maven how-to](https://maven.apache.org/run.html).þþ# ContributionsþþWe welcome contributions! Please see [the guide](./CONTRIBUTING.md) to see how you can best do this.

column17: Github Mirror of VIATRA Eclipse repository
column43: # VIATRAþþThe Eclipse VIATRA framework is a model and data transformation tool that helps move information back and forth in the most efficient way. The platform focuses specifically on event-driven and reactive transformations, which happen on-the-fly as the models change.þþVIATRA is a long-running project that incorporates the results of over 15 years of active research and development. VIATRA offersþþ * a domain-specific language for graph queries and reactive transformationsþ * a Java runtime library which is scalable and easy to embed.þþVIATRA primarily targets model-driven engineering tools based on the industry-standard Eclipse Modeling Framework, though it can be used in other contexts as well. VIATRA is an enabling technology and its biggest benefit is the power it gives you to close abstraction gaps. These exist in every data-driven application where structured data needs to be moved across various languages or representation formats.þþVIATRA helps you create model transformations that convert objects between languages. Trivial transformations (i.e. copying pieces of data from one document to another) are easy with any general purpose programming language such as Java. In contrast, VIATRA gives you easy-to-use and reusable programming patterns to address non-trivial transformations, such asþþ * Changing of structure, i.e. converting a UML model to a source code.þ * Derived data and abstractions: manipulating data during conversion, e.g. filtering information for creating ‘abstract views’þ * Combining multiple sources of information in a significant way to produce a new result, e.g. when creating data streams for dashboardsþ * Changing structure: projection of data containing only relevant information during the conversion phraseþþþþ## Most important linksþþ * [Project homepage](http://eclipse.org/viatra)þ * [Download links](http://eclipse.org/viatra/downloads.hml)þ * [Documentation pages](http://eclipse.org/viatra/documentation/index.html)þ * [Contributing](CONTRIBUTING.md)þþ## LicenseþþAll code in this repository is available under the Eclipse Public License v2.0: [http://www.eclipse.org/legal/epl-v20.html](http://www.eclipse.org/legal/epl-v20.html)

column17: Elexis 3 Core Repository
column43: h1. Elexis 3 Core Repositoryþþþþ*IMPORTANT* Please employ the @3lexisFormatterProfile.xml@ as Eclipse default formatter prior to development and pull requests.þThis accounts for all Elexis 3 related development.þþh2. Install latest buildþþGo to "Jenkins-CI Builds":https://download.elexis.info/elexis/master/products.þþDownload and unzip the zip file for your machine.þþInstall Oracle java 1.8 from "http://www.java.com/de/download/manual.jsp":http://www.java.com/de/download/manual.jspþþStart the Elexis3 application.þþUse Help..Install New Software to add the desired features from the elexis-3-base P2 repository.þþh2. Buildingþþh3. Maven based buildþþYou need Java 1.8+. Maven >= 3.3. Then you should be able to generate the application and p2 update site using the following calls:þþOn Debian 10 (buster) there is no OpenJDK 8 available anymore. You can install it with the following stepsþþbc. wget -qO - https://adoptopenjdk.jfrog.io/adoptopenjdk/api/gpg/key/public | sudo apt-key addþsudo add-apt-repository --yes https://adoptopenjdk.jfrog.io/adoptopenjdk/debþsudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install adoptopenjdk-8-hotspotþsudo update-alternatives --config java # select adoptopenjdk8þjava --version # should now show a Java 8 versionþþþþ@git clone https://github.com/elexis/elexis-3-core@þ@mvn -V clean verify -Dtycho.localArtifacts=ignore -Dmaven.test.skip=true -P all-archs@þþExplanation of the used optionsþ* -V: emits version of Java, Maven, GUI-Toolkit, Architecture. Handy when you ask a problemþ* clean: Build everything from scratchþ* verify: Compile, test and build a P2-site including products. But does NOT install maven artefactsþ* -Dtycho.localArtifacts=ignore: Do not use any locally built maven artefactsþ* -Dmaven.test.skip=true: Skip unit tests (Use it only if you want to speed up the build)þ* -P all-archs: This a work-around for bug https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=491951. We will get rid of around April 2018 when its fix will be in the next Oxygen Releaseþ* --quiet: Used for travis builds to generate Quiet output - only show errors. Without it the log would bee too long and make the travis-build fail.þþIt will be built for your OS/Window-System/Architecture combination. You will find the executables under @ch.elexis.core.p2site/target/products/ch.elexis.core.application.ElexisApp/*/*/*@ þþNote: This will fail in MacOSX. Build instructions for Mac:þþ@Install Homebrew@þ@brew install homebrew/versions/maven30@þ@git clone https://github.com/elexis/elexis-3-core@þ@mvn clean install -Pall-archs -Dmaven.test.skip=true@þþh3. Continuos Intergration buildsþþWe use Travis-CI to ensure that our build system works using a well documented environment. The status for the different branches can be founde under "Travis-CI elexis-3-core":https://travis-ci.org/elexis/elexis-3-core/branchesþþThe downloads found under "http://download.elexis.info/elexis/":http://download.elexis.info/elexis/ are produced by jobs running via the "Medelexis GitLab":https://gitlab.medelexis.ch/elexis/elexis-3-core/-/jobs/þþh3. Building via Eclipse IDEþþIf you want a complete development environment, try "Oomph":https://github.com/elexis/elexis-3-core/tree/master/ch.elexis.sdkþþh3. Eclipse IDE-PreferencesþþWe recommend (and if you want to submit patches, you have to respect) the following settings in the Eclipse IDE, reachabel via Window..Preferences:þþ* General..Workspaceþ** Select UTF-8 as "Textfile encoding"þ** Select UNIX as "New text file line delimiter"þ* Java..Code Style..Formatterþ** Click on "Import.." and select the 3lexisFormatterProfile.xml from the root directory of the elexis-3-core checkoutþ** Select "3lexis Formatter" as "Active Formater"þ* Java..Editor..Save Actionþ** Select: Perform the selected actions on saveþ** Do NOT select: Format source codeþ** Select: Organize importsþ** Do NOT select: Additional actionsþ* Maven..Errors/Warningþ** Set "Plugin execution not covered by lifecycle configuration" to "Ignore"þþh3. Submitting patchesþþTo submit patches you have toþþ* Fork our github repository to your personal accountþ* Clone this repository on your devevelopment machineþ* Create a new branch (eg. @git checkout -b my_branch@)þ* Commit your change (eg. @git commmit -m "My cool changes")þ* Push it to your account (eg. @git push --set-upstream origin my_branch@)þ* Go to your github repository and create a pull requests by clicking on the greeen button "Compare & pull request"þ* Review your changes. There should be only the lines that contribute to the problem. If you have too many changes look at the remarks about Eclipse IDE-Preferencesþþþh2. Developer OverviewþþThis repository hosts the core Elexis 3. It consists of the following plug-ins and features:þþ* @ch.rgw.utility@ Utilities required to drive Elexis.þ* @ch.elexis.core@ Core concepts and interface definitions.þ* @ch.elexis.core.data@ Core persistence and functionality packages and classes.þ* @ch.elexis.core.console.application@ Headless Elexis application.þ* @ch.elexis.core.ui@ User Interface dependent portions. Dependent on Eclipse RCP 3.x.þ* @ch.elexis.core.application@ Core UI Elexis Application.þþ* @ch.elexis.core.releng@ Release Engineering specific parts (Build Target, 3rd party ...)þþ* @ch.elexis.core.logging@ Plug-In for starting ch.qos.logback logging (via slf4j interface)þ* @ch.elexis.core.logging.feature@ Feature for logging and Felix-gogo consoleþ* @ch.elexis.core.logging.default_configuration@ Default logging configuration (logback.xml)þþ* @ch.elexis.core.ui.icons@ Plug-In for central icon management.þ* @ch.elexis.core.ui.contacts@ Plug-In for contact management.þ* @ch.elexis.core.ui.laboratory@ Plug-In for laboratory related tasks.þ* @ch.elexis.core.ui.p2@ Plug-In to realize client side p2 update tasksþ* @ch.elexis.core.common.feature@ Headless Core Feature.þ* @ch.elexis.core.ui.feature@ Core UI Feature.þ* @ch.elexis.core.application.feature@ Core Application Feature.þþFor details about the resp. plug-ins/features switch to the respective directory. The plug-ins and featuresþare contained and inter-dependent as follows:þþ!FeatureStructure.png!þþh3. Guidelines for developing a new plugin/featureþþNew plugins and features should follow the E4 (eclipse 4) guideline. A good tutorial is from "Lars Vogel":https://www.vogella.com/tutorials/EclipseRCP/article.htmlþþThe ch.elexis.core.ui.tasks follows new e4 implementation rules. Analyse its working and adapt it to your problem.þþþh3. Generate JavadocþþElexis uses Javadoc go documents its API interface. The Eclipse IDE offers built-in support for reading the javadoc for a given method or class and provides also helper to generate it.þþThis is accomplished by calling @mvn -DforceContextQualifier=javadoc javadoc:javadoc@. It generates a complete javadoc. The generated output can be search at "target/site/apidocs/index.html":target/site/apidocs/index.html. þþEven when theses javadoc are not used often, they provide a convenient way to get an overview over methods, packages, etc.þþh3. Check whether Javadocs are correctly generatedþþWe use checkstyle to generate Javadoc. Use the following command line:þþ@mvn checkstyle:checkstyle-aggregate site:site@þþThis generates an browsable HTML file "target/site/index.html":target/site/index.html. The links to the modules do not work, unless you call afterwards @ch.elexis.core.releng/cleanup_after_checkstyle.rb@, a small ruby script which generates a few missing links (not supported on Windows).þþIt uses the rules defined in @ch.elexis.core.releng/checkstyle.xml@ to generate warnings for missing Javadoc. For each project, there exists an error report. E.g "target/site/ch.rgw.utility/checkstyle.html":./target/site/ch.rgw.utility/checkstyle.html. An aggregated, overall statistics can be found under "target/site/checkstyle-aggregate.html":target/site/checkstyle-aggregate.htmlþþIf you want to add even more checks, look at ch.elexis.core.releng/checkstyle_full.xml. Adding new checks should be discussed on the developers mailing list.þþþh2. Updating all versions for a newer IDþþWe do this for all new major version, eg. 3.3 -> 3.4. See also http://www.mojohaus.org/versions-maven-plugin/usage.htmlþþSteps to follow are:þþ* Update the version in master pom.xmlþ* Run @mvn org.eclipse.tycho:tycho-versions-plugin:set-version -DnewVersion=3.9.0-SNAPSHOT@þ* Test and check whether the old version number is still present in other files.þþh2. Localisation / translationþþWe are in a transition phase to use trema and support french and italien versions of elexis. For details see "l10n.md":bundles/ch.elexis.core.l10n/doc/l10n.md

column17: A repository with small examples showing off OSGi
column43: # OSGi enRoute ExamplesþþThis is a repository that illustrates the [OSGi enRoute Service Catalog][enroute.services] with example application. Each project in this repository is a stand-alone OSGi enRoute application that exercises _the user of_ a particular service. In general, you can start the debug.bndrun in each project in debug and go to http://localhost:8080/<project-name>. Each project has a readme.md that will give you more details of what the application demonstrates. The applications themselves are also self documenting (at least that is the intent).þþ## ContributingþþWant to hack on osgi.enroute.examples? See [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) for information on building, testing and contributing changes.þþThey are probably not perfect, please let us know if anything feelsþwrong or incomplete.þþ## LicenseþþThe contents of this repository are made available to the public under the terms of the [Apache License, Version 2.0](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0).þBundles may depend on non Apache Licensed code.þþ[enroute.services]: http://enroute.osgi.org/book/400-services.html

column17: Thym Project
column43: The HYbrid Mobile Tools Projectþ====þþThym (The HYbrid Mobile) project delivers IDE components and a framework for developing þHybrid Mobile Applications on the Eclipse platform. The delivered IDE components þsupport the Apache Cordova framework, but facilitate extensibility to other frameworks.þþ## InstallþþThe best way to install Thym is by [adding](http://help.eclipse.org/luna/index.jsp?topic=%2Forg.eclipse.platform.doc.user%2Ftasks%2Ftasks-127.htm&cp=0_3_17_5) the Thym update site andþ[installing](http://help.eclipse.org/luna/topic/org.eclipse.platform.doc.user/tasks/tasks-124.htm?cp=0_3_17_1) with the  Eclipse update manager.þþ### Update sites þþ#### Latest snapshot buildsþþ> http://download.eclipse.org/thym/snapshotsþþ### RequirementsþþPlatform SDKs are needed only for the platforms that you plan to target.þ* [iOS SDK](http://developer.apple.com) with the latest Xcode including the Xcode Command Line Tools þ* [Android SDK](http://developer.android.com) with the absolute latest updates for all Android SDK components. þþþDeveloping and Contributingþ------þþWe'd love to get contributions from you! Take a look atþ[Contribution Documents](CONTRIBUTING.md) to see how to get your changes in.þþþLicenseþ-------þþSee [LICENSE](LICENSE) file.þþSupportþ-------þþPlease log tickets and issues at [Eclipse.org bugzilla](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/enter_bug.cgi?product=Thym).  A [developer mailingþlist](https://dev.eclipse.org/mailman/listinfo/thym-dev) is available for asking questions.

column17: Simple Java Starter Kit
column43: # Vertigoþ=================þþ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-green.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0)þ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/io.vertigo/vertigo.svg?label=Maven%20Central)](https://search.maven.org/search?q=g:%22io.vertigo%22)þþA Simple Java Starter kit for **real projects**.þþIts main purpose is to publish simple and homogeneous APIs over more complex libraries.þþ__Vertigo__ is split into different modules, detailed below.þþ## vertigo-coreþ### Build and configure your own modules þþ* __app__ : everything to configure your appþ* __component__ : everything about components (fast, simple and lightweight Dependency Injection, simple AOP, proxies)þ* __locale__ : manage internationalization of your app (MessageTexts)þ* __param__ : a simple way for your business and technical configuration (external and internal)þ* __definitions__ : a way to store and access all definitions of your appþ* __resource__ : a simple access to resources (builtin : lookup into classpath, webapp, filesystem with relative or absolute path)þ* __lang__ : a set of usefull elements such as assertionþ þþ## vertigo-commonsþ### A set of common tools þþ* __analytics__ : track your process calls, time & errorsþ* __cache__ : keep your objects in memory to improve performanceþ* __codec__ : transform an object into another. (built-in codecs : HTML, SHA1, Base64, Compress, Serialize) þ* __daemon__ : manage all your application daemons (registering, stats) þ* __eventbus__ : a simple event bus for handling events in your app  þ* __node__ : a simple node management for cluster applications (topology, health, config)þ* __config__ : read configs for your application (overridable, externalizable, aggregate multiple configs)þ* __peg__ : a simple parser for your [DSL](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain-specific_language)þ* __script__ : transform a simple String in an executable script right from your code  (because sometimes you need to merge code and data)þ* __transaction__ : simple transaction management þþ## vertigo-databaseþ### A simple data access to your databasesþþ* __sql__ : with built-in handlers : Oracle, MSSql, Postgresql, H2þþ## vertigo-dynamoþ### A simple way to define the model for your application and provide useful api over it like storage, search, etc...þ  þ* __collections__ : collections tools (built-in : fulltext indexation, facetting, filtering)   þ* __criteria__ : a unique api to build filters (predicates, sql)þ* __domain__ : top-2-bottom POJO to simplify communication between layers from Database to GUI/WSþ* __environment__ : initialize your components from different sources (built-in : powerdesigner, DSL, Java annotations)þ* __file__ : manage file creationþ* __kvstore__ : key/value datastoreþ* __store__ : simple access to persistence layer  (built-in : route by object type, CRUD operations, NN operations)þ* __search__ : simple search apiþ* __task__ : create and manage various tasks (such as direct queries to databases)þþþ## vertigo-accountþ### A simple user management system, not only technical.þþ* __authentication__ : provide a set of connectors to easily manage your end users authentication in your appþ* __authorization__ : userSession and security tools to check access to resources (by user roles and/or data properties)   þ* __identity__ : a way to store and identify your user accountsþþþ## vertigo-vegaþ### Share your apps to others.þþ* __rest__ : Add a REST access layer to your application. Mainly oriented for production-ready Single-Page-Applications. Provides a production-ready security level.þþþ## vertigo-studioþ### A set of tools to help you through developpementþ* __mda__ : Model Driven Architecture with tools to generate source code (java, sql, js, ts), multilingual properties...þ* __reporting__ : a set of tools to build indicators about your appþ* __ui__ : more to comeþþ## vertigo-bundleþA bundle of all above modulesþþþ## vertigo-parentþjust the parent pomþþ## Additional note for [Eclipse](https://www.eclipse.org/) usersþA plugin named [KSP Plugin](https://github.com/sebez/vertigo-chroma-kspplugin) developped by [sebez](https://github.com/sebez/) enhances Developer Experience.þþ-----þ#Licenseþ                Copyright (C) 2017, KleeGroup, direction.technique@kleegroup.com (http://www.kleegroup.com)þ                KleeGroup, Centre d'affaire la Boursidiere - BP 159 - 92357 Le Plessis Robinson Cedex - Franceþ                þ                Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");þ                you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.þ                You may obtain a copy of the License atþ                þ                http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þ                þ                Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþ                distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þ                WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þ                See the License for the specific language governing permissions andþ                limitations under the License.

column17: This is the Wi-Fi / Wi-Fi Direct based peer to peer communication framework for Android. It stands for "Croconaut Public Transport", Croconaut was a "startup" from the times when we thought we can finish the product in three months. :)
column43: This is the Wi-Fi / Wi-Fi Direct based peer to peer communication framework for Android. It stands for "Croconaut Public Transport", Croconaut was a "startup" from the times when we thought we can finish the product in three months. :)þþCheckout the [wiki](https://github.com/croconaut/cpt/wiki) for detailed description and information or follow the quick step-by-step guide and surely take a look at [WiFON mini](https://github.com/croconaut/wifon-mini) with a small demonstration how to put all together:þþ# Gradleþþ    repositories {þ        maven {þ            url "https://mymavenrepo.com/repo/fsD4SRhSQewcguNLyevk"þ        }þ        maven {þ            url "https://s3.amazonaws.com/repo.commonsware.com"þ        }þ    }þþ    dependencies {þ        compile 'com.croconaut:cpt:1.0.16'þ    }þþ# Add the broadcast receiverþAndroidManifest.xml:þþ    <receiver android:name=".MyBroadcastReceiver" />þþMyBroadcastReceiver.java:þþ    import com.croconaut.cpt.ui.CptReceiver;þ    þ    public class MyBroadcastReceiver extends CptReceiver {þ        // implement the interface, most important functions are:þ        @Overrideþ        protected void onNearbyPeers(Context context, ArrayList<NearbyUser> nearbyUsers) {þ            // NearbyUser.crocoId shall be used as the recipient's IDþ        }þ        @Overrideþ        protected void onNewMessage(Context context, long messageId, Date receivedTime, IncomingMessage incomingMessage) {þ            // read / request attachments and get your app data (like a text message)þ        }þ    }þþ# Register the broadcast receiver and usernameþ    Communication.register(this, "Miro Kropacek", MyBroadcastReceiver.class);þ    þ# Enable *CPT*þTechnically speaking, you don't have to enable *CPT* if you don't want to transmit it immediately, the message will be stored anyway.þþ    CptController cptController = new CptController(this);þ    cptController.setMode(LinkLayerMode.FOREGROUND);þþ# Send a messageþ    OutgoingPayload outgoingPayload = new OutgoingPayload("Hi there from the other device");    // can be anything Serializable, not only a stringþ    OutgoingMessage outgoingMessage = new OutgoingMessage(targetCrocoId);þ    outgoingMessage.setPayload(outgoingPayload);þ    Communication.newMessage(getContext(), outgoingMessage);þþ# Source code releaseþPlease note that you need to supply your own `google-services.json` file and possibly `myMavenRepoWriteUrl` if you want to deploy the archive.þþAlso, the library isn't 100% ready for targetting API > 22 because it still relies on the static permission model (among other things, there seem to be some issues with notifications, too). So if you plan to release your app on the Play Store, you need to change CPT internals in a way that you can use the dynamic model. Pull requests welcome. :)

column17: The main development version of the PRISM model checker.
column43: # PRISMþþThis is PRISM (Probabilistic Symbolic Model Checker).þþþ## InstallationþþFor detailed installation instructions, check the online manual at:þþ  http://www.prismmodelchecker.org/manual/InstallingPRISM/Instructionsþ  þor see the local copy included in this distribution:þþ * `manual/InstallingPRISM/Instructions.html`þþVery abbreviated instructions for installing/running PRISM are as follows:þþFor Windows binary distributions:þþ * to install, run `prism-XXX-win-installer.exe`þ * to run, use Desktop/Start menu shortcuts or double-click `bin\xprism.bat`þþFor other binary distributions:þþ * to install, enter the PRISM directory and type `./install.sh`þ * to run, execute `bin/xprism` or `bin/prism`þþFor source code distributions:þþ * enter the PRISM directory and type `cd prism` then `make`þ * to check the install, type `make test`þ * to run, execute `bin/xprism` or `bin/prism`þþIf you have problems check the manual, especially the section "Common Problems And Questions".þþþ## DocumentationþþThe best source of information about using PRISM is the online manual:þþ  http://www.prismmodelchecker.org/manual/þþYou can also view the local copy included in this distribution:þþ  * `manual/index.html`þþFor other PRISM-related information, see the website:þþ  http://www.prismmodelchecker.org/þþþ## LicensingþþPRISM is distributed under the GNU General Public License (GPL), version 2.þA copy of this license can be found in the file `COPYING.txt`.þFor more information, see:þþ  http://www.gnu.org/licenses/þþPRISM uses the CUDD (Colorado University Decision Diagram) library of Fabio Somenzi,þwhich is freely available. For more information about this library, see:þþ  http://vlsi.colorado.edu/~fabio/CUDD/þþPRISM also uses various other libraries (mainly to be found in the lib directory).þFor details of those, and for links to source where we distribute only binaries, see:þþhttp://www.prismmodelchecker.org/other-downloads.phpþþþ## AcknowledgementsþþPRISM was created and is still actively maintained by:þþ * Dave Parker (University of Birmingham)þ * Gethin Norman (University of Glasgow)þ * Marta Kwiatkowska (University of Oxford) þþDevelopment of the tool is currently led from Birmingham by Dave Parker. Other current key developers are:þþ * Joachim Klein (formerly Technische Universität Dresden)þþWe gratefully acknowledge contributions to the PRISM code-base from various sources,þincluding (in approximately reverse chronological order):þþ * Steffen Märcker: Fixes and improvements, especially in explicit engineþ * Chris Novakovic: Build infrastructure and explicit engine improvementsþ * Ernst Moritz Hahn: Parametric model checking, fast adaptive uniformisation + various other featuresþ * Frits Dannenberg: Fast adaptive uniformisationþ * Vojtech Forejt: Various model checking code, including multi-objective + GUI enhancementsþ * Hongyang Qu: Multi-objective model checkingþ * Mateusz Ujma: Bug fixes and GUI improvementsþ * Christian von Essen: Symbolic/explicit-state model checkingþ * Vincent Nimal: Approximate (simulation-based) model checking techniquesþ * Mark Kattenbelt: Wide range of enhancements/additions, especially in the GUIþ * Carlos Bederian (working with Pedro D'Argenio): LTL model checking for MDPsþ * Gethin Norman: Precomputation algorithms, abstractionþ * Alistair John Strachan: Port to 64-bit architecturesþ * Alistair John Strachan, Mike Arthur and Zak Cohen: Integration of JFreeChart into PRISMþ * Charles Harley and Sebastian Vermehren: GUI enhancementsþ * Rashid Mehmood: Improvements to low-level data structures and numerical solution algorithmsþ * Stephen Gilmore: Support for the stochastic process algebra PEPAþ * Paolo Ballarini & Kenneth Chan: Port to Mac OS Xþ * Andrew Hinton: Original versions of the GUI, Windows port and simulatorþ * Joachim Meyer-Kayser: Original implementation of the "Fox-Glynn" algorithm þþFor more details see:þþ  http://www.prismmodelchecker.org/people.phpþþþ## ContactþþIf you have problems or questions regarding PRISM, please use the help forum provided. See:þþ  http://www.prismmodelchecker.org/support.phpþþOther comments and feedback about any aspect of PRISM are also very welcome. Please contact:þþ  Dave Parker  þ  (d.a.parker@cs.bham.ac.uk)  þ  School of Computer Science  þ  University of Birmingham  þ  Edgbaston  þ  Birmingham  þ  B15 2TT  þ  ENGLAND

þþ#### Support 8 kinds of opening animationsþ![Lighter](https://github.com/samlss/TimoMenu/blob/master/screenshots/screenshot4.gif)þþ------þ### Dependencyþþ#### GradleþAdd it in your module build.gradle at the end of repositories:þ ```javaþ dependencies {þ implementation 'me.samlss:timomenu:1.0.0'þ }þ ```þþ#### Mavenþ```javaþþ me.samlssþ timomenuþ 1.0.0þ pomþþ```þþ### Sample Usageþþ```javaþ//create menuþTimoMenu timoMenu = new TimoMenu.Builder(this)þ .setGravity(Gravity.BOTTOM)þ .setMenuMargin(new Rect(20, 20, 20, 20))þ .setMenuPadding(new Rect(0, 10, 0, 10))þ .addRow('ItemAnimation', ' List')þ .build();þþ//Show menuþtimoMenu.show(); þþ//Dismiss menu.þtimoMenu.dismiss();þþ```þþþþPlease read [wiki](https://github.com/samlss/TimoMenu/wiki) for more descriptions.þþ### Licenseþþ```þCopyright 2018 samlssþþLicensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");þyou may not use this file except in compliance with the License.þYou may obtain a copy of the License atþþ http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþUnless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþdistributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þWITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þSee the License for the specific language governing permissions andþlimitations under the License.þ```

column17: A heads plugin that has grown for over two years into something more ambitious than other plugins.
column43: ![Loading beautiful image ;)](https://proxy.spigotmc.org/7f8059160ab428b12bd0b5c6ca741095b43342b1?url=https%3A%2F%2Fi.imgur.com%2F4DjCHmg.png)þþ# HeadsPlus Projectþþ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus.svg?label=github%20release)](https://github.com/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus/releases)þþHeadsPlus (referred to as the HeadsPlus Project on Github) is one of Spigot's most ambitious and advanced heads plugins, providing several new and unique features to servers of which have never been seen before. Minecraft's skulls are an important asset to bringing forth incredible amounts of creativity without further intervetion by resource packs, mods and data packs, so HeadsPlus makes sure they are used to the best of their ability.þþCurrently, HeadsPlus has 21,000+ downloads, over 50 reviews (55/60) praising the plugin, 600+ live servers with 600-1200 players, and a committed developer always looking to find ways to improve the plugin even more and make it stand out even more among other plugins.þþ## Installation/CloningþHeadsPlus uses Maven to manage its dependencies, with most of these provided in a library folder within the project.þþThe command which is used by the developer herself is `mvn clean install` and should work fine on itself.þþHeadsPlus uses the CraftBukkit API, which requires you to have run BuildTools on your system for each version.þþ## Using HeadsPlus in MavenþHeadsPlus uses JitPack to host its repository. To use HeadsPlus as a library in your project, add the following in your project:þ```xmlþ    <repositories>þ <repository>þ     <id>jitpack.io</id>þ     <url>https://jitpack.io</url>þ </repository>þ    </repositories>þ    <dependencies>þ        <dependency>þ            <groupId>com.github.Thatsmusic99</groupId>þ     <artifactId>HeadsPlus</artifactId>þ     <version>v6.10.5-SNAPSHOT-1</version>þ </dependency>þ    </dependencies>þ```þþþ## More informationþ- [Wiki](https://github.com/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus/wiki)þ- [Spigot Page](https://www.spigotmc.org/resources/headsplus-1-8-x-1-15-x.40265/)þ- [Issue Tracker](https://github.com/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus/issues)þ- [Discord](https://discord.gg/eu8h3BG)þþ## Important documentsþ- [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)þ- [License (MIT)](https://github.com/Thatsmusic99/HeadsPlus/blob/master/LICENSE)
