column17: Nordstrom Java Utils is a small collection of general-purpose utility classes with wide applicability.
column43: [![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.nordstrom.tools/java-utils.svg)](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.nordstrom.tools/java-utils)þþ# NORDSTROM JAVA UTILSþþ**Nordstrom Java Utils** is a small collection of general-purpose utility classes with wide applicability.þþ## UncheckedThrowþþThe **UncheckedThrow** class uses type erasure to enable client code to throw checked exceptions as unchecked. This allows methods to throw checked exceptions without requiring clients to handle or declare them. It should be used judiciously, as this exempts client code from handling or declaring exceptions created by their own actions. The target use case for this facility is to throw exceptions that were serialized in responses from a remote system. Although the compiler won't require clients of methods using this technique to handle or declare the suppressed exception, the JavaDoc for such methods should include a `@throws` declaration for implementers who might want to handle or declare it voluntarily.þþþ```javaþ ...þ þ String value;þ try {þ value = URLDecoder.decode(keyVal[1], "UTF-8");þ } catch (UnsupportedEncodingException e) {þ throw UncheckedThrow.throwUnchecked(e);þ }þ þ ...þ```þþ## DatabaseUtilsþþ**DatabaseUtils** provides facilities that enable you to define collections of database queries and stored procedures in an easy-to-execute format.þþQuery collections are defined as Java enumerations that implement the `QueryAPI` interface:þ* `getQueryStr` - Get the query string for this constant. This is the actual query that's sent to the database.þ* `getArgNames` - Get the names of the arguments for this query. This provides diagnostic information if the incorrect number of arguments is specified by the client.þ* `getConnection` - Get the connection string associated with this query. This eliminates the need for the client to provide this information.þ* `getEnum` - Get the enumeration to which this query belongs. This enables `executeQuery(Class, QueryAPI, Object[])` to retrieve the name of the query's enumerated constant for diagnostic messages.þþStore procedure collections are defined as Java enumerations that implement the `SProcAPI` interface: þ* `getSignature` - Get the signature for this stored procedure object. This defines the name of the stored procedure and the modes of its arguments. If the stored procedure accepts varargs, this will also be indicated.þ* `getArgTypes` - Get the argument types for this stored procedure object.þ* `getConnection` - Get the connection string associated with this stored procedure. This eliminates the need for the client to provide this information.þ* `getEnum` - Get the enumeration to which this stored procedure belongs. This enables `executeStoredProcedure(Class, SProcAPI, Object[])` to retrieve the name of the stored procedured's enumerated constant for diagnostic messages.þþTo maximize usability and configurability, we recommend the following implementation strategy:þ* Define your collection as an enumeration:þ * Query collections implement `QueryAPI`.þ * Stored procedure collections implement `SProcAPI`.þ* Define each constant:þ * (query) Specify a property name and a name for each argument (if any).þ * (sproc) Declare the signature and the type for each argument (if any).þ* To assist users of your queries, preface their names with a type indicator (GET or UPDATE).þ* Back query collections with configurations that implement the **`Settings API`**:þ * groupId: com.nordstrom.test-automation.toolsþ * artifactId: settingsþ * className: com.nordstrom.automation.settings.SettingsCoreþþ* To support execution on multiple endpoints, implement `QueryAPI.getConnection()` or `SProcAPI.getConnection()` with sub-configurations or other dynamic data sources (e.g. - web service).þþ#### Query Collection Exampleþþ```javaþpublic class OpctConfig extends SettingsCore {þþ private static final String SETTINGS_FILE = "OpctConfig.properties";þþ private OpctConfig() throws ConfigurationException, IOException {þ super(OpctValues.class);þ }þþ public enum OpctValues implements SettingsCore.SettingsAPI, QueryAPI {þ /** args: [ ] */þ GET_RULE_HEAD_DETAILS("opct.query.getRuleHeadDetails"),þ /** args: [ name, zone_id, priority, rule_type ] */þ GET_RULE_COUNT("opct.query.getRuleCount", "name", "zone_id", "priority", "rule_type"),þ /** args: [ role_id, user_id ] */þ UPDATE_USER_ROLE("opct.query.updateRsmUserRole", "role_id", "user_id"),þ /** MST connection string */þ MST_CONNECT("opct.connect.mst"),þ /** RMS connection string */þ RMS_CONNECT("opct.connect.rms");þþ private String key;þ private String[] args;þ private String query;þþ private static OpctConfig config;þ private static String mstConnect;þ private static String rmsConnect;þþ private static EnumSet rmsQueries = EnumSet.of(UPDATE_USER_ROLE);þþ static {þ try {þ config = new OpctConfig();þ } catch (ConfigurationException | IOException e) {þ throw new RuntimeException("Unable to instantiate OPCT configuration object", e);þ }þ }þþ OpctValues(String key, String... args) {þ this.key = key;þ this.args = args;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String key() {þ return key;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String getQueryStr() {þ if (query == null) {þ query = config.getString(key);þ }þ return query;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String[] getArgNames() {þ return args;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String getConnection() {þ if (rmsQueries.contains(this)) {þ return getRmsConnect();þ } else {þ return getMstConnect();þ }þ }þþ @Overrideþ public Enum getEnum() {þ return this;þ }þþ /**þ * Get MST connection string.þ * þ * @return MST connection stringþ */þ public static String getMstConnect() {þ if (mstConnect == null) {þ mstConnect = config.getString(OpctValues.MST_CONNECT.key());þ }þ return mstConnect;þ }þþ /**þ * Get RMS connection string.þ * þ * @return RMS connection stringþ */þ public static String getRmsConnect() {þ if (rmsConnect == null) {þ rmsConnect = config.getString(OpctValues.RMS_CONNECT.key());þ }þ return rmsConnect;þ }þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String getSettingsPath() {þ return SETTINGS_FILE;þ }þþ /**þ * Get OPCT configuration object.þ *þ * @return OPCT configuration objectþ */þ public static OpctConfig getConfig() {þ return OpctValues.config;þ }þþ public enum SProcValues implements SProcAPI {þ /** args: [ ] */þ SHOW_SUPPLIERS("SHOW_SUPPLIERS()"),þ /** args: [ coffee_name, supplier_name ] */þ GET_SUPPLIER_OF_COFFEE("GET_SUPPLIER_OF_COFFEE(>, <)", Types.VARCHAR, Types.VARCHAR),þ /** args: [ coffee_name, max_percent, new_price ] */þ RAISE_PRICE("RAISE_PRICE(>, >, =)", Types.VARCHAR, Types.REAL, Types.NUMERIC),þ /** args: [ str, val... ] */þ IN_VARARGS("IN_VARARGS(<, >:)", Types.VARCHAR, Types.INTEGER),þ /** args: [ val, str... ] */þ OUT_VARARGS("OUT_VARARGS(>, <:)", Types.INTEGER, Types.VARCHAR);þþ private int[] argTypes;þ private String signature;þþ SProcValues(String signature, int... argTypes) {þ this.signature = signature;þ this.argTypes = argTypes;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String getSignature() {þ return signature;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public int[] getArgTypes () {þ return argTypes;þ }þþ @Overrideþ public String getConnection() {þ return OpctValues.getRmsConnect();þ }þþ @Overrideþ public Enum getEnum() {þ return this;þ }þ }þ}þ```þþ### Registering JDBC DriversþþTo provide maximum flexibility, JDBC interacts with database instances through a defined interface (**java.sql.Driver**). Implementations of this interface translate its methods into their vendor-specific protocol, in classes called **drivers**. For example, [OracleDriver](https://download.oracle.com/otn_hosted_doc/jdeveloper/905/jdbc-javadoc/oracle/jdbc/OracleDriver.html) enables JDBC to interact with Oracle database products.þþIn JDBC connection URLs, the vendor and driver are specified as suffixes to the `jdbc` protocol. For the Oracle "thin" driver, this is `jdbc:oracle:thin`. This protocol/vendor/driver combination is handled by **OracleDriver**, and JDBC needs this class to be registered to handle this vendor-specific protocol.þþTo simplify the process of registering vendor-specific JDBC drivers, **DatabaseUtils** loads these for you through the Java **ServiceLoader** facility. Declare the driver(s) you need in a **ServiceLoader** provider configuration file at **_META-INF/services/java.sql.Driver_**:þþ```þoracle.jdbc.OracleDriverþ```þþThis sample provider configuration file will cause **DatabaseUtils** to load the JDBC driver class for Oracle database products. The JAR that declares this class needs to be on the class path for this to work. For Maven projects, you just need to add the correct dependency:þþ```xmlþ[pom.xml]þþ [...]þ þ þ [...]þ þ com.oracle.jdbcþ ojdbc6þ 11.2.0.4.0þ þ þ þ [...]þþ```þþ## PathUtilsþþThe **PathUtils** `getNextPath` method provides a method to acquire the next file path in sequence for the specified base name and extension in the indicated target folder. If the target folder already contains at least one file that matches the specified base name and extension, the algorithm used to select the next path will always return a path whose index is one more than the highest index that currently exists. (If a single file with no index is found, its implied index is 0.)þþ##### Example usage of `getNextPath`þþ```javaþ ...þ þ /*þ * This example gets the next path in sequence for base name `artifact`þ * and extension `txt` in the TestNG output directory.þ * þ * For purposes of this example, the output directory already containsþ * the following files: `artifact.txt`, `artifact-3.txt`þ */þþ Path collectionPath = Paths.get(testContext.getOutputDirectory());þ // => C:\git\my-project\test-output\Default suiteþþ Path artifactPath;þ try {þ artifactPath = PathUtils.getNextPath(collectionPath, "artifact", "txt");þ // => C:\git\my-project\test-output\Default suite\artifact-4.txtþ } catch (IOException e) {þ provider.getLogger().info("Unable to get output path; no artifact was captured", e);þ return;þ }þ þ ...þ```þþ## Params InterfaceþþThe **Params** interface defines concise methods for the creation of named parameters and parameter maps. This facility can make your code much easier to read and maintain. The following example, which is extracted from the **Params** unit test class, demonstrates a few basic features.þþ#### Params Exampleþ```þpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport static com.nordstrom.common.params.Params.param;þimport static org.testng.Assert.assertEquals;þimport static org.testng.Assert.assertFalse;þimport static org.testng.Assert.assertTrue;þþimport java.util.Optional;þimport org.testng.annotations.Test;þimport com.nordstrom.common.params.Params;þþpublic class ParamTest implements Params {þ þ @Testþ public void testDefault() {þ assertFalse(Params.super.getParameters().isPresent());þ }þ þ @Testþ public void testParam() {þ Param param = param("boolean", true);þ assertEquals(param.getKey(), "boolean");þ verifyBoolean(param.getVal());þ }þ þ @Testþ public void testParams() {þ Optional> optParameters = getParameters();þ assertTrue(optParameters.isPresent());þ Map parameters = optParameters.get();þ assertFalse(parameters.isEmpty());þ þ assertTrue(parameters.containsKey("boolean"));þ verifyBoolean(parameters.get("boolean"));þ }þ þ private void verifyBoolean(Object value) {þ assertTrue(value instanceof Boolean);þ assertTrue((Boolean) value);þ }þ þ @Overrideþ public Optional> getParameters() {þ return Params.mapOf(param("boolean", true), param("int", 1), param("String", "one"),þ param("Map", Params.mapOf(param("key", "value"))));þ }þ}þþ```þþThis code uses a static import to eliminate redundant references to the **Params** interface. It also shows the unrestricted data types of parameter values. The use of **Optional** objects enables you to provide an indication that no value was returned without the risks associated with `null`.

column43: <!---þ Licensed to the Apache Software Foundation (ASF) under one or moreþ contributor license agreements.  See the NOTICE file distributed withþ this work for additional information regarding copyright ownership.þ The ASF licenses this file to You under the Apache License, Version 2.0þ (the "License"); you may not use this file except in compliance withþ the License.  You may obtain a copy of the License atþþ      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþ Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþ distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þ WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þ See the License for the specific language governing permissions andþ limitations under the License.þ-->þContributing to [Apache Maven Shade Plugin](https://maven.apache.org/plugins/maven-shade-plugin/)þ======================þþ[![ASF Jira](https://img.shields.io/endpoint?url=https%3A%2F%2Fmaven.apache.org%2Fbadges%2Fasf_jira-MSHADE.json)][jira]þ[![Apache License, Version 2.0, January 2004](https://img.shields.io/github/license/apache/maven.svg?label=License)][license]þ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/org.apache.maven.plugins/maven-shade-plugin.svg?label=Maven%20Central)](https://search.maven.org/artifact/org.apache.maven.plugins/maven-shade-plugin)þ[![Jenkins Status](https://img.shields.io/jenkins/s/https/builds.apache.org/job/maven-box/job/maven-shade-plugin/job/master.svg?)][build]þ[![Jenkins tests](https://img.shields.io/jenkins/t/https/builds.apache.org/job/maven-box/job/maven-shade-plugin/job/master.svg?)][test-results]þþþYou have found a bug or you have an idea for a cool new feature? Contributingþcode is a great way to give something back to the open source community. Beforeþyou dig right into the code, there are a few guidelines that we needþcontributors to follow so that we can have a chance of keeping on top ofþthings.þþGetting Startedþ---------------þþ+ Make sure you have a [JIRA account](https://issues.apache.org/jira/).þ+ Make sure you have a [GitHub account](https://github.com/signup/free).þ+ If you're planning to implement a new feature, it makes sense to discuss your changes þ  on the [dev list][ml-list] first. þ  This way you can make sure you're not wasting your time on something that isn't þ  considered to be in Apache Maven's scope.þ+ Submit a ticket for your issue, assuming one does not already exist.þ  + Clearly describe the issue, including steps to reproduce when it is a bug.þ  + Make sure you fill in the earliest version that you know has the issue.þ+ Fork the repository on GitHub.þþMaking and Submitting Changesþ--------------þþWe accept Pull Requests via GitHub. The [developer mailing list][ml-list] is theþmain channel of communication for contributors.  þThere are some guidelines which will make applying PRs easier for us:þ+ Create a topic branch from where you want to base your work (this is usually the master branch).þ  Push your changes to a topic branch in your fork of the repository.þ+ Make commits of logical units.þ+ Respect the original code style: by using the same [codestyle][code-style],þ  patches should only highlight the actual difference, not being disturbed by any formatting issues:þ  + Only use spaces for indentation.þ  + Create minimal diffs - disable on save actions like reformat source code or organize imports. þ    If you feel the source code should be reformatted, create a separate PR for this change.þ  + Check for unnecessary whitespace with `git diff --check` before committing.þ+ Make sure your commit messages are in the proper format. Your commit message should contain the key of the JIRA issue.þ```þ[MSHADE-XXX] - Subject of the JIRA Ticketþ Optional supplemental description.þ```þ+ Make sure you have added the necessary tests (JUnit/IT) for your changes.þ+ Run all the tests with `mvn -Prun-its verify` to assure nothing else was accidentally broken.þ+ Submit a pull request to the repository in the Apache organization.þ+ Update your JIRA ticket and include a link to the pull request in the ticket.þþIf you plan to contribute on a regular basis, please consider filing a [contributor license agreement][cla].þþMaking Trivial Changesþ----------------------þþFor changes of a trivial nature to comments and documentation, it is not alwaysþnecessary to create a new ticket in JIRA.  In this case, it is appropriate toþstart the first line of a commit with '(doc)' instead of a ticket number.þþDeveloper Tipsþ--------------þþIf you machine is big enough and you want to parallelise the IT execution to validate the buildþbefore a PR you can set the concurrency in MAVEN_OPTS:þþ````þMAVEN_OPTS=-Dinvoker.parallelThreads=2 mvn verify -Prun-itsþ````þþYou can also run a single IT test using:þþ````þmvn verify -Prun-its -Dinvoker.test=myitprojectþ````þþAdditional Resourcesþ--------------------þþ+ [Contributing patches](https://maven.apache.org/guides/development/guide-maven-development.html#Creating_and_submitting_a_patch)þ+ [Apache Maven Shade JIRA project page][jira]þ+ [Contributor License Agreement][cla]þ+ [General GitHub documentation](https://help.github.com/)þ+ [GitHub pull request documentation](https://help.github.com/send-pull-requests/)þ+ [Apache Maven Twitter Account](https://twitter.com/ASFMavenProject)þ+ #Maven IRC channel on freenode.orgþþ[jira]: https://issues.apache.org/jira/projects/MSHADE/þ[license]: https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þ[ml-list]: https://maven.apache.org/mailing-lists.htmlþ[code-style]: https://maven.apache.org/developers/conventions/code.htmlþ[cla]: https://www.apache.org/licenses/#clasþ[maven-wiki]: https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/MAVEN/Indexþ[test-results]: https://builds.apache.org/job/maven-box/job/maven-shade-plugin/job/master/lastCompletedBuild/testReport/þ[build]: https://builds.apache.org/job/maven-box/job/maven-shade-plugin/job/master/

column17: Provides builders, which allow to create various "Material Design"-styled dialogs
column43: # AndroidMaterialDialog - READMEþþ[![API-Level](https://img.shields.io/badge/API-14%2B-orange.svg)](https://android-arsenal.com/api?level=14) [![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-blue.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0) [![Donate](https://img.shields.io/badge/Donate-PayPal-green.svg)](https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=X75YSLEJV3DWE)þþ"AndroidMaterialDialog" is an Android-library, which provides builders for creating dialogs, which are designed according to Android 5's Material Design guidelines even on pre-Lollipop devices. The following screenshots show the appearances of dialogs, which have been created using the library.þþ![](doc/images/example1.png)þþ![](doc/images/example2.png)þþThe library provides the following main features:þþ- The builder `MaterialDialog.Builder` allows to create dialogs, which may contain a title, an icon, a message, up to three buttons and optional list items.þ- By using the builder `ProgressDialog.Builder` it is possible to create dialogs, which show a circular progress bar.þ- The builder `EditTextDialog.Builder` allows to create dialogs that contain an `EditTextWidget`.þ- Dialogs, which are created using the builder `WizardDialog.Builder`, contain a `ViewPager` for switching between multiple fragments.þ- The library comes with a light and dark theme. For both themes a fullscreen variant is available as well.þ- All dialogs may contain a header, which consists of a background image or color and an optional icon.þ- By offering various methods for changing the appearance of UI elements, the library's dialogs are highly customizable. It is even possible to replace a dialog's title, message, content or buttons with custom views. Also the size and position of dialogs can be modified.þ- The library offers built-in support for easy use of animations. This corresponds to showing and hiding dialogs in an animated manner, as well as changing backgrounds and icons by using animations.þþThe project also includes an example application, which implements some example dialogs for demonstrating the use of the library.þþ## License AgreementþþThis project is distributed under the Apache License version 2.0. For further information about this license agreement's content please refer to its full version, which is available at http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.txt.þþPrior to version 3.1.1 this library was distributed under the GNU Lesser General Public License version 3.0 (GLPLv3).þþ## DownloadþþThe latest release of this library can be downloaded as a zip archive from the download section of the project's Github page, which is available [here](https://github.com/michael-rapp/AndroidMaterialDialog/releases). Furthermore, the library's source code is available as a Git repository, which can be cloned using the URL https://github.com/michael-rapp/AndroidMaterialDialog.git.þþAlternatively, the library can be added to your Android app as a Gradle dependency by adding the following to the respective module's `build.gradle` file:þþ```groovyþdependencies {þ    compile 'com.github.michael-rapp:android-material-dialog:5.2.3'þ}þ```þþBefore version 2.0.0 this project was hosted on [Sourceforge](https://sourceforge.net/projects/androidmaterialdialog). These older versions used the legacy Eclipse ADT folder structure and are not available as Gradle artifacts.þþ## ExamplesþþIn the following a few examples, which illustrate the use of the library's most important features, are given. Moreover, this project contains the source code of an example app, which implements use cases of the library for demonstration purposes, as well as a more detailed documentation in the Wiki and auto-generated javadoc files. þþ*Since version 5.0.0 the library requires to use [AndroidX](https://developer.android.com/jetpack/androidx/) instead of the older AppCompat support libraries. Make sure that you have [migrated](https://developer.android.com/jetpack/androidx/migrate) your app to AndroidX and that you are using one of the Material component themes instead of the AppCompat ones, e.g. `Theme.MaterialComponents.Light.DarkActionBar` instead of `Theme.AppCompat.Light.DarkActionBar`.*þþ### Creating a typical alert dialogþþThe code below shows how to create and show an alert dialog by using the library's `MaterialDialog.Builder`. The dialog contains a title and message and can be closed by the user by either using a "OK" button or a "Cancel" button. The `this` parameter, which is passed to the builder's constructor in the example below, must be a `Context`, e.g. an `Activity`. The `null` parameters, which are passed to the `setPositiveButton`- and `setNegativeButton`-methods can be replaced by instances of the type `DialogInterface.OnClickListener` in order to execute some code when the user closes the dialog by clicking the corresponding button.þþ```javaþMaterialDialog.Builder dialogBuilder = new MaterialDialog.Builder(this); þdialogBuilder.setTitle(R.string.dialog_title); þdialogBuilder.setMessage(R.string.dialog_message); þdialogBuilder.setTitle(R.string.dialog_title); þdialogBuilder.setPositiveButton(android.R.string.ok, null); þdialogBuilder.setNegativeButton(android.R.string.cancel, null); þMaterialDialog dialog = dialogBuilder.create();þdialog.show();þ```þþThe appearance of the dialog, which is created by the given sample code, is shown below:þþ![](doc/images/example-alert-dialog.png)þþ### Using custom viewsþþIn order to adjust the appearance of a `MaterialDialog`, it is possible to specify custom views for displaying its title, message, content and button bar. All of these custom views can be given as a layout resource or as a `View` instance. The following example illustrates, how such custom views can be set to a `MaterialDialog.Builder`, which has been instantiated as shown in the previous section.þþ```javaþMaterialDialog.Builder builder = new MaterialDialog.Builder(context);þbuilder.setView(R.layout.custom_dialog_content);þbuilder.setCustomTitle(R.layout.custom_dialog_title);þbuilder.setCustomMessage(R.layout.custom_dialog_message);þbuilder.setCustomButtonBar(R.layout.custom_dialog_button_bar);þbuilder.setCustomHeader(R.layout.custom_dialog_header);þ```þþWhen using custom layouts, which contain views of the same type and being associated with the same id as the views in the original layout, the dialog's methods (e.g. the `setTitle`-method) can be used as before. To do so, the following views must be contained by the different types of layouts:þþ- If using a custom view for displaying the title, the view or one of its children must be an `EditText` with the id `android.R.id.title` to be able to show the title correctly. To display the icon, an `ImageView` with the id `android.R.id.icon` must be contained as well.þ- To enable the dialog's message to be shown, an `EditText` with the id `android.R.id.message` must be available accordingly. þ- If using a custom view for displaying the dialog's buttons, the individual `Button` widgets are referenced via the ids `android.R.id.button1` (primary button), `android.R.id.button2` (secondary button) and `android.R.id.button2` (tertiary button). þ- When using a custom layout for displaying the dialog's header, it must contain an `ImageView` with the id `android.R.id.icon` to be able to show the header's icon.þþAn example, which uses custom views for displaying the title, message, content and buttons, is shown in the screenshot below.þþ![](doc/images/example-custom-views.png)þþ### Creating a progress dialogþþThe following source code shows how a progress dialog, which displays a circular progress bar, can be created. Such as a regular `MaterialDialog`, such a dialog can contain a title, a message and up to three buttons. By using the `setProgressBarPosition`-method, the position of the dialog's progress bar can be specified. Possible values are `LEFT`, `TOP`, `RIGHT` and `BOTTOM`, each specifying the position in relation to the dialog's message.þþ```javaþProgressDialog.Builder dialogBuilder = new ProgressDialog.Builder(this); þdialogBuilder.setTitle(R.string.dialog_title); þdialogBuilder.setMessage(R.string.dialog_message); þdialogBuilder.setPositiveButton(android.R.string.ok, null); þdialogBuilder.setNegativeButton(android.R.string.cancel, null); þdialogBuilder.setProgressBarPosition(ProgressBarPosition.LEFT) þProgressDialog dialog = dialogBuilder.create(); þdialog.show();þ```þþThe screenshot below shows the appearance of a `ProgressDialog`, which has been created using the given sample code. Such as a regular `MaterialDialog`, such a dialog can contain a title, a message and up to three buttons.þþ```javaþEditTextDialog.Builder dialogBuilder = new EditTextDialog.Builder(this);þdialogBuilder.setTitle(R.string.dialog_title);þdialogBuilder.setMessage(R.string.dialog_message);þdialogBuilder.setPositiveButton(android.R.string.ok, null);þdialogBuilder.setNegativeButton(android.R.string.cancel, null);þdialogBuilder.setText("Text");þEditTextDialog dialog = dialogBuilder.create();þdialog.show();þ```þþIt is possible to add one or several `Validator`s to an `EditTextDialog` in order to validate the entered text.þþ![](doc/images/example-progress-dialog.png)þþ### Creating an edit text dialogþþThe following code illustrates how a dialog that contains an `EditText` widget can be created.þþ### Creating a wizard dialogþþA `WizardDialog` allows to show multiple fragments and provides a navigation for switching between them by either using tabs or buttons, which are located at the bottom of the dialog. The source code below shows how such a dialog can be created. The tabs, which indicate the currently selected fragment, are shown in the dialog's header if possible. This behavior can be customized by using the `setTabPosition`-method. If the value `USE_HEADER` is passed to the method, the tabs are shown in the header, if the dialog does neither contain a title, nor a message. The default value `PREFER_HEADER` causes the tabs to be shown in the header regardless of any title or message are shown. And the value `NO_HEADER` prevents the tabs from being shown in the header at all. By default, the tabs, which are shown by the dialog are not clickable and the currently shown fragment can only be changed using swipe gestures or the button bar. If the tabs should be clickable, the `enableTabLayout`-method has to be used. Furthermore, the detection of swipe gestures can be disabled using the `enableSwipe`-method and the visibility of the dialog's button bar can be toggled using the `showButtonBar`-method. þþ```javaþWizardDialog.Builder dialogBuilder = new WizardDialog.Builder(this); þdialogBuilder.showHeader(true); þdialogBuilder.setHeaderBackground(R.drawable.header_background); þdialogBuilder.addFragment(R.string.fragment1_title, Fragment1.class); þdialogBuilder.addFragment(R.string.fragment2_title, Fragment2.class); þdialogBuilder.addFragment(R.string.fragment3_title, Fragment3.class); þdialogBuilder.setTabPosition(TabPosition.PREFER_HEADER);þdialogBuilder.enableTabLayout(true);þdialogBuilder.enableSwipe(true);þdialogBuilder.showButtonBar(true); þWizardDialog dialog = dialogBuilder.create(); þdialog.show();þ```þþThe following screenshot illustrates one possible appearance of a `WizardDialog`:þþ![](doc/images/example-wizard-dialog.png)þþ### Showing a headerþþAll dialogs may contain a header, which consists of a background image or color and an optional icon. The following code shows how a dialog can be configured to contain such a header, once a builder has been instantiated like shown in the previous sections.þþ```javaþ...þdialogBuilder.showHeader(true); þdialogBuilder.setHeaderBackground(R.drawable.header_background); þdialogBuilder.setHeaderIcon(R.drawable.header_icon);þ...þ```þþThe picture below shows a dialog, which contains a header with a background image and an icon:þþ![](doc/images/example-header-dialog.png)þþ### Specifying scrollable areasþþIf the content of a dialog takes to much vertical space, it cannot completely be displayed on the screen anymore. This can especially be a problem in landscape mode, where only limited vertical space is available. To overcome this problem, the library allows to specify which areas of a dialog should be (vertically) scrollable. For example, to specify that the message of a dialog should be scrollable, the following code can be used:þþ```javaþdialogBuilder.setScrollableArea(ScrollableArea.Area.MESSAGE);þ```þþEach dialog consists of several areas, which are represented by the values of the enum `ScrollableArea.Area`. A dialog may consist of the following areas from top to bottom:þþ* `HEADER`þ* `TITLE`þ* `MESSSAGE`þ* `CONTENT`þ* `BUTTON_BAR`þþIf multiple areas of a dialog should be scrollable, this can be achieved as shown below:þþ```javaþdialogBuilder.setScrollableArea(ScrollableArea.Area.HEADER,  þ                                ScrollableArea.Area.CONTENT);þ```þþThe first area, which is provided to the method corresponds to the top area, which should be scrollable (inclusive). The second method parameter specifies the bottom area, which should be scrollable (also inclusive). Both specified areas, as well as all areas, which are located between them, are made scrollable by wrapping them in a single `ScrollView`. The scrolling behavior of a dialog, which has been configured using the above method call, can be seen below:þ þ![](doc/images/example-scrolling.gif) þþþ### Using themesþþThe library comes with pre-defined dark and light theme variants. Furthermore three different fullscreen themes are available per variant. The following table shows the IDs of all themes. They can be referenced in XML using the syntax `@style/MaterialDialog.Light`. In Java code the syntax `R.id.MaterialDialog_Light` can be used respectively. When using a fullscreen theme, dialogs take the whole available space by default. By using the `CenterInside` variants, the dialogs' width and height are restricted to take only as much space as necessary, while the backround is still displayed across the whole screen. The `Translucent` variants use a translucent status and navigation bar (only on devices with API level 21 or greater).þþ|                                 | Dark variant                                         | Dark variant                                               |þ| ------------------------------- |------------------------------------------------------| -----------------------------------------------------------|þ| Default                         | `MaterialDialog`                                     | `MaterialDialog.Light`                                     |þ| Fullscreen                      | `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen`                          | `MaterialDialog.Light.Fullscreen`                          |þ| Fullscreen Translucent          | `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen.Translucent`              | `MaterialDialog.Light.Fullscreen.Translucent`              |þ| Fullscreen Centered             | `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen.CenterInside`             | `MaterialDialog.Light.Fullscreen.CenterInside`             |þ| Fullscreen Centered Translucent | `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen.CenterInside.Translucent` | `MaterialDialog.Light.Fullscreen.CenterInside.Translucent` |þþIn order to use one of the predefined themes, the id of the respective theme has to be passed as an argument to the constructor of the builder `MaterialDialog.Builder` (or another builder provided by the library) as shown in the code below.þþ```javaþWizardDialog.Builder dialogBuilder = new WizardDialog.Builder(this, R.style.MaterialDialog_Light); þ...þ```þþAs an alternative, the theme, which should be used by all of the library's builders by default, can be globally specified. This requires to include the theme attribute `materialDialogTheme` in the app's theme (in the `res/values/styles.xml` file) as shown in the example below. When a divergent theme is passed to a builder's constructor, that particular theme is prefered over the theme, which is specified using the `materialDialogTheme` attribute.þþMoreover, it might be useful to extend the predefined themes in order to overwrite some theme attributes. One common use-case is to overwrite the theme attribute `colorAccent`, which specifies the default text color of a dialog's buttons. In such case a new style resource, which extends one of the built-in themes, must be added to your app's `res/values/styles.xml` file. The following example illustrates how such a style can be defined and can be set as the default theme for all of the library's builders.þþ```xmlþ<resources>þþ    <style name="AppTheme" parent="@style/Theme.MaterialComponents.Light.DarkActionBar">þ        <item name="colorPrimary">@color/color_primary</item>þ        <item name="colorPrimaryDark">@color/color_primary_dark</item>þ        <item name="colorAccent">@color/color_accent</item>þ        <item name="materialDialogTheme">@style/CustomDialogTheme</item>þ    </style>þþ    <style name="CustomDialogTheme" parent="@style/MaterialDialog.Light">þ        <item name="colorAccent">@color/color_accent</item>þ    </style>þþ</resources>þ```þþThe screenshots below show the appearance of dialogs, which use the themes `MaterialDialog`, `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen.Translucent` and `MaterialDialog.Fullscreen.CenterInside.Translucent`.þþ![](doc/images/example3.png) þþ## Using animationsþþThe `setShowAnimation`-, `setDismissAnimation`- and `setCancelAnimation`-methods of a dialog can be used to specify the animations, which should be used when the dialog is shown, dismissed or canceled. All of these methods take an instance of the class `DialogAnimation` as a parameter. This parameter specifies the properties of the animation, e.g. its duration. Currently two types of animations are supported:þþ- **`FadeAnimation`** Allows to show or hide a dialog by fading it in or out. Instances of this animation can be created as shown in the following.þ þ```javaþFadeAnimation animation = new FadeAnimation.Builder(this).setAlpha(0f).setDuration(1000L).create();þ```þ- **`RectangleRevealAnimation`:** Allows to show or hide a dialog by translating it from/to a specific position and animating its size. Instances of this animation can be created as shown below. The `x` and `y` properties specify the position of the dialog in pixels. The coordinate `x=0,y=0` corresponds to the top left corner of the display. The `width` and `height` properties specify the size of the dialog in pixels.þþ```javaþRectangleRevealAnimation animation = new RectangleRevealAnimation.Builder(this).setX(0).setY(0).setWidth(0).setHeight(0).setDuration(1000L).create()þ```þþ- **`CircleRevealAnimation`** (only on devices with API level 21 or greater): Allows to show a dialog by cropping its content to a circle with a specific radius, which grows from a specific position. When the animation is used to hide a dialog, the circle is shrinked to the given radius and position. The code below shows how such an animation can be created. The properties `x` and `y` specify the position in pixels. The coordinate `x=0,y=0` corresponds to the top left corner of the display. The property `radius` correpsonds to the radius of the circle, the dialog's content is cropped to, in pixels.þþ```javaþCircleRevealAnimation animation = new RectangleRevealAnimation.Builder(this).setX(0).setY(0).setRadius(0).setDuration(1000L).create();þ``` þA dialog, which is shown and hidden using a `RectangleRevealAnimation` can be seen below.þþ![](doc/images/example-rectangle-reveal-animation.gif) þþIn the following a dialog, which is shown and hidden using a `CircleRevealAnimation`, is shown.þþ![](doc/images/example-circle-reveal-animation.gif)þþBesides using animations to show or hide dialogs, they can also be used to change a dialog's background, header background or header icon in an animated manner. This is possible by using the `setBackground`-, `setHeaderBackground`- or `setHeaderIcon`-methods, which take instances of the class `DrawableAnimation` or `BackgroundAnimation` as arguments. The following types of animations can be used as the arguments of these methods:þþ- **`CrossFadeTransitionAnimation`:** Allows to change a background or icon using cross-fading. Instances of this class can be created as shown below.þþ```javaþCrossFadeTransitionAnimation animation = new CrossFadeTransitionAnimation(this).setDuration(1000L).create();þ```þþ- **`CircleTransitionAnimation`:** Allows to change a background or icon by cropping the new background or icon as a circle with a specific radius, which grows from a specific position. The `x` and `y` properties, which can be seen in the example below, correspond to the position the circle grows from in pixels. If these properties are not specified, the center is used. The `radius` property corresponds to the initial radius of the circle in pixels.þþ```javaþCircleTransitionAnimation animation = new CircleTransitionAnimation(this).setX(0).setY(0).setRadius(0).setDuration(1000L).create();þ```þþ- **`ScaleTransitionAnimation`:** This type of animation can only be used for animating icons. It is not applicable on backgrounds. It downscales the initial icon until it fully dissapears and afterwards shows the new icon by upscaling it. Both icons should have the same size. Instances of this type of animation can be created using the following code.þþ```javaþScaleTransitionAnimation animation = new ScaleTransitionAnimation.Builder(this).setDuration(1000L).create();þ```þþAn example of a dialog, which uses a `CrossFadeTransitionAnimation` for animating its background, a `CircleTransitionAnimation` for animating its header background and a `ScaleTransitionAnimation` for animating its header icon, can be seen below.þþ![](doc/images/example-animated-wizard-dialog.gif)þþ## Contact informationþþFor personal feedback or questions feel free to contact me via the mail address, which is mentioned on my [Github profile](https://github.com/michael-rapp). If you have found any bugs or want to post a feature request please use the [bugtracker](https://github.com/michael-rapp/AndroidMaterialDialog/issues) to report them.

column43: Docker Pipeline Pluginþ=====================================þþ[![Jenkins Plugin](https://img.shields.io/jenkins/plugin/v/docker-workflow.svg)](https://plugins.jenkins.io/docker-workflow)þ[![GitHub release](https://img.shields.io/github/release/jenkinsci/docker-workflow-plugin.svg?label=changelog)](https://github.com/jenkinsci/docker-workflow-plugin/releases/latest)þ[![Jenkins Plugin Installs](https://img.shields.io/jenkins/plugin/i/docker-workflow.svg?color=blue)](https://plugins.jenkins.io/docker-workflow)þþJenkins plugin which allows building, testing, and using Docker images from Jenkins Pipeline projects.þþSummaryþ---þþA full description is available in the plugin’s [documentation](https://go.cloudbees.com/docs/plugins/docker-workflow/).þþDemoþ---þThe plugin has a Docker-based demo. See the [demo README](demo/README.md) page for setup and launch guidelines.þþReleasingþ---þþPrior to release, edit `demo/plugins.txt` to use the snapshot version and run:þþ    mvn -DskipTests clean installþ    make -C demo runþþand verify that the demo works.þþAfter the Maven release completes, update the `docker-workflow` version in `demo/plugins.txt` to the release version and runþþ    make -C demo runþ    þto sanity check, thenþþ    make -C demo push-latestþþLicenseþ---þ[MIT License](http://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)þþChangelogþ---þþ* For new versions, see [GitHub Releases](https://github.com/jenkinsci/docker-workflow-plugin/releases)þ* For versions 1.19 and older, see the [plugin's Wiki page](https://wiki.jenkins.io/display/JENKINS/Docker+Pipeline+Plugin)

# Esercitazione Bonusþ--------------þLista utenti:þþ```þadminþ123456þþuserþquertyþ```þþUrl icona:þhttps://romannurik.github.io/AndroidAssetStudio/icons-launcher.html#foreground.type=text&foreground.text.text=EsBonus&foreground.text.font=Aclonica&foreground.space.trim=1&foreground.space.pad=0.5&foreColor=rgb(0%2C%2080%2C%20116)&backColor=rgb(58%2C%20219%2C%20238)&crop=0&backgroundShape=square&effects=none&name=ic_launcherþþ--------------þ##### Scadenza: 15/01/19þþPer l’esercitazione bonus (facoltativa) dovrete implementare un’applicazione Android composto da un form di login semplificato, che permetta a un utente di loggarsi inserendo username e password. þþL’applicazione deve contenere due activity:þþ1. Nella prima ci saranno i campi per l’inserimento dei dati richiesti, ovvero username e password (quest’ultimo campo oscurato come visto in FPW); un pulsante (“ACCEDI”) che consente l’accesso; e una text-view che rimandi al form per la registrazione di un nuovo utente (badate bene, questa funzionalità non è da implementare, basta solo il link). þþ1. Tramite il pulsante ACCEDI verrà visualizzata la seconda activity; questa conterrà una text-view con testo “Benvenuto username”, dove username corrisponde al nome dell’utente che ha appena fatto l’accesso correttamente, oppure “Accesso negato” se i dati non sono corretti. In aggiunta, un pulsante (“INDIETRO”) per tornare all’activity precedente. þþþControllo dei dati: la vostra applicazione deve attuare due tipi di controlli. In primo luogo, il passaggio alla successiva activity non può avvenire se uno dei campi, o entrambi, non sono stati compilati dall’utente. In tal caso dovete visualizzare dei messaggi di errore come visto a lezione.þþMentre, il secondo controllo richiede che i campi inseriti dall’utente corrente corrispondano a un utente presente in una lista di utenti registrati, definita da voi e di cui quindi disponete username e password.þþþLinks:þ1. http://moodle.unica.it/course/view.php?id=50þ1. https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Jsmicpid2Y52iOKSpCjxbw-lcpphbHDEIIbtE1BBRb0/edit#heading=h.ukispj1l3ib1

column17: A playful approach to refactoring code smells
column43: # SonarQuestþþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/viadee/sonarQuest.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/viadee/sonarQuest) þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/release-pre/viadee/sonarquest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/releases) þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/license/viadee/sonarquest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/blob/master/LICENSE)þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/stars/viadee/sonarQuest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/stargazers) þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/forks/viadee/sonarQuest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/network/members)þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/contributors/viadee/SonarQuest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/graphs/contributors) þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/last-commit/viadee/SonarQuest.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/commits/master) þ[![](https://img.shields.io/github/commits-since/viadee/SonarQuest/0.7.1.svg)](https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/compare/0.7.1...master) þþþA tool for extending [SonarQube](https://www.sonarqube.org/) by a gamification system. Handle your code quality issues in a playful way by solving quests and adventures, earning rewards for refactoring code smells and optimization.þþ* more about SonarQuest's game concepts and application scenarios: https://www.viadee.de/sonarquest_enþ* Sonar Quest info package: https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/blob/master/docs/SonarQuest_info_package.pdfþþ## GoalþþReduce technical debts in your code project by changing the refactoring process into a game. Create quests from SonarQube issues and write your own story.þþAn example: a team defines the solvation of issues with priority levels "blocker" and "critical" as goals on a fictious adventure map in a game they call "travel through the wild Codeistan". They can reach the respective targets in the adventure by decreasing the number of code smells, bugs and security vulnerabilities detected by SonarQube.þþ![Example](docs/images/screenshot.jpg)þþ## Jump-start for usersþþThe quickest way to get a running SonarQuest and to start playing is to use Docker, see [INSTALLATION.md](installation.md) or if you do not have Docker, just do the following:þþ### Backendþ* download the runnable backend jar from the latest release, e.g. https://github.com/viadee/sonarQuest/releases/tag/0.7.1/þ* start it with "java -jar [name of the jar]"þþ### Frontendþ* check out the *sonarquest-frontend* folder from githubþ* Install *Node.js*. Please follow the instructions on the [Node.js](https://nodejs.org) website.þ* Install *Angular-Cli* globally with `npm install -g @angular/cli`þþAfter that you can start the SonarQuest client:þ1. switch to the directory: `cd sonarQuest-frontend`þ2. install the node modules: `npm install`þ3. start the test server with the SonarQuest client: `ng serve`þYou can access the SonarQuest client in a browser at `http://localhost:4200`þþ### 10 steps into your SonarQuest gameþþ1. Log in as admin with password testþ2. Check the connection to the SonarQube serverþ3. Get all the projects on SonarQube into SonarQuest and make a single project playable as a "world"þ4. Assign a gm and players to this worldþ5. Log in as gm with password testþ6. Get all issues aka tasks for the current worldþ7. Create quests by writing a short story and add tasks to make them solvableþ8. (Optionally) create an adventure and add quests to it to support a story arcþ9. Get your players to log in (all pre-made avatars have the password test and their username as login) and take on your quests by selecting to "fight" in a quest and to "fight" issues in the questsþ10. Login in as a gm from time to time to synchronize SonarQuest with the SonarQube project to have SonarQuest pay out rewards to your players!þþHave fun!þþ## Getting StartedþþSee [INSTALLATION.md](installation.md) for instruction to get started with SonarQuest. These instructions will get you a copy of the project up and running on your local machine for development and testing purposes.þþþ### Used technologies and projectsþThe SonarQuest client is an *Angular* application on the basis of *TypeScript*. *Angular Material*, *Teradata Covalent* and *RPG-Awesome* (Icons) are used for the UI. You need *Node.js* for your development environment.þþþ* [Angular](https://angular.io) (licensed under MIT)þ* [Angular Material](https://material.angular.io) (licensed under MIT)þ* [Teradata Covalent](https://teradata.github.io/covalent/#/) (licensed under MIT)þ* [RPG-Awesome](https://nagoshiashumari.github.io/Rpg-Awesome/) (licensed under BSD 2-Clause)þ* [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/en/)þ* [express.js](https://expressjs.com/) (licensed under MIT)þ* [Spring Boot](https://spring.io/) (licensed under Apache License 2.0)þþþ## ContributingþþInterested in helping out? Welcome! Check out the guide  [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) to get started.þþ## LicenseþþThis project is licensed under the BSD 3-Clause "New" or "Revised" License - see the [LICENSE](LICENSE) file for details.þThe licenses of the reused components of the SonarQuest server can be found in [Licenses SonarQuestServer](sonarQuest-backend/src/main/resources/licenses/licenses.json).þþ## User Guidelinesþþþþ### Player and AvatarsþþA user can choose an individual avatar with a name, a class (e.g. warrior or magician) and a race (e.g. dwarf or elf). A set of predefined avatars is available [here in PDF format](AvatarCards.pdf). þPlease note the username (login) is the character's name by default (first letter is always uppercase!) and the standard password is `test` for all accounts.þþDuring an adventure the party (which may be represented by a project team) takes on quests and every avatar has several possibilities to gain experience points (XP) and get to the next level. Besides, some quests and tasks contain a reward in form of gold -- which can be used to purchase items and improvements in the marketplace.þþThe levels are determined based on experience points (XP) as follows:þþ#### Levelsþþ| Level | 1 | 2  | 3  | 4  | 5  | 6  | 7  | 8  |þ|-------|---|----|----|----|----|----|----|----|þ| XP    | 0 | 10 | 30 | 60 | 100| 150| 210| 280|þþLevels 1 to 100 are included in the standard game data. In case you want to add some extra levels, consider reading the [level calculation documentation](docs/SonarQuest_Level_Calculation.ods). þþ#### Rating systemþEvery issue is assessed in experience points and gold. The higher the severity of a issue the more experience points that a user gets.þ* Blocker = 10 XPþ* Critical = 7 XPþ* Major = 5 XPþ* Minor = 2 XPþ* Info = 1 XPþþThe number of gold is calculated depending on the effort (minutes/10), e.g. approximately 30 minutes = 3 gold, 2 hours = 12 gold.þThus issues with a low severity and a high effort are also attractive for a user.þþ### Quests and AdministrationþþA "Game-Master" is responsible for the administration of quests and adventures and assigning issues from SonarQube to them. This process is supported by automatic generation: The results from the previous SonarQube-Build are being loaded and evaluated using the severity the effort to solve them. Subsequently, the issues are randomly grouped to predefined quests. These can be assigned to team adventures.þWhen a quest is solved, i.e. the related SonarQube issues don't exist anymore, the avatar receives the reward.þþAdditionally, a Game Master is able to manually create "special tasks" which are rewarded by bonus experience points or bonus gold, such as:þþ- Increase the coverage of a changed class for 10%þ- Increase the documentation quality of a changed classþ- Apply the DRY principle in one class

# Warp 10 Platform [![Tweet](https://img.shields.io/twitter/url/http/shields.io.svg?style=social)](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Get%20The%20Most%20Advanced%20Time%20Series%20Platform&url=https://warp10.io/download&via=warp10io&hashtags=tsdb,database,timeseries,opensource)þ[![Build Status](https://www.travis-ci.org/senx/warp10-platform.svg?branch=master)](https://www.travis-ci.org/senx/warp10-platform)þ[![Download](https://api.bintray.com/packages/senx/generic/warp10/images/download.svg)](https://bintray.com/senx/generic/warp10/_latestVersion)þþ

þþ## IntroductionþþWarp 10 is an Open Source Geo Time Series Platform designed to handle data coming from sensors, monitoring systems and the Internet of Things.þþGeo Time Series extend the notion of Time Series by merging the sequence of sensor readings with the sequence of sensor locations. If your data have no location information, Warp 10 will handle them as regular Time Series.þþ## FeaturesþþThe Warp 10 Platform provides a rich set of features to simplify your work around sensor data.þþ* Warp 10 Storage Engine, our collection and storage layer, a Geo Time Series Databaseþ* WarpScript, a language dedicated to sensor data analysis with more than 1000 functions and extension capabilitiesþ* Plasma and Mobius, streaming engines allowing to cascade the Warp 10 Platform with Complex Event Processing solutions and to build dynamic dashboardsþ* Runner, a system for scheduling WarpScript program executions on the server sideþ* [Sensision](https://github.com/senx/sensision), a framework for exposing metrics and pushing them into Warp 10þ* Standalone version running on a [Raspberry Pi](https://blog.senx.io/warp-10-raspberry-bench-for-industrial-iot/) as well as on a beefy server, with no external dependenciesþ* Replication and sharding of standalone instances using the Datalog mechanismþ* Distributed version based on Hadoop HBase for the most demanding environmentsþ* Integration with [Pig](https://github.com/senx/warp10-pig), [Spark](https://github.com/senx/warp10-spark2), [Flink](https://github.com/senx/warp10-flink), [NiFi](https://github.com/senx/nifi-warp10-processor), [Kafka Streams](https://github.com/senx/warp10-plugin-kstreams) and [Storm](https://github.com/senx/warp10-storm) for batch and streaming analysis.þþ## Getting HelpþþThe team has put lots of efforts into the [documentation](https://warp10.io/) of the Warp 10 Platform, there are still some areas which may need improving, so we count on you to raise the overall quality.þþWe understand that discovering all the features of the Warp 10 Platform at once can be intimidating, that's why we've put together a [Google Group](https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/warp10-users) we recommend you subscribe to. You can also use [StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/) [warp10](https://stackoverflow.com/search?q=warp10) and [warpscript](https://stackoverflow.com/search?q=warpscript) tags.þþOur goal is to build a large community of users to move our platform into territories we haven't explored yet and to make Warp 10 and WarpScript the standards for sensor data and the IoT.þþWe also suggest you subscribe to our Twitter account [@warp10io](https://twitter.com/warp10io).þþ## Commercial SupportþþShould you need commercial support for your projects, [SenX](https://senx.io/) offers support plans which will give you access to the core team developing the platform.þþDon't hesitate to contact us at [sales@senx.io](mailto:sales@senx.io) for all your enquiries.þþ#### TrademarksþþWarp 10, WarpScript, WarpFleet, Geo Time Series and SenX are trademarks of SenX S.A.S.
