column17: CMPE 202 Course Repository
Pull request template status check
column43: # Tyrþ  þ![Powered by OpenShift Online](https://www.openshift.com/images/logos/powered_by_openshift.png)þþPull request template status checkþþ## Developmentþþ1. Build with Maven - mvn clean installþ1. Create a testing repository - for start you can fork my þhttps://github.com/xstefank/test-repo where the PR template is set up or þyou can create your own :)þ    - For creating new repository check the github manuals/helpþ    - PRs needs to be created to YOUR repository, you need to specify it þ    under the base fork field in the Open a Pull Request pageþ1. The project requires two properties to be set up to run correctlyþ    - GitHub OAuth token - þ        - in `config.properties` file (will be described later)þ        - or by the `GITHUB_OAUTH_TOKEN` environment propertyþ    - Configuration file specifying the format of the PR - the example can þ    be found in `tyr-runner/src/main/resources/format-example.yaml`, there areþ    two ways how to specify to the application where is this file locatedþ        - System property **template.format.url** - url of the configuration fileþ        - System property **template.format.file** -  path to the configuration fileþ1. start Tyr - `java -jar tyr-runner.jar` with above system properties setþ1. Expose local server instance with ngrok - https://ngrok.com/þ    - Here you need to expose **http** port **8080** as the default applicationþ    interface where the application runs, consult the ngrok documentation for theþ    information of how to specify these argumentsþ1. Now you should have everything prepared locally, next step is to let þGitHub know where your Tyr instance runsþ1. Add a webhook for Tyrþ    - In you test-repo - go to Settings -> Webhooks -> Add webhookþ    - Fill in Payload URL -> *your local exposed IP which is provided by þ    ngrok + “/pull-request”* (e. g., http://f202cf7c.ngrok.io/pull-request)þ    - Fill in Content type -> application/jsonþ    - Set *Let me select individual events* and check only *Pull requests* þ    and *Pull request review comments*þ    - Leave Active set and click “Add webhook”þ    - Don’t worry about the error - the first JSON differs from what the þ    subsequent PR JSONs will look likeþ1. If you create a PR now (create a new branch based on master for instance) þyou should already see some output in the server logsþ    - Be careful to which repository and branch you are doing the PR!!! þ    You need to specify your repository, the point is to try to set up Tyr þ    on your repository.þ1. However, you will still probably see problems with the custom PR check þwhich the app is trying to send to GitHub as there is a requirement to þprovide an oauth token to the GitHub APIþ1. Go to your profile -> settings (top right) -> Developer Settings -> þPersonal access tokensþ1. Generate new tokenþ1. Tick repo:statusþ1. Generate tokenþ1. The last step is to let Tyr know what is the token valueþ    - add the token to **config.properties** file (the example is provided in þ    the `tyr-runner/src/main/resources` folder) and copy this file to the same directoryþ    where Tyr is runningþ1. Restart Tyrþ1. Rerun (update existing or create new PR) - everything should be working nowþ1. If everything runs ok the PR should be updated with the valid error or þgreen color, and in terminal where the server runs you’ll see þ**Status update: 201**þþ## OpenShift deploymentþþThis project contains an openshift profile to be easily deployable toþ[Openshift platform](https://www.openshift.com/). þþTo deploy to Openshift:þþ1. login to your OS account (`oc login`)þ1. `mvn fabric8:deploy -Popenshift`

# Q-municate þQ-municate is a code of a chat application with a wide range of communication features included (such as messaging, file transfer, push notifications, audio/video calls).þhttp://q-municate.com/þþWe are happy to offer you a chat application out of the box. You can customize this application to on your needs (with attribution as stated in the license). QuickBlox is used for the backend http://quickblox.com. Find more information about Q-municate Android in our [Developers section](http://quickblox.com/developers/Q-municate#Q-municate_Android)þþ## Software Environmentþ* The Android application runs on Android 4.2+ þ* The Android App is developed as native Android application.þ* Web component is based on QuickBlox platform.þ* The App and Web panel has English language interface.þ* The App works only in Portrait screen modeþ* The App uses Internet connection: 3G or Wi-Fi when available.þþþQ-municate is a fully fledged chat application using the Quickblox API.þþ## Q-municate application uses following QuickBlox modules:þ* [Chat](http://quickblox.com/modules/chat)þ* [Users](http://quickblox.com/modules/users/)þ* [Content](http://quickblox.com/modules/content/) þ* [Custom objects](http://quickblox.com/modules/custom/)þ* [Messages](http://quickblox.com/modules/messages/)þ* [VideoChat](http://quickblox.com/developers/VideoChat/)þþþ## It includes features such as:þþ* Free Calls and Messaging: In Q-municate, everything is free;þ* File Transfer: Send Images to your friends and contacts;þ* Private / Group Chat: Enjoy private and group conversations with your contacts;þ* Facebook Registration: Use simple FB registration to fill in your profile and register account;þ* Friends Import: Q-municate will automatically connect you with your phone and Facebook contacts, who already use Q-municate. So there is no need to add your friends manually;þ* Offline Calls and Messages: Push notifications will inform you about missed chat messages and calls even, if you are offline. Don't worry, Q-municate will retrieve chat history during the next application use;þ* Messages Statuses: Send, read, now typing;þ* Delete Chat History/Remove Contact and Chat: Clear private chat history or delete this chat at all.þþPlease note all these features are available in open source code, so you can customize your app depending on your needs.þþþ## App screenshotsþ          þ

column17: Maven3 plugin that automates the third-party dependency management for Eclipse RCP
column43: # p2-maven-plugin [![Build Status](https://secure.travis-ci.org/reficio/p2-maven-plugin.png)](http://travis-ci.org/reficio/p2-maven-plugin)þþ## Truly mavenize your Eclipse RCP project!þþ### IntroþWelcome to the p2-maven-plugin! This is an easy-to-use Maven3 plugin responsible for the automation of the third-party dependency management in the Eclipse RCP environment.þþ### Why should you bother?þAre you familiar with the automated dependency management like in Maven, Gradle or any other fancy tool? You just define a project descriptor, add a bunch of dependencies and everything happens "automagically"... Piece of cake huh?!þþWell, there are, however, these RCP "unfortunates" for whom it is not quite that easy... Why's that, you might think?þþFirstly, Eclipse RCP is an OSGi environment which extends the Java dependency model, so you can’t simply take a "jar" file and hope that it's going to work; believe me - it will not. Secondly, there are some additional RCP conventions that have to be followed, which makes it even more complex.þþBut wait! Isn't Tycho supposed to solve all of these problems? Yeah, well, Tycho can do a lot, but there is definitely "something" missing... What is more, the learning curve is really steep, so it’s very easy to go off down the wrong path wasting a lot of time on simple things.þþThe following blog entry outlines the problem perfectly: https://bit.ly/2XhgJSQþThe author presents five different approaches how to configure the build and dependency management in a Tycho / Eclipse RCP project and, in the end, she couldn’t really propose a satisfactory solution! Unfortunately, there is no "one-click" easy solution, but if you stick to some best practices and use the right tools you can relax while Maven does most of the hard work for you.þþp2-maven-plugin simply tries to bridge the gap between Maven-like and RCP-like dependency management styles so that all Maven features can be seamlessly used with "No Fear!"þþRead further to fully understand why dependency management with Maven and Tycho is not that easy.þþ### Java vs. Maven vs. Eclipse RCP - dependency warþIn order to add a third-party dependency to an Eclipse RCP project the dependency has to reside in a P2 update site.þþEclipse (and other providers) provide a set of public update sites, but obviously not all popular and publicly available dependencies are there (that is the problem number #1). Pretty often you would also like to add a corporate / internal dependency - and you do not have to be a genius to figure out that it is not somewhere on the web…þþSince Eclipse RCP is an OSGi environment in order to add a dependency to a p2 update site the dependency has to be an OSGi bundle (that is the problem number #2).þþSo, let's sum up for now: all our artifacts have to be OSGi bundles, but they are not always bundles and they have to be located in a P2 site, but we do not have that site. How do we proceed then?þþIt is not that difficult, there is a 'bnd' tool written by Peter Kriens that can transform your jars into bundles. There is also a convenience tool provided by Eclipse RCP that can generate a P2 site (in a cumbersome and painful way though). Both tools assume that all your jars/bundles are located in a local folder - which means that you have to download them by-hand. You could use Maven to automate it a bit, but there is a significant difference in the way how Maven calculates a dependency tree and this is not always compatible with the OSGi way (that is the problem number #3). Let us elaborate on it a bit more.þþIn a P2 update site, there may be three versions of the same dependency, as bundles may selectively include one class from version X, and a second class from version Y (that is normal in the world of OSGi). In Maven, though, if you specify two versions of a dependency only one of them will be fetched as you don't want to have two almost identical dependencies on your classpath (Java simply cannot deal with that).þþSo in essence, to solve all problems mentioned above you have to do three things by-hand:þþ* download all required dependencies to a folder,þ* recognize which dependencies are not OSGi bundles and bundle them using the 'bnd' tool,þ* take all your bundles and invoke a P2 tool to generate a P2 update site.þþUfff, that is a mundane, cumbersome, repeatable and stupid activity that may take you a few hours - imagine now that you have to do it multiple times…þþThat's where p2-maven-plugin comes into play. It solves problems #1, #2, #3 and does all the hard work for you. Isn't that just brilliant? I think it is... :)þþ## How to use it in 2 minutes?þUsing p2-maven-plugin is really simple. I have prepared a quickstart pom.xml file so that you can give it a try right away. We're going to generate a site and expose it using the jetty-maven-plugin. This example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/quickstart/pom.xmlþþþp2-maven-plugin is now on maven central. You can find the latest version number here https://search.maven.org/#search%7Cgav%7C1%7Cg%3A%22org.reficio%22%20AND%20a%3A%22p2-maven-plugin%22þþHere's the pom.xml:þþ```xmlþ<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>þ<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001 XMLSchema-instance"þ    xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/maven-v4_0_0.xsd">þ    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>þþ    <groupId>org.reficio.rcp</groupId>þ    <artifactId>example-p2-site</artifactId>þ    <packaging>pom</packaging>þ    <version>1.4.1-SNAPSHOT</version>þþ    <build>þ        <plugins>þ            <plugin>þ                <groupId>org.reficio</groupId>þ                <artifactId>p2-maven-plugin</artifactId>þ                <version>1.3.0</version>þ                <executions>þ                    <execution>þ                        <id>default-cli</id>þ                        <configuration>þ                            <artifacts>þ                                <!-- specify your depencies here -->þ                                <!-- groupId:artifactId:version -->þ                                <artifact><id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id></artifact>þ                                <artifact><id>commons-lang:commons-lang:2.4</id></artifact>þ                                <artifact><id>commons-lang:commons-lang:2.5</id></artifact>þ                                <artifact><id>commons-lang:commons-lang:2.6</id></artifact>þ                                <artifact><id>org.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.1</id></artifact>þ                            </artifacts>þ                        </configuration>þ                    </execution>þ                </executions>þ            </plugin>þþ            <plugin>þ                <groupId>org.mortbay.jetty</groupId>þ                <artifactId>jetty-maven-plugin</artifactId>þ                <version>8.1.5.v20120716</version>þ                <configuration>þ                    <scanIntervalSeconds>10</scanIntervalSeconds>þ                    <webAppSourceDirectory>${basedir}/target/repository/</webAppSourceDirectory>þ                    <webApp>þ                        <contextPath>/site</contextPath>þ                    </webApp>þ                </configuration>þ            </plugin>þþ        </plugins>þ    </build>þþ</project>þ```þþThe artifacts may be specified using the following notation:þþ```þ<groupId>:<artifactId>[:<extension>[:<classifier>]]:<version>þ```þþThere are many more config options, but basically that's the thing that you need for now. in order to generate the site invoke the following command 'mvn p2:site' in the folder where the pom.xml file resides. When the process finishes your P2 site is ready!þþYou will see the following output:þ```þ$ mvn p2:siteþþ[INFO] Scanning for projects...þ[INFO]                                                                         þ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO] Building example-p2-site 1.0.0þ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO]þ[INFO] --- p2-maven-plugin:1.0.0:site (generate-p2-site) @ example-p2-site ---þ[INFO] Command line:þ    /bin/sh -c cd /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources && /System/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/1.6.0.jdk/Contents/þ    Home/bin/java -jar /opt/maven-ext/org/eclipse/tycho/tycho-bundles-external/0.14.0/eclipse/plugins/þ    org.eclipse.equinox.launcher_1.3.0.v20111107-1631.jar -nosplash -application org.eclipse.equinox.p2.publisher.FeaturesAndBundlesPublisherþ    -artifactRepository file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/repository -metadataRepository file:/opt/þ    workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/repository -publishArtifacts -compress -source /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-þ    maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/sourceþGenerating metadata for ..þGeneration completed with success [0 seconds].þ[INFO] Command line:þ    /bin/sh -c cd /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/repository && /System/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/þ    1.6.0.jdk/Contents/Home/bin/java -jar /opt/maven-ext/org/eclipse/tycho/tycho-bundles-external/0.14.0/eclipse/plugins/þ    org.eclipse.equinox.launcher_1.3.0.v20111107-1631.jar -nosplash -application org.eclipse.equinox.p2.publisher.CategoryPublisher -þ    categoryDefinition file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/repository/category.xml -metadataRepositoryþ    file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/src/main/resources/target/repository/        þGenerating metadata for ..þGeneration completed with success [0 seconds].þ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO] BUILD SUCCESSþ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO] Total time: 5.164sþ[INFO] Finished at: Sat Jul 07 16:28:49 CEST 2012þ[INFO] Final Memory: 7M/81Mþ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ```þþYour p2 site is located in the target/repository folder and looks like this:þ```þpom.xmlþtargetþ├── repositoryþ│   ├── artifacts.jarþ│   ├── category.xmlþ│   ├── content.jarþ│   └── pluginsþ│   │   ├── org.apache.commons.io_2.1.0.jarþ│   │   ├── org.apache.commons.lang_2.4.0.jarþ│   │   ├── org.apache.commons.lang_2.5.0.jarþ│   │   ├── org.apache.commons.lang_2.6.0.jarþ│   │   └── org.apache.commons.lang3_3.1.0.jarþ│   │þ│   └── featuresþ│   │   └── com.example.feature_1.0.0.jarþ```þþUnfortunately, it's not the end of the story since tycho does not support local repositories (being more precise: repositories located in a local folder). The only way to work it around is to expose our newly created update site using an HTTP server. We're going to use the jetty-plugin - don't worry, the example above contains a sample jetty-plugin set-up. Just type 'mvn jetty:run' and open the following link http://localhost:8080/site. Your P2 update site will be there!þþNow, simply reference your site in your target definition and play with your Eclipse RCP project like you were in the Plain Old Java Environment. Remember to enable the "Group items by category" option, otherwise you will not see any bundles.þþ```þ$ mvn jetty:runþþ[INFO] Scanning for projects...þ[INFO]þ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO] Building example-p2-site 1.0.0þ[INFO] ------------------------------------------------------------------------þ[INFO]þ[INFO] >>> jetty-maven-plugin:8.1.5.v20120716:run (default-cli) @ example-p2-site >>>þ[INFO]þ[INFO] <<< jetty-maven-plugin:8.1.5.v20120716:run (default-cli) @ example-p2-site <<<þ[INFO]þ[INFO] --- jetty-maven-plugin:8.1.5.v20120716:run (default-cli) @ example-p2-site ---þ[INFO] Configuring Jetty for project: example-p2-siteþ[INFO] Webapp source directory = /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repositoryþ[INFO] Reload Mechanic: automaticþ[INFO] Classes directory /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/classes does not existþ[INFO] Context path = /siteþ[INFO] Tmp directory = /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/tmpþ[INFO] Web defaults = org/eclipse/jetty/webapp/webdefault.xmlþ[INFO] Web overrides =  noneþ[INFO] web.xml file = nullþ[INFO] Webapp directory = /opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repositoryþ2012-08-20 14:20:13.473:INFO:oejs.Server:jetty-8.1.5.v20120716þ2012-08-20 14:20:13.582:INFO:oejpw.PlusConfiguration:No Transaction manager found - if your webapp requires one, please configure one.þ2012-08-20 14:20:13.878:INFO:oejsh.ContextHandler:started o.m.j.p.JettyWebAppContext{/site,file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/},file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/þ2012-08-20 14:20:13.878:INFO:oejsh.ContextHandler:started o.m.j.p.JettyWebAppContext{/site,file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/},file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/þ2012-08-20 14:20:13.878:INFO:oejsh.ContextHandler:started o.m.j.p.JettyWebAppContext{/site,file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/},file:/opt/workspaces/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/examples/quickstart/target/repository/þ2012-08-20 14:20:13.938:INFO:oejs.AbstractConnector:Started SelectChannelConnector@0.0.0.0:8080þ[INFO] Started Jetty Serverþ[INFO] Starting scanner at interval of 10 seconds.þ```þþ## Best Practicesþ* **DO NOT** to use the Tycho's pomDependencies->consider option as it is simply of NO goodþ* **DO NOT** define your external dependencies in the `dependencies` section of the pom.xml (mvn compilation will work in the console, but it will not work in the Eclipse IDE when you import the project, since the 'Target Configuration' knows nothing about the dependencies defined there)þ* Use the MANIFEST-FIRST approach - define all your dependencies in the MANIFEST.MF files.þ* If some of your dependencies are not OSGi bundles or are not available in P2 update sites, SIMPLY define them in the p2-maven-plugin config, generate the site and make it available using jetty (or any other mechanism). Then add the URL of the exposed site to the target platform definition. In such a way you will have a consistent, manifest-first dependency management in Eclipse RCP project!þ* Whenever you have to add another external dependency, simply re-invoke "mvn p2:site" and the site will be regenerated.þ* You can automate the generation/exposition of our site using for example Jenkins and Apache2þþ## Maven compatibilityþp2-maven-plugin is compatible with Maven 3.x (we test it against 3.0.x, 3.1.x, 3.2.x)þþ## ExamplesþThere are many more use examples, just have a look:þþ### Default optionsþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/quickstart/pom.xmlþþThis is the simplest and the shortest setup. Only the identifiers of the dependencies have to be specified.þWhat will be the behavior like if we use the configuration listed below?þþ* specified dependencies will be fetchedþ* transitive dependencies will be fetchedþ* jars containing source code will NOT be fetchedþ* jars that are **NOT** osgi bundles will be "bundled" using bnd tool; if instructions are specified, they will be APPLIED.þ* jars that are osgi bundles will be simply included, if instructions are specified, they will be **IGNORED** (see override example)þ* p2 site will be generatedþþHow the instructions works:þþ* instructions are applied only to the root artifact that you specify!þ* instructions are not applied to the TRANSITIVE dependencies!þ* transitive dependencies are never overridden (see `<override>` option)þ* transitive dependencies are bundled using the default instructions quoted below.þ*  other instructions, such as, Bundle-SymbolicName, Bundle-Name, Bundle-Version, etc. are calculated according to the following rules: http://felix.apache.org/site/apache-felix-maven-bundle-plugin-bnd.htmlþ*  if you specify any instructions they will be applied only if the jar is not already an OSGi bundle - otherwise you have to use the override option - please see the /examples/override/pom.xml exampleþþThe default instructions are:þ```xmlþ<instructions>þ    <Import-Package>*;resolution:=optional</Import-Package>þ    <Export-Package>*</Export-Package>þ</instructions>þ```þþThe following definition of an artifact:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ</artifact>þ```þþis an equivalent of the following definition:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ    <transitive>true</transitive>þ    <source>false</source>þ    <override>false</override>þ    <singleton>false</singleton>þ    <instructions>þ        <Import-Package>*;resolution:=optional</Import-Package>þ        <Export-Package>*</Export-Package>þ    </instructions>þ    <excludes/>þ</artifact>þ```     þIf the instruction name cannot be used as a XML tag (for example `-noee`), you can use the properties format:þ```xmlþ<instructionsProperties>þ    <property>þ        <name>-noee</name>þ        <value>true</value>þ    </property>þ</instructionsProperties>þ```þInstructions in properties format take precedence over the ones in map format in case of duplicates, which means that if you defined the same instruction both in properties and map format, the value from properties will be used and the warning will be printed to log.þþ### Source optionþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/source/pom.xmlþþThis is the configuration snippet that enables you to include the source jars and generate the source bundles for all the dependencies. `<source>true</source>` section has to be included to enable this option.þIf enabled together with the transitive option it will fetch sources of transitive dependencies as well.þþExample:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ    <source>true</source>þ</artifact>þ```þþþ### Transitive optionþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/transitive/pom.xmlþþThis is the configuration snippet that enables you to exclude transitive dependencies. `<transitive>false</transitive>` section has to be included to enable this option.þþExpected behavior:þþ* specified dependencies will be fetchedþ* transitive dependencies will NOT be fetchedþþExample usage:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>org.mockito:mockito-core:1.9.0</id>þ    <transitive>false</transitive>þ</artifact>þ```þþ### Maven phase bindingþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/phase/pom.xmlþþYou can also bind the invocation of the plugin to a Maven phase. Just specify the following binding and your p2-maven-plugin will be invoked during the 'mvn compile' phase.þ```xmlþ<id>generate-p2-site</id>þ<phase>compile</phase>þ<goals>þ    <goal>site</goal>þ</goals>þ```þþ### Override optionþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/override/pom.xmlþþThis is the configuration snippet that enables you to override the default MANIFEST.MF files in jars that are already OSGi bundles. `<override>true</override>` section has to be included to enable this optionþþTo manually set the instructions please specify the `<instructions>` section in the configuration of the artifact.þIf you do not specify any instructions the MANIFEST.MF file will be overridden with the default instructions.þPlease see the examples/quickstart/pom.xml for more info.þþRemember:þþ* override flag does not apply to the transitive dependenciesþ* instructions are not applied to the transitive dependenciesþþExpected behavior:þþ* jars that are OSGi bundles will be "bundled" once more using the bnd tool overriding the default MANIFEST.MFþ* if you specify instructions for these jars they will be APPLIED (not to the transitive dependencies though)þþThe following example presents how to enable the override option:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ    <override>true</override>þ</artifact>þ```    þþThe following example presents how to enable the override option specifying the instructions:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ    <override>true</override>þ    <singleton>false</singleton>þ    <instructions>þ        <Import-Package>*;resolution:=optional</Import-Package>þ        <Export-Package>*</Export-Package>þ    </instructions>þ</artifact>þ```þþThis definition of an artifact should look like this:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>commons-io:commons-io:2.1</id>þ    <transitive>false</transitive>þ    <override>true</override>þ</artifact>þ```þþ### Excludes optionþThis example is located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/excludes/pom.xmlþThis examples presents how to selectively exclude some of the transitive dependencies of an artifact.þIn order to enable this functionality the `<excludes>` section has to be includedþin the configuration of the artifact.þIf the fetch of the transitive dependencies is disabled through the `<transitive>false</transitive>` switchþthe `<excludes>` section will be ignored.þþThe `<excludes>` resolver reuses the org.sonatype.aether.util.filter.PatternExclusionsDependencyFilterþthat works in the following way:þ    "PatternExclusionsDependencyFilter is a simple filter to exclude artifacts specified by patterns.þ    The artifact pattern syntax has the following format: [groupId]:[artifactId]:[extension]:[version].þ    Each segment of the pattern is optional and supports 'full' and 'partial' wildcards (*).þ    An empty pattern segment is treated as an implicit wildcard.þ    Version can be a range in case a {@link VersionScheme} is specified."þþExamples of `<exclude>` values:þþ* `<exclude>org.apache.*</exclude>` matches artifacts whose group-id begins with 'org.apache.'þ* `<exclude>:::*-SNAPSHOT</exclude>` matches all snapshot artifactsþ* `<exclude>:objenesis::</exclude>` matches artifacts whose artifactId is objenesisþ* `<exclude>*</exclude>` matches all artifactsþ* `<exclude>:::</exclude>` (or `<exclude>*:*:*:*</exclude>`) matches all artifactsþ* `<exclude></exclude>` matches all artifactsþþExpected behavior:þþ* selected transitive dependencies will be fetchedþþExample usage:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>org.mockito:mockito-core:1.9.0</id>þ    <source>false</source>þ    <transitive>true</transitive>þ    <excludes>þ        <exclude>org.objenesis:objenesis:jar:1.0</exclude>þ    </excludes>þ</artifact>þ```þþ### Singleton optionþThis is the configuration snippet that enables you to generate singleton bundles. `<singleton>true</singleton>` section has to be included to enable this option.þþExpected behavior:þþ* bundle will have a "singleton:=true" string added to its symbolic nameþ* remember that the build may fail if the artifact is already a bundle and the singleton is set to true and the override option is skipped or set to false.þþExample usage:þ```xmlþ<artifact>þ    <id>org.mockito:mockito-core:1.9.0</id>þ    <singleton>true</singleton>þ</artifact>þ```þþ### P2 ResolverþThe plugin also includes the P2 resolver which means that you can include bundles residing in P2 repositories in the generated site.þHave a look at the P2 example located here: https://github.com/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/blob/master/examples/p2/pom.xmlþþIn order to have a P2 artifact resolved include its definition in the `<p2>` tag (not in the `<artifacts>` tag)þ```xmlþ<p2>þ    <artifact>þ        <id>org.junit:4.11.0.v201303080030</id>þ    </artifact>þ</p2>þ```þþNext, add a P2 repository in the `<repositories>` tag (its layout has to be set to `<layout>p2</layout>`):þ```xmlþ    <repositories>þ        <repository>þ            <id>kepler</id>þ            <url>http://download.eclipse.org/tools/orbit/downloads/drops/R20130517111416/repository/</url>þ            <layout>p2</layout>þ        </repository>þ    </repositories>þ```þþIf there's more P2 repositories defined, they will be taken in the top-down manner, until the artifact resolution has been successfully executed.þþAs a result the the specified P2 artifact will be downloaded and included in the generated P2 site.þIt will not be bundled, since all P2 artifacts are alread OSGi bundles by definition.þþ### Eclipse FeaturesþYou can also add eclipse feature bundles to maven and include them in the generated p2 repository.þþ* build may fail if the maven artifact is not a valid eclipse feature jarþ* source and transitive must both be false for feature artifactsþ* plugins must be added separately, adding the feature will not add the corresponding pluginsþþExample usage:þ```xmlþ<configuration>þ    <artifacts>þ        <artifact><id>org.apache.commons:commons-lang3:3.1</id></artifact>þ    </artifacts>þ    <features>þ        <artifact>þ            <id>org.reficio:test.feature:1.0.0</id>þ            <source>false</source>þ            <transitive>false</transitive>þ        </artifact>þ    </features>þ</configuration>þ```þþYour p2 site will look like this:þ```þpom.xmlþtargetþ├── repositoryþ│   ├── artifacts.jarþ│   ├── category.xmlþ│   ├── content.jarþ│   └── pluginsþ│   │   └── org.apache.commons.lang3_3.1.0.jarþ│   │þ│   └── featuresþ│       └── com.example.feature_1.0.0.jarþþ```þþYou can have a look at two integration test cases of this feature that are located in the src/test/integration folder:þþ* feature-bundle-01-itþ* feature-bundle-02-itþþþ### Other tricksþAlternatively, you can get this plugin to generate the feature bundles for you as part of generating the p2 repository,þþExample usage:þ```xmlþ <configuration>þ  <featureDefinitions>þ   <feature>þ    <id>test.feature</id>þ    <version>${project.version}</version>þ    <label>Test Feature 2</label>þ    <providerName>${project.groupId}</providerName>þ    <description>${project.description}</description>þ    <copyright>A copyright</copyright>þ    <license>A licence</license>þ    <generateSourceFeature>true</generateSourceFeature>þ    <artifacts>þ     <artifact>þ      <id>org.reficio.rcp:test.bundle1:1.0.0</id>þ      <transitive>false</transitive>þ      <source>true</source>þ     </artifact>þ     <artifact>þ      <id>org.reficio.rcp:test.bundle2:1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</id>þ      <transitive>false</transitive>þ      <source>true</source>þ     </artifact>þ    </artifacts>         þ   </feature>þ  </featureDefinitions>þ </configuration>þ```þþþ### Other featuresþ* p2-maven-plugin will tweak the version of a snapshot dependency replacing the SNAPSHOT string with a timestamp in the following format "yyyyMMddHHmmss" (feature #14)þ* It's possible to add a classifier to the artifact definition - supported notation: `<groupId>:<artifactId>[:<extension>[:<classifier>]]:<version>`; for example:  `<id>groupid:artifactid:jar:tests:version</id>` (feature #28)þþþ## General configuration optionsþThere are some other plugin options that you can specify in the configuration:þþ<table>þ<tr><th>Option</th><th>Default value</th><th>Description</th></tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>destinationDirectory</td>þ    <td>${project.basedir}/target/repository</td>þ    <td>Folder where the generated p2 site should be copied to</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>categoryFileURL</td>þ    <td>default category file (all plugins in one category)</td>þ    <td>URL of the category.xml file which should be used for the p2 site generation</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>pedantic</td>þ    <td>false</td>þ    <td>Specifies if the bnd tool should be pedantic</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>compressSite</td>þ    <td>true</td>þ    <td>Specifies if to compress the descriptors of the generated site</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>forkedProcessTimeoutInSeconds</td>þ    <td>0 (infinite)</td>þ    <td>Kill the p2 forked process after a certain number of seconds.</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>additionalArgs</td>þ    <td></td>þ    <td>Specifies additional arguments to p2Launcher, for example -consoleLog -debug -verbose</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>skipInvalidArtifacts</td>þ    <td>false</td>þ    <td>Controls if the processing should be continued if bundling errors occur.</td>þ</tr>þ<tr>þ    <td>skipNotExistingArtifacts</td>þ    <td>false</td>þ    <td>Controls if the processing should be continued if an artifact could not be resolved.</td>þ</tr>þ</table>þþþSample configuration snippet with the additional options:þ```xmlþ<configuration>þ    <pedantic>false</pedantic>þ    <additionalArgs>-consoleLog -debug -verbose</additionalArgs>þ    <compressSite>true</compressSite>þ    <forkedProcessTimeoutInSeconds>0</forkedProcessTimeoutInSeconds>þ</configuration>þ```þþ## Last but not leastþþ### Reporting bugsþPlease describe the issue thoroughly. Please include a minimal pom.xml file that can be used to reproduce the problem.þþ### Pull requestsþIf you submit a pull request please make sure to add an unit/integration test case that covers the feature. Pull requests without a proper test coverage may not be pulled at all.þþ### Running integration testsþInvoke the following command to run the integration tests suite:þþ```þ$ mvn packageþ```þþ### ReleasingþþRun the release.sh script (syntax: master version, release version, new master version):þ```þ$ ./release.sh 1.3.0-SNAPSHOT 1.3.0 1.4.0-SNAPSHOTþ```þþRun maven artifacts gpg sign (assumes that gpg is configured on the box)þ```þmvn verify -Pgpgþ```þþTar all the artifacts in the target folder:þ```þtar -cvf p2.tar p2*.*þ```þþUpload p2.tar to bintray (selecting the explode options) and trigger the sync to maven central.þþþþ### Who's behind it?þDo you like the project? Star it on GitHub and follow me on Twitter! Thanks!þþhttp://twitter.com/tombujokþþReficio™ - Reestablish your software!þwww.reficio.orgþþþ[![Bitdeli Badge](https://d2weczhvl823v0.cloudfront.net/reficio/p2-maven-plugin/trend.png)](https://bitdeli.com/free "Bitdeli Badge")

column17: an easy jdbc sql framework of an alternative to ibatis
column43:
eqlþ====þ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/bingoohuang/eql.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/bingoohuang/eql)þ[![Coverage Status](https://coveralls.io/repos/github/bingoohuang/eql/badge.svg?branch=master)](https://coveralls.io/github/bingoohuang/eql?branch=master)þ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.github.bingoohuang/eql/badge.svg?style=flat-square)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.github.bingoohuang/eql/)þ[![License](http://img.shields.io/:license-apache-brightgreen.svg)](http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html)þþAn easy framework of java JDBC to be an alternative to ibatis/mybatis.[中文版](ChineseReadme.md)þþI don't like XML in ibatis.þ+ excuse 1:þþ```xmlþ<select id="selectAB">þ<![CDATA[þ   SELELCT A,Bþ   FROM SOME_TABLEþ   WHERE A > #a#þ]]>þ</select>þ```þWooh, for a simple sql of only three lines, we need add a CDATA block to use **>** (I always forget how to write CDATA, and every time I have to lookup XML CDATA reference). It's so bad. And also the **select** is redundant because the SQL itself is telling us it is a SELECT SQL and not some others.þþ+ excuse 2:þþWhen two or more members are working on the same XML file, only one bad SQL will corrupt all the SQLs in the same file:þþ```xmlþ<update id="xxx">þSELECT 1 FROM DUAL WHERE 1 > 0þ</update>þ```þþOoh, that is "one rotten apple could ruin a whole barrel of apples."þþ+ excuse 3:þþEvery time, when I code with ibatis, I forget how to begin (eg. how to create Sqlmap and how to write valid ibatis xml) and have to copy some initial code from others.þþ+ excuse 4:þþThere is no else in its dynamic. I have to write like:þþ```sqlþ<select id="xxx">þ   SELECT 1 FROM DUALþ   WHERE 1 = 1þ   <isEmpty property="name">þ     AND name = #name#þ   </isEmpty>þ   <isNotEmpty property="name">þ     AND id = #id#þ   </isNotEmpty>þ</select>þ```þþ+ excuse 5:þþI don't like XML. I like free text and freedom. And so I created EQL which is really very easy.þþ# One minute tutorialþ* copy [eql-DEFAULT.properties](https://github.com/bingoohuang/eql/blob/master/src/test/resources/eql/eql-DEFAULT.properties) to your classpath eql and do some changes for your database connection info such as url, password and username.þ* create com/xxx/Demo.java.þ* create com/xxx/Demo.eql(***keep the same package and base filename***) in classpath.þ* write following code in com.xxx.Demo main method:þþ```javaþString str = new Eql().selectFirst("demo").execute();þ```þþ* write an eql in Demo.eqlþþ```sqlþ-- [demo]þselect 'X' from dualþ```þþ* that's all. and you see it is very simple.þþ# Return one rowþþ```javaþMap<String, String> row = new Eql().selectFirst("oneRow").execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [oneRow]þselect 'X', 'Y' from dualþ```þþ# Return a Javabeanþþ```javaþXYBean xy = new Eql().selectFirst("javabean").execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [javabean returnType=XYBean]þselect 'X', 'Y' from dualþ```þþ# Return rowsþþ```javaþList<XYBean> xys = new Eql().select("rows").þ             .returnType(XYBean.class)þ             .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [rows]þselect 'X' X, 'Y' Y from dualþunionþselect 'A' X, 'B' Y from dualþ```þþ# With parameters in sequenceþþ* example 1þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("autoSeq1")þ          .params("x")þ          .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [autoSeq1]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'x' = '##'þ```þþ* example 2þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("autoSeq2")þ          .params("x", "y")þ          .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [autoSeq2]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'x' = '##'þand 'y' = '##'þ```þþ* example 3þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("autoSeq3")þ          .params("y", "x")þ          .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [autoSeq3]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'x' = '#2#'þand 'y' = '#1#'þ```þþ# With parameters by properties nameþþ* example 1þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("bean")þ       .params(new XyBean("x", "y"))þ       .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [bean]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'x' = '#x#'þand 'y' = '#y#'þ```þþ* example 2þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("map")þ        .params(mapOf("x", "a", "y", "b"))þ        .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [map]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'a' = '#x#'þand 'b' = '#y#'þ```þþ* example 3þþ```javaþString x = new Eql().selectFirst("map")þ        .params("a", "b")þ        .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [map]þselect 'X' from dualþwhere 'a' = '#_1#'þand 'b' = '#_2#'þ```þþIn above example, the _1 and _2 are used, they are called built-in parameters.þMore built-in parameters list here:þ1. `_time` current timestamp, type: `java.sql.Timestamp`þ2. `_date` current date, type:`java.util.Date`þ3. `_host` current hostnameþ4. `_ip` current ipþ5. `_params` currrent params arrayþ6. `_paramsCount` length of current params arrayþ7. `_1`,`_2`,`_3`,... the param in sequenceþ8. `_dynamics` current dynamics arrayþ9. `_dynamicsCount` lenght of current dynamics arrayþ10. `_databaseId`, oracle/mysql/h2/db2/sqlserverþþ# Dynamic sqlþþEql's dynamic sql is now base on [OGNL](http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-ognl/) expression.þþ## ifþþ```javaþþ// real sql will be:þ//   select 'X' from dual where 'a' = ?þ// and with one bound param "a"þString x = new Eql().selectFirst("ifDemo")þ          .params(mapOf("x", "a"))þ          .execute();þþ// real sql will be:þ//   select 'X' from dualþString y = new Eql().selectFirst("ifDemo")þ          .params(mapOf("x", "b"))þ          .execute();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [ifDemo]þselect 'X' from dualþ-- if x == "a"þwhere 'a' = '#x#'þ-- endþþ-- [ifDemo2]þselect 'X' from dualþ-- if x == "a"þwhere 'a' = '#x#'þ-- else if x == "b"þwhere 'b' = '#x#'þ-- elseþwhere 'c' = '##'þ-- endþþ-- or use more compact syntaxþþ-- [ifDemo]þselect 'X' from dual /* if x == "a" */  where 'a' = '#x#' /* end */þ```þþ## iffþþ```sqlþ-- [ifDemo]þselect 'X' from dualþ-- iff x == "a"þwhere 'a' = '#x#'þþ-- or use more compact syntaxþþ-- [ifDemo]þselect 'X' from dual /* iff x == "a" */  where 'a' = '#x#'þ```þþto use STATIC fields:þþ```javaþpublic class OgnlStaticTest {þ    public static String STATE = "102";þþ    @Testþ    public void test() {þ        String str = new Eql("mysql").id("ognlStatic").limit(1)þ                .params(ImmutableMap.of("state", "102", "x", "y"))þ                .execute();þ        assertThat(str, is(nullValue()));þþ        str = new Eql("mysql").id("ognlStatic").limit(1)þ                .params(ImmutableMap.of("state", "103", "x", "x"))þ                .execute();þ        assertThat(str, is("X"));þ    }þ}þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [ognlStatic]þselect 'X'þfrom DUALþ-- iff state == @org.n3r.eql.OgnlStaticTest@STATEþwhere 'x' = '#x#'þ```þþ## switchþþ```sqlþ-- [switchSelect returnType=org.n3r.eql.SimpleTest$Bean]þSELECT A,B,C,D,EþFROM EQL_TESTþWHEREþ-- switch aþ--   case 1þ  A = 1þ--   case 2þ  A = 2þ-- endþþ-- or with default keywordþþ-- [switchSelectWithDefault returnType=org.n3r.eql.SimpleTest$Bean]þSELECT A,B,C,D,EþFROM eql_TESTþWHEREþ-- switch aþ--   case 1þ   A = 1þ--   case 2þ   A = 2þ--   defaultþ   A = 3þ-- endþ```þþ## forþþ```javaþMap<String, Object> map = Maps.newHashMap();þmap.put("list", ImmutableList.of("a", "b", "x"));þþString str = new Eql().selectFirst("for1").params(map).execute();þassertThat(str, is("x"));þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [for1]þSELECT 'x'þFROM DUALþWHERE 'x' inþ-- for item=item index=index collection=list open=( separator=, close=)þ#item#þ-- endþ```þþ## is(Not)Null/is(Not)Empty/is(Not)Blankþþ```sqlþ-- [isEmpty]þSELECT BþFROM eql_TESTþ-- isEmpty aþWHERE A in (1,2)þ-- elseþWHERE A in (3,4)þ-- endþþ-- [isNotEmpty]þSELECT BþFROM eql_TESTþ-- isNotEmpty aþWHERE A = '#a#'þ-- endþ```þþ## in statement in sqlþþ```sqlþSELECT NAME FROM EQL_IN WHERE ID IN (/* in _1 */)þ```þþ```javaþList<String> names = new Eql().params(Lists.newArrayList("1", "2")).execute();þ```þþ## trimþþ```sqlþ-- [updateAuthor]þupdate authorþ-- trim prefix=SET suffixOverrides=,þ  -- iff username != nullþ         username='#username#',þ  -- iff password != nullþ         PASSWORD='#password#',þ  -- iff email != nullþ         email='#email#',þ  -- iff bio != nullþ          bio='#bio#',þ-- endþwhere id='#id#'þþ-- [selectBlog]þSELECT STATE FROM BLOGþ-- trim prefix=WHERE prefixOverrides=AND|ORþ   -- iff state != nullþ          state = '#state#'þ   -- iff title != nullþ      AND title like '#title#'þ   -- iff author != null and author.name != nullþ      AND author_name like '#author.name#'þ-- endþGROUP BY STATEþ```þþ# Pagination supportþþ```javaþEqlPage page = new EqlPage(3, 2);þList<SimpleTest.Bean> beans = new Eql().id("testPage")þ   .returnType(SimpleTest.Bean.class)þ   .limit(page)þ   .params("DC")þ   .execute();þassertThat(page.getTotalRows(), is(10));þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [testPage]þSELECT A,B,C,D,EþFROM eql_TESTþWHERE C = '##'þ```þþ# Dynamic table nameþþ```javaþString str = new Eql().selectFirst("replace1")þ   .params("x").dynamics("DUAL").execute();þassertThat(str, is("x"));þþstr = new Eql().selectFirst("replace2").params("x")þ   .dynamics(ImmutableMap.of("table", "DUAL")).execute();þassertThat(str, is("x"));þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [replace1]þSELECT 'x'þFROM $$þWHERE 'x' = '##'þþþ-- [replace2]þSELECT 'x'þFROM $table$þWHERE 'x' = '##'þ```þþ# Batch executeþþ```javaþEql eql = new Eql();þeql.startBatch(/*batchSize*/10);þfor (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {þ    String orderNo = randLetters(10);þ    String userId = randLetters(10);þ    int prizeItem = randInt(10);þ    int ret = eql.insert("insertPrizeBingoo")þ           .params(orderNo, "Olympic", "" + prizeItem, userId)þ           .execute();þþ    assertEquals(0, ret);þ}þþeql.executeBatch();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [insertPrizeBingoo]þINSERT INTO EQL_TEST_BINGOO(ORDER_NO, ACTIVITY_ID, ITEM_ID, USER_ID, BINGOO_TIME)þVALUES(##, ##, ##, ##, SYSDATE)þ```þþ# Like option supportþþ```sqlþ-- [likeDemo]þselect 'x' from demo where name like '#:Like#'þþ-- [leftLikeDemo]þselect 'x' from demo where name like '#:LeftLike#'þþ-- [rightLikeDemo]þselect 'x' from demo where name like '#:RightLike#'þ```þþ```javaþnew Eql().id("likeDemo").params("b").execute();þ// 16:12:51.316 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.Eql - prepare sql likeDemo: select 'x' from demo where name like ?þ// 16:12:51.317 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.map.EqlRun - param: [%b%]þþnew Eql().id("leftLikeDemo").params("c").execute();þ// 16:12:51.326 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.Eql - prepare sql leftLikeDemo: select 'x' from demo where name like ?þ// 16:12:51.326 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.map.EqlRun - param: [%c]þþnew Eql().id("rightLikeDemo").params("a").execute();þ// 16:12:51.331 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.Eql - prepare sql rightLikeDemo: select 'x' from demo where name like ?þ// 16:12:51.331 [main] DEBUG org.n3r.eql.map.EqlRun - param: [a%]þ```þþ# Oracle Blob supportþþ```javaþpublic void testOracleBlob() {þ    new Eqll().id("insertBlob").params("中华人民共和国").execute();þ    byte[] bytes = new Eqll().id("selectBlob").limit(1).execute();þ    assertThat(new String(bytes, Charsets.UTF_8), is("中华人民共和国"));þþ    String ret = new Eqll().id("selectBlobString").limit(1).execute();þ    assertThat(ret, is("中华人民共和国"));þþ    AsResult asResult = new Eqll().id("selectBlobAsResult").limit(1).execute();þ    assertThat(asResult.getSeq(), is(1));þ    assertThat(asResult.getRemark(), is("中华人民共和国"));þþ    Integer effectedRows = new Eqll().id("updateBlob").params("台湾省").execute();þ    assertThat(effectedRows, is(1));þ    ret = new Eqll().id("selectBlobString").limit(1).execute();þ    assertThat(ret, is("台湾省"));þ}þþpublic static class AsResult {þ    private String state;þ    private String remark;þ    private int seq;þþ    // setters ang gettersþ}þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [insertBlob onerr=resume]þDROP TABLE eql_BLOB;þCREATE TABLE eql_BLOB (BOB BLOB);þINSERT INTO eql_BLOB(BOB) VALUES(#:LOB#)þþ-- [selectBlob]þSELECT BOB FROM eql_BLOBþþ-- [selectBlobString returnType=string]þSELECT BOB FROM eql_BLOBþþþ-- [selectBlobAsResult returnType=org.n3r.eql.JavaBlobTest$AsResult]þSELECT 1 as seq, BOB as remark FROM eql_BLOBþþ-- [updateBlob]þUPDATE eql_BLOB SET BOB = '#:LOB#'þ```þþ# [Diamond-miner](https://github.com/bingoohuang/diamond-miner) support exampleþEql also can be loaded from diamond.þFirst create eql/eql-diamond.properties on classpath like:þþ```þsql.resource.loader=org.n3r.eql.diamond.DiamondEqlResourceLoaderþþtransactionType=jdbcþdriver=oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriverþurl=jdbc:oracle:thin:@127.0.0.1:1521:orclþuser=orclþpassword=orclþ```þþAs you see, we redefined sql resource loader to diamond-specific.þAnd then add a config in diamond:þþ```þgroup=EQLþdataId=org.n3r.eql.DiamondTest.eqlþcontent=þþ-- [diamondDemo]þSELECT 'Hello' FROM DUALþþ```þþAnd then in java codeþþ```javaþString str = new Eql("diamond").selectFirst("diamondDemo").execute();þSystem.out.println(str);þ```þþ# Reuse jdbc statements to select/update repeatedly.þþ```javaþEql eql = new Eql().id("selectStmt");þESelectStmt selectStmt = eql.selectStmt();þþselectStmt.executeQuery(3);þString str = selectStmt.next();þassertThat(str, is("CC"));þassertThat(selectStmt.next(), is(nullValue()));þþselectStmt.executeQuery(4);þstr = selectStmt.next();þassertThat(str, is("DC"));þassertThat(selectStmt.next(), is(nullValue()));þþselectStmt.close();þeql.close();þ```þþ```javaþEql eql = new Eql().id("updateStmt");þEUpdateStmt updateStmt = eql.updateStmt();þþint rows = updateStmt.update(3, "Bingoo");þassertThat(rows, is(1));þþrows = updateStmt.update(4, "Dingoo");þassertThat(rows, is(1));þþupdateStmt.close();þeql.close();þ```þþ```sqlþ-- [selectStmt]þSELECT CþFROM eql_TESTþWHERE A = '##'þþ-- [updateStmt]þUPDATE eql_TESTþSET C = '#2#'þWHERE A = '#1#'þ```þþ# Custom result mapper exampleþþ```javaþimport org.n3r.eql.map.EqlRowMapper;þþpublic static class MyMapper implements EqlRowMapper {þ    private String name;þþ    @Overrideþ    public Object mapRow(ResultSet rs, int rowNum) throws SQLException {þ        name = rs.getString(1);þ        return null;þ    }þþ    public String getName() {þ        return name;þ    }þ}þþ@Testþpublic void test() {þ    MyMapper myMapper = new MyMapper();þ    new Eql().returnType(myMapper).execute("SELECT 'X' FROM DUAL");þ    assertThat(myMapper.getName(), is("X"));þ}þ```þþ# Custom config supportþþ```javaþEqll.choose(new EqlJdbcConfig("oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriver",þ        "jdbc:oracle:thin:@127.0.0.1:1521:orcl", "orcl", "orcl"));þþTimestamp ts = new Eqll().limit(1).execute("SELECT SYSDATE FROM DUAL");þþ// orþEqll.choose(new EqlPropertiesConfig(þ        EqlConfigKeys.DRIVER + "=oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriver
" +þ        EqlConfigKeys.URL + "=jdbc:oracle:thin:@127.0.0.1:1521:orcl
" +þ        EqlConfigKeys.USER + "=orcl
" +þ        EqlConfigKeys.PASSWORD + "=orcl
"));þ```þþSupported configs are listed below:þþ## **connection.impl**þ+ Meaning: Full qualified class name(FQCN) that implemented `org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlConnection` interface.þ+ Default: When jndiName is set, use `org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlJndiConnection`, otherwise `org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlSimpleConnection`.þ+ Samples: `org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlC3p0Connection` or your custom implementation.þþ## **jndiName**þ+ Meaning: Specified JNDI name to use JNDI data source.þ+ Default: N/A.þ+ Samples: N/A.þþ## **java.naming.factory.initial**þ+ Meaning: Used together with **jndiName**.þ+ Default: None.þ+ Samples: `weblogic.jndi.WLInitialContextFactory`þþ## **java.naming.provider.url**þ+ Meaning: Used together with **jndiName**.þ+ Default: None.þ+ Samples: `t3://127.0.0.1:7001/`þþ## **transactionType**þ+ Meaning: Used together with **jndiName**.þ+ Default: JDBC.þ+ Samples: JTA.þþ## **driver**þ+ Meaning: JDBC driver name.þ+ Default: None.þ+ Samples: `oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriver`， `com.mysql.jdbc.Driver`, and ...þþ## **url**þ+ Meaning: JDBC url.þ+ Default: Noneþ+ Samples: `jdbc:oracle:thin:@127.0.0.1:1521:orcl`, `jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/diamond?useUnicode=true&&characterEncoding=UTF-8&connectTimeout=1000&autoReconnect=true`þþ## **user**þ+ Meaning: JDBC username.þ+ Default: None.þ+ Samples: orcl.þþ## **password**þ+ Meaning: JDBC password.þ+ Default: None.þ+ Samples: orcl.þþ## **expression.evaluator**þ+ Meaning: Full quantified class name which implements `org.n3r.eql.base.ExpressionEvaluator`.þ+ Default: `org.n3r.eql.impl.OgnlEvaluator`.þ+ Samples: customed implementation.þþ## **sql.resource.loader**þ+ Meaning: EQL resource loader. FQCN which implements `org.n3r.eql.base.EqlResourceLoader`.þ+ Default: `org.n3r.eql.impl.FileEqlResourceLoader` which read eql file of the same package and same base name with Eql's used java class.þ+ Samples: `org.n3r.eql.diamond.DiamondEqlResourceLoader` or custom implementation.þþ## **dynamic.language.driver**þ+ Meaning: EQL dynamic support language driver. FQCN which implements `org.n3r.eql.base.DynamicLanguageDriver`.þ+ Default: `org.n3r.eql.impl.DefaultDynamicLanguageDriver` which use SQL special comment to achieve dynamic SQL.þ+ Samples: `org.n3r.eql.impl.FreemarkerDynamicLanguageDriver` or custom implementation.þþ## **sql.parse.lazy**þ+ Meaning: Parse dynamic EQL while execution or not.þ+ Default: false.þ+ Samples: true or yes.þþ# Integrated with [diamond-client](https://github.com/bingoohuang/diamond-miner)þ## Read connection configuration from diamondþ* Add a diamond stone:þþ```þgroup=EqlConfig,dataId=DEFAULT,content=þdriver=oracle.jdbc.driver.OracleDriverþurl=jdbc:oracle:thin:@127.0.0.1:1521:orclþuser=orclþpassword=orclþ```þþ* Use Dql to replace Eql to work with diamond connection configuration.þþ```javaþ// read diamand content of group=EqlConfig, dataId=DEFAULT as connection configþnew Dql().id("xxx").execute();þþ// read diamond content of group=EqlConfig, dataId=DSMALL as connection configþnew Dql("DSMALL").id("yyy").execute();þ```þþ## Read eql from diamondþIn the connection config, set `sql.resource.loader` to `org.n3r.eql.diamond.DiamondEqlResourceLoader`.þþ```javaþpackage org.n3r.eql;þþpublic class DiamondTest {þ    @Testþ    public void test1() throws InterruptedException {þ        // Will read diamond content of group=EQL,dataId=org.n3r.eql.DiamondTest.eqlþ        // The diamond content can have the same structure with normal eql file.þ        String str = new Eql("diamond").selectFirst("diamondDemo").execute();þ        System.out.println(str);þ    }þ}þ```þþ## Caching sql query resultþSql query result caching can be enabled with cache keyword in sql options:þþ```sqlþ-- [test1 cache]þSELECT TO_CHAR(SYSTIMESTAMP, 'HH24:MI:SS.FF6') FROM DUALþ```þþThe default cache model is based on guava cache with 1 day expired after write.þþIf you want to use an alternative cache model, you can use write like following:þ```sqlþ-- global settings cacheModel.impl.myCache=@org.n3r.eql.cache.GuavaCacheProvider("expireAfterWrite=3s,maximumSize=1000")þþ-- [test1 cache cacheModel=myCache]þSELECT TO_CHAR(SYSTIMESTAMP, 'HH24:MI:SS.FF6') FROM DUALþ```þþThe class `org.n3r.eql.cache.GuavaCacheProvider` is provided by eql and its cache builder spec is same to guava [cache spec](http://docs.guava-libraries.googlecode.com/git/javadoc/com/google/common/cache/CacheBuilderSpec.html).þCustom cache provider class should implement `org.n3r.eql.cache.EqlCacheProvider` and optionally to implement `org.n3r.eql.spec.ParamsAppliable` when there are parameters to set.þþþ# simple POJO-based CRUD supportedþþ**@EqlTable**þþTo specify the table name related to the class.þIf class is not annotated by @EqlTable, the default table name will be underscore_lowercase converted from CamelClass name. eg. Person to person, PersonInfo to person_info.þþ**@EqlId**þþTo specify whether the field is a Primary Key in the table.þIf the property name is **id**, it is also regarded as implicit @EqlId.þþ**@EqlColumn**þþTo specify the column name which is different with POJO's property name.þWhen non-annotated with @EqlColumn, the default column name will be underscore_lowercase converted from propertyName. eg. name to name, personName to person_name.þþ**@EqlSkip**þþTo skip the mapping to table field.þþ**CRUD**þþthe update and delete api will use the id field as its condition.þthe read api will use all the non-null fields as its combined condition.þþ```javaþ@EqlTable(name = "personx")þpublic static class Person2 {þ    @EqlIdþ    @EqlColumn(name = "id")þ    private String pid;þ    @EqlColumn(name = "name")þ    private String pname;þ    private Integer age;þþ    @EqlSkipþ    private String remark;þþ    // getters and settersþ}þþ@Testþpublic void testAnnotation() {þ    Person2 person = new Person2();þ    person.setPid("1002");þ    person.setPname("bingoo");þ    person.setAge(30);þþ    // delete from person where id = ?þ    new Pql("mysql").delete(person);þþ    // insert into person（id,name,age) values(?,?,?)þ    new Pql("mysql").create(person);þþ    person.setPname("huang");þ    person.setAge(null);þ    // update person set age = ? where id = ?þ    int effectedRows = new Pql("mysql").update(person);þ    assertThat(effectedRows, is(1));þþ    Person2 queryPerson = new Person2();þ    queryPerson.setPid("1002");þþ    // select id,name,age from person where id = ?þ    List<Person2> resultPerson = new Pql("mysql").read(queryPerson);þ    assertThat(resultPerson.size(), is(1));þþ    effectedRows = new Pql("mysql").delete(queryPerson);þ    assertThat(effectedRows, is(1));þ}þ```þþ# EqlerþIn order to simplify the eql api usage, here eqler is introduced.þEqler is an interface wherein the methods is used to execute sql and process results.þAn Eqler instance is created by EqlerFactory.þThe following are examples:þþ``` javaþpackage org.n3r.eql.eqler.crud;þþimport org.n3r.eql.eqler.annotations.EqlerConfig;þimport org.n3r.eql.eqler.annotations.Sql;þimport org.n3r.eql.eqler.annotations.SqlId;þþimport java.util.List;þimport java.util.Map;þþ@EqlerConfig("mysql")þpublic interface StudentEqler {þ    void prepareData();þþ    int addStudent(int studentId, String name, int age);þþ    @Sql("insert into eql_student values(#studentId#, #name#, #age#)")þ    int addStudent(Student student);þþ    @Sql("insert into eql_student values(#a#, #b#, #c#)")þ    int addStudentAnotherWay(@NamedParam("a") int studentId, @NamedParam("b") String name, @NamedParam("c") int age);þþ    @Sql("select * from eql_student")þ    List<Student> queryAllStudents();þþ    String queryStudentName(int studentId);þþ    @SqlId("queryStudent")þ    Map<String, Object> queryStudentMap(int studentId);þþ    Student queryStudent(int studentId);þ}þ```þþ```sqlþ--  org/n3r/eql/eqler/crud/StudentEqler.eqlþþ-- [prepareData]þdrop table if exists eql_student;þcreate table eql_student(student_id int, name varchar(10), age int);þþ-- [addStudent]þinsert into eql_studentþvalues('##', '##', '##')þþ-- [queryStudentName]þselect name from eql_student where student_id = '##'þþ-- [queryStudent]þselect student_id, name, age from eql_student where student_id = '##'þ```þþ```javaþ@Testþpublic void test() {þ    StudentEqler eqler = EqlerFactory.getEqler(StudentEqler.class);þ    eqler.prepareData();þþ    eqler.addStudent(1, "bingoo", 123);þ    eqler.addStudent(new Student(2, "huang", 124));þ    eqler.addStudentAnotherWay(3, "dingoo", 125);þþ    List<Student> students = eqler.queryAllStudents();þ    assertThat(students.toString(), is(equalTo(þ            "[Student{studentId=1, name='bingoo', age=123}, " +þ                    "Student{studentId=2, name='huang', age=124}, " +þ                    "Student{studentId=3, name='dingoo', age=125}]"þ    )));þþ    Student student1 = eqler.queryStudent(1);þ    assertThat(student1.toString(), is(equalTo("Student{studentId=1, name='bingoo', age=123}")));þþ    Map<String, Object> student2 = eqler.queryStudentMap(2);þ    assertThat(student2.toString(), is(equalTo("{age=124, name=huang, student_id=2}")));þþ    String studentName = eqler.queryStudentName(1);þ    assertThat(studentName, is(equalTo("bingoo")));þ}þ```þþ# TODOþ+ Inline comment such as `/* iff ... */` is parsed by regular expression, and this method will not ignore `/* ... */` in the literal string such as `'literal string /* if xxx */'`.þþ# FAQþ## MySQLNonTransientConnectionExceptionþ```þcom.mysql.jdbc.exceptions.jdbc4.MySQLNonTransientConnectionException: Communications link failure during rollback(). Transaction resolution unknown.þ at sun.reflect.NativeConstructorAccessorImpl.newInstance0(Native Method)þ at sun.reflect.NativeConstructorAccessorImpl.newInstance(NativeConstructorAccessorImpl.java:62)þ at sun.reflect.DelegatingConstructorAccessorImpl.newInstance(DelegatingConstructorAccessorImpl.java:45)þ at java.lang.reflect.Constructor.newInstance(Constructor.java:423)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.Util.handleNewInstance(Util.java:377)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.Util.getInstance(Util.java:360)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.SQLError.createSQLException(SQLError.java:956)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.SQLError.createSQLException(SQLError.java:935)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.SQLError.createSQLException(SQLError.java:924)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.SQLError.createSQLException(SQLError.java:870)þ at com.mysql.jdbc.ConnectionImpl.rollback(ConnectionImpl.java:4606)þ at org.n3r.eql.trans.SimpleDataSource.popConnection(SimpleDataSource.java:638)þ at org.n3r.eql.trans.SimpleDataSource.getConnection(SimpleDataSource.java:207)þ at org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlSimpleConnection.getConnection(EqlSimpleConnection.java:17)þ at org.n3r.eql.trans.EqlJdbcTran.getConn(EqlJdbcTran.java:58)þ at org.n3r.eql.Eql.createConn(Eql.java:105)þ at org.n3r.eql.Eql.execute(Eql.java:157)þ```þþTry use url like  `jdbc:mysql://127.0.0.1:13306/dba?useUnicode=true&&characterEncoding=UTF-8&connectTimeout=3000&socketTimeout=3000&autoReconnect=true` instead of `jdbc:mysql://127.0.0.1:13306/dba`þþ# FAQþ## java.lang.NullPointerExceptionþA single primitive return type like int/long/short will cause NPE when SQL results no rows. þIn this situation, the related wrapper type like Integer/Long/Short should be used instead.þ```javaþ@Testþpublic void returnInteger() {þ    Integer intValue = new Eql("h2").limit(1)þ            .returnType(Integer.class).execute("select 1 where 2 > 3");þ    assertThat(intValue).isNull();þ}þþ@Test(expected = NullPointerException.class)þpublic void returnInt() {þ    int intValue = new Eql("h2").limit(1)þ            .returnType(int.class).execute("select 1 where 2 > 3");þ}þ```þ## IDEA plugin þ[eql-plugin](https://github.com/Bpazy/eql-plugin)þþ# dockerþ## MySQLþþ1. `docker pull mysql:5.6`þ2. `docker run -p 13306:3306 --name mysql -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=my-secret-pw -d mysql:5.6`þ3. `mysql -uroot -pmy-secret-pw  -h127.0.0.1 -P13306` 或者进入容器 `docker exec -it mysql bash`， 执行`mysql -uroot -pmy-secret-pw`þ4. þ ```sqlþ create database dba;þ create database dbb;þ create database dbc;þ ```þþ## ORACLEþ1. `docker pull wnameless/oracle-xe-11g`þ2. `docker run -d -p 49160:22 -p 49161:1521 -e ORACLE_ALLOW_REMOTE=true wnameless/oracle-xe-11g`þ3. download oracle jdbc from [oracle website](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/database/features/jdbc/index-091264.html)þ4. `mvn install:install-file -Dfile=ojdbc6.jar -DgroupId=com.oracle -DartifactId=ojdbc6 -Dversion=11.2.0.4.0 -Dpackaging=jar`þConnect database with following setting:þþ```þhostname: localhostþport: 49161þsid: xeþusername: systemþpassword: oracleþPassword for SYS & SYSTEMþþLogin by SSHþssh root@localhost -p 49160þpassword: adminþSupport custom DB Initializationþ```þþ# OGNL 相关知识þeql默认使用OGNL表达式来做动态条件SQL的判断，OGNL表达式可以参见[ognl language guide](https://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-ognl/language-guide.html).þ## 注意项þ`'a'` 表示单个字符a，要表示字符串a，需要使用双引号`"a"`;þ`'ab'`和`"ab""` 都可以表示字符串ab。þþ## OGNL has the following kinds of constants:þþ1. String literals, as in Java (with the addition of single quotes): delimited by single- or double-quotes, with the full set of character escapes;þ2. Character literals, also as in Java: delimited by single-quotes, also with the full set of escapes;þ3. Numeric literals, with a few more kinds than Java. In addition to Java's ints, longs, floats and doubles, OGNL lets you specify BigDecimals with a "b" or "B" suffix, and BigIntegers with an "h" or "H" suffix (think "huge"---we chose "h" for BigIntegers because it does not interfere with hexadecimal digits);þ4. Boolean (true and false) literals;þ5. The null literal.þþIf you want to compare variable with string in dynamic sql, be careful with single or double quotes.þþ## Testing code:þþ```javaþ@SneakyThrowsþpublic static void main(String[] args) {þ    val map = ImmutableMap.of(þ            "a", "1",þ            "b", "11",þ            "c", 0,þ            "d", "0");þ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("a == '1'", map)); // falseþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("a == 1", map)); // trueþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("a == "1"", map)); // trueþþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("b == '11'", map)); // trueþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("b == 11", map)); // trueþþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("c == "0"", map)); // trueþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("c == '0'", map)); // falseþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("c == 0", map)); // trueþþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("d == "0"", map)); // trueþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("d == '0'", map)); // falseþ    out.println(Ognl.getValue("d == 0", map)); // trueþ}þ```

column17: Android diary for any kind of activities
column43: ![ActivityDiary-logotype](/artwork/logo/logotype-a.png)þþ![](https://api.travis-ci.org/ramack/ActivityDiary.svg)þþþþþþþþþ# FunctionalityþActivityDiary is a diary for any kind of activities - track and organize your tasks in agile way with this android app and get reminded.þþIn the long term many functions shall be implemented, see https://github.com/ramack/ActivityDiary/wiki for the ideas and design decisions.þþCurrently you can select the your current activity, attach notes and pictures and browse your history:þþþ# Getting StartedþActivityDiary is designed to be intuitive, but if you have trouble, check out the [Frequently Asked Questions](/FAQ.md) and try the [User Guide](https://github.com/ramack/ActivityDiary/wiki/How-to-help). In case of further trouble do not hesitate to [create a ticket](https://github.com/ramack/ActivityDiary/issues/new) and we will try to help you and improve the documentation.þþ# DonationsþIn case you want to support the project and its developers you can do that on [Liberapay](https://liberapay.com/ActivityDiary).þþ# License and CopyrightþActivity Dairy is free software: you can redistribute it and/or modify it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation, either version 3 of the License, or (at your option) any later version.þþThis program is distributed in the hope that it will be useful, but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE. See the GNU General Public License for more details.þþYou should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License along with this program. If not, see .þþCopyright notices in this project are mostly given with a reference to the year in form of xxxx-yyyy as a short cut with the meaning, that there is a contribution in every year in the given range.þþ# Authors and ContributionþThis app is currently under development by Raphael Mack [@ramack](https://github.com/ramack) who you can reach via e-mail on activity-diary@rampro.de.þAny form of contribution is warmly welcome and a [small guide how to help is in the wiki](https://github.com/ramack/ActivityDiary/wiki/How-to-help). I am happy to read tickets with suggestions or bug reports or even better pull requests with fixes or new features. For code contributions it would be good to have a ticket describing the changes as a place for discussion before starting to work on it. I so far work directly in the master branch as long as I am alone; For pull requests it might be worth working on a dedicated feature branch. It is good practice to use descriptive commit messages and reference tickets using #xxx, which is even suggested for TODO comments in the code. Small commits are fine and there is no need to squash multiple changes into one commit.þþBy submitting a pull request on github the submitter certifies the following:þ`Developer Certificate of OriginþVersion 1.1þþCopyright (C) 2004, 2006 The Linux Foundation and its contributors.þ1 Letterman DriveþSuite D4700þSan Francisco, CA, 94129þþEveryone is permitted to copy and distribute verbatim copies of thisþlicense document, but changing it is not allowed.þþþDeveloper's Certificate of Origin 1.1þþBy making a contribution to this project, I certify that:þþ(a) The contribution was created in whole or in part by me and Iþ have the right to submit it under the open source licenseþ indicated in the file; orþþ(b) The contribution is based upon previous work that, to the bestþ of my knowledge, is covered under an appropriate open sourceþ license and I have the right under that license to submit thatþ work with modifications, whether created in whole or in partþ by me, under the same open source license (unless I amþ permitted to submit under a different license), as indicatedþ in the file; orþþ(c) The contribution was provided directly to me by some otherþ person who certified (a), (b) or (c) and I have not modifiedþ it.þþ(d) I understand and agree that this project and the contributionþ are public and that a record of the contribution (including allþ personal information I submit with it, including my sign-off) isþ maintained indefinitely and may be redistributed consistent withþ this project or the open source license(s) involved.`þþSo to say submission of a pull request is considered as the act of signing this certificate. This is also why each contributor shall setup his/her development environment such that the full name and a valid email address is part of the commit meta data. Modified files shall contain an updated copyright notice to include all authors.þþ# StatusþActivityDiary is usable for the most basic functions and therefore released for public use. The number of available languages is still very limited and it would be great if you could support translating this app. The number of active testers is very small and therefore testing is limited to some trying during development and a bit automated testing. # DataSpread: A Spreadsheet-Database Hybrid Systemþþ![dataspread-fiverr2-cropped](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1056605/21773459/cec3c198-d654-11e6-8d0e-5c7a867ed77b.png)þþþ[DataSpread][dataspread-github] is a _spreadsheet-database hybrid system_, with a spreadsheet frontend, and a database backend. Thus, DataSpread inherits the flexibility and ease-of-use of spreadsheets, as well as the scalability and power of databases. A paper describing DataSpread's architecture, design decisions, and optimization can be found [here][dataspread-site]. DataSpread is a multi-year project, supported by the National Science Foundation via award number 1633755.þþ### VersionþThe current version is 0.3.þþ### FeaturesþDataSpread is built using [PostgreSQL][postgressite] and [ZKSpreadsheet][zksite], an open-source web-based spreadsheet tool.þþDataSpread's version 0.1 enables users to scale to **billions of cells and return results for common spreadsheet operations within seconds**. It does so via on-demand loading of spreadsheet data.þþþLike traditional spreadsheet software, DataSpread supports standard spreadsheet book and sheet operations like Load, Rename, Delete, and Import (via XLS and XLSX, and CSV). Any updates to the spreadsheets are automatically saved.þþLike traditional spreadsheet software, DataSpread supports the use of 225+ spreadsheet functions, along with formatting and styling operations. It also supports row and column operations like insert, delete, cut, copy, and paste; during insertion and deletion, formulae are updated as is the case in traditional spreadsheet software. þþIt supports all these operations while scaling to *arbitrarily large* spreadsheets.þþIn future releases, DataSpread will support SQL on the spreadsheet frontend, along with other relational algebra-based interactions. It will also support joint formula evaluation and optimization. þþ### Key Design Innovationsþþ* DataSpread employs a _flexible hybrid data model_ to represent spreadsheet data within a database. þ* DataSpread uses _positional indexing techniques_ to both locate data by position, and keep it up-to-date as the data is updated. þ* DataSpread also employs a _LRU caching mechanism_ to retrieve and keep in memory data from the database on demand. þ* DataSpread also employs _speculative fetching_ to fetch additional data beyond the user's current spreadsheet window. þþþþ## Setup Instructions:þþYou can directly use DataSpread via our cloud-hosted [site][siteinfo].þþTo host DataSpread locally you can either use one of the pre-build war files, available [here][warlink], or build the war file yourself from the source.þþ### Required Softwareþþ* [Java Platform (JDK)][java] >= 8þ* [PostgreSQL][posrgres] >= 10.5þ* [PostgreSQL JDBC driver][jdbc] = 42.1.4þ* [Apache Tomcat][tomcat] >= 8.5.4þ* [Apache Maven][maven] >= 3.5.0þ* [NodeJS][node] >= 10.9þþþ### Building Instructions (To generate a war file)þþ1. Clone the DataSpread repository. Alternatively, you can download the source as a zip or tar.gz. þþ2. Use maven to build the `war` file using the following command.  After the build completes the war is available at `webapp/target/DataSpread.war`. þþ ```þ mvn clean installþ ```þþ### Deploying DataSpread locally. þþ1. Install PostgreSQL database. [Postgres.app][Postgres.app] is a quick way to get PostgreSQL working on Mac. For other operating systems check out the guides [here][postgre_install].  þþ2. Create a database and an user who has access to the database.  Note the database name, username and password. Typically when you have PostgreSQL installed locally the password is blank.  þþ3. Install Apache Tomcat. You can use the guide [here][tomcat_install]. Make a note of the directory where tomcat is installed. This is known as `TOMCAT_HOME` in all documentation. þþ4. Update the Tomcat configuration. You need to update the following file, which is present in `conf` folder under `TOMCAT_HOME` folder.  þþ    1. `context.xml` by adding the following text at the end of the file before the closing XML tag.   þþ ```þ <Resource name="jdbc/ibd" auth="Container"þ           type="javax.sql.DataSource" driverClassName="org.postgresql.Driver"þ           url="jdbc:postgresql://127.0.0.1:5432/<database_name>"þ           username="<username>" password="<password>"þ                  maxTotal="20" maxIdle="10" maxWaitMillis="-1" defaultAutoCommit="false" accessToUnderlyingConnectionAllowed="true"/>þ ```þþ Replace `<database_name>`, `<username>` and `<password>` with your PostgreSQL's database name, user name and password respectively.þþ5. Copy `postgresql-42.1.4.jar` (Download from [here][jdbc]) to `lib` folder under `TOMCAT_HOME`.  It is crucial to have the exact version of this file. þ þ6. Deploy the war file within Tomcat. This can be done via Tomcat's web interface or by manually copying the war file in the `webapps` folder under `TOMCAT_HOME`.þþ7. Now you are ready to run the program. Visit the url where Tomcat is installed. It will be typically [http://localhost:8080/][install_loc] for a local install.þþþLicenseþ----þMITþþ[install_loc]: http://localhost:8080/þ[tomcat_install]: https://www.ntu.edu.sg/home/ehchua/programming/howto/Tomcat_HowTo.htmlþ[postgre_install]: https://wiki.postgresql.org/wiki/Detailed_installation_guidesþ[Postgres.app]: http://postgresapp.comþ[jdbc]: http://central.maven.org/maven2/org/postgresql/postgresql/42.1.4/postgresql-42.1.4.jarþ[ant]: https://ant.apache.org/bindownload.cgiþ[tomcat]: http://tomcat.apache.org/download-80.cgiþ[java]: http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index-jsp-138363.htmlþ[posrgres]:https://www.postgresql.org/download/þ[siteinfo]: http://kite.cs.illinois.edu:8080þ[zksite]: https://www.zkoss.org/product/zkspreadsheetþ[postgressite]: https://www.postgresql.org/þ[warlink]: https://github.com/dataspread/releases/releasesþ[dataspread-github]: http://dataspread.github.ioþ[dataspread-site]: http://data-people.cs.illinois.edu/dataspread.pdfþ[maven]: https://maven.apache.org/install.htmlþ[node]: https://nodejs.org/en/download/current/

column17: Mirror of Apache Geronimo specs
column43: Structureþ========þþOnly specs under active development should be in trunk.  Once you release, delete the trunk.  If you need to make a change or bugfix, copy the latest tag into trunk and work with that.þþBe certain that all dependencies are marked "provided"þþDo not copy any code into branches under any circumstances.þþBuildingþ========þþThe is normally no root pom, so you need to build specs individually.þþTo build you will need:þþ * J2SE SDK 1.5+ (http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5)þ * Maven 2.0.9+ (http://maven.apache.org)þþTo build all changes incrementally:þþ    mvn installþþTo perform clean builds, which are sometimes needed after some changes to the þsource tree:þþ    mvn clean installþþþReleasingþ=========þþUse the maven-release-plugin.  þþStage to your people.apache.org account or to your local machine and scp to people.apache.org.þþAfter a release vote has passed use the maven-stage-plugin to transfer the voted artifacts to the apache release repo.
