column17: JUnit Foundation is a lightweight collection of JUnit watchers, interfaces, and static utility classes that supplement and augment the functionality provided by the JUnit API.
column43: [![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.nordstrom.tools/junit-foundation.svg)](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.nordstrom.tools/junit-foundation)þþ# INTRODUCTIONþþ**JUnit Foundation** is a lightweight collection of JUnit watchers, interfaces, and static utility classes that supplement and augment the functionality provided by the JUnit API. The facilities provided by **JUnit Foundation** include method invocation hooks, test method timeout management, automatic retry of failed tests, shutdown hook installation, and test artifact capture.þþ## Test Lifecycle NotificationsþþThe standard **RunListener** feature of JUnit provides a basic facility for implementing setup, cleanup, and monitoring procedures. However, the granularity of notifications offered by this feature is relatively coarse, firing before the first **`@Before`** method and after the last **`@After`** method - a unit of functionality known as an `atomic test`. Notifications are available for the start, finish, and failure of atomic tests, but not for the `particle methods` of which they're composed - individual **`@Test`** and configuration methods (**`@Before`**, **`@After`**, **`@BeforeClass`**, and **`@AfterClass`**).þþWith **JUnit Foundation**, you can get notifications for the invocation of every configuration and test method. This method interception feature is analogous to the **IInvokedMethodListener** feature of TestNG. You can also get notifications for the creation of test class instances, the creation and invocation of JUnit runners (both test classes and suites), and the completion of test runs. **JUnit Foundation** also provides notifications for the start, finish, and failure of `atomic tests`, with all of the details and context that are omitted by the standard JUnit **RunListener**.þþ### Notification Context and Test Run HierarchyþþThe notifications provided by **JUnit Foundation** include the context that owns them - the JUnit runner. With this context and associated mapping methods, you're able to explore the entire hierarchy of the test run. For example, you can get the class runner that owns an invoked method or the suite runner that owns a class runner:þþ#### Walking the Object HierarchyþþThe objects passed to your service provider implementation are members of a hierarchy that **JUnit** builds to represent the test collection being executed. **JUnit Foundation** provides a set of static methods that enable you walk this object hierarchy.þþ* `LifecycleHooks.getParentOf(Object child)`  þGet the parent runner that owns specified child runner or framework method.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getRunnerForTarget(Object target)`  þGet the parent runner that owns the specified instance.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getTargetForRunner(Object runner)`  þGet the JUnit test class instance owned by the specified parent runner.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getTestClassOf(Object runner)`  þGet the test class object associated with the specified parent runner.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getAtomicTestOf(Object runner)`  þGet the atomic test object for the specified class runner.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getCallableOf(Object runner, Object child)`  þGet the _callable_ closure associated with the specified parent runner and child runner or framework method.þþ###### Exploring the Test Run Hierarchyþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.LifecycleHooks;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.MethodWatcher;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.RunReflectiveCall;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.TestClassWatcher;þimport org.junit.runners.model.FrameworkMethod;þimport org.junit.runners.model.TestClass;þþpublic class ExploringWatcher implements TestClassWatcher, MethodWatcher<FrameworkMethod> {þþ    // ...þþ    @Overrideþ    public void testClassStarted(TestClass testClass, Object runner) {þ        // if this is a Suite runnerþ        if (runner instanceof org.junit.runners.Suite) {þ            // get the parent of this runnerþ            Object parent = LifecycleHooks.getParentOf(runner);þ            // ...þ        }þ        // ...þ    }þþ    @Overrideþ    public void beforeInvocation(Object runner, FrameworkMethod method, ReflectiveCallable callable) {þ        Object target = LifecycleHooks.getFieldValue(callable, "val$target");þ        // if target definedþ        if (target != null) {þ            // get the test class of the runnerþ            TestClass testClass = LifecycleHooks.getTestClassOf(runner);þ            // ...þ        }þ        // ...þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public void afterInvocation(Object runner, FrameworkMethod method, ReflectiveCallable callable, Throwable thrown) {þ        // if child is a 'before' configuration methodþ        if (null != method.getAnnotation(Before.class)) {þ            // get the atomic test of the runnerþ            AtomicTest<FrameworkMethod> atomicTest = LifecycleHooks.getAtomicTestOf(runner);þ            // get the "identity" methodþ            FrameworkMethod identity = atomicTest.getIdentity();þ            // ...þ        }þ        // ...þ    }þþ    // ...þþ}þ```þþ#### Nonexistent Object AssociationsþþNote that some associations are not available for specific context:þþ* `TestClass` objects for `Suite` runners have no associated atomic tests.þ* `FrameworkMethod` objects for static configuration methods (**`@BeforeClass`**/**`@AfterClass`**) have no associated atomic tests.þ* `FrameworkMethod` objects for ignored test methods (**`@Ignore`**) have no associated target test class instances.þþ#### Useful Utility Methodsþþ**JUnit Foundation** provides several static utility methods that can be useful in your service provider implementation.þþ* `LifecycleHooks.isParticleMethod(Object child)`  þDetermines if the specified child is a test or configuration method.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getAnnotation(Object object, Class<T> annotationType)`  þReturns the annotation of the specified type if the object is tagged with such an annotation.þ* `LifecycleHooks.describeChild(Object target, Object child)`  þGet a `Description` for the indicated child object from the runner for the specified test class instance.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getInstanceClass(Object instance)`  þGet class of specified test class instance.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getFieldValue(Object target, String name)`  þGet the value of the specified field from the supplied object.þ* `LifecycleHooks.encloseCallable(Method method, Object target, Object... params)`  þSynthesize a _callable_ closure with the specified parameters.þþ### How to Enable NotificationsþþThe hooks that enable **JUnit Foundation** test lifecycle notifications are installed dynamically with bytecode enhancement performed by [Byte Buddy](http://bytebuddy.net). To maintain compatibility with solution-specific runners like [SpringRunner](https://spring.io/guides/tutorials/bookmarks/#_testing_a_rest_service), **JUnit Foundation** intercepts calls to several core JUnit classes directly via its Java agent implementation:þþ#### Maven Configuration for JUnit Foundationþ```xmlþ<!-- pom.xml -->þ<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"þ  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/maven-v4_0_0.xsd">þþ  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>þ  <artifactId>example-maven-pom</artifactId>þ  þ  <!-- ... -->þ  þ  <properties>þ    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>þ    <maven.compiler.target>1.7</maven.compiler.target>þ    <maven.compiler.source>1.7</maven.compiler.source>   þ  </properties>þ  þ  <dependencies>þ    <dependency>þ      <groupId>com.nordstrom.tools</groupId>þ      <artifactId>junit-foundation</artifactId>þ      <version>12.2.0</version>þ      <scope>test</scope>þ    </dependency>þ  </dependencies>þ  þ  <build>þ    <pluginManagement>þ      <plugins>þ        <!-- Add this if you plan to import into Eclipse -->þ        <plugin>þ          <groupId>org.eclipse.m2e</groupId>þ          <artifactId>lifecycle-mapping</artifactId>þ          <version>1.0.0</version>þ          <configuration>þ            <lifecycleMappingMetadata>þ              <pluginExecutions>þ                <pluginExecution>þ                  <pluginExecutionFilter>þ                    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>þ                    <artifactId>maven-dependency-plugin</artifactId>þ                    <versionRange>[1.0.0,)</versionRange>þ                    <goals>þ                      <goal>properties</goal>þ                    </goals>þ                  </pluginExecutionFilter>þ                  <action>þ                    <execute />þ                  </action>þ                </pluginExecution>þ              </pluginExecutions>þ            </lifecycleMappingMetadata>þ          </configuration>þ        </plugin>þ      </plugins>þ    </pluginManagement>þ    <plugins>þ      <!-- This provides the path to the Java agent -->þ      <plugin>þ        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>þ        <artifactId>maven-dependency-plugin</artifactId>þ        <version>3.1.1</version>þ        <executions>þ          <execution>þ            <id>getClasspathFilenames</id>þ            <goals>þ              <goal>properties</goal>þ            </goals>þ          </execution>þ        </executions>þ      </plugin>þ      <plugin>þ        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>þ        <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>þ        <version>2.22.0</version>þ        <configuration>þ          <argLine>-javaagent:${com.nordstrom.tools:junit-foundation:jar}</argLine>þ        </configuration>þ      </plugin>þ    </plugins>þ  </build>þ</project>þ```þþ#### Gradle Configuration for JUnit Foundationþ```groovyþ// build.gradleþþ// ...þþapply plugin: 'maven'þsourceCompatibility = 1.7þtargetCompatibility = 1.7þrepositories {þ    mavenLocal()þ    mavenCentral()þ    // ...þ}þdependencies {þ    // ...þ    compile 'com.nordstrom.tools:junit-foundation:12.2.0'þ}þext {þ    junitFoundation = configurations.compile.resolvedConfiguration.resolvedArtifacts.find { it.name == 'junit-foundation' }þ}þtest.doFirst {þ    jvmArgs "-javaagent:${junitFoundation.file}"þ}þtest {þ//  debug trueþ    // not required, but definitely usefulþ    testLogging.showStandardStreams = trueþ}þ```þþ#### IDE Configuration for JUnit FoundationþþTo enable notifications in the native test runner of IDEs like Eclipse or IDEA, add the `-javaagent` option to the JVM options of your run/debug configuration.þþ#### ServiceLoader Configuration FilesþþTo provide reliable, consistent behavior regardless of execution environment, **JUnit Foundation** notification subscribers are registered through the standard Java **ServiceLoader** mechanism. To attach **JUnit Foundation** watchers and standard JUnit run listeners to your tests, declare them in **ServiceLoader** [provider configuration files](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/ext/basics/spi.html#register-service-providers) in a **_META-INF/services/_** folder of your project resources:þþ###### com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitWatcherþ```shellþ# implements com.nordstrom.automation.junit.MethodWatcherþcom.mycompany.example.MyMethodWatcherþ# implements com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ShutdownListenerþcom.mycompany.example.MyShutdownListenerþ# extends org.junit.runner.notification.RunListenerþ# implements com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitWatcherþcom.mycompany.example.MarkedRunListenerþ```þþ###### org.junit.runner.notification.RunListenerþ```shellþ# extends org.junit.runner.notification.RunListenerþcom.mycompany.example.MyRunListenerþ```þþThe preceding **ServiceLoader** provider configuration files declare a **JUnit Foundation** [MethodWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/MethodWatcher.java), a **JUnit Foundation** [ShutdownListener](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ShutdownListener.java), and two standard **JUnit** [RunListener](https://github.com/junit-team/junit4/blob/41d44734f41aba0cf6ba5a11ff5d32ffed155027/src/main/java/org/junit/runner/notification/RunListener.java) providers.þþNote that every **JUnit Foundation** service provider interface extends a common marker interface - [JUnitWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/JUnitWatcher.java). All watcher/listener service providers can be declared in a single common configuration file, eliminating the need to declare classes implementing multiple interfaces in several different configuration files.þþAs indicated by the comments, the **`MarkedRunListener`** service provider extends the standard **`RunListener`** class and implements the **`JUnitWatcher`** marker interface. The marker allows this service provider to be declared in the common configuration file. This approach is employed by the **`RunAnnouncer`** run listener that **JUnit Foundation** uses to provide enhanced run event notifications.þþ### Defined Service Provider Interfacesþþ**JUnit Foundation** defines several service provider interfaces that notification subscribers can implement:þþ* [JUnitWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/JUnitWatcher.java)  þ**JUnitWatcher** is a marker interface for JUnit test execution event watchers. It can also be used to mark extensions to the standard **RunListener** class.þ* [ShutdownListener](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ShutdownListener.java)  þ**ShutdownListener** provides callbacks for events in the lifecycle of the JVM that runs the Java code that comprises your tests. It receives the following notification:þ  * The JVM that's running the tests is about to close. This signals the completion of the test run.þ* [RunnerWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/RunnerWatcher.java)  þ**RunnerWatcher** provides callbacks for events in the lifecycle of **`ParentRunner`** objects. It receives the following notifications:þ  * A **`ParentRunner`** object is about to run.þ  * A **`ParentRunner`** object has finished running.þ* [TestObjectWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/TestObjectWatcher.java)  þ**TestObjectWatcher** provides callbacks for events in the lifecycle of Java test class instances. It receives the following notification:þ  * An instance of a JUnit test class has been created for the execution of a single `atomic test`.þ* [RunWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/RunWatcher.java)  þ**RunWatcher** provides callbacks for events in the lifecycle of `atomic tests`. This is a functional replacement for the standard JUnit **RunListener**, with the execution context that the standard interface lacks. It receives the following notifications:þ  * An `atomic test` is about to start.þ  * An `atomic test` has finished, pass or fail.þ  * An `atomic test` has failed.þ  * An `atomic test` flags that it assumes a condition that is false.þ  * An `atomic test` has been ignored.þ* [MethodWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/MethodWatcher.java)  þ**MethodWatcher** provides callbacks for events in the lifecycle of a `particle method`, which is a component of an `atomic test`. It receives the following notifications:þ  * A `particle method` is about to be invoked.þ  * A `particle method` has just finished.þþ###### Service Provider Example - Implementing MethodWatcherþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport org.junit.After;þimport org.junit.AfterClass;þimport org.junit.Before;þimport org.junit.BeforeClass;þimport org.junit.Test;þimport org.junit.runners.model.FrameworkMethod;þimport org.slf4j.Logger;þimport org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;þþpublic class LoggingWatcher implements MethodWatcher<FrameworkMethod> {þþ    private static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(LoggingWatcher.class);þþ    @Overrideþ    public void beforeInvocation(Object runner, FrameworkMethod method, ReflectiveCallable callable) {þ        if (null != method.getAnnotation(Test.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info(">>>>> ENTER 'test' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(Before.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info(">>>>> ENTER 'before' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(After.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info(">>>>> ENTER 'after' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(BeforeClass.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info(">>>>> ENTER 'before-class' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(AfterClass.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info(">>>>> ENTER 'after-class' method {}", method.getName());þ        }þ    }þþ    @Overrideþ    public void afterInvocation(Object runner, FrameworkMethod method, ReflectiveCallable callable, Throwable thrown) {þ        if (null != method.getAnnotation(Test.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info("<<<<< LEAVE 'test' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(Before.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info("<<<<< LEAVE 'before' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(After.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info("<<<<< LEAVE 'after' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(BeforeClass.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info("<<<<< LEAVE 'before-class' method {}", method.getName());þ        } else if (null != method.getAnnotation(AfterClass.class)) {þ            LOGGER.info("<<<<< LEAVE 'after-class' method {}", method.getName());þ        }þ    }þ}þ```þþNote that the implementation in this method watcher uses the annotations attached to the method objects to determine the type of method they're intercepting. Because each test method can have multiple configuration methods (both before and after), you may need to define additional conditions to control when your implementation runs. Examples of additional conditions include method name, method annotation, or an execution flag.þþ### Support for Standard JUnit RunListener ProvidersþþAs indicated previously, **JUnit Foundation** will automatically attach standard JUnit **`RunListener`** providers that are declared in the associated **`ServiceLoader`** provider configuration file (i.e. - **_org.junit.runner.notification.RunListener_**). Run listeners that implement the **`JUnitWatcher`** marker interface can be declared in the common configuration file (i.e. - **_com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitWatcher_**). Declared run listeners are attached to the **`RunNotifier`** supplied to the `run()` method of JUnit runners. This feature eliminates behavioral differences between the various test execution environments like Maven, Gradle, and native IDE test runners.þþ**JUnit Foundation** uses this feature internally; notifications sent to **`RunWatcher`** service providers are published by an auto-attached **`RunListener`**. This notification-enhancing run listener, named [RunAnnouncer](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/RunAnnouncer.java), is registered via the aforementioned [**ServiceLoader** provider configuration file](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/resources/META-INF/services/com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitWatcher).þþ### Getting Attached Watchers and Listenersþþ**JUnit Foundation** attaches service providers that handle published event notifications via the standard **ServiceLoader** facility. You can acquire references to these service providers through the following methods:þþ* `LifecycleHooks.getAttachedWatcher(Class<T> watcherType)`  þGet reference to an instance of the specified watcher type.þ* `LifecycleHooks.getAttachedListener(Class<T> listenerType)`  þGet reference to an instance of the specified listener type.þþ### Support for Parallel ExecutionþþThe ability to run **JUnit** tests in parallel is provided by the JUnit 4 test runner of the [Maven Surefire plugin](https://maven.apache.org/surefire/maven-surefire-plugin/examples/fork-options-and-parallel-execution.html). This feature utilizes private **JUnit** interfaces and undocuments behaviors, which greatly complicated the task of adding event notification hooks. As of version [9.0.3](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/releases/tag/junit-foundation-9.0.3), **JUnit Foundation** supports parallel execution of both classes and methods.þþ### Support for Parameterized Testsþþ**JUnit** provides a custom [Parameterized](https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/runners/Parameterized.html) runner for executing parameterized tests. Third-party solutions are also available, such as [JUnitParams](https://github.com/Pragmatists/JUnitParams) and [ParameterizedSuite](https://github.com/PeterWippermann/parameterized-suite). Each of these solutions has its own implementation strategy, and no common interface is provided to access the parameters supplied to each invocation of the test methods in the parameterized class.þþFor lifecycle notification subscribers that need access to test invocation parameters, **JUnit Foundation** defines the [ArtifactParams](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactParams.java) interface. This interface, along with the [AtomIdentity](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/AtomIdentity.java) test rule, enables test classes to publish their invocation parameters.þþThe following example demonstrates how to publish invocation parameters with the [Parameterized](https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/runners/Parameterized.html) runner. The implementation is relatively simple, due to the strategy used by the runner to inject parameters into the test methods.þþThe `Parameterized` runner relies on instance fields to inject parameter values, and requires the test implementer to provide a constructor that initializes these fields. Alternatively, the implementer can mark the instance fields with the `@Parameter` annotation.þþ###### Publishing Invocation Parameters - `Parameterized` Runnerþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;þimport static org.junit.Assert.assertTrue;þþimport java.util.Map;þimport org.junit.Rule;þimport org.junit.Test;þimport org.junit.runner.Description;þimport org.junit.runner.RunWith;þimport org.junit.runners.Parameterized;þimport org.junit.runners.Parameterized.Parameters;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactParams;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.AtomIdentity;þimport com.google.common.base.Optional;þþ@RunWith(Parameterized.class)þpublic class ExampleTest implements ArtifactParams {þ    þ    @Ruleþ    public final AtomIdentity identity = new AtomIdentity(this);þ    þ    private String input;þ    þ    public ExampleTest(String input) {þ        this.input = input;þ    }þ    þ    @Parametersþ    public static Object[] data() {þ        return new Object[] { "first test", "second test" };þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public AtomIdentity getAtomIdentity() {þ        return identity;þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Description getDescription() {þ        return identity.getDescription();þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Optional<Map<String, Object>> getParameters() {þ        return Param.mapOf(Param.param("input", input));þ    }þ    þ    @Testþ    public void parameterized() {þ        System.out.println("invoking: " + getDescription().getMethodName());þ     Optional<Map<String, Object>> params = identity.getParameters();þ     assertTrue(params.isPresent());þ     assertTrue(params.get().containsKey("input"));þ        assertEquals(input, params.get().get("input"));þ    }þ}þ```þþThe following example demonstrates how to publish invocation parameters with the [JUnitParams](https://github.com/Pragmatists/JUnitParams) runner. The implementation is more complex than the `Parameterized` example above, due to the strategy used by the runner to inject parameters into the test methods.þþThe `JUnitParams` runner injects parameters via test method arguments, with values provided by a `val$params` field in the "callable" closures associated with each test method invocation. Unlike the `Parameterized` runner, where all test methods in the class run with the same set of values, the `JUnitParams` runner allows each test method in the class to run with its own unique set of values. This variability must be accounted for in the implementation of the `getParameters()` method.þþThe example below queries the method for its parameter types, then uses these to cast each injected value to its corresponding type. This implementation assigns generic ordinal names to the parameters, because Java 7 reflection doesn't expose the names of method arguments. These could be acquired via the Java 8 API, or explicit mappings between test method signatures and argument names could be provided.þþ###### Publishing Invocation Parameters - `JUnitParams` Runnerþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;þþimport java.util.Map;þimport org.junit.Test;þimport org.junit.runner.RunWith;þimport org.junit.internal.runners.model.ReflectiveCallable;þimport org.junit.runners.model.FrameworkMethod;þimport junitparams.JUnitParamsRunner;þimport junitparams.Parameters;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactParams;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.AtomIdentity;þimport com.google.common.base.Optional;þþ@RunWith(JUnitParamsRunner.class)þpublic class ArtifactCollectorJUnitParams implements ArtifactParams {þ    þ    @Ruleþ    public final AtomIdentity identity = new AtomIdentity(this);þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public AtomIdentity getAtomIdentity() {þ        return identity;þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Description getDescription() {þ        return identity.getDescription();þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Optional<Map<String, Object>> getParameters() {þ        // get runner for this targetþ        Object runner = LifecycleHooks.getRunnerForTarget(this);þ        // get atomic test of target runnerþ        AtomicTest<FrameworkMethod> test = LifecycleHooks.getAtomicTestOf(runner);þ        // get "callable" closure of test methodþ        ReflectiveCallable callable = LifecycleHooks.getCallableOf(runner, test.getIdentity());þ        // get test method parametersþ        Class<?>[] paramTypes = test.getIdentity().getMethod().getParameterTypes();þþ        try {þ            // extract execution parameters from "callable" closureþ            Object[] params = LifecycleHooks.getFieldValue(callable, "val$params");þþ            // NOTE: The "callable" closure also includes:þ            // * this$0 - test case FrameworkMethod objectþ            // * val$target - test class instance ('this')þ            // Only 'val$params' is unavailable elsewhere.þþ            // allocate named parameters arrayþ            Param[] namedParams = new Param[params.length];þ            // populate named parameters arrayþ            for (int i = 0; i < params.length; i++) {þ                // create array item with generic nameþ                namedParams[i] = Param.param("param" + i, paramTypes[i].cast(params[i]));þ            }þþ            // return params map as Optionalþ            return Param.mapOf(namedParams);þ        } catch (IllegalAccessException | NoSuchFieldException e) {þ            return Optional.absent();þ        }þ    }þ    þ    @Testþ    @Parameters({ "first test", "second test" })þ    public void parameterized(String input) {þ        System.out.println("parameterized: input = [" + input + "]");þ        assertEquals("first test", input);þ    }þ}þ```þþ#### Artifact capture for parameterized testsþþFor scenarios that require artifact capture of parameterized tests, the [ArtifactCollector](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactCollector.java) class extends the [AtomIdentity](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/AtomIdentity.java) test rule. This enables artifact type implementations to access invocation parameters and **Description** object for the current `atomic test`. For more details, see the [Artifact Capture](#artifact-capture) section below.þþ## Test Method Timeout Managementþþ**JUnit** provides two mechanisms for limiting the duration tests:þþ* The [timeout](https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/Test.html#timeout()) parameter of the **`@Test`** annotation  þWith the `timeout` parameter, you can set an explicit timeout interval in milliseconds on an individual test method. If a test fails to complete within the specified interval, **JUnit** terminates the test and throws **TestTimedOutException**.þ* The [Timeout](https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/rules/Timeout.html) test rule  þWith the **`Timeout`** test rule, you can apply the same timeout interval to all of the methods in a test class.þþ**JUnit Foundation** consolidates and extends the functionality of these mechanisms:þþ* A global per-test timeout interval can be activated by setting the `TEST_TIMEOUT` configuration option to the desired default test timeout interval in milliseconds. This timeout specification is applied via the `timeout` parameter of the **`@Test`** annotation to every test method that doesn't explicitly specify a `timeout` parameter with a longer interval.þ* A global per-class timeout interval can be activated by setting the `TIMEOUT_RULE` configuration option to the desired default test timeout interval in milliseconds. This timeout specification is applied via the `Timeout` test rule to every test class that doesn't declare a `Timeout` test rule with a longer interval.þ* Timeout enforcement can be disabled locally by declaring a `Timeout` test rule that specifies an interval of zero (0).þ* Timeout enforcement can be disabled globally by setting the `TIMEOUT_RULE` configuration option, specifying an interval of zero (0).þ* Unless enforcement is disabled, per-test timeout intervals override shorter intervals specified by rule-based mechanisms.þþ## Automatic retry of failed testsþþSome types of tests are inherently non-deterministic, which can cause them to fail sporadically in the absence of an actual defect. Most of the time, these tests will pass if you run them again. For these sorts of "noise" failures, **JUnit Foundation** provides an automatic retry feature.þþAutomatic retry is applied by the **JUnit Foundation** Java agent, activated by setting the `MAX_RETRY` configuration option to the maximum retry attempts that will be made if a test method fails. The automatic retry feature can be disabled on a per-method or per-class basis via the **`@NoRetry`** annotation.þþ**_META-INF/services/com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitRetryAnalyzer_** is the service loader retry analyzer configuration file. By default, this file is absent. To add managed analyzers, create this file and add the fully-qualified names of their classes, one line per item.þþFailed attempts of tests that are selected for retry are tallied as ignored tests. These tests are differentiated from actual ignored tests by the presence of a **`@RetriedTest`** annotation in place of the original **`@Test`** annotation. See `RunListenerAdapter.testIgnored(Description)` for more details.þþ## Shutdown hook installationþþ**JUnit** provides a run listener feature, but this operates most readily on a per-class basis. The method for attaching these run listeners also imposes structural and operational constraints on **JUnit** projects, and the configuration required to register for end-of-suite notifications necessitates hard-coding the composition of the suite. All of these factors make run listeners unattractive or ineffectual for final cleanup operations.þþ**JUnit Foundation** enables you to declare shutdown listeners in a service loader configuration file.  þAs shown previously under [ServiceLoader Configuration Files](#serviceloader-configuration-files), **_META-INF/services/com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitWatcher_** is the configuration file where shutdown listeners are declared. By default, this file is absent. To add managed listeners, create this file and add the fully-qualified names of their classes, one line per item. When it loads, the **JUnit Foundation** Java agent uses the service loader to instantiate your shutdown listeners and attaches them to the active JVM.þþ## Artifact Captureþþ* [ArtifactCollector](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactCollector.java):  þ**ArtifactCollector** is a JUnit [test watcher](http://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/latest/org/junit/rules/TestWatcher.html) that serves as the foundation for artifact-capturing test watchers. This is a generic class, with the artifact-specific implementation provided by instances of the **ArtifactType** interface. For artifact capture scenarios where you need access to the current method description or the values provided to parameterized tests, the test class can implement the **ArtifactParams** interface.þ* [ArtifactParams](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactParams.java):  þBy implementing the **ArtifactParams** interface in your test classes, you enable the artifact capture framework to access test method description objects and parameterized test values. These can be used for composing, naming, and storing artifacts. þ* [ArtifactType](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactType.java):  þClasses that implement the **ArtifactType** interface provide the artifact-specific methods used by the **ArtifactCollector** watcher to capture and store test-related artifacts. The unit tests for this project include a reference implementation (**UnitTestArtifact**) that provides a basic outline for a scenario-specific artifact provider. This artifact provider is specified as the superclass type parameter in the **UnitTestCapture** watcher, which is a lightweight extension of **ArtifactCollector**. The most basic example is shown below:þþ###### Implementing ArtifactTypeþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport java.nio.file.Path;þimport java.nio.file.Paths;þþimport org.slf4j.Logger;þimport org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;þþimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactType;þþpublic class MyArtifactType extends ArtifactType {þ    þ    private static final String ARTIFACT_PATH = "artifacts";þ    private static final String EXTENSION = "txt";þ    private static final String ARTIFACT = "This text artifact was captured for '%s'";þ    private static final Logger LOGGER = LoggerFactory.getLogger(MyArtifactType.class);þþ    @Overrideþ    public boolean canGetArtifact(Object instance) {þ        return true;þ    }þþ    @Overrideþ    public byte[] getArtifact(Object instance, Throwable reason) {þ        if (instance instanceof ArtifactParams) {þ            ArtifactParams publisher = (ArtifactParams) instance;þ            return String.format(ARTIFACT, publisher.getDescription().getMethodName()).getBytes().clone();þ        } else {þ            return new byte[0];þ        }þ    }þþ    @Overrideþ    public Path getArtifactPath() {þ        return super.getArtifactPath(instance).resolve(ARTIFACT_PATH);þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public String getArtifactExtension() {þ        return EXTENSION;þ    }þþ    @Overrideþ    public Logger getLogger() {þ        return LOGGER;þ    }þ}þ```þþPay special attention to the implementation of `getArtifact(Object, Throwable)` above. This code will only capture artifacts for test classes that implement the **ArtifactParams** interface, and it uses this interface to get the description object for the current test.þþ###### Creating a type-specific artifact collectorþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactCollector;þþpublic class MyArtifactCapture extends ArtifactCollector<MyArtifactType> {þ    þ    public MyArtifactCapture(Object instance) {þ        super(instance, new MyArtifactType());þ    }þ}þ```þþThe preceding code is an example of how the artifact type definition can be assigned as the type parameter in a subclass of **ArtifactCollector**. This isn't strictly necessary, but will make your code more concise, as the next example demonstrates. This technique also provides the opportunity to extend or alter the basic artifact capture behavior.þþ###### Attaching artifact collectors to test classesþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactCollector;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactParams;þþimport org.junit.Rule;þimport org.junit.runner.Description;þþpublic class ExampleTest implements ArtifactParams {þþ    @Rule   // Option #1: Attach a pre-composed artifact capture subclassþ    public final MyArtifactCapture watcher1 = new MyArtifactCapture(this);þ    þ    @Rule   // Option #2: Compose type-specific artifact collector in-lineþ    public final ArtifactCollector<MyArtifactType> watcher2 = new ArtifactCollector<>(this, new MyArtifactType());þ    þ    // ...þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public AtomIdentity getAtomIdentity() {þ        return watcher1;þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Description getDescription() {þ        return watcher1.getDescription();þ    }þ}þ```þþThis example demonstrates two techniques for attaching artifact collectors to test classes. Either technique will activate basic artifact capture functionality. Of course, the first option is required to activate extended behavior implemented in a type-specific subclass of **ArtifactCollector**.þþ### Parameter-Aware Artifact CaptureþþAlthough the **ExampleTest** class in the previous section implements the [ArtifactParams](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ArtifactParams.java) interface, this non-parameterized example only shows half of the story. In addition to the **Description** objects of `atomic tests`, classes that implement parameterized tests are able to publish their invocation parameters, and the artifact capture feature is able to access them.þþThe following example extends the previous artifact type to add parameter-awareness:þþ###### Parameter-aware artifact typeþ```javaþclass MyParameterizedType extends MyArtifactType {þþ    @Overrideþ    public byte[] getArtifact(Object instance, Throwable reason) {þ        if (instance instanceof ArtifactParams) {þ            ArtifactParams publisher = (ArtifactParams) instance;þ            StringBuilder artifact = new StringBuilder("method: ")þ                            .append(publisher.getDescription().getMethodName()).append("\n");þ            if (publisher.getParameters().isPresent()) {þ                for (Entry<String, Object> param : publisher.getParameters().get().entrySet()) {þ                    artifact.append(param.getKey()).append(": [").append(param.getValue()).append("]\n");þ                }þ            }þ            return artifact.toString().getBytes().clone();þ        } else {þ            return new byte[0];þ        }þ    }þ}þ```þþNotice the calls to `getParameters()`, which retrieve the invocation parameters published by the test class instance. There's also a call to `getDescription()`, which returns the **Description** object for the current `atomic test`.þþThe implementation below composes a type-specific subclass of **ArtifactCollector** to produce a parameter-aware artifact collector:þþ###### Parameter-aware artifact collectorþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactCollector;þþpublic class MyParameterizedCapture extends ArtifactCollector<MyParameterizedType> {þ    þ    public MyParameterizedCapture(Object instance) {þ        super(instance, new MyParameterizedType());þ    }þ}þ```þþThe following example implements a parameterized test class that publishes its invocation parameters through the **ArtifactParams** interface. It uses the custom **Parameterized** runner to invoke the `parameterized()` test method twice - once with input "first test", and once with input "second test". The test class constructor accepts the invocation parameter as its argument and stores it in an instance field for use by the test.þþ* The `getAtomIdentity()` method provides access to the **ParameterizedCapture** test watcher, which implements the **AtomIdentity** interface.þ* The `getDescription()` method acquires the **Description** object for the current `atomic test` from the `watcher` test rule.þ* The `getParameters()` method uses static methods of the **ArtifactParams** interface to assemble the map of invocation parameters from the `input` instance field populated by the constructor.þþ###### Parameterized test classþ```javaþpackage com.nordstrom.example;þþimport static org.junit.Assert.assertEquals;þimport static org.junit.Assert.assertTrue;þþimport java.util.Arrays;þimport java.util.Map;þimport org.junit.Rule;þimport org.junit.Test;þimport org.junit.runner.Description;þimport org.junit.runner.RunWith;þimport org.junit.runners.Parameterized;þimport org.junit.runners.Parameterized.Parameters;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.ArtifactParams;þimport com.nordstrom.automation.junit.AtomIdentity;þimport com.google.common.base.Optional;þþ@RunWith(Parameterized.class)þpublic class ParameterizedTest implements ArtifactParams {þ    þ    @Ruleþ    public final MyParameterizedCapture watcher = new MyParameterizedCapture(this);þ    þ    private String input;þ    þ    public ParameterizedTest(String input) {þ        this.input = input;þ    }þ    þ    @Parametersþ    public static Object[] data() {þ        return new Object[] { "first test", "second test" };þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public AtomIdentity getAtomIdentity() {þ        return watcher;þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Description getDescription() {þ        return watcher.getDescription();þ    }þ    þ    @Overrideþ    public Optional<Map<String, Object>> getParameters() {þ        return Param.mapOf(Param.param("input", input));þ    }þ    þ    @Testþ    public void parameterized() {þ        Optional<Map<String, Object>> params = watcher.getParameters();þ        assertTrue(params.isPresent());þ        assertTrue(params.get().containsKey("input"));þ        assertEquals(input, params.get().get("input"));þ    }þ}þ```

column17: Java library for RSS and Atom feeds
column43: # Romeþþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/rometools/rome.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/rometools/rome)þ[![Maven Central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.rometools/rome/badge.svg)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.rometools/rome)þþRome is a Java framework for RSS and Atom feeds. The framework consist of several modules:þþ> ⚠️ Maintenance and development of the project is currently limited due to a shortage of active maintainers. Consider becoming an active maintainer.þþ## Project structureþþ| Module | Description |þ| ------ | ----------- |þ| `rome` | Library for generating and parsing RSS and Atom feeds. |þ| `rome-modules` | Generators and parsers for extensions like MediaRSS, GeoRSS and others. |þ| `rome-opml` | [OPML](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OPML) parsers and tools. |þ| `rome-fetcher` | DEPRECATED (see [#276](https://github.com/rometools/rome/issues/276) for details) |þþOther deprecated modules: `rome-certiorem`, `rome-certiorem-webapp` and `rome-propono`.þþ## ExamplesþþParse a feed:þþ```javaþString url = "https://stackoverflow.com/feeds/tag?tagnames=rome";þSyndFeed feed = new SyndFeedInput().build(new XmlReader(new URL(url)));þSystem.out.println(feed.getTitle());þ```þ**Beware!** The `URL` class used in this example is rudimentary and works only for simplest cases. Please consider using a separate library for fetching the feed (see example in [#276](https://github.com/rometools/rome/issues/276)).þþGenerate a feed:þþ```javaþSyndFeed feed = new SyndFeedImpl();þfeed.setFeedType("rss_2.0");þfeed.setTitle("test-title");þfeed.setDescription("test-description");þfeed.setLink("https://example.org");þSystem.out.println(new SyndFeedOutput().outputString(feed));þ```

column17: This repository contains plugins for buschmais' jQAssistant.
column43: jqassistant-pluginsþ===================þThis repository contains plugins for buschmais' [jQAssistant](http://jqassistant.org).þþHow to installþ==============þ* add [jQAssistant](http://jqassistant.org) to dependencies in your project (and jgit if git processing is desired).þþ* declare additional dependencies in your project:þ þ    - groupId de.kontext-e.jqassistant.pluginþ    - artifactId jqassistant.plugin.checkstyle or .findbugs or .jacoco or .git or .pmdþ    - e.g. for gradle:   runtime("de.kontext-e.jqassistant.plugin:jqassistant.plugin.checkstyle:1.3.3")þþþ* you may want to configure some properties in jqassistant.properties or as system property (java -Dpropertyname=propertyvalue):þþ    - jqassistant.plugin.checkstyle.basepackage=de.kontext_e.jqassistant.pluginþ    - jqassistant.plugin.findbugs.filename=findbugs.xmlþ    - jqassistant.plugin.jacoco.filename=jacoco.xmlþ    - jqassistant.plugin.pmd.filename=pmd.xmlþ    - jqassistant.plugin.git.range= - a valid git range if not the complete history should be imported -þþ* execute jQAssistant tasksþþ* If you want to add the git plugins to your [jQAssistant](http://jqassistant.org) downloaded commandline installation you currently have toþ  manually add the an org.eclipse.jgit jar file to the plugins directory of jqassistant: Use at least version þ  [4.8.0.201706111038-r from Maven Central](https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/eclipse/jgit/org.eclipse.jgit/4.8.0.201706111038-r/org.eclipse.jgit-4.8.0.201706111038-r.jar).þþSome docsþ=========þFrom master branch. Note: most recent versions from branches may differ.þþ* [Asciidoc Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/asciidoc/src/main/asciidoc/asciidoc.adoc)þ* [Checkstyle Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/checkstyle/src/main/asciidoc/checkstyle.adoc)þ* [SpotBugs/FindBugs Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/spotbugs/src/main/asciidoc/spotbugs.adoc)þ* [Git Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/git/src/main/asciidoc/git.adoc)þ* [JaCoCo Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/jacoco/src/main/asciidoc/jacoco.adoc)þ* [JavaParser Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/javaparser/src/main/asciidoc/javaparser.adoc)þ* [PlantUML Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/plantuml/src/main/asciidoc/plantuml.adoc)þ* [PMD Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/pmd/src/main/asciidoc/pmd.adoc)þ* [Excel Plugin](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/blob/master/excel/src/main/asciidoc/excel.adoc)þþLatest Changesþ==============þþRelease 1.8.0þ-------------þ* Use jQAssistant 1.8þ* 67 JaCoCo plugins slows down scanningþ* 68 Adopt XO related annotations for jQA 1.8þ* 70 Upgrade Gradle from v4 to v5þþRelease 1.7.0þ-------------þ* Use jQAssistant 1.7þ* added a plantuml constraint plantuml:WrongDirection that checks packages with package diagramsþ* more properties in PlantUML nodesþ* new plugin to import Excel filesþþRelease 1.6.0þ-------------þ* Use jQAssistant 1.6þ* Renamed FindBugs plugin to SpotBugs (still scans FindBugs reports)þ* use classpath trick to make long classpath work with Windowsþ* Upgrade to Gradle 4.10.2þ* Upgraded Dependencies to stay compatible with jQAssistant 1.6þþRelease 1.5.0þ-------------þ* Use jQAssistant 1.5þ* #61 PlantUML jar to version 1.2018.11 to be compabible with main distroþ* Simplified Checkstyle plugin graph connection to Java graph; configuration property "jqassistant.plugin.checkstyle.basepackage" is obsolete nowþ* Own jqa uses Neo4j 3 nowþ* jacoco: use jqa Java plugins 'SignatureHelper' to create the signature string which replaces own dependency to ASM by dependency to jqa Java plugin; should be more robust and create less troubleþ* updated to JavaParser version 3.6.25þ* removed some dependencies to other JARs for easier maintenanceþþRelease 1.4.1þ-------------þ* FindBugs plugin also reads new SpotBugs format (tested with SpotBugs 3.1.3)þ* AsciiDoc plugin: relations renamed: HAS_HEADER -> HAS_HEADER_ROW, HAS_BODY -> HAS_ROW, HAS_FOOTER -> HAS_FOOTER_ROWþ* AsciiDoc plugin: new rownumber property for :Row nodesþ* AsciiDoc plugin: new relation OF_COLUMN from Cell nodes to the column they belong toþ* Experimental JavaParser plugin: #58 replaced deprecated GraphDatabaseService by Cypher queriesþ* #59 Plugins shall migrate existing file nodes instead of creating new onesþþRelease 1.4.0þ-------------þ* Relation names changed, see [this blog post](http://techblog.kontext-e.de/jqa-change-relation-names/) for detailsþ* Use jQAssistant 1.4þþRelease 1.3.3þ-------------þ* #52 git plugin: protect against multiple scans of the same repoþ* #53 PlantUML: scan sequence diagramsþ* #54 Try javaparser project to scan also Java sourcesþ* #55 Asciidoc plugin: import also attributes on tables, sections, and listsþ* #56 Asciidoc: document an example for defining labels for types matched by regular expressions in tables; see [issue 56](https://github.com/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins/issues/56)þ* #57 PlantUML: Add stereotype propertyþþRelease 1.3.2þ-------------þ* #46 Git Plugin: enhanced the graph of a git repositoryþ* #47 guarded item.getFile() by path.endsWith("/HEAD") to speed up scanningþ* #48 For contributors: raised language level to 1.8þ* #49 Git Plugin: Add also properties committer, shortMessage, and encoding to GitCommitþþRelease 1.3.1þ-------------þ* PlantUML plugin supports Component DiagramsþþRelease 1.3.0þ-------------þ* Update to jQAssistant 1.3.0þ* Update to jgit 4.8.0.201706111038-rþ* Speedup Git "git:CurrentBranch" (thanks Dirk Mahler)þ* Added label "Git" to git repository node (thanks Dirk Mahler)þþþ## Compatibility Notesþþ### v1.5.0þþA newer PlantUML jar is now used. This had some API changes. As a consequence, there are someþincompatibilities with former graphs that may affect existing queries:þþ* :Diagram Property "type" is completely upper casedþ* Sequence Diagram labels are in bracketsþ* Component Diagram is not a :DescriptionDiagram but a :ClassDiagramþþ## Continuous Buildþþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/kontext-e/jqassistant-plugins)

column17: Atom File Icons plugin for IntelliJ IDEA products
column43:
# Atom Material Icons Plugin for JetBrainsþþ

þ
þ þ

þ Atom Material File Iconsþ
þ
þ

þþþThis plugin is a port of the [Atom File Icons](https://github.com/file-icons/atom) for Atom and the icons of the [Material Theme UI](https://github.com/ChrisRM/material-theme-jetbrains) plugin.þþ## Chrome Extensionþþþþ## Featuresþþ- Replaces **file icons** with their relevant logo iconsþ - According to their extension (Java, PHP, Ruby...)þ - According to the framework (Android, NPM, RSpec...)þ - According to the program used with (Babel, Docker, CircleCI...)þ- Replaces **directories**:þ - With a common pattern: src, main, app, img, docs...þ - With a specific pattern: node_modules, .vscode, .git...þ- Replaces the **PSI (Program Structure Interface)** icons:þ - Classes, Interfaces, Enums, Abstract...þ - Methods, Lambdas, Inherits, Overrides...þ- Replaces the **UI Icons**:þ - Toolbar icons (actions)þ - Gutter icons (debugger)þ - Node icons (folders)...þ- **Monochrome filter**: Set a monochrome filter to the whole UIþ - Ability to select the colorþ- **Arrows Style**: Customize the look of the arrows in Tree componentsþ - Material: Chevron-like arrowsþ - Darcula: Regular triangle arrowsþ - Plus-Minus: Plus and Minus signsþ - Arrows: Simple Arrowsþ - None: No arrowsþ- **Hollow Folders**: Add custom decorations on folders contianing opened filesþ- **Accent Color**: Change the color of specific iconsþ - Closing tab buttonþ - Highlighted arrowsþ - Loading indicator...þ- **Customizability**: Custom Settingsþ - Settings Pagesþ - Toolbar Action Buttons þ- **Custom File and Directory associations** (NEW): Customize your own associations þ - File associations by Regexþ - Folder associationsþ - Preview default iconsþþþ## File Iconsþ![File Icons](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mallowigi/iconGenerator/master/assets/files.png)þþ## Folder Iconsþ![Folder Icons](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mallowigi/iconGenerator/master/assets/folders.png)þþ## CreditsþþSpecial credits to:þ- The [Material Theme UI plugin](https://www.material-theme.com) for the implementationþ- [Atom File Icons](https://github.com/file-icons/atom) and [Sublime Text A File Icon](https://github.com/SublimeText/AFileIcon) for the ideaþ- [Scientifics Study Vectors](https://www.svgrepo.com/svg/121720/atom) for the plugin iconþ- [File-Icons](https://github.com/file-icons/source/blob/master/charmap.md)þ- [FontAwesome 4.7.0](https://fontawesome.com/v4.7.0/cheatsheet/)þ- [MFixx](https://github.com/file-icons/MFixx/blob/master/charmap.md)þ- [Devicons](https://github.com/file-icons/DevOpicons/blob/master/charmap.md)þ- [Octicons](https://octicons.github.com/)þ- [Material Design Icons](https://materialdesignicons.com/)

column17: Cliente @firma
column43: # Cliente @firmaþþEl Cliente @firma es uno de los productos de la Suite @firma de soluciones de identificación y firma electrónica. Se proporciona de a las Administraciones Públicas para que dispongan de los instrumentos necesarios para implementar la autenticación y firma electrónica avanzada de una forma rápida y efectiva.þþEl cliente de firma es una herramienta de firma electrónica en entornos de escritorio y dispositivos móviles, que funciona en forma de Applet de Java integrado en una página Web mediante JavaScript, como aplicación de escritorio, o como aplicación móvil, dependiendo del entorno del usuario.þþEs software libre con licencia GPL 2+ y EUPL 1.1. Puede consular más información y el código del producto en la forja del CTT.þþ## Construcción del Cliente @firmaþþLos módulos del Cliente @firma se encuentran preparados para su compilación y empaquetado mediante Apache Maven. A continuación se indican los distintos parámetros a utilizar para construir sus artefactos según el uso que se desee dar.þþA cualquiera de los comandos que se indican se le puede agregar el parámetro `-DskipTests` para omitir los tests JUnit.þþ### Módulos básicos y serviciosþþLos módulos del Cliente @firma incluidos en este repositorio se pueden construir mediante el siguiente comando de Maven.þþ`mvn clean install`þþEste comando generará todos los módulos básicos del proyecto y los distintos servicios WAR:þþ* `afirma-server-simple-webstart`: WAR con el servicio para la ayuda al despliegue JNLP de AutoFirma.þ* `afirma-server-triphase-signer`: WAR con el servicio para la generación de firmas trifásicas.þ* `afirma-signature-retriever`: WAR con el servicio de recuperación de datos del servidor intermedio.þ* `afirma-signature-storage`: WAR con el servicio de guardado de datos en el servidor intermedio.þþ### Artefactos desplegables y aplicacionesþþPara la construcción de los productos MiniApplet y AutoFirma (JAR), ya preparados para su distribución será necesario utilizar el perfil `env=install` mediante el comando:þþ`mvn clean install -Denv=install`þþCon esto, se podrán construir los artefactos:þþ* `afirma-simple`: JAR autoejecutable de AutoFirma (`AutoFirma.jar`).þ* `afirma-ui-miniapplet`: JAR del MiniApplet firmado con certificado de pruebas (`miniapplet-full_X_Y.jar`).þ* `afirma-ui-simple-configurator`: JAR autoejecutable del configurador necesario para la instalación de AutoFirma (`AutoFirmaConfigurador.jar`).þ* `afirma-ui-simple-webstart`: JAR de AutoFirma WebStart firmado con certificado de prueba (`AutoFirmaWS__V1.6.jar`).þþ### Despliegue en repositorio de artefactosþþPara el despliegue de los distintos módulos en un repositorio de artefactos, además de la construcción de los los propios artefactos, es necesario aportar el código fuente de la aplicación, su JavaDoc y firmar los distintos artefactos. Para evitar generar estos recursos y realizar la firma de los artefactos para la operativa ordinaria de compilación y empaquetado se ha creado un perfil `env=deploy` para que se utilice sólo cuando se va a proceder al despliegue de los artefactos en un repositorio. Se puede hacer eso mediante el comando:þþ`mvn clean deploy -Denv=deploy`

column43: = connect-javaþAll Java artifacts related to the Connect project.þþ== DescriptionþAs part of support from the Maven Release plugin for sub-folders in Maven Releases, we have shifted toþa single repository for all Java related artifacts.þþThis includes our libraries, maven plugins, composites (third party dependencies) and tiles (plugins).þþThis is intended to make it easier to onboard new people, do commits across artifacts when required, create moreþfinely grained artifacts.þþMost of these artifacts stem from logging, tracing and wiring requirements to speed up the performance of Microservicesþwritten in Java. þþ== Installation InstructionsþHow to installþþ== Build StatusþTravisCI link or something else - delete if not neededþþ== DocumentationþThere is no further specific documentation for this.þþThe main documentation for link:http://connect.cd[Connect] can be found at: link:http://docs.connect.cd[docs.connect.cd]þþ'''þimage::http://website.clearpoint.co.nz/connect/connect-logo-on-white-border.png[]þlink:http://connect.cd[Connect] is a Continuous Delivery Platform that gathers best practice approaches for deploying working software into the cloud with confidence.þþThe main documentation for link:http://connect.cd[Connect] can be found at link:http://docs.connect.cd[docs.connect.cd]þþAny queries on the link:http://connect.cd[Connect] platform can be sent to: connect@clearpoint.co.nz

implement index supporting time travel keyword search over social media data
column43: # socialtsqueryþþ## coreþThis project implements indices supporting time travel keyword search over social media data. Currently three indexing structures, i.e., LSMO, TPII and LSMI are supported. The query processing algorithm for processing the top-k temporal keyword over social media data is also implemented based on those indices.þþ## standalone serverþThrift is used to implement a RPC server so that users can use thrift client to remotely invoke insertion and query operations.þþþ## HowToþ1. execute the following command to package the project into a  Jar file. It will generate the file socialtsquery-1.0-jar-with-dependencies.jar in directory target.þ```þmvn assembly:assembly -Dmaven.test.skip=trueþ```þþ2.  Examine scripts prefixed with load in directory "script" to find out how we can use the generated jar to load data.þþ3. execute the following commands to run tests:þ```þjava -Xmx 5024M -jar  target/socialtsquery-1.0-jar-with-dependencies.jar expr.DiskBasedPerfTest  -c conf/weibo/lsmo_bdb_scale/index_lsmo_bdb_weibo_part4.conf  -c conf/weibo/lsmo_bdb_scale/index_lsmo_bdb_weibo_part8.conf  -c conf/weibo/lsmo_bdb_scale/index_lsmo_bdb_weibo_part12.conf -c conf/weibo/lsmo_bdb_scale/index_lsmo_bdb_weibo_part16.conf  -c conf/weibo/lsmo_bdb_scale/index_lsmo_bdb_weibo_part20.conf -e /home/xiafan/expr/keywordnum_2_50/weibo -q /home/xiafan/Dropbox/数据/query/weibo/nqueryseed.txt -s factsþ```

column17: Security oriented software fuzzer. Supports evolutionary, feedback-driven fuzzing based on code coverage (SW and HW based)
column43:
# Honggfuzzþþ## DescriptionþþA security oriented, feedback-driven, evolutionary, easy-to-use fuzzer with interesting analysis options. See the [Usage document](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/USAGE.md) for a primer on Honggfuzz use.þþ## Codeþþ * Latest stable version: [2.3](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/releases)þ * [Changelog](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/CHANGELOG)þþ## Featuresþþ * It's __multi-process__ and __multi-threaded__: there's no need to run multiple copies of your fuzzer, as honggfuzz can unlock potential of all your available CPU cores with a single running instance. The file corpus is automatically shared and improved between all fuzzed processes.þ * It's blazingly fast when the [persistent fuzzing mode](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/PersistentFuzzing.md)) is used. A simple/empty _LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput_ function can be tested with __up to 1mo iterations per second__ on a relatively modern CPU (e.g. i7-6700K).þ * Has a [solid track record](#trophies) of uncovered security bugs: the __only__ (to the date) __vulnerability in OpenSSL with the [critical](https://www.openssl.org/news/secadv/20160926.txt) score mark__ was discovered by honggfuzz. See the [Trophies](#trophies) paragraph for the summary of findings to the date.þ * Uses low-level interfaces to monitor processes (e.g. _ptrace_ under Linux and NetBSD). As opposed to other fuzzers, it __will discover and report hijacked/ignored signals from crashes__ (intercepted and potentially hidden by a fuzzed program).þ * Easy-to-use, feed it a simple corpus directory (can even be empty for the [feedback-driven fuzzing](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/FeedbackDrivenFuzzing.md)), and it will work its way up, expanding it by utilizing feedback-based coverage metrics.þ * Supports several (more than any other coverage-based feedback-driven fuzzer) hardware-based (CPU: branch/instruction counting, __Intel BTS__, __Intel PT__) and software-based [feedback-driven fuzzing](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/FeedbackDrivenFuzzing.md) modes. Also, see the new __[qemu mode](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/tree/master/qemu_mode)__ for blackbox binary fuzzing.þ * Works (at least) under GNU/Linux, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Mac OS X, Windows/CygWin and [Android](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/Android.md).þ * Supports the __persistent fuzzing mode__ (long-lived process calling a fuzzed API repeatedly). More on that can be found [here](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/PersistentFuzzing.md).þ * It comes with the __[examples](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/tree/master/examples) directory__, consisting of real world fuzz setups for widely-used software (e.g. Apache HTTPS, OpenSSL, libjpeg etc.).þ * Provides a __[corpus minimization](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/USAGE.md#corpus-minimization--m)__ mode.þþ---þþ

þ þ

þþ---þþ## Requirementsþþ * **Linux** - The BFD library (libbfd-dev) and libunwind (libunwind-dev/libunwind8-dev), clang-5.0 or higher for software-based coverage modesþ * **FreeBSD** - gmake, clang-5.0 or newerþ * **NetBSD** - gmake, clang, capstone, libBlocksRuntimeþ * **Android** - Android SDK/NDK. Also see [this detailed doc](https://github.com/google/honggfuzz/blob/master/docs/Android.md) on how to build and run itþ * **Windows** - CygWinþ * **Darwin/OS X** - Xcode 10.8+þ * if **Clang/LLVM** is used to compile honggfuzz - link it with the BlocksRuntime Library (libblocksruntime-dev)þþ## TrophiesþþHonggfuzz has been used to find a few interesting security problems in major software packages; An incomplete list:þþ * Dozens of security problems via the [OSS-Fuzz](https://bugs.chromium.org/p/oss-fuzz/issues/list?q=honggfuzz&can=1) projectþ * [Pre-auth remote crash in __OpenSSH__](https://anongit.mindrot.org/openssh.git/commit/?id=28652bca29046f62c7045e933e6b931de1d16737)þ * __Apache HTTPD__þ * [Remote crash in __mod\_http2__ • CVE-2017-7659](http://seclists.org/oss-sec/2017/q2/504)þ * [Use-after-free in __mod\_http2__ • CVE-2017-9789](http://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2017-9789)þ * [Memory leak in __mod\_auth\_digest__ • CVE-2017-9788](http://cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2017-9788)þ * [Out of bound access • CVE-2018-1301](http://seclists.org/oss-sec/2018/q1/265)þ * [Write after column17: Mirror of Apache Qpid JMS
column43: # QpidJMSþþThe QpidJMS project provides a JMS based client that uses the AMQP v1.0 protocol.þþBelow are some quick pointers you might find useful.þþ## Building the codeþþThe project requires Maven 3. Some example commands follow.þþClean previous builds output and install all modules to local repository withoutþrunning the tests:þþ    mvn clean install -DskipTestsþþInstall all modules to the local repository after running all the tests:þþ    mvn clean installþþPerform a subset tests on the packaged release artifacts withoutþinstalling:þþ    mvn clean verify -Dtest=TestNamePattern*þþExecute the tests and produce code coverage report:þþ    mvn clean test jacoco:reportþþ## ExamplesþþFirst build and install all the modules as detailed above (if running againstþa source checkout/release, rather than against released binaries) and thenþconsult the README in the qpid-jms-examples module itself.þþ## DocumentationþþThere is some basic documentation in the qpid-jms-docs module.þþ## Distribution assembliesþþAfter building the modules, src and binary distribution assemblies can be found at:þþ    apache-qpid-jms/target

column17: PetBlocks is a spigot and also a sponge plugin to use blocks and custom heads as pets in Minecraft.
column43: # PetBlocks  [![Build Status](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.github.shynixn.petblocks/petblocks-api/badge.svg?style=flat-square)](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/com.github.shynixn.petblocks/petblocks-api) [![GitHub license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-Apache%20License%202.0-blue.svg?style=flat-square)](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Shynixn/PetBlocks/master/LICENCE) þþþ| branch        | status        |  version | download |þ| ------------- | ------------- |  --------| ---------| þ| master        | [![Build Status](https://img.shields.io/travis/Shynixn/PetBlocks/master.svg?style=flat-square)](https://travis-ci.org/Shynixn/PetBlocks)| ![GitHub license](https://img.shields.io/nexus/r/https/oss.sonatype.org/com.github.shynixn.petblocks/petblocks-bukkit-plugin.svg?style=flat-square)  |[Download latest release](https://github.com/Shynixn/PetBlocks/releases)|þ| development   | [![Build Status](https://img.shields.io/travis/Shynixn/PetBlocks/development.svg?style=flat-square)](https://travis-ci.org/Shynixn/PetBlocks) |![GitHub license](https://img.shields.io/nexus/s/https/oss.sonatype.org/com.github.shynixn.petblocks/petblocks-bukkit-plugin.svg?style=flat-square) |  [Download snapshots](https://oss.sonatype.org/content/repositories/snapshots/com/github/shynixn/petblocks) |þ## DescriptionþþPetBlocks is a spigot and also a sponge plugin to use blocks and custom heads as pets in Minecraft.þþ## Featuresþþ* Use blocks as pets in minecraftþ* The GUI and pets are completely customizableþ* Version support 1.8.R1 - 1.16.R1þ* Check out the [PetBlocks-Spigot-Page](https://www.spigotmc.org/resources/12056/) to get more information. þþ## Installationþþ* Please check out the [PetBlocks Documentation](https://shynixn.github.io/PetBlocks/) for further information.þþ## Screenshotsþþ![alt tag](http://www.mediafire.com/convkey/8853/81wf7uswm0xh9qgzg.jpg)þþ## Contributingþþ* Clone the repository to your local environmentþ* Install Java 8 (later versions are not supported by the ``downloadDependencies`` and ``setupDecompWorkspace`` task)þ* Install Apache Mavenþ* Make sure ``java`` points to a Java 8 installation (``java -version``)þ* Make sure ``$JAVA_HOME`` points to a Java 8 installationþ* Make sure ``mvn`` points to a Maven installation (``mvn --version``)þ* Execute gradle sync for dependenciesþ* Install the additional spigot dependencies by executing the following gradle task (this task can take a very long time)þþ```xmlþ[./gradlew|gradlew.bat] downloadDependenciesþ```þþ* Install the ForgeGradle development workspace for spongeþþ```xmlþ[./gradlew|gradlew.bat] setupDecompWorkspaceþ```þþ* Build the plugin by executingþþ```xmlþ[./gradlew|gradlew.bat] shadowJarþ```þþ* The PetBlocks-Bukkit.jar file gets generated at petblocks-bukkit-plugin/build/libs/petblocks-bukkit-plugin.jarþ* The PetBlocks-Sponge.jar file gets generated at petblocks-sponge-plugin/build/libs/petblocks-sponge-plugin.jarþþ## LicenceþþCopyright 2015-2020 ShynixnþþLicensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");þyou may not use this file except in compliance with the License.þYou may obtain a copy of the License atþþ   http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþUnless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþdistributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þWITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þSee the License for the specific language governing permissions andþlimitations under the License.

column17: Helper library for Spring Boot web applications
column43: # Spring Lemonþþ> Minimize your development cost with our intensive consulting/training — [click here](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/) for details.þþWhen developing **real-world** Spring REST APIs and microservices, you face many challenges likeþþ1. How to follow a stateless and efficient security model – using JWT authentication, session sliding etc.þ1. How to configure Spring Security to suit API development, e.g. returning _200_ or _401_ responses on login, configuring _CORS_, _JSON vulnerability protection_, etc.þ1. How to elegantly do _validations_ and _exceptions_ and send precise errors to the client.þ1. How to easily mix manual and bean validations in a single validation cycle.þ1. How exactly to support multiple _social sign up/in_, using _OpenID Connect_ or _OAuth2_ providers such as _Google_ and _Facebook_.þ1. How to code a robust user module (with features like _sign up_, _sign in_, _verify email_, _social sign up/in_, _update profile_, _forgot password_, _change password_, _change email_, _token authentication_ etc.) and share it across all your applications.þ1. How to correctly and effeciently _secure microservices_, using long-lived and short-lived JWTs.þ1. What would be good ways to _test your API_.þ1. How to do _Captcha validation_.þ1. How to properly organize _application properties_.þ1. How to use _PATCH_ and _JsonPatch_ to handle partial updates correctly.þ1. How to do all the above reactively, using WebFlux and WebFlux security.þþCoding all this rightly needs in-depth knowledge of Spring. It also takes a lot of development time and effort, and needs to be properly maintained as new versions of Spring comes out.þþ**Spring Lemon** relieves you of all this burden. It's a set of configurable and extensible libraries, providing all above features. Use these to develop quality reactive or non-reactive monolith or microservices applications quickly and easily.  þþEven if you don't plan to use Spring Lemon, it's a good example to learn from, because it showcases the essential best practices for developing elegant web services and microservices using Spring.þþMost Spring Boot applications can use Spring Lemon straight away, with some simple configurations. But, if you don't find it suitable for your application, feel free to fork it, or just roll out your own library by learning its patterns and practices. Better yet, be a contributor!þþRead [this quick starter guide](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Getting-Started-With-Spring-Lemon) or watch [this video tutorial](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-lemon-restful-web-services-development) for getting started.þþ## Libraries hierarchyþþ* [spring-lemon-exceptions](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Exceptions-Guide): Useful for elegant exception handling and validation in any Spring projectþ    * [spring-lemon-commons](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Commons-Guide): Common for all things belowþ        * [spring-lemon-commons-web](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Commons-Web-Guide): For developing Spring Web (non-reactive) microservicesþ            * [spring-lemon-commons-jpa](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Commons-JPA-Guide): For developing Spring Web (non-reactive) JPA microservicesþ                * [spring-lemon-jpa](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-JPA-Guide): For developing Spring Web (non-reactive) JPA monolith or auth-microserviceþ        * [spring-lemon-commons-reactive](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Commons-Reactive-Guide): For developing Spring WebFlux (reactive) microservicesþ            * [spring-lemon-commons-mongo](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Commons-MongoDB-Guide): For developing Spring WebFlux (reactive) MongoDB microservicesþ                * [spring-lemon-reactive](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Spring-Lemon-Reactive-Guide): For developing Spring WebFlux (reactive) MongoDB monolith or auth-microserviceþþFor example usages, seeþþ* [Demo non-reactive monolith](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/tree/master/lemon-demo-jpa)þ* [Demo reactive monolith](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/tree/master/lemon-demo-reactive)þ* [Demo non-reactive microservices](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-01) and its [configuration repository](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-01-config)þ* [Demo reactive microservices](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-02) and its [configuration repository](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-02-config)þþ## Documentation and Resourcesþþ> _Our [Spring Framework Recipes For Real World Application Development](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-framework-book-of-best-practices) — a live book discussing key real-world topics on developing Spring applications and APIs — is now available for FREE. [Click here](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-framework-book-of-best-practices) to get it._þþ1. Feature demo: https://youtu.be/6mNg-Feq8CYþ1. _Getting started guide_þ   1. [Book](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Getting-Started-With-Spring-Lemon)þ   1. [Video Tutorial](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-lemon-restful-web-services-development)þ1. _[Official Documentation](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki)_þ1. _Example applications_þ    * [Demo non-reactive monolith](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/tree/master/lemon-demo-jpa)þ    * [Demo reactive monolith](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/tree/master/lemon-demo-reactive)þ    * [Demo non-reactive microservices](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-01) and its [configuration repository](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-01-config)þ    * [Demo reactive microservices](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-02) and its [configuration repository](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/np-microservices-sample-02-config)þ1. _[API documentation](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/305915/RVu2mqEH)_ of the above applications.þ1. _[Example AngularJS front-end application](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/tree/master/lemon-demo-angularjs)_ — A sample AngularJS 1.x front-end. It'll work for the application developed in the above [getting started guide](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Getting-Started-With-Spring-Lemon) as well all the above example applications. See the [Getting Started Guide](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Getting-Started-With-Spring-Lemon) on how to use it.þ1. _[Spring Framework Recipes For Real World Application Development](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-framework-book-of-best-practices)_ — a live book discussing key real-world topics on developing Spring applications, APIs and microservoces. Includes many Spring Lemon topics. [Click here](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-framework-book-of-best-practices) to get it now for FREE!þ1. [Using Spring Lemon Effectively](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/wiki/Using-Spring-Lemon-Effectively)þ1. [DZone Articles](https://dzone.com/users/1211183/skpatel20.html)þ1. Video tutorials coming soon:þ   1. Spring Framework 5 REST API Development — A Complete Blueprint For Real-World Developersþ   1. Spring WebFlux Reactive REST API Development — A Complete Blueprint For Real-World Developersþ   1. Microservices Using Spring Cloud — A Rapid Course For Real World Developersþ   1. Join [here](https://www.naturalprogrammer.com/p/spring-framework-book-of-best-practices) to get notified and avail heavy discounts when the above courses get releasedþþ## Help and Supportþ1. Community help is available at [stackoverflow.com](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/spring-lemon), under the `spring-lemon` tag. Do not miss to tag the questions with `spring-lemon`!þ1. [Submit an issue](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/issues) for any bug or enhancement. Please check first that the issue isn't already reported earlier.þ1. See [here](https://github.com/naturalprogrammer/spring-lemon/releases).
