column17: 根据兴趣尝试的web项目
column43: 这是我和同学一起开发的一个类似新闻发布web工程þþ架构的基本样子þþ![1539828111931](https://github.com/hangliugithub/news/blob/master/images/1539828111931.png)þþ当然中间数据库分片的mycat可以用keepalived+haproxy+mycat 实现mycat这个中间件的高可用上图自己画的时候忘掉了þþ整个项目使用springboot构建的，实现前后台分离，springboot在构建这样的微服务可以大量的节省开发人员的工作þþ由于开发的时间不长，上面还有很多待扩展的功能，前台展示有用户选择的兴趣推送不同的新闻热点，从而实现用户登录之后每一个人看到的东西不一样。þþ当然实现完整的商业项目需要加上完善的异常逻辑þþ基本实现的功能：þþ登录注册模块：用户注册和登录的实现þþ后台管理模块：权限管理，用户管理，评论管理þþ前台展示：新闻消息的展示，发表评论，elsticsearch搜索功能þþ项目所用的技术点þþ前端技术：`js`,`bootstrap`,`jQuery`þþ后端技术：`spring`，`springboot`，`redis`，`elasticsearch`,`mycat`,`mysql`þþ其中消息的测试数据是我用`python` 利用爬虫框架`scrapy`爬取的新闻网的内容,通过处理存入数据库

column17: xowa offline wiki application
column43: ## OverviewþXOWA is an offline Wikipedia application that lets you run Wikipedia on your computer.þþ![XOWA showing Wikipedia's article on Wikipedia](http://xowa.sourceforge.net/wiki/file_screenshot_wikipedia_xowa.png)þþ## Featuresþ* Run a complete copy of English Wikipedia from your computer.þ* Display 5.0+ million articles in full HTML formatting.þ* Show images within an article. Access 4.0+ million images using the offline image databases.þ* Set up over 800+ other wikis including: English Wiktionary, English Wikisource, English Wikiquote, English Wikivoyage, Non-English wikis (French Wiktionary, German Wikisource, Dutch Wikivoyage), Wikidata, Wikimedia Commons and many more.þ* Update your wiki whenever you want, using Wikimedia's database backups.þ* Navigate between offline wikis. Click on "Look up this word in Wiktionary" and instantly view the page in Wiktionary.þ* Edit articles to remove vandalism or errors. þ* Install to a flash memory card for portability to other machines.þ* Run on Windows, Linux and Mac OS X. (Android Alpha available)þ* Run as an HTTP server to browse from Firefox, Chrome or Safariþ* View the HTML source for any wiki page.þ* Search for any page by title using a Wikipedia-like Search box. Search across wikis as well.þ* Browse pages by alphabetical order using Special:AllPages.þ* Find a word on a page.þ* Access a history of viewed pages.þ* Bookmark your favorite pages.þ* Preview articles by hovering over linksþ* Customize any one of over 50 optionsþþ## RequirementsþXOWA is written in Java and requires 1.7 or above.þþ## Installationþ* Download xowa_app_your_operating_system_name.zip from https://github.com/gnosygnu/xowa/releases/þ* Unzip to any folder on your hard drive (or flash memory card)þ* Run XOWAþ * On '''Windows''', double-click '''C:\xowa\xowa_64.exe'''þ * On '''Linux''', open a terminal and run sh /home/your_user_name/xowa/xowa_linux_64.shþ * On '''OS X''', open a terminal and run sh /Users/your_user_name/xowa/xowa_macosx_64.shþþ## Development Infoþ### Compilation instructions (Command-line)þ#### REQUIREMENTSþ* Java JDK 1.7 (or higher): https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jdk8-downloads-2133151.htmlþ* Apache Ant 1.9.13 (or higher): https://ant.apache.org/bindownload.cgiþ* A ROOT_DIR directory on your file-systemþ* (Windows) cygwin: https://www.cygwin.com/þ* (Mac OS X) wget via homebrew (or just download the file manually): https://stackoverflow.com/questions/33886917/how-to-install-wget-in-macosþþ#### PROCESSþ* Copy-paste https://github.com/gnosygnu/xowa/blob/master/xowa_get_and_make.sh to a plain-text file; EX: /cygdrive/c/xowa_dev/xowa_get_and_make.shþ* Adjust these environment variables to your system: PLAT_NAME, ROOT_DIR, ANT_BINARY, JAVA_JDK_DIRþ* cd to your ROOT_DIRþ* Run the file using "sh xowa_get_and_make.sh"þ* Run the xowa_dev.jarþ * (Windows) java -jar xowa_dev.jarþ * (Linux) SWT_GTK3=0 && java -jar xowa_dev.jarþ * (Mac OS X) java -Xmx256m -d64 -XstartOnFirstThread -jar xowa_dev.jarþþ### Compilation instructions (ANT command-line)þ#### Setup the XOWA appþ* Download the latest XOWA app package for your operating system. For example, if you're on a 64-bit Linux system, "xowa_app_linux_64_v1.9.5.1.zip".þ* Unzip the XOWA app package to a directory. For the sake of simplicity, these instructions assume this directory is "/xowa/"þ* Review your directories. You should have the following:þ * An XOWA jar: "/xowa/xowa_linux_64.jar"þ * An XOWA "/bin/any/" directory with several jar files. For example, "/xowa/bin/any/java/apache/commons-compress-1.5.jar"þ * An XOWA "/bin/linux_64/" directory with an SWT jar: "/xowa/bin/linux_64/swt/swt.jar"þþ#### Setup the XOWA sourceþ* Download the latest XOWA source archive. For example: "xowa_source_v1.9.5.1.7z"þ* Unzip the source to "/xowa/dev". When you're done, you'll have a file called "/xowa/dev/build.xml" as well as othersþ * NOTE: if you're not on a Linux 64-bit system, overwrite the swt jar at "/xowa/dev/150_gfui/lib/swt.jar" with the copy from your "/bin/OS" directory. For example, if you're on a 64 bit Windows system, replace "/xowa/dev/150_gfui/lib/swt.jar" with "/bin/windows_64/swt/swt.jar"þþ#### Run the ant fileþ* Open up a console, and run "ant -buildfile build.xml -Dplat_name=linux_64"þþ### IDE instructions (Eclipse)þ#### EnvironmentþThe '''xowa_source.7z''' was built with Eclipse Indigo. There are no OS dependencies, nor are there dependencies on Eclipse.þþ#### Setupþ* Follow the steps in these two sections from above:þ * Setup the XOWA appþ * Setup the XOWA sourceþ* Launch Eclipse. Choose a workbench folder of "/xowa/dev"þ* If the projects don't load, do File -> Import -> Existing Projects Into Workspaceþ* Select all projects. Do File -> Refresh.þ* Right-click on 400_xowa in the Package Explorer. Select Debug As -> Java Application. Select Xowa_main. XOWA should launch.þ* Right-click on 400_xowa in the Package Explorer. Select Debug As -> JUnit Test. All tests should pass.þþ#### Eclipse-specific settingsþThis section documents specific project customizations that differ from the standard Eclipse defaults.þþ##### Project propertiesþResource -> Text file encoding -> Other -> UTF-8þþ##### PreferencesþThese settings are available under Window -> Preferencesþþ* Disable Spellingþ * General -> Editors -> Text Editors -> Spellingþ*Ignore Warningsþ * Java -> Compiler -> Errors/Warningsþ * Annotations -> Unhandled token in '@SuppressWarnings'þ * Potential programming problems -> Serializable class without serialVersionUIDþ * Generic Types -> Unnecessary generic type operation (In Eclipse Luna: "Unchecked generic type operation")þ * Generic Types -> Usage of a raw typeþ * Unnecessary Code -> Unused importþþ##### Configuration argumentsþ* Configuration argumentsþ * Run -> Debug Configurations -> Argumentsþ * --root_dir /xowa/ --show_license n --show_args nþþ## LicenseþXOWA is licensed under the terms of the General Public License (GPL) Version 3,þor alternatively under the terms of the Apache License Version 2.0.þþSee LICENSE.txt for more information.

column17: Portable OpenSSH
column43: # Portable OpenSSHþþ[![Fuzzing Status](https://oss-fuzz-build-logs.storage.googleapis.com/badges/openssh.svg)](https://bugs.chromium.org/p/oss-fuzz/issues/list?sort=-opened&can=1&q=proj:openssh)þþOpenSSH is a complete implementation of the SSH protocol (version 2) for secure remote login, command execution and file transfer. It includes a client ``ssh`` and server ``sshd``, file transfer utilities ``scp`` and ``sftp`` as well as tools for key generation (``ssh-keygen``), run-time key storage (``ssh-agent``) and a number of supporting programs.þþThis is a port of OpenBSD's [OpenSSH](https://openssh.com) to most Unix-like operating systems, including Linux, OS X and Cygwin. Portable OpenSSH polyfills OpenBSD APIs that are not available elsewhere, adds sshd sandboxing for more operating systems and includes support for OS-native authentication and auditing (e.g. using PAM).þþ## DocumentationþþThe official documentation for OpenSSH are the man pages for each tool:þþ* [ssh(1)](https://man.openbsd.org/ssh.1)þ* [sshd(8)](https://man.openbsd.org/sshd.8)þ* [ssh-keygen(1)](https://man.openbsd.org/ssh-keygen.1)þ* [ssh-agent(1)](https://man.openbsd.org/ssh-agent.1)þ* [scp(1)](https://man.openbsd.org/scp.1)þ* [sftp(1)](https://man.openbsd.org/sftp.1)þ* [ssh-keyscan(8)](https://man.openbsd.org/ssh-keyscan.8)þ* [sftp-server(8)](https://man.openbsd.org/sftp-server.8)þþ## Stable ReleasesþþStable release tarballs are available from a number of [download mirrors](https://www.openssh.com/portable.html#downloads). We recommend the use of a stable release for most users. Please read the [release notes](https://www.openssh.com/releasenotes.html) for details of recent changes and potential incompatibilities.þþ## Building Portable OpenSSHþþ### DependenciesþþPortable OpenSSH is built using autoconf and make. It requires a working C compiler, standard library and headers, and [zlib](https://www.zlib.net/). ``libcrypto`` from either [LibreSSL](https://www.libressl.org/) or [OpenSSL](https://www.openssl.org) may also be used, but OpenSSH may be built without it supporting a subset of crypto algorithms.þþFIDO security token support need [libfido2](https://github.com/Yubico/libfido2) and its dependencies. Also, certain platforms and build-time options may require additional dependencies, see README.platform for details.þþ### Building a releaseþþReleases include a pre-built copy of the ``configure`` script and may be built using:þþ```þtar zxvf openssh-X.YpZ.tar.gzþcd opensshþ./configure # [options]þmake && make testsþ```þþSee the [Build-time Customisation](#build-time-customisation) section below for configure options. If you plan on installing OpenSSH to your system, then you will usually want to specify destination paths.þ þ### Building from gitþþIf building from git, you'll need [autoconf](https://www.gnu.org/software/autoconf/) installed to build the ``configure`` script. The following commands will check out and build portable OpenSSH from git:þþ```þgit clone https://github.com/openssh/openssh-portable # or https://anongit.mindrot.org/openssh.gitþcd openssh-portableþautoreconfþ./configureþmake && make testsþ```þþ### Build-time CustomisationþþThere are many build-time customisation options available. All Autoconf destination path flags (e.g. ``--prefix``) are supported (and are usually required if you want to install OpenSSH).þþFor a full list of available flags, run ``configure --help`` but a few of the more frequently-used ones are described below. Some of these flags will require additional libraries and/or headers be installed.þþFlag | Meaningþ--- | ---þ``--with-pam`` | Enable [PAM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pluggable_authentication_module) support. [OpenPAM](https://www.openpam.org/), [Linux PAM](http://www.linux-pam.org/) and Solaris PAM are supported.þ``--with-libedit`` | Enable [libedit](https://www.thrysoee.dk/editline/) support for sftp.þ``--with-kerberos5`` | Enable Kerberos/GSSAPI support. Both [Heimdal](https://www.h5l.org/) and [MIT](https://web.mit.edu/kerberos/) Kerberos implementations are supported.þ``--with-selinux`` | Enable [SELinux](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Security-Enhanced_Linux) support.þ``--with-security-key-builtin`` | Include built-in support for U2F/FIDO2 security keys. This requires [libfido2](https://github.com/Yubico/libfido2) be installed.þþ## DevelopmentþþPortable OpenSSH development is discussed on the [openssh-unix-dev mailing list](https://lists.mindrot.org/mailman/listinfo/openssh-unix-dev) ([archive mirror](https://marc.info/?l=openssh-unix-dev)). Bugs and feature requests are tracked on our [Bugzilla](https://bugzilla.mindrot.org/).þþ## Reporting bugsþþ_Non-security_ bugs may be reported to the developers via [Bugzilla](https://bugzilla.mindrot.org/) or via the mailing list above. Security bugs should be reported to [openssh@openssh.com](mailto:openssh.openssh.com).

column17: A mirror of the OpenJDK langtools repository
column43: Building the "langtools" workspace.þþThe "langtools" workspace can be built from the command line with Ant.þThe build file is make/build.xml, in conjunction with make/build.properties.þSome additional user-specific properties files are also read, to allowþyou to customize selected properties as needed.þþIndividual tools within the workspace can also be built and worked onþwith NetBeans, using the projects in the make/netbeans directory.þþThe "langtools" workspace can also be built from the command line withþGNU Make, although the Makefile is simply a wrapper around the Antþbuild file. This is provided for systems (such as the full OpenJDK build)þthat expect to be able to build this workspace with GNU Make.þþSystem Requirements:þ  Ant:      version 1.6.5 or laterþ  NetBeans: version 6.0 or later (optional)þ  JDK:      currently version 1.5.0, although 1.6.0 is recommendedþ  OS:       any system supporting the above toolsþþFor more information:þ  Ant:      http://ant.apache.org/þ  GNU Make: http://www.gnu.org/software/make/þ  NetBeans: http://www.netbeans.org/þþþTesting the "langtools" workspace.þþThe primary set of tests for the compiler is the compiler TCK. Thisþtests that the compiler performs according to the specifications inþJLS and JVMS.þþIn addition, there is a substantial collection of regression and unitþtests for all the tools in the main langtools test/ directory.þþFinally, there is a small set of tests to do basic validation of a buildþof the langtools workspace for use by JDK. These tests check the contentsþof the dist/ directory generated by the build, and verify that the variousþtools can do basic "Hello World"-style processing. These tests should beþrun by jtreg, with the -jdk option set a version of JDK capable of runningþthe default output of the javac compiler in this workspace. Currently, þthis means JDK 6 or better.

column17: A simple tool to calculate the overall performance of an investment portfolio.
column43: # AboutþþA simple tool to calculate the overall performance of an investment portfolio.þþSee https://www.portfolio-performance.info for more details.þþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/buchen/portfolio.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/buchen/portfolio) [![Latest Release](https://img.shields.io/github/release/buchen/portfolio.svg)](https://github.com/buchen/portfolio/releases/latest) [![Release Date](https://img.shields.io/github/release-date/buchen/portfolio?color=blue)](https://github.com/buchen/portfolio/releases/latest) [![License](https://img.shields.io/github/license/buchen/portfolio.svg)](https://github.com/buchen/portfolio/blob/master/LICENSE)þþ[![LOC](https://sonarcloud.io/api/project_badges/measure?project=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&metric=ncloc)](https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app) [![Bugs](https://sonarcloud.io/api/project_badges/measure?project=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&metric=bugs)](https://sonarcloud.io/project/issues?id=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&resolved=false&types=BUG) [![Vulnerabilities](https://sonarcloud.io/api/project_badges/measure?project=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&metric=vulnerabilities)](https://sonarcloud.io/project/issues?id=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&resolved=false&types=VULNERABILITY) [![Code Coverage](https://sonarcloud.io/api/project_badges/measure?project=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&metric=coverage)](https://sonarcloud.io/component_measures?id=name.abuchen.portfolio%3Aportfolio-app&metric=Coverage)þþ## Prerequisitesþþ* [Java 8](https://www.java.com)þ* [Maven](https://maven.apache.org)þ* [Eclipse](https://www.eclipse.org)þþ## Developing with Eclipseþþ### Eclipse SetupþþTo develop, use the latest [Eclipse IDE](https://www.eclipse.org/downloads/) release plus **Plug-in Development Environment (PDE)**. PDE homepage is https://www.eclipse.org/pde/ and it can be installed via Help/Install new Software. The link for the update site is mentioned in the PDE docs.þþOptionally, install via the Eclipse Marketplaceþ* infinitestþ* ResourceBundle Editorþ* SonarLintþ* Eclipse Checkstyle Plug-inþþ### SetupþþClone the git repository.þþImport projects byþ* selecting "Import Projects..." on the Git repository in the Git perspectiveþ* choosing "File" > "Import..." > "Existing Projects into Workspace" from the menuþþAfter importing the Portfolio Performance projects in Eclipse, they will not compile due to missing dependencies: the target platform is missing.þþ### Set Target Platformþþ* Open the portfolio-target-definition projectþ* Open the portfolio-target-definition.target file with the Target Editor (this may take a while as it requires Internet access). If you just get an XML file, use right click and chose Open With *Target Editor*þ* In the resulting editor, click on the "Set as Active Target Platform" link at the top right (this may also take a while)þþ### Run ProgramþþRun the application and the tests with the launch configurations stored in ~/portfolio-app/eclipse folder (right-click "Run As").þþ:warning: The launch configuration needs an update when bundles are added and removed or the OS platform changes. If the program does not start, try selecting "Add required plug-ins" in the launch configuration dialog.þþþ## Building with MavenþþMaven is not required (anymore) to develop Portfolio Performance as you can develop using the Eclipse IDE with the setup above. The Maven build is used for the [Travis CI](https://travis-ci.org/buchen/portfolio) build.þþ### Configureþþ*Mac OS X / Linux*þ```þexport MAVEN_OPTS="-Xmx1g"þ```þþ*Windows*þ```þset MAVEN_OPTS="-Xmx1g"þ```þþ### BuildþþRun Maven 3.x.x in the 'portfolio-app' directory:þþ```þmvn clean verify -Dtycho.disableP2Mirrorsþ```þþ## LicenseþþEclipse Public Licenseþhttps://www.eclipse.org/legal/epl-v10.html

column17: Remote Session is a small collection of utility classes for interacting with remote systems via Secure Shell (SSH) protocol.
column43: [![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.nordstrom.tools/remote-session.svg)](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.nordstrom.tools/remote-session)þþ# REMOTE SESSION UTILITIESþþ**Remote Session** is a small collection of utility classes for interacting with remote systems via Secure Shell (SSH) protocol. Built around the [JSch](http://www.jcraft.com/jsch/) library from _JCraft_, available functions include:þþ* Secure file transferþ* Remote interactive shellþ* Remote command executionþþ**Remote Session** wraps the capabilities of **JSch** in a simplified API that handles many of the details related to setting up and managing remote sessions. Originated by [Mykhaylo Adamovych](http://stackoverflow.com/users/448078/mykhaylo-adamovych), the implementation was copied verbatim from a post on [Stack Overflow](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/2405885/run-a-command-over-ssh-with-jsch). JavaDoc has been added for completeness and comprehensibility.þþ## Secure File Transferþþ**Remote Session** enables clients to upload and download files via secure file transfer protocol (SFTP).þþ```javaþ    SshUtils.sftp("file:/C:/home/file.txt", "ssh://user:pass@host/home");þ    SshUtils.sftp("ssh://user:pass@host/home/file.txt", "file:/C:/home");þ```þþ**NOTE**: The transferred file retains its original name. If specified, the name component of `toUrl` will be ignored.  þ**NOTE**: As indicated by the examples, source and target URIs must refer to opposing locations: `file` for local file system and `ssh` for remote file system.þþ* For upload: **fromUri** = `file`; **toUri** = `ssh`þ* For download: **fromUri** = `ssh`; **toUri** = `file`þþ## Remote Interactive Shellþþ**Remote Session** supports interacting with remote systems via a secure `shell` channel, in which input and output are streamed between local and remote systems. Each of the three methods provided for secure shell interaction exhibit different operational characteristics.þþ###### Unbounded Stream I/Oþ```javaþ    InputStream is = System.in;þ    OutputStream os = System.out;þ    SshUtils.shell("ssh://user:pass@host", is, os);þ    PrintStream ps = new PrintStream(is, true);þ    ps.println("ls -la");þ    ps.println("exit");þ    System.out.println(IOUtils.toString(os, Charset.defaultCharset()));þ```þþWith unbounded stream I/O, the channel remains open until the input stream is closed or an `exit` command is submitted.þþ###### Submit Specified Commandþ```javaþ    String remoteOutput = SshUtils.shell("ssh://user:pass@host/work/dir/path", "ls");þ```þþFrom the client perspective, this is effectively equivalent to `exec(String, String)`. The primary difference is the channel used for communication (`shell` instead of `exec`).þþ###### Submit Command with Streamed Outputþ```javaþ    OutputStream os = System.out;þ    SshUtils.shell("ssh://user:pass@host", "ls -la", os);þ    System.out.println(IOUtils.toString(os, Charset.defaultCharset()));þ```þþThis is essentially a hybrid of the previous two secure-shell methods, well-suited for long-running commands that you'd like to leave running while you handle other tasks.þþ## Remote Command Executionþþ**Remote Session** enables you to submit commands to remote systems atomically. Instead of submitting commands through an input stream, you specify each command as a property of the channel and execute it.þþ###### Execute Specified Commandþ```javaþ    System.out.println(SshUtils.exec("ssh://user:pass@host/work/dir/path", "ls -t | head -n1"));þ```þþ###### Execute Command þ```javaþ    String connectUri = "ssh://user:pass@host/work/dir/path";þ    String command = "ls -t | head -n1";þ    try (SessionHolder<ChannelExec> session = new SessionHolder<>(ChannelType.EXEC, URI.create(connectUri))) {þ        String workDir = session.getWorkDir();þ        if (workDir != null) command = "cd " + workDir + " && " + command;þ        System.out.println(session, command);þ    }þ```þþ## JSch Reference Implementation (SshUtils)þþ**SshUtils** is a reference implementation of a **JSch** client. It enables you to execute the specified command, optionally executing an initial command to switch to an alternate user first.þþ```javaþ    String userName = "user";þ    String password = "password";þ    String hostName = "host";þ    String sudoCmd = "sudo su - admin";þ    String batchDir = "/work/dir/path";þ    String batchCmd = "./script.ksh parm1 parm2";þ    String output = SshUtils.executeBatch(userName, password, hostName, sudoCmd, batchDir, batchCmd);þ    System.out.println(output);þ```þþThe implementation of `SshUtils` demonstrates how to use a couple of important **Remote Session** classes:þ* `SessionHolder` - This is a wrapper class for objects that extend the `Channel` class. The wrapper implements the `Closeable` interface, and `SshUtils` uses a "try-with-resources" block to ensure that the channel is always closed regardless of the outcome of command execution. `SessionHolder` includes these methods (among others):þ  * `getChannel` - Get the channel to the remote session created for this `SessionHolder`.þ  * `getChannelStream` - Get a new channel stream object for this session.þ  * `disconnect` - Disconnect channel and session.þ  * `assertExitStatus` - Verifies that the remote task completed normally.þ* `ChannelStream` - This class encapsulates input/output operation for the channel attached to this session. It includes these methods:þ  * `waitForInput` - Wait for input to be available.þ  * `writeln` - Write the specified string to the remote host, followed by a carriage return.þ  * `waitForPrompt` - Wait for the specified prompt to be received from the remote host.þ  * `readChannel` - Read the input from the channel.þ

column43: # vertigo-extensionsþþ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache%202.0-green.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0)þ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/io.vertigo/vertigo.svg?label=Maven%20Central)](https://search.maven.org/search?q=g:%22io.vertigo%22)þþ=================þþVertigo extensions are mini-appplications that provide **high value services** on a given topic.þUse them to enhance your applications!þþEach extension can be used :þ - as a dependency to your existing vertigo appþ - as a standalone app for microservices architecturesþþþ## vertigo-social [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-yes-green.svg)]()þ### Add collaboration features to help your usersþþ* __comment__ :  a simple way to add comments and metadata to business objectsþ* __notification__ : a standalone way to push notification to usersþ* __mail__ : a simple api to send mailsþ* __handle__ : *WIP*þþ## vertigo-orchestra [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-yes-green.svg)]()þ### Manage, execute and monitor background operations and communications.þFor more details see [here](/vertigo-orchestra/)þþ## vertigo-quarto [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-yes-green.svg)]()þ### Publishing managment.þþ* __converter__ : obviously, converts your documents from one format to anotherþ* __publisher__ : lightweight publishing tool. Produces documents from user defined templates and application data. A rule system can be used to dynamically skip activities.þþ## vertigo-audit [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-no-red.svg)]()þþ## vertigo-adapters [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-no-red.svg)]()þStandalone adapters to easily use third party services (Twitter, IFTTT, etc...) with your vertigo appþþ## vertigo-geo [![Ready to use?](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ready%20to%20use%3F-no-red.svg)]()þþ-----þ#Licenseþ                Copyright (C) 2017-2019, Vertigo.io, KleeGroup, direction.technique@kleegroup.com (http://www.kleegroup.com)þ                KleeGroup, Centre d'affaire la Boursidiere - BP 159 - 92357 Le Plessis Robinson Cedex - Franceþ                þ                Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");þ                you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.þ                You may obtain a copy of the License atþ                þ                http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þ                þ                Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþ                distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þ                WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þ                See the License for the specific language governing permissions andþ                limitations under the License.

column17: A library for loading and saving GTFS feeds of arbitrary size with disk-backed storage
column43: # gtfs-lib [![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/conveyal/gtfs-lib.svg?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/conveyal/gtfs-lib)þþA library for loading and saving GTFS feeds of arbitrary size with disk-backed storage.þþBased on observations over several years of experience using the OneBusAway GTFS library (which is used by OpenTripPlanner), Conveyal created this new GTFS library to meet our current needs.þþThe main design goals are:þþ- Avoid all reflection tricks and use imperative code style even if it is a bit verboseþ- Allow loading and processing GTFS feeds (much) bigger than available memoryþ- Introduce the concept of feed IDs, and do not use agency IDs for this purpose.þ- Perform extensive syntax and semantic validation of feed contentsþ- Tolerate and recover from parsing errors, aiming to load the entire file even when values are missing or corruptedþþA gtfs-lib GTFSFeed object should faithfully represent the contents of a single GTFS feed file. At least during the initial load, no heuristics are applied to clean up the data. Basic syntax is verified, and any problems encountered are logged in detail. At this stage, fields or entites may be missing, and the data may be nonsensical. Then in an optional post-load validation phase, semantic checks are performed and problems are optionally repaired.þþ## Usageþþgtfs-lib can be used as a Java library or run via the command line.  If using this library with PostgreSQL for persistence, you must use at least version 9.6 of PostgreSQL.þþ### Library (maven)þþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.conveyal</groupId>þ  <artifactId>gtfs-lib</artifactId>þ  <version>${choose-a-version}</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþ### Command lineþþ```bashþ## download repoþ$ git clone https://github.com/conveyal/gtfs-lib.gitþ$ cd gtfs-libþ## build the jarþ$ mvn packageþ## Run the validation suite on a GTFS file and save the results to json files.þ## Note: Change the version number to match the shaded jar file name in /target directory.þ$ java -cp gtfs-lib-3.4.0-SNAPSHOT-shaded.jar com.conveyal.gtfs.GTFS --load /path/to/gtfs.zip --validate --json /optional/path/to/resultsþ```þþ### Load and Validation resultsþþThe result from running the load or validate command line option withþthe `--json` option is a json file containing summary information aboutþthe feed and the process (load or validate) that was run. The results willþbe stored at `[feedId]-[load|validate].json` in the system temp directoryþor the optional directory specified with the `--json` option.þþ#### load.jsonþþ```jsonþ{þ  "filename" : column17: CoreASM core projects
column43: The CoreASM Modeling Frameworkþ==============================þþCoreASM is an open source project that focuses on offering a lean executableþASM (Abstract State Machines) language, in combination with a supporting toolþenvironment for high-level design, experimental validation and formalþverification (where appropriate) of abstract system models.þþCoreASM offers a rich ASM language with a formally defined semantics that isþfaithful to the original semantics of ASM and is the first ASM tool thatþexplicitly supports distributed ASM computation models with custom schedulingþpolicies. The extensibility of its language and modeling environment, the mostþsignificant feature of CoreASM, provides utmost flexibility for extending itsþlanguage definition and execution engine in order to tailor it to theþparticular needs of virtually any conceivable application context. CoreASM isþone of the few ASM tools that is implemented as an open framework. þþCoreASM can be used in differnt forms: it offers a modeling framework, it canþbe viewed as a tool suite with different tools it offers around the engine,þwhile the engine itself can be used as an stand-alone tool (using itsþcommand-line or Eclipse plugin UI).þþ### What is Carma?þþCarma is a command-line CoreASM Engine driver. It runs CoreASM specificationsþusing a CoreASM Engine and offers control over the engine.  þþþ### How is it related to CoreASM on SourceForge?þþThese are the same projects. At some point in 2013 we have stopped maintaing theþcode on sourceforge and started moving the repository to github.þþþHow To Build CoreASM?þ---------------------þþYou can build the CoreASM core projects using [Maven](http://maven.apache.org). þJust run the following command in `org.coreasm.parent` project:þþ    mvn clean installþþTo build/update eclipse project files, run:þþ    mvn eclipse:eclipseþþA detailed manual how to setup an Eclipse based development environment for CoreASM can be found in our [wiki](https://github.com/CoreASM/coreasm.core/wiki) .þþþThe Latest Versionþ------------------þþLatest released versions of Carma, CoreASM Eclipse and the CoreASM Engine can be found on [github](https://github.com/CoreASM/coreasm.core). Older versions can be found on the CoreASM þProject web site <http://www.coreasm.org>.þþþLicensingþ---------þ þBoth the Carma project and the CoreASM Engine project are licensed under the þAcademic Free License version 3.0 which is available from either of theseþweb pages: þ  <http://www.opensource.org/licenses/afl-3.0.php>þ  <http://www.coreasm.org/afl-3.0.php>þþþThanks for using Carma.þþThe CoreASM Development Teamþ2005-2013

column17: Selenium Foundation is an automation framework designed to extend and enhance the capabilities provided by Selenium (WebDriver).
column43: [![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.nordstrom.ui-tools/selenium-foundation.svg)](https://search.maven.org/search?q=g:com.nordstrom.ui-tools%20AND%20a:selenium-foundation&core=gav)þþ# INTRODUCTIONþ**Selenium Foundation** is an automation framework designed to extend and enhance the capabilities provided by **Selenium** (_WebDriver_).þþ## SELENIUM API SUPPORTþþ**Selenium Foundation** includes support for both **Selenium 2** and **Selenium 3**. This project has transitioned from Maven to Gradle so that both configurations can be handled by a single [project definition file](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/build.gradle).þþ### Dependency Artifact CoordinatesþþThe Maven group ID is `com.nordstrom.ui-tools`, and the artifact ID is `selenium-foundation`. Artifacts whose versions have the `s2` suffix support the **Selenium 2** API. Artifacts whose versions have the `s3` suffix support the **Selenium 3** API.þþTo add a dependency on **Selenium Foundation** for Maven, use the following:þþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.nordstrom.ui-tools</groupId>þ  <artifactId>selenium-foundation</artifactId>þ  <!-- either Selenium 2 support: -->þ  <version>18.3.0-s2</version>þ  <!-- or Selenium 3 support: -->þ  <version>18.3.0-s3</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþTo add a dependency for Gradle:þþ```javaþdependencies {þ  // either Selenium 2 support:þ  compile 'com.nordstrom.ui-tools:selenium-foundation:18.3.0-s2'þ  // or Selenium 3 support:þ  compile 'com.nordstrom.ui-tools:selenium-foundation:18.3.0-s3'þ}þ```þþ### Building Selenium Foundationþþ#### Building in EclipseþþFor Eclipse, we recommend enabling Gradle integration through the official [BuildShip](https://marketplace.eclipse.org/content/buildship-gradle-integration) plugin. By default, this project will build it's **Selenium 3** configuration. To build the **Selenium 2** configuration, add this program argument to the run configuration for the `build` task:þþ> `-Pprofile=selenium2`þþ#### Building from Command LineþþBoth configurations of **Selenium Foundation** can by built from the command line. þþ> **`gradle build`** `# build Selenium 3 configuration`  þ> **`gradle build -Pprofile=selenium2`** `# build Selenium 2 configuration`  þþUse the `install` task to install SNAPSHOT builds in your local Maven repository:þþ> **`gradle install`** `# build Selenium 3 configuration`  þ> **`gradle install -Pprofile=selenium2`** `# build Selenium 2 configuration`  þþ#### Maven SupportþþAlthough Gradle is used to produce official releases, **Selenium Foundation** also includes a fully-functional Maven POM file.þþ> **`mvn package -Pselenium3`** `# build Selenium 3 configuration`  þ> **`mvn package -Pselenium2`** `# build Selenium 2 configuration`þþNote that the version number in this POM file is merely a placeholder - a token that gets replaced during the normal build process. Finalized, functional `POMs` can be found within the **Selenium Foundation** JARs themselves at `META-INF\maven\com.nordstrom.ui-tools\selenium-foundation\pom.xml`þþ## GETTING STARTEDþþThe [QuickStart](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/test/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/QuickStart.java) class provides a fully-functional example of a test class built around **Selenium Foundation**,  [TestNG Foundation](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation), and the [Settings API](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Settings). It demonstrates how to set up required elements and introduces several key features that you're likely to use on a regular basis. þþ## HIGHLIGHTSþþ### Automatic Driver Targetingþþ**Selenium Foundation** provides a complete set of base classes for building well-factored page models. This includes page components and frames. **Selenium Foundation** allows you to focus on modeling your application (instead of managing which window or frame the driver is addressing) by handling all driver targeting for you. You'll never see `driver.switchTo(...)` in page model automation built with **Selenium Foundation**, because the framework automatically ensures that the driver is addressing the window or frame associated with each page model method before it's invoked.þþ### Support for Frame-Based Components and Shadow-DOM Hierarchiesþþ**Selenium Foundation** provides base classes for modeling frame-based components and shadow-DOM hierarchies. These base classes handle the specific details of interacting with these DOM features through the underlying Selenium API, managing search context and driver targeting for you. The implementation of your components will be totally dedicated to the functionality of the elements you're modeling - never cluttered with boilerplate code to switch driver focus or traverse into shadow hierarchies.þþ### Landing Page Verification / Model-Directed NavigationþþPage classes can be explicitly associated with web application paths through the **`@PageUrl`** annotation. These associations can be declared as either fixed paths or patterns, and these declarations are used by **Selenium Foundation** to verify landing page paths at page transitions. You can also perform direct navigation to web application paths associated with page classes through the **`@PageUrl`** annotation.þþ### Customizable Transition Error DetectionþþIn conjunction with automatic landing page verification, **Selenium Foundation** invokes registered custom [transition error detectors](docs/TransitionErrorDetection.md). Implement the [TransitionErrorDetector](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/interfaces/TransitionErrorDetector.java) interface, then register your detectors in the corresponding service loader configuration file (**META-INF/services/com.nordstrom.automation.selenium.interfaces.TransitionErrorDetector**).þþExamples of the sorts of conditions you may want to detect include error pages (e.g. - page not found) or non-context error messages (e.g. - communication issues, access token timeout). For recoverable conditions, error detectors can also server as error handler. For example, you could implement a detector that automatically logs back in if your test encounters an access timeout.þþ### Component Collection Classesþþ**Selenium Foundation** also includes collection classes ([ComponentList](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/model/ComponentList.java), [ComponentMap](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/model/ComponentMap.java), [FrameList](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/model/FrameList.java), and [FrameMap](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/model/FrameMap.java)) that enable you to define collections of components for your page models. For example, you can define a **SearchResultTile** component and include a map of these tiles keyed by product ID in your **SearchResultsPage** class. **Selenium Foundation** collections are lazy-initialized automatically - the composition of the collection is determined when it's instantiated, but each item in the collection is only populated when it's explicitly referenced.þþ### Automatic Stale Element Reference ProtectionþþOne of the most impactful features of **Selenium Foundation** saves your automation from the dreaded **StaleElementReferenceException** failure. Web element search operations performed within the **Selenium Foundation** framework return enhanced references, which retain all of the parameters needed to re-acquire the reference if it goes stale. Every web element method call is guarded by an automatic recovery feature. If a reference goes stale, **Selenium Foundation** re-acquires the reference and re-issues the web element method call that encountered the exception. Your automation continues on normally, blissfully unaware of the disaster that was averted.þþ### Optional ElementsþþAnother useful extension provided by **Selenium Foundation** is the optional element. This feature enables you to model elements that only exist on the page under specific conditions. For example, you can model an error message that only exists when a form is submitted with no value in a required field. Determining if the element exists is as easy as calling the `hasReference()` method of the optional element object.þþ### Page-Load Synchronizationþþ**Selenium Foundation** automatically synchronizes your automation with ordinary page transitions, ensuring that tests don't get tripped up by application hesitation. Synchronizing your automation with dynamic content creation is easily done by implementing a simple interface (**DetectsLoadCompletion**). This greatly simplifies the modeling of single-page applications and pages rendered with dynamic content loading.þþ### Grid-Based Driver CreationþþTo avoid divergent behavior between local and remote execution, **Selenium Foundation** acquires driver sessions for local runs from a local instance of **Selenium Grid**. In addition to eliminating ordinary behavioral differences, this strategy provides two major benefits:þþ1. Adding support for a new driver is a simple configuration change - No need to crack open the code!þ2. You get explicit control over the maximum number of concurrent sessions, so you can run your tests in parallel without over-taxing your system.þþ### Automatic Phase-to-Phase Driver Hand-OffþþDrivers allocated for per-test configuration setup methods (i.e. - **`@BeforeMethod`**) are automatically handed off to the tests for which configuration is being performed. Drivers allocated for tests are automatically handed off to per-test configuration cleanup methods (i.e. - **`@AfterMethod`**).  This hand-off behavior greatly simplifies the implementation of generic setup and cleanup processing that interacts with your application under test.þþ### Automatic Capture of Screenshots and Page SourceþþTo assist in root-cause analysis, **Selenium Foundation** automatically captures a screenshot and page source for each failed test. By using the **ReporterAppender**, the log output of each **TestNG** test is captured as part of the test result object. This information is automatically shown on test result pages in **Jenkins**. No more digging through intermingled output in console logs!þþ### Support for TestNG and JUnitþþ**Selenium Foundation** includes support for both **TestNG** and **JUnit 4**. Feature parity is enabled by several core abstractions, and through features provided by the **TestNG Foundation** and **JUnit Foundation** libraries.þþ## TESTNG REQUIRED ELEMENTSþþThere are several required elements that must be included in every TestNG test class to activate the features of **Selenium Foundation**. To assist you in this process, we've included the [TestNgBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/support/TestNgBase.java) class as a starter. This class includes all of the required elements outlined below, and adds the [ScreenshotCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/listeners/ScreenshotCapture.java) and [PageSourceCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/listeners/PageSourceCapture.java) listeners.þþ**TestNgBase** is an abstract class that implements the [TestBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/core/TestBase.java) interface, which provides a common abstraction for both TestNG and JUnit 4 tests.þþ### Outline of Required ElementsþþThe following is an outline of the elements that must be included in every TestNG test that uses **Selenium Foundation**:þþ* [ListenerChain](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/testng/ListenerChain.java):  þ**ListenerChain** is a TestNG listener that enables you to add other listeners at runtime and guarantees the order in which they're invoked. This is similar in behavior to a JUnit 4 rule chain.þ* The [@LinkedListeners](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/testng/LinkedListeners.java) annotation:  þ To attach listeners to an active **ListenerChain**, mark your test class with the **`@LinkedListeners`** annotation. The [TestNgBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/support/TestNgBase.java) class is marked with a **`@LinkedListeners`** annotation that specifies four listeners that manage several core features of **Selenium Foundation**:þ  * [ScreenshotCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/listeners/ScreenshotCapture.java):  þ  **ScreenshotCapture** is a TestNG listener that automatically captures screenshots in the event of test failures. Tests are also able to request on-demand screenshot capture through the `captureArtifact(ITestResult)` method.þ  * [PageSourceCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/listeners/PageSourceCapture.java):  þ  **PageSourceCapture** is a TestNG listener that automatically captures page source in the event of test failures. Tests are also able to request on-demand page source capture through the `captureArtifact(ITestResult)` method.þ  * [DriverListener](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/listeners/DriverListener.java):  þ  **DriverListener** is a TestNG listener that manages driver sessions and local Selenium Grid servers.þ  * [ExecutionFlowController](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/testng/ExecutionFlowController.java):  þ  **ExecutionFlowController** is a TestNG listener that propagates test context attributes:  þ  [_before_ method] → [test method] → [_after_ method]þþThe **`@LinkedListeners`** annotation is processed by the **ListenerChain**, which must be activated so that the other core listeners will be connected and functioning correctly. Although you can use the standard TestNG **`@Listeners`** annotation to activate **ListenerChain**, we recommend that you use the **ServiceLoader** mechanism for this purpose in your actual project. This is the technique employed by the test suite of the **Selenium Foundation** project. For details, see [Selenium Foundation Test Support](docs/SeleniumFoundationTestSupport.md).þþ## AUTOMATIC RETRY OF FAILED TESTSþþ**Selenium Foundation** includes a context-specific extension of the [RetryManager](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/testng/RetryManager.java) analyzer of [TestNG Foundation](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation). This retry analyzer considers any test that fails due to a **WebDriverException** to be retriable. By default, this retry analyzer is disabled. To enable automatic retry of **WebDriverException** failures, specify a positive value for the **MAX_RETRY** setting of **TestNG Foundation**:þþ| _testng.properties_ |þ| --- |þ| testng.max.retry=2 |þþThe base class for this retry analyzer enables you to add your own analyzers through the **ServiceLoader**. You can also entirely replace this analyzer with your own. See the [TestNG Foundation](https://github.com/Nordstrom/TestNG-Foundation#attaching-retry-analyzers-via-retrymanager) documentation for more details.þþ## DEMONSTRATED FEATURESþþThe **QuickStart** class demonstrates several important **Selenium Foundation** features:þþ* [InitialPage](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/annotations/InitialPage.java):  þ**InitialPage** is a Java annotation that enables you to specify the initial page class and/or URL that should be loaded at the start of the test method. This can be applied to each test individually, or it can be applied at the class level to specify the default page for all tests in the class. It can also be applied to **`@Before...`** configuration methods to provide driver sessions opened to the desired page.þ* [SeleniumConfig](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/SeleniumConfig.java):  þ**SeleniumConfig** declares settings and methods related to Selenium WebDriver and Grid configuration. This class is built on the **Settings API**, composed of defaults, stored values, and System properties.þ* [SeleniumSettings](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/SeleniumConfig.java):  þ**SeleniumSettings** declares the constants, property names, and default values for the settings managed by SeleniumConfig. Defaults can be overridden via System properties or the _settings.propeties_ file in your user "home" directory. See **ESSENTIAL SETTINGS** below for more details.þ* [ReporterAppender](https://github.com/sbabcoc/logback-testng/blob/master/src/main/java/com/github/sbabcoc/logback/testng/ReporterAppender.java):  þ**ReporterAppender** is a **Logback** appender for TestNG Reporter. The **Selenium Foundation** project ships with a _logback.xml_ file that attaches this appender. See the complete **logback-testng** information page [here](https://github.com/sbabcoc/logback-testng).þ* **`TestBase.optionalOf(Object)`**:  þThis static utility method wraps the specified object in an [Optional](https://google.github.io/guava/releases/19.0/api/docs/com/google/common/base/Optional.html) object. If the object to be wrapped is 'null', this method returns an empty optional.þþ## DRIVER ACQUISITION AND HAND-OFFþþIn the preceding section, driver sessions are acquired automatically for each test or requested implicitly by applying the **`@InitialPage`** annotation. The core functionality used to initiate driver sessions implicitly can also be invoked ad hoc to acquire drivers explicitly:þþ```javaþWebDriver driver = GridUtility.getDriver();þ```þþThis method uses the configured settings for Selenium Grid and desired browser from the current test execution context to instantiate a new driver session.þþIf the **`@InitialPage`** annotation is applied to a **`@BeforeMethod`** configuration method, the driver instantiated for this method is automatically handed off to the test that follows. The initial page as specified for the configuration method is handed off as well. If actions performed by your configuration method trigger page transitions, you need to store the final page accessed by the configuration method as the initial page for the test method:þþ```javaþ@BeforeMethodþ@InitialPage(LoginPage.class)þpublic void logInBeforeTest() {þ    LoginPage loginPage = (LoginPage) getInitialPage();þ    MainMenuPage mainMenuPage = loginPage.logInAs(USER.StandardUser);þ    // update initial page for test methodþ    setInitialPage(mainMenuPage);þ}þþ@Testþpublic void testMenuFeatures() {þ    MainMenuPage mainMenuPage = (MainMenuPage) getInitialPage();þ    ...þ}þþ```þþ## ESSENTIAL SETTINGS þþYou'll probably find that the defaults assigned to most settings will suffice in most basic scenarios. However, it's likely that you'll need to override one or more of the following. The **Property Name** column indicates the name of the System property associated with the setting. To override a setting, you can either add a line for the setting to your _settings.properties_ file or define a System property. þþ| Constant | Property Name | Default |þ| --- | --- |:---:|þ| BROWSER_NAME | selenium.browser.name | (none) * |þ| TARGET_HOST | selenium.target.host | localhost |þ| TARGET_PATH | selenium.target.path | / |þþ\* NOTE: By default, HtmlUnit is selected as the browser. For easier override, this is specified through **BROWSER_CAPS** instead of **BROWSER_NAME**. For details, see [Manipulate Settings with SeleniumConfig](docs/ManipulateSettingsWithSeleniumConfig.md). þþ## OVERRIDING DEFAULTS þþ**SeleniumConfig** searches a series of locations for a _settings.properties_ file. This file will typically be stored in your user "home" folder. Any settings declared in this file will override the defaults assigned in the **SeleniumSettings** enumeration. Settings that are declared as System properties will override both the defaults assigned by **SeleniumSettings** and settings declared in _settings.properties_. For example: þþ| _settings.properties_ |þ| --- |þ| selenium.target.host=my.server.com |þ| selenium.browser.name=chrome |þþThis sample _settings.properties_ file overrides the values of **TARGET_HOST** and **BROWSER_NAME**. The latter can be overridden by System property declaration: þ> `-Dselenium.browser.name=firefox`þþThe hierarchy of evaluation produces the following results: þþ> **BROWSER_NAME** = <mark>firefox</mark>; **TARGET_HOST** = <mark>my.server.com</mark>; **TARGET_PATH** = <mark>/</mark> þþ## INSTALLING DRIVERS þþWhichever browser you choose to run your automation on, you need to make sure to install the latest driver for that browser compatible with your target version of **Selenium WebDriver**, along with a compatible release of the browser itself. We recommend that you install the drivers and browsers on the file search path to avoid the need to provide additional configuration details via scenario-specific means. þþHere are the official homes for several of the major drivers: þþ* GhostDriver (PhantomJS) - [http://phantomjs.org/download.html](http://phantomjs.org/download.html)þ* ChromeDriver - [https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/downloads](https://sites.google.com/a/chromium.org/chromedriver/downloads)þ* IEDriver - [http://selenium-release.storage.googleapis.com/index.html?path=2.53/](http://selenium-release.storage.googleapis.com/index.html?path=2.53/)þþ**NOTE**: GhostDriver and ChromeDriver are simple binary installations, but several system configuration changes must be applied for IEDriver to work properly. For details, visit the InternetExplorerDriver project Wiki on GitHub and follow the [Required Configuration](https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/wiki/InternetExplorerDriver#required-configuration) procedure.þþ# JUNIT 4 SUPPORTþþIn addition to the TestNG support documented above, **Selenium Foundation** also includes support for **JUnit 4**. This support is built upon **JUnit Foundation**, which provides the framework for method interception (used for driver management), artifact capture (used to acquire screenshots and page source), and automatic retry of failed tests.þþ## JUnit 4 Required ElementsþþThere are several required elements that must be included in every JUnit 4 test class to activate the features of **Selenium Foundation**. To assist you in this process, we've included the [JUnitBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/JUnitBase.java) class as a starter. This class includes all of the required elements outlined below.þþ**JUnitBase** is an abstract class that implements the [TestBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/core/TestBase.java) interface, which provides a common abstraction for both TestNG and JUnit 4 tests.þþ### Outline of Required ElementsþþThe following is an outline of the elements that must be included in every JUnit 4 project that uses **Selenium Foundation**:þþ* **JUnit Foundation** [event notifications](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation#how-to-enable-notifications):  þThe JUnit support provided by **Selenium Foundation** relies on event notifications published by **JUnit Foundation**. Notifications are enabled by a Java agent, which uses bytecode enhancement to install hooks on test and configuration methods.þ###### Maven configuration for Java agent:þ```xmlþ    <plugins>þ      <!-- This provides the path to the Java agent -->þ      <plugin>þ        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>þ        <artifactId>maven-dependency-plugin</artifactId>þ        <version>3.1.1</version>þ        <executions>þ          <execution>þ            <id>getClasspathFilenames</id>þ            <goals>þ              <goal>properties</goal>þ            </goals>þ          </execution>þ        </executions>þ      </plugin>þ      <plugin>þ        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>þ        <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>þ        <version>2.22.0</version>þ        <configuration>þ          <argLine>-javaagent:${com.nordstrom.tools:junit-foundation:jar}</argLine>þ        </configuration>þ      </plugin>þ    </plugins>þ```  þ###### Gradle configuration for Java agent:  þ```gradleþext {þ    junitFoundation = configurations.compile.resolvedConfiguration.resolvedArtifacts.find { it.name == 'junit-foundation' }þ}þþtest.doFirst {þ    jvmArgs "-javaagent:${junitFoundation.file}"þ}þ```þþ* [DriverWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/DriverWatcher.java):  þ**DriverWatcher** implements the **JUnit Foundation**  [MethodWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/MethodWatcher.java) interface to manage driver sessions. It provides initial page support, and it also supplies a JUnit 4 [TestWatcher](https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/rules/TestWatcher.html):þ  * **`DriverWatcher.getTestWatcher()`**:  þ  The test rule returned by this static method is responsible for closing the driver attached to the current test method.þ* [DriverListener](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/DriverListener.java):  þ**DriverListener** implements the **JUnit Foundation** [ShutdownListener](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/ShutdownListener.java) interface to shut down the local Selenium Grid serves at the end of the run.þ* [RuleChain](http://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/latest/org/junit/rules/RuleChain.html):  þ Use **RuleChain** for attaching test rules that must be applied in a specific order. The [JUnitBase](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/JUnitBase.java) class includes a **RuleChain** that specifies three watchers that manage core features of **Selenium Foundation**:þ  * [ScreenshotCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/ScreenshotCapture.java):  þ  **ScreenshotCapture** is a JUnit 4 test watcher that automatically captures a screenshot in the event of test failure.þ  * [PageSourceCapture](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/PageSourceCapture.java):  þ  **PageSourceCapture** is a JUnit 4 test watcher that automatically captures page source in the event of test failures.þ  * [DriverWatcher](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/DriverWatcher.java):  þ  As described previously, the test watcher returned by `DriverWatcher.getTestWatcher()` closes the driver attached to the current test method.þþ## AUTOMATIC RETRY OF FAILED TESTSþþ**Selenium Foundation** includes an implementation of the [JUnitRetryAnalyzer](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/JUnitRetryAnalyzer.java) interface of [JUnit Foundation](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation). This retry analyzer considers any test that fails due to a **WebDriverException** to be retriable. By default, this retry analyzer is disabled. To enable automatic retry of **WebDriverException** failures:þþ* Add a service loader retry analyzer configuration file in the **_META-INF/services_** folder:þþ###### com.nordstrom.automation.junit.JUnitRetryAnalyzerþ```þcom.nordstrom.automation.selenium.junit.RetryAnalyzerþ```þþ* Specify a positive value for the **MAX_RETRY** setting of **JUnit Foundation**:þþ| _junit.properties_ |þ| --- |þ| junit.max.retry=2 |þþIn this example, these two configurations will enable **JUnit Foundation** to retry tests that fail with **WebDriverException** twice before counting them as failures. See the [JUnit Foundation](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation#automatic-retry-of-failed-tests) documentation for more details.þþ## DEMONSTRATED FEATURESþþThe **JUnitBase** class demonstrates several features of the **Selenium Foundation** API:þþ* **`TestBase.optionalOf(Object)`**:  þThis static utility method wraps the specified object in an [Optional](https://google.github.io/guava/releases/19.0/api/docs/com/google/common/base/Optional.html) object. If the object to be wrapped is 'null', this method returns an empty optional.þ* **`RuleChainWalker.getAttachedRule(RuleChain, Class<T extends TestRule>)`**:  þThis static utility method gets reference to an instance of the specified test rule type on the supplied rule chain. In **JUnitBase**, this is used to acquire a reference to the **ScreenshotCapture** watcher for capturing on-demand screenshot artifacts.þ* **`ScreenshotCapture.getAtomIdentity()`**:  þThis instance method of **ScreenshotCapture** enables test code to acquire the [AtomIdentity](https://github.com/Nordstrom/JUnit-Foundation/blob/master/src/main/java/com/nordstrom/automation/junit/AtomIdentity.java) object for the current JUnit 4 test method. This object can be interrogated for many useful propeties of the test method, including test class instance, **Description** object, and instance parameters.þ* **`ScreenshotCapture.getDescription()`**:  þThis instance method of **ScreenshotCapture** enables test code to acquire the [Description](http://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/latest/org/junit/runner/Description.html) object for the current JUnit 4 test method. This object can be interrogated for many useful propeties of the test method, including method name, attached annotations, and containing class.þþ# FEATURE PARITYþþAll of the features of **Selenium Foundation** are available regardless of which testing framework you choose - either TestNG or JUnit 4. Once the initial configuration is done, the abstraction provided by the **TestBase** interface enables your code to be almost entirely framework-agnostic. This is clearly demonstrated in [ModelTestCore](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/test/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/core/ModelTestCore.java), which contains the implementations for a collection of tests that are invoked from both TestNG (via [ModelTest](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/test/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/model/ModelTest.java)) and JUnit 4 (via [JUnitModelTest](https://github.com/Nordstrom/Selenium-Foundation/tree/master/src/test/java/com/nordstrom/automation/selenium/junit/JUnitModelTest.java)).

column17: A microservices-based Streaming and Batch data processing in Cloud Foundry and Kubernetes
column43:
þ þ þ þ

þþ

þ þ þ þ þ þ þ
þ þ þ þ

þþ*Spring Cloud Data Flow* is a microservices-based toolkit for building streaming and batch data processing pipelines inþCloud Foundry and Kubernetes.þþData processing pipelines consist of Spring Boot apps, built using the [Spring Cloud Stream](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-stream)þor [Spring Cloud Task](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-task) microservice frameworks. þþThis makes Spring Cloud Data Flow ideal for a range of data processing use cases, from import/export to event streamingþand predictive analytics.þþ----þþ## Componentsþþ**Architecture**: The Spring Cloud Data Flow Server is a Spring Boot application that provides RESTful API and REST clientsþ(Shell, Dashboard, Java DSL).þA single Spring Cloud Data Flow installation can support orchestrating the deployment of streams and tasks to Local,þCloud Foundry, and Kubernetes.þþFamiliarize yourself with the Spring Cloud Data Flow [architecture](https://dataflow.spring.io/docs/concepts/architecture/)þand [feature capabilities](https://dataflow.spring.io/features/).þþ**Deployer SPI**: A Service Provider Interface (SPI) is defined in the [Spring Cloud Deployer](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-deployer)þproject. The Deployer SPI provides an abstraction layer for deploying the apps for a given streaming or batch data pipeline,þand managing the application lifecycle.þþSpring Cloud Deployer Implementations:þþ* [Local](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-deployer-local)þ* [Cloud Foundry](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-deployer-cloudfoundry)þ* [Kubernetes](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-deployer-kubernetes)þþ**Domain Model**: The Spring Cloud Data Flow [domain module](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow/tree/master/spring-cloud-dataflow-core)þincludes the concept of a *stream* that is a composition of Spring Cloud Stream applications in a linear data pipelineþfrom a *source* to a *sink*, optionally including *processor* application(s) in between. The domain also includes theþconcept of a *task*, which may be any process that does not run indefinitely, including [Spring Batch](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-batch)þjobs.þþ**Application Registry**: The [App Registry](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow/tree/master/spring-cloud-dataflow-registry)þmaintains the metadata of the catalog of reusable applications.þFor example, if relying on Maven coordinates, an application URI would be of the format:þ`maven://::`.þþ**Shell/CLI**: The [Shell](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow/tree/master/spring-cloud-dataflow-shell)þconnects to the Spring Cloud Data Flow Server's REST API and supports a DSL that simplifies the process of defining aþstream or task and managing its lifecycle.þþ**Community Implementations**: There are also community maintained Spring Cloud Data Flow implementations that are currentlyþbased on the 1.7.x series of Spring Cloud Data Flow.þþ * [HashiCorp Nomad](https://github.com/donovanmuller/spring-cloud-dataflow-server-nomad)þ * [OpenShift](https://github.com/donovanmuller/spring-cloud-dataflow-server-openshift)þ * [Apache Mesos](https://github.com/trustedchoice/spring-cloud-dataflow-server-mesos)þþThe [Apache YARN](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow-server-yarn) implementation has reached end-of-lineþstatus. Let us know at [Gitter](https://gitter.im/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow) if you are interested in forkingþthe project to continue developing and maintaining it.þþ----þþ## BuildingþþClone the repo and type þþ $ ./mvnw clean install þþLooking for more information? Follow this [link](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow/blob/master/spring-cloud-dataflow-docs/src/main/asciidoc/appendix-building.adoc).þþ### Building on WindowsþþWhen using Git on Windows to check out the project, it is important to handle line-endings correctly during checkouts.þBy default Git will change the line-endings during checkout to `CRLF`. This is, however, not desired for _Spring Cloud Data Flow_þas this may lead to test failures under Windows.þþTherefore, please ensure that you set Git property `core.autocrlf` to `false`, e.g. using: `$ git config core.autocrlf false`.þFore more information please refer to the [Git documentation, Formatting and Whitespace](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Customizing-Git-Git-Configuration).þþ----þþ## ContributingþþWe welcome contributions! Follow this [link](https://github.com/spring-cloud/spring-cloud-dataflow/blob/master/spring-cloud-dataflow-docs/src/main/asciidoc/appendix-contributing.adoc) for more information on how to contribute.þþ----þþ## Code formatting guidelinesþþ* The directory ./src/eclipse has two files for use with code formatting, `eclipse-code-formatter.xml` for the majority of the code formatting rules and `eclipse.importorder` to order the import statements.þþ* In eclipse you import these files by navigating `Windows -> Preferences` and then the menu items `Preferences > Java > Code Style > Formatter` and `Preferences > Java > Code Style > Organize Imports` respectfully.þþ* In `IntelliJ`, install the plugin `Eclipse Code Formatter`. You can find it by searching the "Browse Repositories" under the plugin option within `IntelliJ` (Once installed you will need to reboot Intellij for it to take effect).þThen navigate to `Intellij IDEA > Preferences` and select the Eclipse Code Formatter. Select the `eclipse-code-formatter.xml` file for the field `Eclipse Java Formatter config file` and the file `eclipse.importorder` for the field `Import order`.þEnable the `Eclipse code formatter` by clicking `Use the Eclipse code formatter` then click the *OK* button.þ** NOTE: If you configure the `Eclipse Code Formatter` from `File > Other Settings > Default Settings` it will set this policy across all of your Intellij projects.

column17: Logisim Italian Fork
column43:
# Logisim ITAþLogisim is a digital circuit simulator, [originally available here](https://www.cburch.com/logisim/).

þThis is an italian fork based on the original Logisim version.
þ[DOWNLOAD AND CHANGELOG](https://logisim.altervista.org)
þ[CONTACT US](https://logisim.altervista.org/contacts.html)
þ[PLUGINS](https://logisim.altervista.org/plugins.html)
þ[USER TUTORIALS](https://logisim.altervista.org/userstutorial.php)
þ[DEVS TUTORIALS](https://logisim.altervista.org/developerstutorial.php)
þ## Why you should use Logisim ITAþ* No retro-compatibility problems with old .circ filesþ* A lot of new components and small changesþ* Bug fixes and optimizationsþ* Constantly supported and listening to all your suggestions/reportsþ## Changelogþ* Core Stuff:þ * Italian, Simplified Chinese and partial french translation!þ * Autoupdates!þ * Compiled with Java 14þ * Complete new movement system with mouse draggingþ * Auto center and Auto zoom when opening new files/circuits or with ctrl-0, double mouse wheel click and with the round button you'll see on the lower-right cornerþ * Almost infinite canvas, arrows will show you in what direction is the circuit if it's outside of your viewþ * Zoom in and out using mouse wheel where you're pointing atþ * Double click with Edit Tool to label componentsþ * Load libraries from folder at startup (Preferences / Fork)þ * Selectable painting refresh rate, default 60Hz (Legacy was 20Hz and sometimes lagging)þ * Anti Aliasing, Look and Feel and Fill Component's Background preferenceþ * Clock custom frequencyþ * Press ESC or DEL to cancel "Add Tool" action, F1 opens Library Referenceþ * Increased output limit in Analyze Circuit to 32þ * Analyze Circuit should calculate table/expression with any kind of componentþ * Added "Clear Log" buttonþ * Added missing tooltipsþ * Changed some default valuesþ* New components:þ * Wiring->Programmable Generatorþ * TTL gates (7400, 7402, 7404, 7408, 7432, 7447, 7485, 7486, 74165, 74283, 747266)þ * I/O->Digital Oscilloscopeþ * I/O->Switchþ * I/O->Dip Switchþ * I/O->Sliderþ * I/O->RGB LEDþ * I/O->Buzzerþ * Memory->PLA ROMþ * Plexers->7-Segment Display Decoderþ* Component changes:þ * New FF layoutþ * The Shift Register will show you its internal bits even when set to serial loadþ * Right click on Pin, Edit Contents and set its value typing the decimal numberþ * Added Sel pin in Registerþ * Added Preset pin in Register and Counterþ * TTY and Keyboard components can use 16-bit values (UTF-16)þ* New Attributes:þ * Controlled Buffer / Inverter: Negate Control Input attributeþ * Added Sel Active Level attribute in components with Sel pinþ * Priority Plexer "No Input" attributeþ * Joystick "Facing" attributeþ * Bit Selector "Select location" attributeþ * Added Label Color attribute for each component with Label attribute and Text Toolþ * Added Label for RAM, ROM and PLA ROMþ * FF D, S-R: "Latch" option in Trigger attributeþ * New Counter behavior (different pin logic)þ* Fixed bugs:þ * Big fixes to Log menu and Log output fileþ * Big fixes for Text Toolþ * Fixed empty template bug introduced in Logisim 2.7.0þ * Fixed input positions in wide gates with 4 inputsþ * Fixed opening new file in new window with old window not usedþ * Fixed bugged 32b multiplierþ * Some fix from original early version 2.7.2.255þ## Bugsþ* All the original Logisim's bugs we haven't fixed yet:þ * Some random blue/red line caused by bad values refreshþ * Some problem with high frequenciesþ * String attribute not calling attributechanged method while writing its valueþ* Programmable Generator: trying to edit its values by clicking on "(click to edit)" is a bit buggy, use "Edit Contents" instead in menu by clicking with right mouse buttonþ## Features we want to addþ* Solve dirty points when rotatingþ* Add a new type of libraryþ* Draw also in circuitsþ* Suggest us everything at logisimit@gmail.comþ## Retro-compatibilityþDue to a bug in the original Logisim, wide gates with 4 inputs had a bad pin positioning.þI fixed this problem but if you open an old file containing gates with those attributes, its inputs will be disconnected and a warning message will appearþ## EXE and JAR downloads + microprocessor projectþAll in our website [here](https://logisim.altervista.org)þ## How to compile & useþWatch our tutorials on "TUTORIAL" section of our [website](https://logisim.altervista.org/developerstutorial.php)þ## TranslationþNew strings are translated really bad (Google Translate) because i just know Italian and English.
You can help me translating other languages or adding a new one, if you want so, contact me at logisimit@gmail.com

column17: UH Groupings uses Internet2's Grouper middleware to implement the concept of groupings, an enhanced group that is made up of a basis group, an include group and an exclude group.  UH Groupings proposes to be a kinder, gentler UI for our community.
column43: Manage your groupings in one place, use them in many.þþA grouping is a collection of members (e.g., all full-time Hilo faculty). UH Groupings allows you to create groupings, manage grouping memberships, control members' self-service options, designate sync destinations, and more.þþGroupings can be synchronized with one or more of the following: email LISTSERV lists, attributes for access control via CAS and LDAP, etc. Additionally, UH Groupings allows you to leverage group data from official sources, which can substantially reduce the manual overhead of membership management.þþUH Groupings utilizes the Internet2 Grouper project.  Grouper is an enterprise access management system designed for the highly distributed management environment and heterogeneous information technology environment common to universities.þþ[![License](https://img.shields.io/hexpm/l/plug.svg)](https://github.com/apereo/cas/blob/master/LICENSE)þ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui.png?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui)þ[![Coverage Badge](https://api.codacy.com/project/badge/Grade/69274196397f4587b88b0ecce5856d0a)](https://www.codacy.com/app/mhodgesatuh/uhgroupings?utm_source=github.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uhgroupings&utm_campaign=Badge_Grade)þ[![LGTM Badge](https://img.shields.io/lgtm/grade/javascript/github/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui)](https://lgtm.com/projects/g/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui/context:javascript)þ[![LGTM Java Badge](https://img.shields.io/lgtm/grade/java/github/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui)](https://lgtm.com/projects/g/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-ui/context:java)þþ##### JavaþYou'll need a Java JDK to build and run the project (version 1.8).þþThe files for the project are kept in a code repository,þavailable from here:þþhttps://github.com/uhawaii-system-its-ti-iam/uh-groupings-uiþþ##### BuildingþTo run the Application from the Command Line:þþ    $ mvn clean spring-boot:runþþTo build a deployable war file for local development, if preferred:þþ    $ mvn clean packageþþYou should have a deployable war file in the target directory.þDeploy as usual in a servlet container, e.g. tomcat.þþ##### Running Unit TestsþThe project includes Unit Tests for various parts of the system.þFor this project, Unit Tests are defined as those tests that willþrely on only the local development computer.þA development build of the application will run the Unit Tests.þA test and production build of the application will run both theþUnit Tests and the System Tests (which may require network access).þYou can also run specific Unit Tests using the appropriate commandþline arguments.þþTo run the Unit Tests with a standard build:þþ    $ mvn clean testþþTo run a test class:þþ    $ mvn clean test -Dtest=StringsTestþþTo run a single method in a test class:þþ    $ mvn clean test -Dtest=StringsTest#trunctateþþ##### Running System TestsþThe project files include a handful of System Tests.þFor this project, System Tests are defined as those tests that mayþcall live remote systems, such as a search against the productionþLDAP server. A standard build of the application will exclude theþSystem Tests, but you can explicitly run them by specifying theþappropriate command line argument.þþTo run the System Tests:þþ    $ mvn -Dtest=*SystemTest clean test

column17: WebDSL compiler
column43: # WebDSLþMain repository for the WebDSL domain-specific language for web applications.þþ## InstallationþEither follow the [installation instructions][1], or build from source.þSee also [how to get WebDSL in Eclipse][2].þþ## Buildingþþ### Install Dependencies (macOS + brew)þþ`brew install wget autoconf automake maven ant nailgun`þþ### Build WebDSL compilerþInvoke the following commands from the root of the repository:þþ    ./bootstrapþ    ./configure --prefix=/usr/localþ    makeþ    make installþþYou can check the current version of your WebDSL installation:þþ    webdsl versionþþIt will report the hash of the commit from which WebDSL was built.þþ> Note: If you get this error when invoking `make`:þ>þ>     Making all in srcþ>     make[1]: *** No rule to make target `libwebdsl-front.rtree',þ>       needed by `src-gen/org/webdsl/webdsl_generator/Main.java'.  Stop.þ>     make: *** [all-recursive] Error 1þ>þ> Clean the temporary files from the repository, e.g.:þ>þ>     git clean -fXdþ>þ> Then reissue the commands for building WebDSL.þþ## Build and run a WebDSL applicationþþExample application: https://github.com/webdsl/elib-exampleþþ### Command-line buildþþ- Download latest WebDSL compiler jar: http://webdsl-2015.ewi.tudelft.nl/compiler/webdsl.zipþ- Extract the zip file. þ- Add the webdsl/bin directory to your path, or use the full path, and run in the project directory:þ`webdsl run elib-example`þþ### IDE buildþþ- Get an Eclipse with latest WebDSL pluging pre-installed atþhttp://buildfarm.metaborg.org/view/WebDSL/job/webdsl-eclipsegen/lastSuccessfulBuild/artifact/dist/eclipse/ or use updatesite http://webdsl.org/update to install plugin.þ- Import the project into your Eclipse workspace.þ- Right-click the project and select 'Convert to a WebDSL Project', click 'Finish' to use default settings.þ- Build the project with ctrl+alt+b or cmd+alt+b, this will also deploy and run the application on Tomcat.þ- Open the 'Servers' view to manage the Tomcat instance.þþþþ[1]: https://webdsl.org/singlepage/Downloadþ[2]: https://webdsl.org/selectpage/Download/WebDSLplugin
